<body>
<h2>NAFTAmath: First Year Assessment</h2>
<h3>Introduction</h3>
<p>Some disturbing trends have emerged one year after
implementation of the North American Free Trade Agreement, a
never-before tried, high-risk experiment in which two countries
at far different stages of economic development and democratic
rights are attempting to merge their economies. These trends have
worsened in the wake of Mexico&thorn;s economic crisis and peso
devaluation, which combined with the NAFTA poses severe risks to
the interests of workers on both sides of the border. The overall
U.S. Trade surplus with Mexico, which declined 19 percent from
1993, is likely to become a substantial deficit in 1995. </p>
<p>One of the many deficiencies of NAFTA is that the agreement
specifically excludes exchange rate policies from coverage. The
danger in a &quot;competitive&quot; peso devaluation lies in the
inherent downward pressure on wages for workers in both countries
and additional incentives for U.S. companies to relocate to
Mexico. NAFTA already has locked into legal status a low-risk
environment for investment that provides full access to the U.S.
market with zero tariffs. While the movement of billions of
dollars in direct foreign investment to Mexico has been
accelerated, the structural ties between the U.S. and Mexican
economies may shave U.S. economic growth by 0.4 of a percentage
point in 1995, by some estimates, and cost 350,000 American jobs. </p>
<p>As of Jan. 3, 1995, the U.S. Department of Labor had received
321 petitions involving 34,799 dislocated workers who believed
that NAFTA had caused their unemployment. Of that first-year
total, DOL has certified 152 petitions covering 17,320 workers as
experiencing NAFTA-related unemployment. For the U.S. worker
whose job moves to Mexico, it is unlikely that he or she will
find employment opportunities that pay wages and benefits
anywhere near the level paid by the job lost. Manufacturing
workers who lose their jobs to Mexico, especially those with
years of seniority, inevitably will encounter severe economic
hardship and a reduction in the standard of living for their
families. </p>
<p>Despite reports of rising unemployment, inflation and economic
gloom in Mexico, the export-only border assembly plants known as
maquiladoras appear to be emerging as big winners because of the
peso&thorn;s devaluation. The 2,140 mostly American-owned
maquiladora plants in Mexico near the U.S. border already were
experiencing a banner year before devaluation, having displaced
tourism and petroleum as Mexico&thorn;s official top generator of
dollars. During the first 10 months of 1994, maquiladora
employment increased 6.2 percent to 600,376 employees, and an
employer association forecasts the opening of another 600
assembly plants in 1995. </p>
<p>Because of the devalued peso, U.S. employers in the Mexican
maquilas will realize an annual windfall of more than $750
million, while their employees, whose earnings are far below
those of other Mexican production workers, endure even more
hardship. The top 10 percent of Mexicans earn as much as the
bottom 70 percent. The poverty rate in Mexico is approximately 40
percent and the unemployment rate in excess of 20 percent.
Two-thirds of Mexican workers are either unemployed or make less
than $10 a day, when the cost of basic subsistence for a typical
family of 5 is now approximately $16 a day. </p>
<p>Also inadequate is the promise of relief to workers who are
dislocated because of trade under NAFTA. The number of petitions
and certifications for NAFTA-TAA may be just the tip of the
iceberg. While meritorious petitions are being denied, service
workers such as truck drivers and railroad workers are
ineligible. The rigid deadline for enrolling in training is
preventing qualified workers from receiving assistance, and the
design and structure of the program for indirectly affected
workers is needlessly cumbersome. Because the program is so
inadequate, several unions have recommended that petitions be
filed for regular TAA instead of NAFTA-TAA. </p>
<p>Unions continue to seek justice under the NAFTA labor side
agreement, with no satisfaction. But a representative of the U.S.
Council on International Business noted that the ability of
Mexican and American unions to use NAFTA procedures to
&quot;create a public spotlight&quot; is troubling to many
executives. That is obviously very small consolation for workers
who lose their jobs and those facing the threat of job loss at
the bargaining table. </p>
<h3>The U.S. Trade Surplus Shrinks</h3>
<p>After 12 months of trade in the wake of the North American
Free Trade Agreement, implemented Jan. 1, 1994, some disturbing
developments appear in the numbers. An economic slowdown in
Mexico, combined with the devaluation of the peso, has resulted
in a shrinking U.S. trade surplus with Mexico. Exports of goods
to Mexico increased by 22 percent from 1993 to 1994. However,
U.S. IMPORTS from Mexico increased by an unprecedented 24
percent. For the first year of NAFTA, the overall trade surplus
in goods fell to $1.348 billion, a 19 percent decrease from 1993. </p>
<p>The shrinking trade surplus with Mexico in 1994 (the fourth
quarter saw a trade DEFICIT of $448 million) is a continuation of
a trend that began more than two years ago. The annual trade
surplus with Mexico appears to have peaked in 1992 at $5.4
billion, declining to only $1.7 billion in 1993 and then to $1.3
billion in 1994. </p>
<p>The economic slowdown in Mexico, in combination with a 50
percent devaluation of the peso, will make it more difficult to
export goods to Mexico in 1995 while leading to increased imports
from Mexico. This means that the U.S. bilateral trade balance
with Mexico will move to a substantial DEFICIT position in 1995. </p>
<p>Another disturbing trend in U.S.-Mexico trade during the first
year of NAFTA involves the exchange of high value-added goods
associated with high-paying jobs. U.S. manufacturers were
supposed to clean up in Mexico. Instead, electronics, computer
products and telecommunication equipment came into the United
States from Mexico twice as fast as they&thorn;ve gone in the
other direction. </p>
<p>A fact often emphasized by the Clinton administration is that
the percentage of U.S. auto exports to Mexico increased
substantially in the first year of NAFTA. In fact, the United
States exported 39,000 new cars and trucks to Mexico in 1994
&thorn; as compared with 6,000 in 1993. But Mexico increased its
exports of new cars and trucks to the United States from 331,000
in 1993 to 400,000 in 1994, an increase almost double the total
number coming from the United States. Furthermore, economists
anticipate the peso devaluation means U.S. exports to Mexico will
revert to approximately 5,000 new cars and trucks in 1995, while
Mexican exports will continue to soar. </p>
<p>As the following tables show, some industries will gain and
some will lose as a result of NAFTA. The restructuring of the
U.S. economy due to increases in North American trade will cause
substantial job loss in the &quot;loser&quot; industries. </p>
<h3>U.S. Job Loss From NAFTA</h3>
<p>During the NAFTA debate in Congress, supporters claimed that
170,000 U.S. jobs would be created by 1995 as a result of the
trade agreement. The figure was determined by using the
calculation that every billion dollars of net exports creates
20,000 jobs. According to this methodology, the trade surplus
with Mexico must reach $8.5 billion by 1995 to produce the
170,000 jobs. It is clear that given the shrinking trade surplus
with Mexico ($1.3 billion in 1994), NAFTA will not produce the
number of jobs claimed by NAFTA supporters by 1995. </p>
<p>More recently, NAFTA supporters claim that increased exports
to Mexico have created more than 100,000 jobs in 1994. They
refuse to acknowledge, however, that increased IMPORTS from
Mexico are destroying U.S. jobs. </p>
<p>Underscoring this reality is the disturbing admission of
Julius Katz, former deputy U.S. Trade Representative, who told
the Wall St. Journal, &quot;the job numbers are totally phony
numbers.&quot; </p>
<h3>AFL-CIO projections</h3>
<p>NAFTA locks into legal status a low-risk environment for
investment and provides full access to the U.S. market with zero
tariffs. Throughout the debate over the ratification of NAFTA,
the AFL-CIO maintained that NAFTA would only accelerate the
movement of billions of dollars in direct foreign investment to
Mexico, and result in the loss of up to 550,000 U.S. jobs over 10
years. Unfortunately, the first-year data on job loss as a result
of NAFTA tend to support the long-term projections of the
AFL-CIO. </p>
<h3>Joint Economic Committee</h3>
<p>A 1994 staff analysis by the Joint Economic Committee of
Congress, 1994 U.S.-Mexico Trade Data: NAFTA Impacts, contradicts
the notion that NAFTA has resulted in substantial job creation. </p>
<p>The JEC report points out that while exports do create jobs,
jobs are also eliminated by increased imports. Further, a
significant portion of the growth in exports has occurred in
products that are imported into the United States and then re-
exported to Mexico &thorn;so-called transshipments of foreign
goods. A more accurate measure of the overall effect of
U.S-Mexico trade is net exports &thorn;domestically produced
exports minus imports used for consumption. U.S. net exports to
Mexico declined by approximately $500 million over the first nine
months of NAFTA. </p>
<p>In fact, the JEC report suggests that the U.S. economy may
have lost up to 10,000 jobs from January to September as a result
of the decline in U.S. net exports to Mexico. The JEC job loss
estimate would be substantially increased with a year- end study
because of the $448 million trade deficit with Mexico in the
fourth quarter of 1994. </p>
<h3>NAFTA Transitional Adjustment Assistance</h3>
<p>Estimates of the employment impact of NAFTA can vary
considerably depending on methodology and assumptions. Some
numbers, however, cannot be disputed. </p>
<p>As of Jan. 3, 1995, the U.S. Department of Labor had received
321 petitions involving 34,799 dislocated workers who believed
that NAFTA had caused their unemployment. Of that first-year
total, DOL has certified 152 petitions covering 17,320 workers as
experiencing NAFTA-related unemployment. </p>
<h3>New Projections Following the Peso Crisis</h3>
<p>David Wyss, research director at DRI/McGraw Hill, told members
of the Senate Budget Committee Jan. 26, 1995, that Mexico&thorn;s
financial woes could shave U.S. economic growth by 0.4 of a
percentage point and cost 350,000 American jobs. If
Mexico&thorn;s troubles continue to spread in Latin America,
those estimates could double, he told lawmakers. According to
Wyss, reduced exports to Mexico increase the likelihood that the
U.S. economic slowdown could become a full-fledged recession. </p>
<p>The WEFA Group projects a severe recession in Mexico during
1995. Inflation will soar to about 23 percent and manufacturing
wages will rise by only 12 percent, resulting in a sharp cut in
real wages and, as a consequence, more than a 4 percent drop in
real consumer spending. Investment will decline by nearly 8
percent because of higher interest rates, a shortage of financial
capital and declining demand. WEFA expects total output in Mexico
to decline by nearly 3 percent, severely affecting U.S. exports
to Mexico. WEFA forecasts that U.S. exports to Mexico would be
cut by 50 percent and result in a loss of $24.7 billion in real
U.S. gross domestic product. The impact on U.S. employment will
be severe. </p>
<p>John Sharp, Texas State Comptroller, estimated that the fiscal
crisis in Mexico stemming from the devaluation of the peso will
shave as much as 0.5 of a percentage point off the state&thorn;s
overall growth rate of 3.2 percent for 1995. Jobs in the
manufacturing sector in Texas may decline by as much as 0.6
percent this year, he said. &quot;Because our state economy is
increasingly intertwined with Mexico&thorn;s, what happens to our
southern neighbor matters a great deal to us,&quot; Sharp said. </p>
<p>According to economists at the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas,
the peso crisis could cost about 1 percent of total employment in
Texas over the next three years and choke exports in certain
industries. Texas industries that will be hardest hit by the
devaluation include furniture and fixtures, transportation
equipment, and electronics and electric equipment, according to
the Dallas Fed. Two-thirds of Texas&thorn;s total export sales of
furniture and fixtures now go to Mexico. </p>
<h3>Foreign Investment in NAFTA Countries</h3>
<h4>Investment in Mexico Soars</h4>
<p>The AFL-CIO has always maintained that NAFTA is as much about
foreign investment in Mexico as it is about trade liberalization.
NAFTA locks into legal status a low-risk environment for
investment and adds incentives to expand the Mexican export
platform to the United States, providing full access to the U.S.
market by eliminating tariffs on goods to this country. Available
data on investment in Mexico following the implementation of
NAFTA more than vindicate the AFL-CIO warnings. </p>
<p>Given time to analyze the agreement, economists from other
countries have subsequently come to the same conclusion.
&quot;NAFTA is a foreign sourcing and
competitiveness-strengthening strategy deployed by U.S.
multinational companies to take advantage of Mexico&thorn;s low
costs,&quot; claims Professor Satoru Nakamoto, Osaka City
University. &quot;With the added clarity and security that
[investment] provisions provide to foreign investors in North
America and the drastic reductions of Mexico&thorn;s tariffs on
regionally originating goods, transnational corporations will be
encouraged to rationalize the organization of their
North-American operations and to increase substantially foreign
direct investment in Mexico,&quot; states Professor Alan Rugman,
University of Toronto. </p>
<h4>Portfolio Investment</h4>
<p>Portfolio investment outlays for financial instruments such as
stocks, bonds and mutual funds of other countries &thorn; is more
short-term and more easily reversible. In 1993, portfolio
investment in Mexico increased by more than 400 percent over the
previous year, to $10.7 billion. Although the year-end numbers
are not yet available, portfolio investment in 1994, prior to the
peso devaluation, was running approximately 25 percent ahead of
1993. Portfolio investment will be more difficult to attract to
Mexico in light of the financial crisis and economic downturn.
The billions of dollars of &quot;hot money&quot; invested in
Mexico has now fled to opportunities that involve less
uncertainty than in Mexico. </p>
<h4>Foreign Direct Investment</h4>
<p>Foreign direct investment outlays for plants, equipment and
other tangible assets in other countries &thorn; has been on an
upward trend in Mexico since the mid- 1980s, the majority of
which came from the United States. This trend should continue for
the foreseeable future, especially since the devaluation of the
peso has effectively reduced the cost of purchasing such assets
in Mexico. </p>
<p>Direct foreign investment for 1994 totalled $8 billion, an
increase of 64 percent over the previous year. Of the $8 billion
total direct foreign investment, 40 percent was channeled into
manufacturing, 40 percent into services (including financial
services), 8.5 percent in transport and communications, 7.9
percent into commercial activities and 3.5 percent in
construction. </p>
<p>The United States led all foreign investors in Mexico with 50
percent of all direct investment. England followed with 14
percent, Japan 9 percent, The Netherlands 5 percent, Germany 5
percent and Canada only 2 percent. During the Salinas
administration, foreign investment in Mexico totalled more than
$50 billion. The United States led all foreign investors,
accounting for 63.2 percent of investment. </p>
<p>The most remarkable feature of the investment surge in Mexico
in 1994 was that it occurred in a period of great uncertainty in
Mexico. Political unrest in Chiapas, assassinations of key
political figures and kidnaping of prominent businessmen have
temporarily dampened enthusiasm for direct foreign investment in
Mexico. When the business climate stabilizes in Mexico, foreign
investment will far outstrip that of the first year of NAFTA. </p>
<p>Despite reports of rising unemployment, inflation and economic
gloom in Mexico, the export-only border assembly plants known as
maquiladoras appear to be emerging as big winners because of the
peso&thorn;s devaluation, the Washington Post reported Feb. 4,
1995. The 2,140 mostly American-owned maquiladora plants in
Mexico near the U.S. border already had had a banner year before
devaluation, now displacing tourism and petroleum as
Mexico&thorn;s official top generator of dollars. During the
first 10 months of 1994, maquiladora employment increased 6.2
percent to 600,376 employees, said Raul Avila, president of the
National Maquiladora Industry Council, which forecasts the
opening of another 600 assembly plants in 1995. An example of a
company that has moved production to Mexico is Woolrich, a
sportswear manufacturer based in Woolrich, Pa. Company officials
had promised to keep production in this country, but less than a
year after NAFTA went into effect, the temptation of Mexico
&thorn; where apparel workers earn on average $1 an hour &thorn;
apparently was too much to resist. The company laid off 450
workers in Pennsylvania and Colorado and hired Mexican
contractors. </p>
<p>Another company, Magnetek, which makes electronic equipment in
Huntington, Ind., and Owosso, Mich., moved 71 jobs to Matamoros,
Mexico, following the implementation of NAFTA, primarily because
of labor cost saving. Laid off U.S. workers who were asked to
train their replacements from Mexico found out that the same work
will now be done for one-tenth the cost to the employer. In the
past year, Magnetek dismissed older workers in two plants in
Mexico and replaced them with younger employees at half pay. </p>
<p>U.S.-based multinational companies from General Electric to
Nike still see vast opportunities emerging in Mexico. GE CEO Jack
Welch claimed in Business Week that he sees the future of his
company to be in Mexico. In 1994, GE&thorn;s Mexican plants
increased their sales about 18 percent, to more than $1 billion,
with about half of that total exported to the United States. GE
plans to invest even more in Mexico, especially to take advantage
of accelerated Mexican privatization in power generation,
transportation and finance. In fact, on Feb. 9, 1995, a
consortium led by GE was awarded the right to construct and lease
a 700-megawatt thermonuclear power plant in the state of
Chihuahua near El Paso, Texas. Nike is negotiating to make its
athletic shoes in Mexico for the Mexican, Latin American and U.S.
markets. Lower labor costs resulting from the peso&thorn;s plunge
are one attraction, Keith Peters, a Nike spokesman, told the New
York Times. &quot;Even if workers win some raises, companies
wanting to build Mexican plants to export still come out
ahead,&quot; the New York Times reported. &quot;Investment and
production costs have fallen while they can reap revenues in
dollars.&quot; </p>
<h4>Multinational Investment in Canada</h4>
<p>Since the implementation of NAFTA, a surge of investment is
linking corporations on both sides of the border as never before.
The change is driven in part by a cheap Canadian dollar, which
has plunged to just 70 cents, down from a high of 89 cents in
1989. In autos, for example, it has been reported by
Canada&thorn;s Motor Vehicle Association that it now costs 20 to
25 percent less to assemble a car in Canada than in the United
States. </p>
<p>Such savings have the Big Three automakers investing billions
of dollars in Canadian production facilities. Ford Motor Co. of
Canada has spent more than $700 million to revamp its plant in
Oakville, Ontario, to produce Windstar minivans. Ford also is
spending an additional $1.5 billion to upgrade its Ontario truck
and engine plants. Because of similar investments, Chrysler
Canada Ltd. last year produced approximately half of the minivans
and most of the popular LH models. </p>
<p>The advantages of producing in Canada and exporting to the
United States have not been lost on other foreign auto
manufacturers. Toyota is spending $427 million to more than
double the capacity of its Corolla assembly line near Cambridge,
Ontario, to 200,000 cars a year. All the extra cars will be
exported to the United States. </p>
<p>Much of the large trade imbalance with Canada consists of auto
trade. In 1994, Canada exported 2.1 million new cars and trucks
to the United States, while only 808,000 new cars and trucks went
in the other direction. </p>
<h4>Exchange Rates: Peso Meltdown</h4>
<p>One of the many deficiencies of NAFTA is that the agreement
specifically excludes exchange rate policies from coverage. The
peso became grossly overvalued in large part because it was
effectively pegged against the dollar even as Mexican rates of
inflation were much higher than rates of inflation in the United
States. Thus, while the real value of the peso declined relative
to the dollar, Mexican government policy did not allow this to be
reflected in the official exchange rate. The overvalued peso
contributed to a surge in imports to Mexico, by making them
artificially inexpensive, and contributed to a current account
deficit for Mexico in excess of $29 billion in 1994. In testimony
before Congress nine months prior to the implementation of NAFTA,
the AFL-CIO warned that, &quot;the recent history of Mexican
exchange rate policy, together with economic pressure, suggests
that devaluation is inevitable.&quot; </p>
<h4>Competitive Peso Devaluation</h4>
<p>Former President Carlos Salinas, who was competing to become
director of the World Trade Organization even before he left
office, maintained an overvalued peso because he figured that to
devalue the peso was to devalue his presidency. In an effort to
prop up the peso, Mexico&thorn;s foreign capital reserves, which
stood at $28 billion less than a year ago, were drawn down by the
Salinas administration to below $7 billion in order to buy pesos
to keep their value artificially high. According to MIT Professor
Rudi Dornbusch, &thorn;Salinas persevered with his strategy of
politics first, reality later, and the peso remained disastrously
overvalued.&quot; </p>
<p>In January 1994, at the start of NAFTA, the peso was trading
at 3.1 pesos to the dollar. The peso devaluation continued slowly
through the first three-quarters of 1994, by approximately 11
percent to 3.45 pesos to the dollar. In December 1994, the
administration of incoming President Zedillo finally initiated a
long-overdue devaluation of the peso. The situation quickly got
out of control and the peso could not be supported, forcing
Mexico to allow the peso to freely float in value relative to the
dollar. By mid-January in 1995, the value of the peso had fallen
to 5.7 pesos to the dollar, a drop of approximately 50 percent in
the first year of NAFTA. </p>
<p>The 1994 Mexican current account deficit of $31 billion was
made up of payments on foreign debt and an imbalance in trade in
goods and services, including $1.9 billion with the United
States. Current account deficits must be matched by capital
inflows, but Mexico was relying on short-term financial
instruments &thorn; stocks and mutual fund investments, and
government bonds &thorn; to finance the deficit. Even if Mexico
is able to cut the current account deficit by half, the
government still will need to attract more than $15 billion in
new capital annually. Part of the Zedillo rescue plan is designed
to keep that capital flowing in. </p>
<p>An important component of the Mexican financial crisis was the
capital flight by wealthy Mexicans &thorn; a move to quality,
lower-risk investment. In order to discourage further capital
flight, interest rates in Mexico have risen to more than 30
percent, thus reducing the chances for a quick economic recovery.
Most analysts foresee zero or negative economic growth, probably
in the range of -1.5 percent to -5 percent for 1995. </p>
<p>In order to shore-up confidence in the peso, the Clinton
administration initially pledged $9 billion out of a total $18
billion relief package. If the high-risk Zedillo restructuring
plan fails, &quot;the markets will blow right by the first $18
billion as if it were a rounding error,&quot; claimed a banker.
The administration then proposed an additional $40 billion in
loan guarantees to restore confidence in the Mexican financial
system. </p>
<p>When the Congress balked, the administration committed $20
billion from the U.S. Exchange Stabilization Fund as part of a
total international package of $53 billion in an attempt to
provide a credible aid package. In effect, the U.S. Treasury, the
International Monetary Fund, the Bank for International
Settlements of Switzerland, commercial banks, Latin American
countries and Canada are providing protection for speculative
investors who placed more than $75 billion in Mexico without due
regard for the risks involved. </p>
<p>To secure the U.S. loans, the Mexicans agreed to collateral
terms requiring importers of Mexican crude oil, oil products and
petrochemicals to remit payments to a special Mexican account at
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York. In the event of default,
the United States would hold the money there. </p>
<p>The terms of the U.S. rescue match those demanded by the
International Monetary Fund and will reinforce already tough
conditions. Among the main conditions: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Mexico must limit credit expansion to 10 billion pesos
        for all of 1995. </li>
    <li>Mexico must try to limit money growth to less than the
        rate of inflation. </li>
    <li>Mexico must maintain &quot;substantially positive&quot;
        real interest rates. </li>
    <li>Mexico should raise $12 billion to $14 billion through
        privatizations and concession operations over the next
        three years. </li>
    <li>Mexico must increase the transparency of central bank and
        government actions by publishing timely financial
        statistics. </li>
    <li>Economic Fundamentals Are Not Good </li>
</ul>
<p>Despite the reassuring rhetoric of the Clinton administration,
substantial risk exists that some of the loans to Mexico will
fail. If oil imports from Mexico are insufficient, U.S. taxpayers
will be forced to pick up the tab for Mexico should that
government not be able to fulfill its financial obligations. The
freely floating peso will be stabilized only to the extent that
capital flows can be attracted back to Mexico, and the current
account deficit reduced. </p>
<p>The notion that the peso &quot;meltdown&quot; is just a blip
on the radar screen is evidence of the type of wishful thinking
that led to the crisis in the first place. This is akin to the
captain of the Titanic announcing, &quot;it&thorn;s OK,
we&thorn;re only stopping for ice.&quot; For the administration
to repeat the unfounded assertion that &quot;fundamentals in
Mexico are good&quot; is a prescription for further disaster.
Fundamentals in Mexico are NOT good. As Dornbusch states,
&quot;the myth of the superperforming Mexican economy was kept
alive.&quot; When evaluated against real measures of sustainable
development &thorn; jobs creation, real wage increases and more
equal income distribution -the Salinas reforms were a dismal
failure. Job growth was not adequate to meet the needs of the one
million people who enter the work force each year and growing
income inequality makes Mexican society increasingly unstable. </p>
<p>According to data from Mexican income-expenditure surveys, the
number of workers per family in Mexico rose from 1.49 in 1977 to
1.63 in 1992, during a period in which the number of people in
poverty continued to rise. Income inequality actually worsened
during the supposed &quot;economic miracle&quot; of the Salinas
administration. Between 1989 and 1992, the mean income of
families within the lowest income group fell by 7 percent, while
the incomes of families at the top of the income pyramid grew by
11 percent. The top 10 percent of Mexicans earn as much as the
bottom 70 percent. The poverty rate in Mexico is approximately 40
percent and the unemployment rate in excess of 20 percent.
Two-thirds of Mexican workers are either unemployed or make less
than $10 a day, when the cost of basic subsistence for a typical
family of 5 is now approximately $16 a day. </p>
<p>By 1992, the richest 20 percent of the population received
54.2 percent of national income, while the poorest 20 percent
received only 4.3 percent. The extreme concentration of wealth in
Mexico is perhaps best illustrated by looking at its wealthiest
person, Carlos Slim Helu, owner of Telefonos de Mexico &thorn;
identified by Forbes to be worth $6.6 billion. Slim&thorn;s net
worth is more than the annual income of the poorest 17 million
combined. Forbes also claims that Slim is one of 30 billionaires
in Mexico &thorn; a number exceeded by only the United States,
Japan and Germany. </p>
<p>For the majority of Mexican workers, the only relevant
indicator of changes in the standard of living is wages in pesos
after adjusting for inflation. The Bureau of Labor Statistics
publishes annual international comparisons of hourly compensation
costs &thorn; wages and fringe benefits &thorn; converted into
real (inflation-adjusted) pesos by using the Mexican consumer
price indices from the IMF &quot;International Financial
Statistics.&quot; </p>
<p>The results of converting Mexican hourly compensation into
real 1988 pesos show that real compensation fell 43 percent
between 1980 and 1988. Although real compensation for Mexican
workers has improved somewhat since 1988, by 1993, real
compensation remained 30 percent lower than it was in 1980.
Harley Shaiken, a professor at the University of California at
Berkeley, has shown that between 1980 and 1994, when real
compensation was falling in Mexico, manufacturing worker
productivity rose by 64 percent. </p>
<h3>Effects of Devaluation</h3>
<h4>Change in the Balance of Trade with Mexico</h4>
<p>As a consequence of the peso devaluation, the price of
U.S.-made products purchased with pesos will rise, slowing down
U.S. exports to Mexico and, thus, eliminating thousands of jobs
in U.S. export industries. At the same time, since goods made in
Mexico are now cheaper in dollars, imports from Mexico will
increase, and the balance of trade with Mexico will turn to a
trade deficit. When added to the large and growing U.S. trade
deficit with Canada (caused in part by a devaluation of the
Canadian dollar to a nine-year low), the Mexican trade deficit
will only add to this country&thorn;s enormous overall trade
imbalance. </p>
<p>A crucial element of the Zedillo recovery plan is to cut the
current account deficit in half by both increasing exports to the
United States and by drastically reducing imports from the United
States. This means that U.S. exporters to Mexico should
anticipate increased use of informal barriers to trade to limit
imports from the United States. Along with the peso devaluation,
these measures mean that the U.S. trade balance with Mexico will
go into a substantial deficit position for the foreseeable
future. But Mexico&thorn;s attempt to export its way to economic
recovery will be made all the more difficult because the peso
devaluation has made the importation of capital equipment to
modernize Mexican factories much more expensive. Lacking access
to U.S. capital markets, Mexican firms will be forced to enter
into joint ventures with U.S. firms if they wish to modernize in
order to export. </p>
<h4>Production Costs in Mexico Lowered</h4>
<p>The peso devaluation reduces the cost of producing in Mexico
relative to producing in the United States. Purchases of land,
manufacturing plants and equipment that are denominated in pesos
are now cheaper. The key factor of labor costs has decreased
relative to labor costs in the United States. At the new exchange
rate, the Mexican real hourly compensation for production workers
in manufacturing would be only about one-twelfth of that of the
United States. &quot;This devaluation gives us a competitive
edge,&quot; says Carlos Slim Helu, whose Grupo Carso conglomerate
exports everything from copper tubing to auto parts. For
maquiladora employers, the $80 average weekly compensation to a
Mexican worker would be reduced to $50. The decrease in overall
costs of producing in Mexico will provide added incentive for
U.S. multinational corporations to relocate their manufacturing
operations south of the border. It also is possible that Mexico
will provide incentives in addition to cheaper currency to
attract more factories. </p>
<p>To Chrysler and others, the devaluation could make Mexico a
much more attractive place to manufacture &thorn; as long as the
cost of local inputs such as labor outweigh the price of imported
components. Lower labor costs will &quot;flow right through to
the bottom line,&quot; says Chrysler President Robert A. Lutz.
&thorn; Business Week, Jan. 16, 1995 </p>
<h4>Dislocated Workers</h4>
<p>For U.S. workers, especially in manufacturing industries,
devaluation can only mean the loss of more jobs. Following the
crisis of 1982, the dramatic devaluations of the peso contributed
directly to the surge in foreign investment in Mexico that
resulted in the maquiladora program. This &quot;free trade&quot;
zone along the Mexican side of the border now consists of
approximately 2,140 factories employing 600,000 workers whose
jobs should have been in the United States. Combining &quot;free
trade&quot; agreements and currency realignment will produce a
double-whammy for workers in the United States. </p>
<p>For the U.S. worker whose job moves to Mexico, it is unlikely
that he or she will find employment opportunities that pay wages
and benefits anywhere near the level paid by the job lost.
Manufacturing workers who lose their jobs to Mexico, especially
those with years of seniority, inevitably will encounter severe
economic hardship and a reduction in the standard of living for
their families. </p>
<p>Zenith Corp., one of the most prominent members of the
pro-NAFTA, corporate lobbying group, USA*NAFTA, has been one of
the largest exporters of jobs to Mexico over the past decade. On
Feb. 24, 1995, Zenith closed forever the doors of a television
plant in Springfield, Mo., that once employed more than 4,000
workers. It was a sorry ending to years of uncertainty and deceit
endured by workers, who in 1987 agreed to a 8.2 percent wage cut
and a five-year contract extension with the understanding that
they might otherwise lose their jobs to Mexico. In a 1991 letter
to employees announcing a &quot;consolidation&quot; of operations
that resulted in a 75 percent reduction in the workforce, Zenith
still maintained that &quot;there is a future in
Springfield.&quot; &quot;The story going round the plant was, if
you didn&thorn;t give them wage concessions, they were going to
move to Mexico,&quot; said Lionel Hudspeth, a line inspector and
relief operator until his 25-year career at Zenith ended in May
1992. </p>
<p>Michael Yeubanks, business manager of Electrical Workers Local
1453, noted that although unemployment is low in the region,
workers who find new jobs can expect entry-level wages and a
sharp reduction in benefits. &quot;They all have to start at the
bottom again,&quot; he said. Some of the last workers at the
Springfield plant, about 430 cabinet molders, were certified by
the Department of Labor in November as eligible for trade
adjustment assistance as a result of a shift of production to
Mexico. </p>
<p>Sportswear manufacturer, Woolrich, is another company that
moved production to Mexico in 1994. Fairy Jean Breining, a
laid-off veteran of 24 years, qualifies for a government
retraining program. But she is 59 and claims, &quot;I don&thorn;t
see any point in signing up for retraining, since no one&thorn;s
going to hire a woman my wage anyway.&quot; </p>
<h4>Wage Effect</h4>
<p>Another major effect of the peso devaluation &thorn; one that
will impact on the majority of U.S. workers &thorn; is the
additional downward pressure on U.S. wages as a result of the
reduced wages in Mexico. As a result of NAFTA, U.S. manufacturing
workers are now integrated in a North American work force that
includes workers in Mexico whose average hourly compensation in
manufacturing has been reduced to approximately $1.80 (only $1.15
in the U.S.-dominated maquiladoras) following the peso
devaluation. The average hourly compensation in U.S.
manufacturing in 1993 was $16.79. The relative cheapening of
Mexican labor through the peso devaluation will put added
downward pressure on real wages in United States. </p>
<p>An employer&thorn;s threat to move to Mexico must be taken
seriously by workers during collective bargaining. A prime
example of the downward pressure on wages can be seen in the
contract settlement at Leviton, a Warwick, R.I., manufacturer of
electrical outlets. To avoid losing their jobs to Mexico, IBEW
members voted to accept a laundry list of concessions in a
contract that was settled in August 1994. Mindful that Leviton
already has two Mexican factories, in Tijuana and Tecate, the
workers voted to extend their contract for two years, accept a
wage freeze and work 12-hour shifts at straight time. An employee
accompanied by his child said, &quot;you have no choice if you
have kids; they have to eat.&quot; </p>
<h4>Mexican Workers</h4>
<p>The devalued peso will increase the price of U.S.-made
products beyond the reach of millions of Mexican consumers.
Simple subsistence will be hard for Mexican workers, who clearly
will bear the brunt of the crisis. The &quot;economic emergency
plan&quot; implemented in January failed to restrain inflation or
halt Mexico&thorn;s currency collapse. The new plan of economic
austerity announced March 9, 1995, sets a target inflation rate
of 42 percent and allows labor unions to freely negotiate wage
contracts individually with each employer. This arrangement will
result in substantial reductions in real wages for Mexican
workers. Once again, following 10 long years of austerity,
Mexican workers are being forced to bear the burden of failed
economic programs. </p>
<p>&quot;Business is grinding to a halt as expectations of a
severe recession begin to bite,&quot; Business Week reported Feb.
27, 1995. &quot;Construction is dead. New-truck sales plunged by
86 percent in January, and bus sales fell by 66 percent.
Mercedes-Benz shut its two plants for three weeks in January, and
Grupo Dina plans to shut down truck production for 60 days.&quot;
The magazine quoted Sergio Raimond-Kedihas, dean of
Mexico&thorn;s leading business school, as saying, &quot;We are
on the verge of seeing the economy explode into pieces.&quot; </p>
<p>A Mexican government official admitted, &quot;we are in
trouble,&quot; the Washington Post reported Feb. 28. Since the
devaluation, inflation has skyrocketed to an annualized rate
exceeding 60 percent while the nation&thorn;s biggest industrial
association reported a loss of 250,000 jobs in less than two
months. </p>
<h4>Maquiladora Windfall</h4>
<p>Because of the devalued peso, U.S. employers in the Mexican
maquilas will realize an annual windfall of more than $750
million, while their employees, whose earnings are far below
those of other Mexican production workers, endure even more
hardship. At the very least, these U.S. companies should reject
this windfall and return it to the poorest of Mexican workers by
increasing their wages to compensate for their decline in real
wages. </p>
<p>The question of currency devaluation must be examined in light
of both political and economic factors. NAFTA represents a
never-before tried, high-risk experiment in which two countries
at far different stages of economic development and democratic
rights are attempting to merge their economies. The danger in a
&quot;competitive&quot; peso devaluation lies in the inherent
downward pressure on wages for workers in both countries and
additional incentives for U.S. companies to relocate to Mexico.
The combination of peso devaluation and NAFTA will be detrimental
to the interests of workers on both sides of the border. </p>
<h3>NAFTA Transitional Adjustment Assistance Program</h3>
<h4>Background</h4>
<p>The NAFTA-TAA Bridge Program was set up to provide training,
reemployment services and income support for workers dislocated
because of open trade with Mexico and Canada. The process for
establishing eligibility and delivering assistance involves close
working partnership between the Department of Labor and state
governors&thorn; offices. </p>
<p>A petition first is filed with the governor&thorn;s office,
which makes preliminary findings and transmits the findings to
DOL within 10 days. DOL makes the final determination on
certification within 30 days of receipt of the governor&thorn;s
findings. </p>
<p>NAFTA-TAA covers workers directly affected by trade with
Canada and Mexico, as well as workers at companies indirectly
affected, such as suppliers and assemblers for directly affected
firms. </p>
<p>If DOL certifies the petition, workers are entitled to
employment services; training for a new occupation; income
support for up to 52 weeks after unemployment insurance is
exhausted, if the worker is enrolled in training; and job search
and relocation allowances. Unlike regular TAA, waivers of the
training requirement are NOT allowed under <strong>NAFTA-TAA.</strong> </p>
<h4>Petition Activity</h4>
<p>The Labor Department as of Jan. 3, 1995, had made decisions on
297 of 321 petitions it had received covering 34,799 laid-off
workers. It had certified 152 for assistance and denied 145. The
152 certifications covered 17,320 workers. </p>
<p>Of the 152 certifications, 99 were from companies employing
11,589 workers who lost their jobs because of trade with Mexico.
Out of the Mexico total, 75 firms covering 8,261 workers received
certification because of a shift of production. Another 24 firms
covering 3,328 workers were certified because they were adversely
affected (lost their jobs) by imports. </p>
<p>A total of 47 firms involving 4,505 workers were certified
because of trade with Canada. Of the Canadian total, 22 firms
covering 2,457 workers were certified because of a shift of
production. The remaining 25 firms covering 2,048 workers were
adversely affected by imports. </p>
<p>Seventy-two of the 145 denials were attributed to the fact
that there was no shift in production or that company imports
were insignificant. The reason cited for denials in 25 cases was
that workers did not produce a particular good, while in 20 cases
the reason for denial was that production was transferred
domestically. During the first year of operation, the DOL
received petitions covering workers in 41 states. Pennsylvania
had the most petitions filed (39), followed by New York (31),
Washington (30), Texas (24), California (17), Tennessee (15),
Georgia (14) and New Jersey (12). </p>
<p>Since more than half the petitions originated in just seven
states, there is reason to believe there are serious problems
with information and outreach. In some states, petition forms are
not on hand in Employment Service offices despite the clear and
legal requirement that they be available; posters describing the
program are not on the walls; state officials staffing the state
offices are not even aware that the NAFTA-TAA program exists. </p>
<p>There are other reasons to believe that the number of
petitions and certifications may be just the tip of the iceberg.
Meritorious petitions are being denied. Service workers such as
truck drivers and railroad workers are ineligible. The rigid
deadline for enrolling in training is preventing qualified
workers from receiving assistance. The design and structure of
the program for indirectly affected workers is needlessly
cumbersome. Because the program is so inadequate, several unions
have recommended that petitions be filed for regular TAA instead
of <strong>NAFTA-TAA.</strong> </p>
<h4>General Accounting Office Report</h4>
<p>In November 1994, the GAO issued a report on the first nine
months of operation of the NAFTA-TAA program. The GAO noted the
Department of Labor had addressed a number of shortcomings of the
program, including the time frame for determinations. </p>
<p>The report also pointed out that DOL had broadened the
NAFTA-TAA program&thorn;s eligibility requirements to include
secondary workers (those who are indirectly affected), had
provided limited guidance to go along with a slow and cumbersome
funding mechanism that may make it difficult for workers to gain
benefits. In addition, since NAFTA-TAA eliminates waivers and
requires workers to enroll in training, these restrictions have
resulted in some workers receiving incomplete assessments and
remedial assistance, and a limited mix of services. </p>
<p>Finally, in implementing NAFTA-TAA, DOL did not address other
shortcomings, such as the lack of ongoing support, follow-up and
performance monitoring. While DOL has encouraged closer
coordination between federal dislocated worker programs, it has
not formally required states to track participants. </p>
<h4>A Worker's Guide to the NAFTA TAA Program</h4>
<p>A worker who has lost his or her job since NAFTA began or
anticipates job dislocation and is in need of detailed
information on the procedures of the NAFTA- specific Transitional
Adjustment Program should request the Workers Guide to the NAFTA
TAA Program from the AFL-CIO Human Resources Development
Institute, 815 16th St. N.W., Washington, D.C. 20006. Phone
202/638-3912. </p>
<h4>Labor Supplemental Agreement</h4>
<p>The North American Agreement on Labor Cooperation (NAALC),
signed as part of the NAFTA, establishes a number of structures
to monitor labor issues in North America, as well as to address
complaints about the non-enforcement of labor law in any of the
three NAFTA countries. These structures, which have been formed
very slowly, do not have any enforcement powers or mechanisms. </p>
<p>The agreement establishes a commission for labor cooperation
that consists of a Ministerial Council to meet at least once a
year and a Secretariat to assist and provide technical support to
the council. The Secretariat, recently established and located in
Dallas, is by agreement directed by a Canadian national who will
appoint a staff of 15. </p>
<p>John S. McKennirey, who was Canada&thorn;s lead negotiator for
the labor side agreement and director general of staff relations
and compensation at Canada&thorn;s Department of National
Revenue, recently was named the executive director of the
Secretariat for a three-year term. McKennirey is expected to have
the Secretariat up and running by mid-April. Among other things,
the Secretariat will prepare background reports on labor law,
labor market conditions and training issues of the three
countries, and undertake studies on a wide range of labor issues. </p>
<p>The agreement also calls upon each country to establish a
National Administrative Office (NAO) to serve as a contact point
for the other countries, to receive submissions from the public
on labor law matters and to coordinate tri- national labor
cooperative activities. The U.S. NAO, housed in the Department of
Labor and directed by Irasema T. Garza, can be phoned at
202/501-6653 and FAXed at 202/501-6615. </p>
<h4>Honeywell and GE</h4>
<p>The NAO in 1994 accepted complaints from the Teamsters on
labor law violations at a Honeywell plant in Chihuahua, and the
unaffiliated United Electrical Workers on violations at a GE
facility in Juarez. Public hearings on these submissions took
place in Washington, D.C., on Sept. 12, 1994. </p>
<p>The NAO issued a Public Report of Review on the submissions on
Oct. 12, 1994, concluding that the information gathered on the
two submissions did not establish that the Government of Mexico
failed to promote compliance with or enforce the specific laws
involved. Accordingly, the NAO did not recommend ministerial
consultations on the matters presented in these two submissions
and essentially threw out the two complaints over the firing of
maquila workers for union organizing efforts. </p>
<p>However, the NAO did acknowledge the strong concerns raised by
these submissions, the vital importance of the freedom of
association and the right to organize, and the implications for
workers of the failure of governments to protect such rights. </p>
<h4>Sony</h4>
<p>A complaint filed with the NAO by the International Labor
Rights Education and Research Fund, the National Association of
Democratic Lawyers, the Coalition for Justice in the Maquiladoras
and the American Friends Service Committee charged that a
subsidiary of Sony Corporation stifled union organizing in its
plants in Nuevo Laredo. &quot;What happened to us was very
unfair,&quot; said Rosa Huerta, one of about a dozen workers from
Sony&thorn;s Magnetico de Mexico plants testifying at the NAO
hearing in San Antonio, Feb. 14, 1995. </p>
<p>The workers testified they were prevented from meeting to
discuss union leadership, given less than a day&thorn;s notice
about a union election, were confronted by police during a
peaceful demonstration and, in some cases, fired after attempts
to organize. One worker said she was stripped of her union post
and ultimately forced to resign &thorn; she was told that if she
wouldn&thorn;t accept the resignation request and severance pay
(giving up her legal rights against the company), she would be
blacklisted by other maquiladora plants. </p>
<p>Another worker said a protest staged predominantly by female
workers was met with force. &quot;Without warning, the police
started to strike us with their sticks,&quot; she said, and one
woman was hospitalized. Sony did not register to speak at the
hearing, relying on private communique with the NAO. The NAO will
report its findings by April 11, 1995. </p>
<h4>Sprint</h4>
<p>A new twist to the NAFTA labor side agreement was added in
February 1995, when a Mexican trade union filed a complaint
against a U.S. corporation for violating the rights of U.S.
workers. The Union of Telephone Workers of the Republic of Mexico
has asked the Mexican NAO to investigate Sprint Corp. for closing
a San Francisco subsidiary targeted by a union campaign. </p>
<p>Francisco Hernandez Juarez, the Mexican union&thorn;s general
secretary, in his complaint, said that Sprint&thorn;s mass firing
of 235 Latino telemarketers in July 1994 occurred one week before
a representation vote by the Communications Workers. He asked the
Mexican NAO to declare that Sprint cannot establish itself in
Mexico until it reinstates the fired U.S. workers and agrees to
recognize workers in both countries when a majority of workers
vote to unionize. </p>
<p>Ed Potter, international labor council for the U.S. Council on
International Business, said the ability of Mexican and American
unions to use NAFTA procedures to &quot;create a public
spotlight&quot; is troubling to many executives. &quot;This
generally makes business pretty mad,&quot; he said. That is a
good summation of business cooperation under the NAFTA side
agreements. </p>
<p>The NAO also oversees a tri-national program on labor
cooperation. The AFL- CIO and its affiliated unions participated
in seminars on occupational health and safety in the electronics,
construction and petrochemical industries during 1994. </p>
<p>Prepared by the Task Force on Trade, AFL-CIO contact Greg
Woodhead, 202-637-5181</p>
