<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>Answers To Common Questions About Union Summer 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Answers To Common Questions<br>
About Union Summer 1996</h1>
<ul>
<li><h2>What is Union Summer? </h2>
<p>Union Summer is a program of the AFL-CIO (American Federation of Labor and Congress 
of Industrial Organizations) designed to bring hundreds of young workers and college 
students into the streets and neighborhoods this summer to work on union organizing 
campaigns and political initiatives. Union Summer participants will intern for a three-week 
period. </p>
</li>
<li><h2>Why is Union Summer happening now? </h2>
<p>Our country is facing a serious crisis. The disparity between the rich and poor has hit 
Depression-era levels. For the first time, a generation of Americans is looking at having a 
lower standard of living than their parents had. In light of this trend, there is an increasing 
consensus across the United States that only a massive, activist, and visionary social 
movement for working people's rights will turn this country around. Historically, young 
people have played a pivotal role in sparking social change. The time has come to light that 
spark once again. </p>
</li>
<li><h2>What kind of qualifications do I need to participate in 
Union Summer? </h2>
<p>You need to be an energetic, passionate, people-oriented individual. You need to have a 
commitment to social justice. You do not need fancy qualifications. You do not need a 
college degree. And while it would certainly be a plus, no previous union experience is 
necessary. </p>
</li>
<li><h2>What am I going to be doing? </h2>
<p>The bulk of what you do will center around helping workers in their fight for workplace 
justice. You may be visiting workers at home to find out what they would like to change at 
their jobs. You may be organizing picket lines or participating in direct actions, such as 
marches and demonstrations.<br>
You may be rallying community support or helping a boycott campaign. You may be 
educating and registering voters around living wage campaigns. Whatever you do will help 
workers in their fight for workplace justice. </p>
</li>
<li><h2>Where is Union Summer going to take place? </h2>
</li>
<li>There will be multiple Union Summer sites around the country: the Deep South, California, 
the Midwest, and New England are some of the likely candidates. At this point, we cannot 
announce the specific locations because the targeted industries and corporations will use this 
advance notice to increase the level of harassment and intimidation of their employees. &#160;</li>
<li>&#160;</li>
<li><h2>Will I get paid? </h2>
</li>
<li>Union Summer is not a job. It is an educational internship designed to teach organizing skills 
and give participants a chance to practice those skills, to see people power in action - to 
help make history. That said, we realize that everyone has basic needs that must be met. 
Union Summer activists will receive free housing and a stipend of $210 per week to help 
defray other costs. </li>
<li>The AFL-CIO is strongly encouraging international unions, local unions, and central labor 
bodies to make it easier for their members or members' sons and daughters to participate by 
(1) paying for their transportation to and from the Union Summer site; and (2) reimbursing 
them for the difference between their regular wage and the Union Summer stipend. </li>
<li><h2>Can I choose where I go, and how will I get there? </h2>
<p>Union Summer staff will place people based on many factors, including location and the 
needs of particular campaigns. Many Union Summer activists will be assigned to the site 
nearest them. You can put in a request for a particular placement. However, there is no 
guarantee that you will get it. </p>
<p>Transportation to and from the campaign will be your responsibility. There is a lot of room 
for creativity. Some people are already talking about organizing caravans to their sites! </p>
</li>
<li><h2>How do I apply for Union Summer? </h2>
<blockquote>
<p>Union Summer<br>
1101 14th Street, NW, Suite 320<br>
Washington, DC 20005<br>
<br>
Fax: (202) 408-0303 </p>
</blockquote>
<p>To request an application or information, call (800) 952-2550 or (202) 408-0300. </p>
<p align=center><a href="home.html">Union Summer Home</a> | <a href="program.html">Program</a><br>
<a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> </p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
