<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Questions and Answers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="center"><img src="images/orglogot.gif" align="bottom"
width="496" height="134"> </p>
<h2 align="center">Answers to Common Questions about the AFL-CIO
Organizing Institute</h2>
<dl>
    <dd><font size="4">What is the Organizing Institute?</font></dd>
    <dd>The Organizing Institute was created in the fall of 1989
        to promote and foster union organizing. In November of
        that year, we held the first weekend training session for
        people interested in a career as union organizers. Since
        then, we have developed a highly selective program to
        recruit and train a new generation of union organizers,
        to place them for training on the campaigns of designated
        unions, and to facilitate job matches for graduates into
        full-time, paid positions as union organizers with
        International Unions affiliated with the AFL-CIO. In
        addition to this program, this Institute also has a
        variety of other programs designed to assist unions in
        the area of external organizing. </dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">What does a Union Organizer do? </font></dd>
    <dd>Union organizers assist workers in gaining union
        recognition at their worksite. Where workers do not
        currently have a union, a union organizer will work with
        employees to build support and leadership to form their
        own local union, usually in the face of intense employer
        opposition. The union must prove it represents a majority
        and get recognition from the employer. This often, but
        not exclusively, happens through a secret ballot election
        held at the workplace. Ultimately, the goal is to win a
        binding agreement between the workers and their employer
        that includes real improvements in the living and working
        conditions of the employees.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">What Unions are participation in the
        Organizing Institute training program?</font></dd>
    <dd>The following sixteen unions directly participate in the
        training program by providing intern and apprentice
        campaigns and hiring graduates: American Federation of
        State, County, and Municipal Employees (AFSCME),
        Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers Union (ACTWU),
        American Federation of Teachers (AFT), Communications
        Workers of America (CWA), Hotel Employees and Restaurant
        Employees (HERE), International Brotherhood of Teamsters
        (IBT), International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's
        Union (ILWU), International Ladies Garment Workers Union
        (ILGWU), Service Employees International Union (SEIU),
        United Auto Workers (UAW), United Brotherhood of
        Carpenters and Joiners (UBC), United Food and Commercial
        Workers (UFCW), United Mineworkers of America (UMWA), and
        United Steelworkers of America (USWA), Laborers
        International Union of North America (LIUNA), and Oil,
        Chemical, and Atomic Workers (OCAW).</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">I'm interested in applying to the program.
        What is involved in the application process? </font></dd>
    <dd>All interested candidates must complete and return,
        either by mail, fax, our application, as well as submit a
        resume. (You can download an application at this web
        site.) We attempt to process and review applications
        within two to three weeks after receiving them. After
        careful review of the application, qualified applicants
        are contacted for either a face-to-face or telephone
        interview. All applicants are notified by telephone or
        letter if they have been accepted or not. This is an
        extremely selective program -- union organizing is a
        challenging job and is not for everyone. We accept
        applications until the Friday before the 3-day training
        you are considering attending. To guarantee that your
        application will be reviewed, it is suggested that we
        receive your application before that preceding Friday.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">What do you look for in qualified
        applicants? </font></dd>
    <dd>We look for applicants possessing relevant skills and
        past experience. The best experience comes from having
        participated with a union in organizing campaigns.
        However, we do credit organizing experience in other
        fields, including union leadership, electoral
        campaigning, student government, issue organizing, or
        community service. Those applicants with no labor
        background should share the values and goals of the labor
        movement. We also judge applicants according to their
        communications skills, ability to motivate people,
        willingness to travel and/or relocate, and strategic
        thinking.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">How often are the three-day training
        weekends held? </font></dd>
    <dd>The 3-day trainings are held each month in various
        locations. They are held every other month in Washington,
        D.C. and regularly in San Francisco. Other sites where we
        have held trainings include Chicago, Los Angeles, San
        Francisco, New York, and Atlanta.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">What is the weekend session like? What are
        the costs? </font></dd>
    <dd>The 3-day training is an intense and fascinating look at
        what it takes to be a union organizer. The sessions
        themselves are lead by senior organizers from among the
        fourteen unions in the program. The talent and enthusiasm
        of the participants are a large part of the overall
        success of the weekend. Institute staff meet individually
        with participants on Sunday afternoon. The cost of the
        training, including housing and meals, are paid by the
        Organizing Institute. Travel to and from the training is
        the responsibility of the applicant.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">I won't be able to start the internship
        for several months. Should I wait and apply when I'm
        available to intern? </font></dd>
    <dd>We recommend you apply when you are investigating career
        options, even if that is six or eight months before you
        are available to begin the internship, and even if it is
        before you are sure that this is the career for you. In
        fact, the 3-day training provides an excellent
        opportunity to find out more about union organizing to
        assist you in deciding if you want to pursue this
        program. If I am selected to go on the internship, how
        soon does it start? The next available internship usually
        begins a week or two after the training. If you are
        unable to begin the internship at that time, you may
        postpone. Although we encourage people to begin the
        internship as soon as possible, some people elect to
        begin the field training weeks or even months after
        attending a 3-day session.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">What happens on the internship? </font></dd>
    <dd>The internship is usually 3 weeks long. We group together
        6 to 12 interns who have attended the 3-day training and
        assign them to an ongoing campaign with a participating
        union. The Institute and the Union assign staff to work
        with you on a daily basis. The intern's main
        responsibility is one on one communication with workers.
        This is done by visiting workers at home or at the
        workaday. The days are long; you're up early and often
        are in meetings until after 9pm. Some have called it
        &quot;boot camp&quot; or &quot;immersion training.&quot;
        You work 21 days in a row, with little time off.
        Internships tend to be on large, strategically important
        campaigns. Interns file weekly reports and supplement
        their field training with workshops and discussion
        groups.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">What happens on the apprenticeship? </font></dd>
    <dd>If you are selected to go on the apprenticeship after the
        internship ends, you will be assigned to a campaign with
        one of the participating unions. As an apprentice, you
        are given responsibility for all or a major part of a
        campaign. You will work directly for a senior organizer,
        assigned by the Union, who will be your &quot;teaching
        fellow&quot;. Sometimes that person is on site and
        sometimes they are available by phone. Although you will
        fill out weekly reports and keep in contact with
        Institute staff by phone, your primary training will come
        from this experienced organizer.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">How does the pay work on the
        apprenticeship? </font></dd>
    <dd>As an apprentice you are paid $400 per week on a biweekly
        basis by the Organizing Institute. You are covered for
        individual health insurance. The Institute is then
        reimbursed by the Union to whom you are assigned. The
        Union is responsible for housing and transportation and a
        meal allowance. The amount of that allowance is
        determined by the Union in accordance with their
        policies.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">How does job placement work? </font></dd>
    <dd>The Unions have told us that they are in need of talented
        and committed organizers to wage the battle for union
        recognition. Our track record on job matches for
        graduates bears out this claim. Over 95% of Institute
        graduates have been placed. The unions in the program are
        notified of all graduates. They then contact the
        apprentice to arrange interviews. You should notify the
        Institute if you have any preferences in selecting a
        position. This program works because it is directly
        linked to employment opportunities in union organizing.
        Unions and applicants alike are interested in the program
        because of the job match component.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">How much travel is involved? What is the
        pay? </font></dd>
    <dd>The jobs vary by union and by location within a union.
        However, most jobs require the organizer to be available
        to work on the road at times, and in some jobs the
        organizer will work away from home most of the time. Even
        when working from home, long days, including regular
        evening and weekend work, is standard. Most unions look
        for flexibility in travel and relocation. The pay ranges
        from $18,000 to $30,000 per year plus benefits.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dd><font size="4">I am interested in a job in the labor
        movement, but not organizing, can the Organizing
        Institute help me? </font></dd>
    <dd>We are a very single purpose organization. We are looking
        for people to do one particular job - Organize the
        Unorganized. That means that we rarely hear about and
        don't usually recommend people for other types of careers
        in the labor movement. If you are not sure if union
        organizing is for you, by all means apply and pursue this
        program as one option. </dd>
</dl>
<hr size="3" width="85%">
<h3 align="center">For more information, contact the OI office
at:</h3>
<p align="center"><font size="4">1101 Fourteenth St NW Suite 320,
Washington, DC 20005<br>
800-848-3021/202-408-0700</font></p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="/orginst/index.htm">Organizing Institute Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
