<html>
<head>
<title>Stand UP for Good Jobs</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">America Needs Good Jobs</h1>
<h3>The Current Situation</h3>
<p>During the past two years, the American economy has created
5,700,000 new jobs. This is especially welcome since only 2.2
million jobs were created in the entire four years of the Bush
Administration. </p>
<p>But much more remains to be done. </p>
<p>The unemployment rate is still 5.4 percent, which means that
officially 7.2 million workers are looking for jobs. But, in
addition, there are 1.7 million Americans who have become so
discouraged that they are no longer looking for work and
therefore are not included in the unemployment figure. And there
are 4.5 million additional workers who want full-time jobs but
cannot find them and therefore are working only part-time. In
total, then, 13.4 million workers are unemployed or
underemployed. </p>
<p>Most troubling of all, the United States continues to lose
many of our best jobs and replace them with low-wage, part-time
or temporary jobs. Fully 20% of all new jobs are temporary. More
workers today are employed by fast food restaurants than in the
steel and auto industries combined, and the largest single
employer in the U.S. is Manpower Inc., a temporary help agency,
which now employs almost twice as many people as General Motors. </p>
<h3>What Should Be Done</h3>
<p>We cannot hope to create enough good, middle-class jobs unless
the government does its part. The Clinton Administration has put
forward a modest program to increase investments in
transportation, communication, new technology and in our current
and future workers. Those investments can be paid for by ending
corporate welfare, closing tax loopholes and requiring
corporations to pay their fair share of taxes. The government
should stop giving tax breaks to companies that move jobs
overseas, and should protect our markets from unfair competition. </p>
<h3>The New Leadership's Agenda</h3>
<p>The new Congress has no program to help create good jobs.
Instead, they are proposing to slash and burn programs that are
vital to job creation. </p>
<h4>Look at what they are doing:</h4>
<p>The House of Representatives already has passed a bill that
cuts spending this year by more than $17 billion. These cuts will
have their most severe impact on low-income elderly households
and on poor children. But the cuts will also directly affect our
ability to provide good jobs to working families. Indeed, 25
percent of the cuts are made in job training and employment
programs and education programs. These cuts include the
elimination of 615,000 summer jobs for youth, almost 200,000
slots for job training, and more than 50,000 slots for dislocated
workers. </p>
<p>The House leaders are pushing tax cuts that benefit
corporations and families earning more than $200,000. To pay for
these, they plan to take billions more away from employment and
job training programs, education programs, and from
vitally-needed investments in transportation and new technology. </p>
<p>They plan $1.2 trillion in additional cuts that will destroy
the government's ability to create the conditions necessary for
developing good jobs. </p>
<p>Most Republicans and some Democrats want to make it even
easier to flood the American market with imports made in
sweatshops, in prison camps, and by child labor earning just a
few dollars a day. They believe that we should let other
countries sell their goods in the United States even if those
countries have an unfair advantage because they exploit their own
workers. </p>
<h3>What This Means To You</h3>
<p>If these proposals are not stopped now, jobs will be lost in
manufacturing, construction, transportation, communication, and
in public service. There will be fewer opportunities for workers
to upgrade skills and fewer opportunities for retraining if you
lose your job. And your kids will have a harder time getting the
education and skills they will need and finding a good job to
support their families. </p>
<p>That's why their agenda must be blocked.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="index.htm">America Needs a Raise Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
