http://aflcio.org:80/standup/suwages.html 204.127.237.106 19970215092602 text/html 6855
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 09:25:39 GMT
Last-modified: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 14:44:37 GMT
Content-length: 6668
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Stand UP for Good Wages</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">America Needs Good Wages</h1>
<h3>The Current Situation</h3>
<p>Working men and women are working harder and harder for less.
Since 1979, the average hourly pay for non-supervisory workers
has declined by 10 percent. For workers who never completed high
school, average pay dropped by more than 20 percent. </p>
<p>Younger workers face a particularly difficult time. For
workers without college degrees, entry-level wages are now $6.61
an hour and that provides 25 percent less buying power than in
1979. Even for college graduates, entry-level wages have
declined. As a result, the typical head of household under age 25
now earns just $16,000, a third less buying power than in 1979. </p>
<p>All this is happening while productivity is increasing and
profits are swelling. And all this is happening at the same time
that the incomes of the richest one percent of the population
have increased by 53 percent while incomes of most Americans have
fallen. </p>
<h3>What Should Be Done</h3>
<p>The federal government can play an important part in helping
to improve wages by increasing the floor established by the
minimum wage as President Clinton has proposed. The government
also can make sure that employers who replace full- time workers
with part-time, temporary or contract workers or who try to get
rid of their union workers not realize a competitive advantage. </p>
<h3>The New Leadership's Agenda</h3>
<p>The Republican leadership has no program to raise wages or to
reduce the increasing wage gap. They have even called for
elimination of the minimum wage. They believe in what they call a
&quot;free market&quot; in which workers compete with each other
for work so the jobs go to those willing to accept the least.
That means that those who are most desperate, and least
demanding, would set labor standards for all. In fact, this
program would drive down wages. </p>
<h4>Here is what they propose:</h4>
<p><b>Davis-Bacon</b> </p>
<p>The Republican leaders are pushing bills in both the House
(H.R. 500) and the Senate (S. 141) to repeal the Davis-Bacon Act.
That Act says that when construction is done for the federal
government, the construction workers are entitled to be paid the
usual wage paid in their community for that kind of work. The law
stabilizes wage standards in the community by denying any
competitive advantage to contractors who find or import cheap
labor. </p>
<p>If the Davis-Bacon Act were repealed, the federal government
could be forced to hire contractors who pay the cheapest wages,
and that would lower wages for everyone in the industry. In fact,
studies show that the average construction worker would lose
about $1,500 a year if the Davis- Bacon Act were repealed. </p>
<p><b>Service Contract Act</b> </p>
<p>The House Republicans are also pushing a bill (H.R. 246) to
repeal the Service Contract Act. That law requires contractors
who provide services to the federal government for example, firms
that run cafeterias in federal buildings or provide janitors or
guards for federal buildings to pay their employees the
prevailing wage for the kind of work the employees do. </p>
<p>Most of the 1,000,000 employees covered by this law don't earn
much money as it is, but repeal of the Service Contract Act would
push their wages down toward the minimum wage. </p>
<p><b>Minimum Wage</b> </p>
<p>Congress is fighting President Clintons proposal to increase
the minimum wage from $4.25 to $5.15 by 1997. Since 1979, the
real value of the minimum wage has fallen by more than 25 percent
because of increases in the cost of living. Today, 2.1 million
workers earn the minimum wage, and 4.4 million more earn less
than $5.15 and would get an increase if the minimum wage were
increased. At the current minimum wage level, these workers can't
earn enough to support their families. </p>
<p><b>Overtime Pay</b> </p>
<p>The new leaders in Congress want to do away with the 40-hour
workweek. Since 1935, workers who work more than 40 hours in a
week have been entitled to overtime pay. But most Republicans and
the Democrats who vote with them think that employers should be
allowed flexibility to require their employees to work more than
40 hours in one week and less in another without having to pay
overtime. </p>
<p>They also believe that it should be up to the employer to
decide whether to pay overtime or to give the employees
compensatory time off instead. And they want to expand the group
of employees who are denied any right to overtime or compensatory
time off no matter how long they work. </p>
<p><b>Social Security</b> </p>
<p>The House and Senate voted to allow Social Security trust
funds to be used to balance the budget rather than preserving
those funds to pay Social Security in the future.Republican
leaders also are planning to cut billions of dollars from
Medicare, which will leave seniors without adequate protection
and shift health care costs to private employers and employees. </p>
<p><b>Transportation Employees</b> </p>
<p>The new leaders in Congress are taking special aim at programs
that protect transportation workers. For more than 30 years,
transit employees have been assured that federal grants to
transit agencies will not be used to reduce the pay, benefits or
rights of transit employees. The extermists want to strip away
this protection. They also want to take from rail employees their
right to severance pay if they are laid off because a route is
terminated. </p>
<h3>What This Means To You</h3>
<p>If the new leaders in Congress are not stopped now, 60 years
of laws protecting workers will be discarded. Some of the
Republican proposals will hit hardest at workers in particular
industries construction, service and transportation although the
loss of income for these workers will hurt everyone in the
communities in which they live. </p>
<p>Other proposals, such as the plan to repeal the 40-hour work
week, will directly affect every working family. Workers will no
longer be able to count on regular schedules, and may be forced
to work excessive hours. Family lives will be disrupted as the
work schedules of parents change from week to week and as parents
are forced to work more and more overtime hours. </p>
<p>That's why their agenda must be blocked.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="index.htm">America Needs a Raise Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
