<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Stand UP for Worker Protections</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">America Needs Worker Protections</h1>
<h3>The Current Situation</h3>
<p>In 1970, President Nixon signed into law the Occupational
Safety and Health Act, which guarantees every American worker a
safe and healthful working environment. Since 1970, the number of
people killed on the job has been cut in half and injury rates
have fallen by almost 25 percent. But we still have a long way to
go. </p>
<p>Each year more than 55,000 workers are killed as a result of
occupational accidents or occupational diseases, another 60,000
workers are permanently disabled, and nearly 7 million workers
are injured on the job. Thats one workplace death or injury every
5 seconds. Additionally 25,000,000 workers each year are exposed
to toxic chemicals in their workplaces. </p>
<p>Workplace safety and health cannot be achieved without strong
safety and health standards which apply to all employers, so that
no employer can gain a competitive advantage by cutting corners
on workplace safety. Unfortunately, the procedures for setting
standards under the Occupational Safety and Health Act are so
complicated that it takes on average seven years to issue a new
safety or health standard. And the penalties for violating the
law are quite weak: the average fine for conditions posing a
substantial probability of death or serious harm is only $800. </p>
<h3>The New Leadership's Agenda</h3>
<p>The Republican leaders have no program to make workplaces
safer or healthier. They think the government is doing too much
already to protect the safety and health of workers. Their
ultimate aim is to gut the law. </p>
<h4>Specifically, here is what the new Congress is doing:</h4>
<p>Some Republican House members are working on what they call
&quot;reform&quot; of the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Their proposal would: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Relax the duty employers now have to provide a safe
        workplace. </li>
    <li>Make it more difficult for OSHA to issue new occupational
        safety and health standards by requiring the Agency to
        jump through a whole new set of procedural hoops. </li>
    <li>Deprive OSHA of the authority to issue standards tough
        enough to protect employee health. </li>
    <li>Take away the right of workers and their unions to get a
        workplace inspection in response to a complaint about
        serious hazards. </li>
    <li>Exempt large numbers of employers from inspections and
        reduce the already-weak penalties in the law, including
        reducing the maximum penalty to just $7,000. </li>
</ul>
<p>Not content to wait for the opportunity to &quot;reform&quot;
the law, some Republicans are using the budget process to weaken
enforcement of the Occupational Safety and Health Act. Today, we
spend little more than $1 per citizen on OSHA which pays for one
OSHA inspector per 4,000 workplaces. The House Republicans want
to cut that still more by 12 percent this year and still more
over the next five years. And they propose a 75 percent cut in
the budget for the National Institute of Occupational Safety and
Health which would essentially eliminate government research on
workplace health hazards. </p>
<p>The House also has passed a bill that would prevent any new
occupational safety or health standard from being issued or even
worked on in 1995. They have passed another bill which, in the
name of &quot;regulatory reform,&quot; would add 23 new steps to
the process required to issue new occupational safety and health
standards. Among other things, the Labor Department would have to
prove that the lives being saved are worth the cost to
businesses. These requirements are so complex and difficult that
the process of issuing new safety and health standards would
grind to a halt. </p>
<h3>What This Means To You</h3>
<p>If the new leaders in Congress are not stopped now, OSHA will
be gutted and workplaces will become more dangerous. The process
of issuing safety and health standards will be stopped cold
before the Labor Department can issue the urgently needed
ergonomics standard to attack the largest and fastest growing
cause of worker injury and to protect millions of workers facing
crippling injuries from repetitive motion and poor work design.
There will be fewer OSHA inspectors, weaker penalties, and less
research on the causes of occupational injuries and diseases.
Thousands more workers will be killed, injured, or develop
debilitating occupational diseases each and every year. </p>
<p>That's why their agenda must be blocked. </p>
<h3>What You Can Do</h3>
<p>Visit the <a href="http://www.standup.westlake.com/">Stand Up
Online Center</a>. </p>
<p>ORGANIZE a call-in to Congressional Representatives. Use the
AFL-CIO's toll-free number- 1-800- 97-AFL-CIO. Ask for your House
Representative. Tell them you oppose H.R. 1834 and demand that
they vote against it. </p>
<p>ORGANIZE a petition campaign to Congress in opposition to the
Republican assault on worker safety. Schedule a public event to
present the petition to your congressional representative.
Petitions are available from the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>GATHER your co-workers together and have everyone fill out
post cards to Congress opposing the assault on worker safety.
Post cards are available from the AFL-CIO. Encourage friends and
co- workers to write letters to Congress voicing their opinions. </p>
<p>DISTRIBUTE flyers and petitions at plant gates, union meetings
and other key places around your community. Explain that
Republicans in Congress want to take away worker safety and
health protections and action is needed now. Camera-ready flyers
are available from the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>HOLD a public meeting back home with Congressional
representatives. Bring injured workers and family members who can
talk first hand about the need for strong safety and health
protections. Invite local religious leaders and other allies to
participate in the meeting. Tips on setting up such meetings are
available from the AFL-CIO Legislative Department (202-637-5000). </p>
<p>WRITE a letter to the editor of your local paper. Sample
letters are available from the AFL-CIO. Talk to reporters you
know and encourage them to write a story on how the threat to job
safety protections puts workers in your community in danger. </p>
<p>CALL in to talk radio shows and discuss the threat to job
safety protections. Tell listeners about the threat in your
community and about how they can get involved. Talk with local
radio hosts about getting experts on to discuss job safety
matters. </p>
<p>PLACE an ad in your local newspaper to educate the public and
fellow workers and tell your Congressional representatives your
union opposes cuts in health and safety protections. Camera ready
ads are available from the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>WRITE a story on the Republican assault for your union
newspaper. Contact the AFL-CIO safety and health department for
additional background. </p>
<p>POST announcements and information about the Republican
assault on computer bulletin boards. </p>
<p>EDUCATE other union members and their families about the
Republican assault on worker safety. </p>
<p>MOBILIZE them in the campaign for safe jobs and encourage them
to do all of the above. </p>
<p align="center">For More Information: AFL-CIO Department of
Occupational Safety and Health 202-637-5210.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="index.htm">America Needs a Raise Page</a></p>
