http://aflcio.org:80/standup/suvoice.html 204.127.237.106 19970215092657 text/html 7201
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 09:26:30 GMT
Last-modified: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 14:44:37 GMT
Content-length: 7014
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Stand UP for a Real Voice on the Job</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">America Needs a Real Voice on the Job</h1>
<h3>The Current Situation</h3>
<p>Only about one in nine workers in private industry today has a
union. The other 89 percent have no democratic voice on the job. </p>
<p>The reason is that the law does not protect workers trying to
form a union. During organizing campaigns, one out of four
private employers fires employees for union activity. Even though
this is illegal, the typical employer gets away with it. Even if
they are caught, the average amount they are penalized is under
$3,000. </p>
<p>Employees who want to form a union are regularly threatened
and harassed. Virtually every employer finds other ways of
scaring employees about what will happen to them if they dare to
vote for a union. And even when employees succeed in forming a
union, one out of three employers refuses ever to agree to a
first contract with the employees' elected union. </p>
<p>The United States is the only developed nation that allows
employers to act this way. The United States also has the lowest
rate of union representation, and the largest gap between
high-paid and low-wage workers. </p>
<h3>What Should Be Done</h3>
<p>Workers need a real, democratically-chosen voice on the job so
they can participate in creating better, more productive
workplaces and in determining the terms and conditions under
which they work. Companies should be required to recognize a
union selected by a majority of employees and to bargain
collectively over all subjects of concern to the workers.
Employers who interfere in the workers decision to form a union
should be subject to stiff penalties. And employers should not be
allowed to permanently replace employees who engage in a lawful
strike. </p>
<h3>The New Leadership's Agenda</h3>
<p>The new leaders in Congress have no use for unions or for
collective bargaining. Unions stand in their way. Thats why they
are trying to make it even more difficult for workers to form a
union and easier for employers to break a union. Here is what
some Republicans and the Democrats who vote with them are
proposing: </p>
<p>They have introduced a bill in the House (H.R. 743) and in the
Senate (S.295) to make it legal for employers to create company
unions. This so-called TEAM Act would let management create an
employee organization, write the rules, choose the leaders and
then deal with these hand-picked spokespersons as if they were
the real voice of the workers. Unionized companies could use
these management-controlled organizations to undermine the real
union, and non-union companies could create company unions to
prevent their workers from forming a real union. (For more
information about this issue, see the Questions and Answers on
the TEAM Act that follows.) </p>
<p>They are trying to force President Clinton to use taxpayer
dollars to do business with employers who permanently replace
their striking employees. President Clinton has issued an
Executive Order which requires the federal government to cease
doing business with such companies. The Republicans are trying to
prevent the Clinton Administration from implementing this Order. </p>
<p>They have proposed a national so-called &quot;right to
work&quot; law. This would make it illegal for unions and
employers to require employees to pay their fair share of the
cost of negotiating and administering the contract, even when a
majority of the employees support such a requirement. Instead,
workers would have the right to &quot;a free ride&quot; to enjoy
the benefits of union representation without paying the cost. The
end result would, of course, be to weaken unions by depriving
them of the resources needed to provide effective representation. </p>
<h3>What This Means To You</h3>
<p>If the new leaders in Congress are not stopped now, your union
could be replaced by a company union controlled by the employer
rather than by you and your fellow employees. Workers who do not
now have a union to represent them will find it even harder to
organize a union. And fewer unions means less bargaining power
for workers who are organized. </p>
<p>That's why their agenda must be blocked. </p>
<hr>
<h2 align="center">Questions and Answers about the &quot;Teamwork
for Employees Act&quot; (H.R. 743/S. 295) </h2>
<h3>What Is The Teamwork For Employees Act?</h3>
<p>The Teamwork for Employees Act is a Republican proposal to
amend the National Labor Relations Act to let employers pick and
control representatives who are supposed to speak for employees. </p>
<h3>How Would The Bill Do That?</h3>
<p>Under section 8(a)(2) of the NLRA, it is illegal for an
employer to &quot;dominate&quot; an organization in which
employees participate to deal with their employer concerning
their wages or working conditions. That has been the law for 60
years. The Republicans' bill would change that to permit
employers to &quot;establish, assist, and maintain&quot; employee
organizations. </p>
<h3>What Would This Mean For Union Members?</h3>
<p>Passing this bill would give employers a new tool for busting
unions. The employer could create a company union and pay all its
costs. The employer could then deal with the company union
instead of with the real union. The employer could even grant
concessions to the company union that the employer would not
agree to with the real union. In these ways the employer could
very easily undermine support for your union. </p>
<h3>Is That The Only Problem With This Bill?</h3>
<p>Not at all. The bill would also allow non-union employers to
create company unions. That would make it even harder than it is
today for workers to form a real union. When organizing becomes
more difficult, all workers union and non- union alike suffer
since it becomes easier for employers to divide and conquer. Who
is behind this effort to weaken the labor laws? The Republicans'
bill is being pushed by big business groups, including the
National Association of Manufacturers and the Chamber of
Commerce. They want to take quick advantage of the Republicans'
control of Congress to take from workers the right to choose
their own representatives. </p>
<h3>Why Are They Doing This?</h3>
<p>The Republicans and business interests say they want to
promote labor- management cooperation and teamwork. But the
current law allow all of that. What the law prohibits is employer
control of employee representatives. This bill is really designed
to give employers new tools to deny workers a real voice in the
workplace. </p>
<h3>What Should I Do?</h3>
<p>Write your Representative TODAY. Our message: Vote against the
TEAM Act.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="index.htm">America Needs a Raise Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
