<html>
<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News, chronicler of labor events, retires</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>AFL-CIO News,
    chronicler of labor events, retires</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    Michael Byrne </p>
    <p>With this issue, the AFL-CIO News closes a chapter in
    labor communications that has marked time for organized
    workers since the 1955 merger of the American Federation of
    Labor and the Congress of Industrial Organizations. </p>
    <p>The News is being retired in favor of a new official
    publication, America@work, a monthly magazine aimed at
    providing union leaders and activists with information they
    can use to build a stronger labor movement. </p>
    <p>America@work, debuting this month, will focus on the new
    vision for the labor movement, the strategies and tactics
    that are helping unions grow and the activists who are
    leading the charge. The new magazine also will offer readers
    a chance to talk back. </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO News has had its day, and it was effective in
    telling the story of unions working together for change. </p>
    <p>The News was created out of the CIO News and the AFL News
    Reporter back in late 1955. The debut issue featured a
    triumphant George Meany of the AFL and Walter Reuther of the
    CIO at the merger convention, where Meany was elected
    president. </p>
    <p>That first convention passed a resolution inaugurating a
    public relations program that would &quot;use all available
    media, including radio and television.&quot; It also urged
    unions to &quot;support the labor press, and particularly the
    new AFL-CIO News.&quot; </p>
    <p>To edit the new weekly newspaper, AFL-CIO President George
    Meany brought in a young Newspaper Guild activist, Saul
    Miller, who for 25 years directed not only the AFL-CIO News,
    but also the Federationist, a monthly magazine that ceased
    publication in the early 1980s. </p>
    <p>Miller told his staff that the AFL-CIO News was, in
    essence, the hyphen between the AFL and the CIO. It would
    cover all union activity impartially and objectively, and it
    should do nothing to indicate that it favored any one union
    over another. </p>
    <p>That first year featured the move into a new headquarters
    building, dedicated by President Dwight D. Eisenhower, who
    declared that &quot;labor is the United States.&quot; Later
    that year, after much public soul-searching through the pages
    of the AFL-CIO News, the federation endorsed Adlai Stevenson,
    the Democratic candidate who sought to unseat Eisenhower. </p>
    <p>Throughout its existence, the AFL-CIO News commanded a
    degree of respect and credibility among opinion leaders and
    members of the press. It was the only publication that
    exclusively covered the labor movement, and its currency was
    information, not rhetoric. </p>
    <p>&quot;The journalistic standards of the AFL-CIO News never
    changed during my time there,&quot; said John Barry, managing
    editor from 1968 to 1988. &quot;We were pro-labor, of course,
    but we maintained a semblance of objectivity. We were careful
    not to provide unattributed editorial comments.&quot; </p>
    <p>Rex Hardesty, who had edited the Federationist until it
    was retired in 1982, helped to change the face of the News
    when he became director of the department in 1986. He
    eliminated the editorial page, arguing that editorials were
    redundant in a publication that should reflect the position
    of the AFL-CIO in every story. And, in an economic move
    necessitated by higher postal rates, he instituted the
    current biweekly format and four-color production. </p>
    <p>The brighter, more accessible News was a major departure
    from the traditional &quot;gray lady&quot; that chronicled
    the labor movement for decades. </p>
    <p>&quot;I wanted to redesign the paper when I arrived back
    in 1961,&quot; Barry recalled. &quot;But Saul told me that
    Mr. Meany wouldn't hear of changing it. Twenty years later,
    after Meany died, I was told to redesign it. But I only made
    some slight changes, like going from five to four columns and
    adding some boxes.&quot; </p>
    <p>The labor press always has been crucial to the success of
    the AFL-CIO News. Since the News circulated primarily to
    leadership, currently to about 53,000, the federation has
    depended on union newspapers to pass along to union members
    the information and message of the unified labor movement. In
    recent years, that has been facilitated electronically
    through LaborNET and the federation's home page on the
    Internet. </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO News mandate to promote solidarity became even
    more important after Meany died, when President Lane Kirkland
    inherited a labor movement under siege from a new Republican
    president, who stacked the National Labor Relations Board in
    favor of business and fired striking Air Traffic Controllers.
    The News played a key role in promoting two Solidarity Day
    marches on Washington, in 1981 and 1991. </p>
    <p>During this time, a philosophy parallel to solidarity was
    developed for the News. It became increasingly clear that the
    News also would have to seek out stories that provided
    illustrations and lessons in how the labor movement could
    grow. </p>
    <p>That imperative was clarified by the 1985 landmark report
    by the AFL-CIO Committee on the Evolution of Work, chaired by
    Secretary-Treasurer Tom Donahue. &quot;The Changing Situation
    of Workers and Their Unions&quot; emphasized the need for
    innovative organizing techniques, new benefits for union
    members and new communications efforts, especially through
    the electronic media. </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO News also chronicled one of the most
    revolutionary changes in the federation, the first contested
    election in AFL-CIO history, in which President John J.
    Sweeney defeated Donahue at the 1995 convention. </p>
    <p>A study of AFL-CIO communications commissioned by Donahue
    and presented after the convention recommended that the
    federation develop new communications vehicles and to
    reassess the utility of the AFL-CIO News. With the debut of
    the weekly Work in Progress in January and the monthly
    America@work, the AFL-CIO News now can pass the torch. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
