<html>
<head>
<title>Voter turnout efforts take hold</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Voter turnout efforts
take hold <br>
Electronic voter guides punctuate Labor '96 drive </strong></font><br>
by<br>
Michael Byrne </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>More than 10,000 new union activists are busy in
    congressional districts across the country, explaining the
    issues to their union brothers and sisters and urging them to
    get out and vote this Nov. 5. </p>
    <p>Labor '96 has moved into the all-important
    get-out-the-vote (GOTV) phase, as AFL-CIO and affiliated
    union staff have dispersed to help coordinators mobilize
    union workers around issues important to working families. </p>
    <p>At the same time, the federation was airing new television
    and radio voter guides providing information to voters on
    where candidates stand on the issues. </p>
    <p>&quot;The electronic voter guides are one more step in the
    AFL- CIO's continuing effort to raise the issues that are
    central to the lives of working Americans and to shine a
    light on Congress's and candidates' records with respect to
    those issues,&quot; said AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney. </p>
    <p>&quot;We plan to continue to lobby officeholders and
    would-be officeholders to adopt positions on issues like
    education, health care and retirement security that are good
    for working people,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>This year, working women were being engaged in the
    political discussion as never before, with a full week of
    outreach cosponsored by the AFL-CIO Working Women's
    Department and 9to5, the National Association of Working
    Women. (<a href="women.htm">See story, Page 4</a>.) </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO's issues-based campaign continued to draw fire
    from the Republican Party leadership, which filed suit to
    force the Federal Election Commission to act on its numerous
    complaints. The suit amounts to &quot;another publicity
    stunt,&quot; said AFL-CIO General Counsel Jon Hiatt, who said
    it was filed &quot;to distract public attention from the real
    issue in this year's campaign -- the Republican Congress's
    dismal record on working family issues such as Medicare,
    health care, education, taxes and pension rights.&quot; </p>
    <p>The ads are protected by the First Amendment and comply
    with federal campaign laws, Hiatt pointed out. The
    Republicans previously had used threats of legal action
    against local TV and radio stations in an effort to keep the
    ads off the air, but only a handful of stations pulled the
    ads. </p>
    <p>The ads are the most expensive part of the $35 million
    Labor '96 program approved by a special convention in March.
    But the union spending is only a drop in the bucket compared
    with the spending of business groups, which are on the way to
    again outspend labor groups by a 7-1 margin, AFL-CIO
    Political Director Steve Rosenthal said. </p>
    <p>&quot;That spending advantage will be seen dramatically in
    the last month before the election,&quot; Rosenthal said.
    &quot;Those Republicans who voted for business special
    interests and against workers now will be blitzing the
    airwaves with their commercials. We won't be able to match
    them in spending but, like always, we have the people
    advantage.&quot; </p>
    <p>Unions hope the &quot;people advantage&quot; will be
    magnified this year with the massive mobilization through the
    Labor '96 campaign, making the vote of union households the
    key both for the re- election of President Clinton and for a
    wholesale housecleaning of the anti-worker Congress. To
    achieve this goal, the campaign has to overcome what
    Rosenthal calls the 40-40-40 problem. </p>
    <p>&quot;In a district with, say, 35,000 union members, 40
    percent aren't registered. That leaves 21,000,&quot; he said.
    &quot;Then, 40 percent likely won't vote, and we're down to
    12,600. Of those, 40 percent may vote against their own
    economic interests. We have to do better than 7,560 union
    members out of 35,000 voting for pro-worker candidates.&quot; </p>
    <p>Labor '96 is approaching this 40-40-40 problem at every
    level -- seeking to get more union members registered to vote
    and mobilizing them to vote through a political education
    program that emphasizes not candidates or political parties,
    but where candidates stand on those issues important to them. </p>
    <p>&quot;The labor movement is united as never before for
    Labor '96,&quot; Sweeney said. He points not only to the
    unanimity of the March special convention, but also at the
    willingness of affiliated unions to share their membership
    lists for the coordinated campaign. The Political Department
    is working from a list of more than 15 million union members
    and retirees, nearly twice as many as in previous years. </p>
    <p>The solidarity also is showing up in congressional
    districts, where affiliated unions have contributed more than
    half of the 158 coordinators now in the field. In addition,
    for get-out-the-vote activity, international unions are
    sending hundreds of staff into the field. </p>
    <p>These workers will be going to union halls, plants and
    union members' homes to talk about the election, passing out
    candidate comparison fliers, making telephone calls and
    knocking on members' doors, among other activity. </p>
    <p>In a conference call with Executive Council members Sept.
    26, Sweeney urged international union presidents to join him,
    Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka and Executive Vice
    President Linda Chavez-Thompson on the campaign trail. </p>
    <p>&quot;In areas where their union members are concentrated,
    a visit from the union president could be crucial,&quot;
    Rosenthal said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
