<head>
<title>Strawberry campaign elevated to national cause</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Strawberry campaign
    elevated to national cause</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>The fight for justice and dignity by California's
    strawberry pickers is being celebrated and publicized coast
    to coast. </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO and the Farm Workers have formed the National
    Strawberry Commission for Workers' Rights to counter the
    industry's California Strawberry Commission. The labor panel
    includes organizations from communities across the country --
    civil rights, women, religious, social, academic and civic. </p>
    <p>In addition, the UFW is planning a tour of East Coast
    cities, from Boston to Washington, beginning Nov. 18 in
    Philadelphia. Strawberry workers will join in news
    conferences, meetings with politicians, presentations at
    universities and store visits. </p>
    <p>The UFW's drive to organize 20,000 strawberry pickers who
    work the soil of millionaire strawberry growers 10 to 12
    hours a day began last spring -- and the entire labor
    movement has answered the call, beginning with a presentation
    to the AFL-CIO Central Labor Council Conference by two
    strawberry workers and UFW President Arturo S. Rodriguez in
    July. </p>
    <p>Encouraged by the two national days of action and
    continuing efforts by the CLCs, Rodriguez traveled to
    Washington Oct. 10 to meet with AFL-CIO leaders and to plan
    new initiatives. In a speech to AFL-CIO staff, he explained
    the plight of the workers. </p>
    <p>&quot;Over the years, these workers have reported claims
    of sexual harassment, inadequate bathroom facilities,
    violations of wage and child labor laws, polluted drinking
    water for the workers, exposure to pesticides and employer
    mistreatment toward workers who demonstrate support for the
    union,&quot; he said. &quot;And that's just to name a
    few.&quot; </p>
    <p>Rodriguez thanked the labor movement for helping to rally
    public support for a living wage, proper field sanitation,
    health insurance, protection from arbitrary firings and a
    real voice for the workers. </p>
    <p>Analysis by the California Institute of Rural Studies at
    the University of California at Davis found that a 50 percent
    increase in most of the workers' wages would result in no
    more than a five- cent increase in the price of a pint of
    strawberries. &quot;Given the profitability of this crop --
    over $650 million a year gross -- the industry can easily
    afford to provide a living wage for its workers,&quot;
    Rodriguez said. </p>
    <p>In St. Louis, more than 100 Coalition of Labor Union Women
    members participated Sept. 28 in a demonstration at Sam's in
    support of the strawberry workers. Led by CLUW President
    Gloria Johnson, protesters met with the general manager and
    persuaded him to FAX to Sam's corporate office a leaflet and
    pledge to support the workers. The general manager also
    stated he &quot;would encourage them to sign the
    pledge.&quot; </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, central labor councils across the country
    continue to fulfill their commitment to gain support for the
    strawberry workers in their communities. During the Sept. 16
    National Day of Action, council representatives visited 181
    stores and obtained more than 90 signatures from store
    managers in support of the workers. </p>
    <p>In Florida last week, seven new store managers signed the
    pledge to support the workers. </p>
    <p>The CLC officers also have been successful in obtaining
    support from politicians in their communities. Several mayors
    and city council members have attended -- and actively
    participated -- in news conferences and store visits. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
