<html>
<head>
<title>LIUNA blasts through `whole market'</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>LIUNA blasts through
    `whole market'<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>Nearly 1,000 demolition workers in New York City have
    joined Laborers Local 79 and signed a pact with benefits and
    increased wages. </p>
    <p>The LIUNA organizing victory follows the pattern of a
    similar drive this year by Local 78, which organized most of
    the city's asbestos abatement workers. The industrywide
    campaign with the demolition workers increased the union's
    market share from 5 percent to roughly 75 percent. </p>
    <p>The &quot;whole market&quot; approach combined
    rank-and-file involvement and support from other unions. </p>
    <p>The local went in with 20 member organizers and conducted
    an education campaign on U.S. labor laws and the right to
    organize. Most of the workers are recent Ecuadoran immigrants
    who were unfamiliar with the power of a union. </p>
    <p>&quot;We conducted more than 15 pickets and strikes in the
    first 10 days of the campaign,&quot; said member organizer
    Mike Hellstrom. &quot;The response and turnout of the
    nonunion workers was really inspiring. Out of 1,200 workers,
    we ended up with 300 hardcore member organizers.&quot; </p>
    <p>They talked to workers about 12-hour days without
    overtime, health insurance and workers' compensation, said
    organizer Dave Johnson. &quot;Broken toes and fingers were
    common,&quot; he said. &quot;Workers were told to wrap broken
    fingers and `get back to work.' &quot; </p>
    <p>The workers targeted demolition contractors working on
    high- profile commercial buildings and conducted several
    &quot;organized walk- outs&quot; that paralyzed a number of
    job sites. The local also received support from the
    Teamsters. </p>
    <p>&quot;When the Teamsters would drive up to haul the trash
    and saw our pickets, they would honor the pickets and drive
    away,&quot; said Johnson. &quot;We were able to shut jobs
    down because of their support.&quot; The four-year contract
    calls for a two-tier wage system that will double and in the
    case of the more experienced workers almost triple their pay
    and provide much-needed health insurance. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
