<DOCOLDNO>IA097-001045-B019-148</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://aflcio.org:80/newsonline/96oct11/rwdsu.htm 204.127.237.106 19970215095936 text/html 4057
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 09:59:18 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 11-Feb-97 14:26:50 GMT
Content-length: 3872
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>RWDSU Wins</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Poorly treated Tyson
    workers go for RWDSU<br>
    Mississippi plant resists,but union breaks through<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>Workers at Tyson Chicken became fed up with the sexual
    harassment and favoritism displayed in the Cleveland, Miss.,
    plant and voted 248-195 on Oct. 4 for representation by the
    Retail, Wholesale and Department Store Union. </p>
    <p>&quot;They were ready,&quot; organizer Regina Hicks said.
    &quot;They were tired of the unfair treatment and knew they
    needed a union to make changes.&quot; </p>
    <p>The story at Tyson is typical not only of the indignities
    suffered by thousands of poultry workers in nonunion plants,
    but of the bullying tactics that businesses use to thwart
    union efforts. </p>
    <p>&quot;Poultry workers are the most exploited workers in
    this country,&quot; said RWDSU President Lenore Miller.
    &quot;We have been organizing poultry workers for many years,
    and unfortunately, the same problems exist.&quot; </p>
    <p>Tyson's corporate behavior was &quot;pretty obscene,&quot;
    RWDSU Secretary-Treasurer Stuart Appelbaum said. Injured
    workers were forced to &quot;return to the line,&quot;
    sometimes dripping human blood on the chicken. Restroom
    breaks were limited to one seven-minute slot a day, forcing
    workers to urinate while standing on line. Female workers
    were subjected to sexual harassment from supervisors, he
    said. </p>
    <p>&quot;I think the catalyst was the absentee policy,&quot;
    said RWDSU's David Mertz. &quot;The policy went from all
    workers having to bring a doctor's note for excused absences
    to no excuses, including medical reasons, for some employees. </p>
    <p>I think this just hit people that while the old policy was
    lousy, the new policy wasn't being administered fairly or
    equally.&quot; </p>
    <p>Outside the plant, the company was just as busy making
    life unpleasant for the workers by trying to solicit the
    community into joining their anti-union stance. </p>
    <p>There are no other unionized plants in Cleveland and, in
    the anti-union South, Tyson was able to scare many in the
    community with threats that the plant would close if the
    union came in. They had people call the workers and tell them
    not to support the union, Hicks said. </p>
    <p>But the workers refused to be cowed. One worker was in the
    beauty parlor when someone warned that she would lose her job
    if she supported the union. &quot;The worker told her, `well,
    I support the union,' &quot; Hicks said. </p>
    <p>Tyson was less successful with the religious community,
    which was asked to sign on to an anti-union ad. But two
    prominent ministers refused to sign the ad, saying they
    wanted to talk to the workers. Later, they advised plant
    managers to &quot;throw the ads in the garbage,&quot; she
    said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
