<head>
<title>Unions fight corporate scofflaws</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Unions fight
    corporate scofflaws<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney delivered a clear and
    unequivocal message that unions will fight back against
    employers who break the law in efforts to stave off workers'
    desire for a union. </p>
    <p>Sweeney was in Everett, Mass., for an Oct. 7 rally to
    support workers at Richmark International, a curtain maker
    that in September fired five employees who signed union
    authorization cards and laid off three more for distributing
    union literature before work. </p>
    <p>About 40 workers responded in a show of solidarity and an
    unfair labor practice strike on Sept. 20. They are seeking to
    organize under the UNITE banner. </p>
    <p>&quot;We're here to bear witness to a simple truth:
    organizing a union is your right,&quot; Sweeney said.
    &quot;Firing working people for organizing unions is wrong.
    As long as workers are fired for an injustice, we are going
    to be fired up for justice.&quot; </p>
    <p>Sweeney joined a march with the workers and community
    leaders, then told the rally that &quot;Richmark workers,
    like thousands of other workers in the nation, are trying to
    improve their lives, their families and their
    communities.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;It is wrong for the big foot of business to try and
    crush them,&quot; he said. &quot;From here on out, organized
    labor says to Richmark and companies like them: `We will
    fight you whether it's in Everett or Birmingham, Akron or
    Spokane.' &quot; </p>
    <p>The workers, mostly immigrant Latino women, sew curtains
    for such stores as J.C. Penney's, Filene's Basement and
    Sears. Most of the workers have not received a raise in nine
    years, are timed by supervisors when they go to the bathroom
    and can't afford health insurance. </p>
    <p>&quot;Richmark International is a perfect example of how
    workers' rights are trampled when they try to exercise their
    democratic right to join a union,&quot; said Robin Clark,
    UNITE's organizing director for the Northeast. </p>
    <p>The union also has asked the state attorney general to
    investigate the company for homework violations. </p>
    <p>&quot;First off, the company doesn't have a homework
    permit,&quot; Clark said. &quot;Then they are sending work
    home and paying workers between $1.50 and $3 per pound. It
    usually takes a couple of hours just to sew a pound.&quot; </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
