<head>
<title>UNITE dramatizes Broadway injustice</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>UNITE dramatizes
    Broadway injustice </strong></font></p>
    <p>On Broadway, the curtain is going up on a drama that
    audiences don't get a chance to see. </p>
    <p>UNITE is telling theater-goers that, while Broadway
    producers and theater owners enjoy record ticket sales, the
    workers who make costumes are working without health
    insurance or retirement benefits. </p>
    <p>In an industry that is largely unionized, only half of the
    approximately 800 costume makers have union protections.
    These costume makers have lower wages and fewer benefits than
    any other skilled worker in the theatrical industry. </p>
    <p>&quot;The companies belonging to the League of American
    Theaters and Producers should take responsibility for the
    conditions under which costumes for their shows are
    made,&quot; the union said. </p>
    <p>The union has been leafleting outside Broadway theaters
    and other theaters around the country. </p>
</blockquote>
