<head>
<title>Union women poised to make difference</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Union women poised
    to make difference</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p>Union working women vote -- and if unions do their work
    this year, they'll bring their sisters, mothers and friends
    along to the polls. </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO and 9to5, the National Association of Working
    Women, cosponsored more than 250 activities nationwide Oct.
    4-11 to kick off get-out-the-vote efforts aimed at turning
    out working women Nov. 5. Numerous surveys show the women's
    vote will be the deciding factor at the polls, and unions,
    community-based organizations, women's groups and religious
    leaders are reaching out to those potential voters throughout
    October. </p>
    <p>Low-income women without college degrees will be
    especially crucial at the polls, said Karen Nussbaum,
    director of the AFL- CIO's Working Women's Department.
    &quot;They are the most volatile group politically and are
    angry their concerns are not being heard,&quot; she said. </p>
    <p>Union members are going into grocery stores or shopping
    malls, day care centers, union halls and union worksites,
    during lunch breaks and after work, to urge their sisters to
    vote on issues important to working families -- higher pay,
    real family values, fairness and respect on the job,
    Medicare, pensions, education and family leave. </p>
    <p>In Columbus, Ohio, a voter registration drive through four
    local supermarkets signed up 800 voters. </p>
    <p>Working women rallied in Atlanta, Denver, Boston,
    Milwaukee and other cities. Women pledging to vote received a
    piece of cake - - and a piece of the action -- courtesy of
    members of the Bakery, Confectionery and Tobacco Workers. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson,
    UNITE and other union members rallied in Philadelphia around
    the theme of &quot;Don't Get Hung Out to Dry -- Vote!!!&quot;
    Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka participated in a rally
    in Minnesota. </p>
    <p>Members of the Retail, Wholesale and Department Store
    Union, in partnership with the New York Hispanic Labor
    Committee, spent the week at the subway stop serving
    Bloomingdale's flagship New York City store registering
    working women and urging them to vote. </p>
    <p>First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton took up the cause in
    Chicago, while Second Lady Tipper Gore addressed women in
    Pennsylvania. </p>
    <p>Events also included door and &quot;desk&quot; knocking,
    kitchen table discussion groups, news conferences, meetings,
    phone banks, mailings, &quot;corner waves&quot; at busy
    intersections and many others. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
