<html>
<head>
<title>OSHA survives, gets new funds</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center">&#160;<font size="4"><strong>OSHA
    survives,gets new funds </strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p>Republican attempts to undermine job safety and health
    failed in the 104th Congress. </p>
    <p>The Occupational Safety and Health Act and Mine Safety and
    Health Act remain intact; OSHA, MSHA and National Institute
    of Occupational Safety and Health funding has been maintained
    or increased; and a prohibition on OSHA efforts to develop an
    ergonomics standard or guidelines has been lifted. </p>
    <p>For fiscal 1997, OSHA's budget has been increased $22
    million to $325 million, MSHA's budget is up by $2 million to
    $197 million and NIOSH's funding is up by $53 million to
    $173.5 million (including money transferred from the defunct
    Bureau of Mines). </p>
    <p>However, the GOP can claim one victory -- the passage of
    the Small Business Regulatory Enforcement Fairness Act, which
    gives small business special consideration in the
    establishment of regulations and increased rights in the
    enforcement process. The measure provides for congressional
    review and disapproval of new final regulations, politicizing
    the standard-setting process and setting up future safety and
    health battles. </p>
    <p>&quot;Reform&quot; initiatives put forth by Rep. Cass
    Ballenger (R-N.C.) and Sens. Judd Gregg (R-N.H.) and Nancy L.
    Kassebaum (R-Kan.) went nowhere, while a sweeping regulatory
    reform measure -- part of the Republicans' &quot;Contract On
    America&quot; -- was passed in the House but died in the
    Senate. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
