<html>
<head>
<title>Bridgestone calls most back</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Bridgestone calls
    most back USWA fight will continueon unfair labor practices<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    James B. Parks </p>
    <p>Under pressure from the Steelworkers' corporate campaign,
    Bridgestone/Firestone has called virtually all the former
    strikers back to work. </p>
    <p>That was the good news announced Sept. 24 by John Sellers,
    newly elected executive vice president of USWA's
    Rubber/Plastics Industry Conference, formerly the Rubber
    Workers. </p>
    <p>&quot;The continuing bad news is that up to 150 workers
    remain off the job because they were fired on trumped-up
    strike-related charges or as part of a long-standing
    harassment campaign against union members,&quot; Sellers
    said. That means the union's campaign will continue, he said. </p>
    <p>The rest of the 2,300 workers illegally &quot;permanently
    replaced&quot; in 1994 by the Japanese-owned tire maker are
    back on the job, or have been notified to return to work, he
    said. The USWA and Bridgestone/Firestone have been unable to
    reach agreement on a contract since July 1994, when 4,000
    workers walked off the job. The workers suspended the strike
    after 10 months. </p>
    <p>Other unresolved issues include securing a fair contract,
    gaining millions of dollars in back pay the company owes the
    strikers under National Labor Relations Board rulings and
    settling the company's unfair labor practices, which the NLRB
    says prolonged the strike. </p>
    <p>&quot;We are more sure than ever of justice for the men
    and women who courageously struck this international renegade
    because of unfair labor practices more than two years
    ago,&quot; Sellers said. &quot;So while our campaign clearly
    is working, it is far from over, and we are once again
    turning up the pressure.&quot; </p>
    <p>USWA members at Bridgestone/Firestone plants in the United
    States now are working without a contract under
    company-imposed work rules. In addition, the union members
    are being harassed by &quot;replacement&quot; workers and
    false company charges that led to firings, Sellers said. </p>
    <p>Workers at the Decatur, Ill., plant are working 12-hour
    shifts, first in a three-day week, then a four-day week, with
    erratic changes between day and night shifts, said Roger
    Gates, president of USWA Local 713. &quot;People don't know
    whether they're coming or going, or what day of the week it
    is,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>The USWA is conducting an international &quot;black
    flag&quot; campaign against the Japanese-owned tire maker.
    The black flag is the traditional racing symbol for
    disqualifying a car for outrageous rules violations. The
    USWA's &quot;black flag&quot; campaign is asking consumers
    not to buy Bridgestone/Firestone products or services until
    all workers are returned to work with back wages and a fair
    contract is negotiated. </p>
    <p>The campaign's successful pressure includes frequent union
    handbilling of customers at 140 Bridgestone-owned MasterCare
    centers in the United States and Canada. It has spawned
    resolutions by 31 local governments, including Atlanta, to
    stop buying the company's products and refusals to sell
    Bridgestone tires by many dealers, including the largest
    dealer in New Orleans. </p>
    <p>In addition, Saturn has agreed to replace Firestone tires
    on its new cars with another brand at the request of buyers. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
