<html>
<head>
<title>Ford, Chrysler pacts reached; UAW, GM talk</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>&#160;Ford, Chrysler
    pacts reached; UAW, GM talk CAW strikes GM Canada;ripple felt
    in U.S. layoffs</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    James B. Parks and Mike Hall </p>
    <p>UAW members overwhelmingly ratified a new contract with
    Ford Motor Co. the same day the union reached a tentative
    agreement with Chrysler Corp. patterned on the Ford deal. </p>
    <p>The Chrysler pact was approved by the union's Chrysler
    Council Oct. 3 and was voted on by the membership in
    balloting that ended Oct 13. Talks are under way with General
    Motors Corp., but they have been slowed because of the
    Canadian Auto Workers' strike against General Motors Ltd. of
    Canada. </p>
    <p>As a result of the Canadian shutdown, GM temporarily laid
    off about 1,800 workers at a Michigan transmission plant and
    a New York engine factory. If the CAW strike continues, more
    layoffs likely are in store. </p>
    <p>The three-year Ford pact was approved by 90 percent of the
    production workers and 83 percent of skilled trades workers,
    who voted separately. </p>
    <p>&quot;Obviously, the breakthroughs achieved by the union
    on job security, higher wages, retirement income gains,
    tuition assistance benefits and other improvements were
    factors in the strong, favorable vote,&quot; said UAW
    President Stephen P. Yokich and Vice President Ernest Lofton,
    director of the union's Ford Department. </p>
    <p>The three-year Ford and Chrysler contracts include
    expanded job security protections -- which provide a
    guaranteed minimum employment floor of 95 percent of current
    covered jobs -- incentives to keep work in plant and creation
    of new jobs. </p>
    <p>Wages are increased substantially through an up-front,
    lump- sum payment of $2,000, followed by a 3 percent wage
    increase in the last two years, cost-of-living allowance
    protection and Christmas bonuses of up to $600 each. </p>
    <p>In addition to substantial improvements in basic pension
    plan benefits, the union negotiated lump-sum payments for
    retirees that will protect against inflation. </p>
    <p>Workers will be able to receive employer-paid tuition
    assistance of up to $1,000 a year for dependent children
    enrolled in college or any other approved post-secondary
    education. Retirees also can receive $1,000 a year if they
    enroll in courses on site at locations from which they
    retired. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
