<html>
<head>
<title>NABET uses media savvy in local TV contract fights</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>NABET uses media
    savvy in local TV contract fights</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p>Television industry employees used to working behind the
    scenes increasingly are finding themselves in the forefront,
    making noise and progress in labor disputes across the
    country. </p>
    <p>Media-savvy locals of the Communication Workers' Broadcast
    Employees and Technicians in New York and California gained
    settlements after getting their messages into the community
    despite a virtual electronic media blackout of their
    disputes, while locals in New Mexico and Michigan are using
    similar tactics. </p>
    <p>Off-camera workers at Buffalo, N.Y.'s WIVB-TV, members of
    NABET-CWA Local 25, approved a new three-year contract after
    a six- month campaign to get viewers and advertisers to
    boycott the station. The new contract boosts starting pay to
    $400 a week from $268 and adds dental and eyeglass coverage
    to medical benefits. </p>
    <p>Workers handbilled outside Rich Stadium and used flyovers
    of Buffalo Bills' games with banners that said: &quot;Turn
    Off News 4 -- It's Bad News for Its Workers.&quot; Bus
    shelter signs also kept the campaign in the public eye. </p>
    <p>The most recent ratings reflect the effectiveness of the
    union's campaign, as the station fell from its first-place
    position in the spring rankings. </p>
    <p>The protracted fight also resulted in a Federal
    Communications Commission complaint after all of Buffalo's
    radio stations declined to run the NABET-CWA boycott message,
    and National Labor Relations Board charges after an incident
    between the station's sales manager and union employees
    handbilling outside an advertiser's business. </p>
    <p>In California, members of NABET-CWA Local 53 won an 11
    percent wage increase, more vacation and improved medical and
    benefits eligibility in a three-year pact with the National
    Captioning Institute. The nonprofit NCI had been insisting on
    a wage freeze and a cut in shift differential pay for the
    workers, who produce the closed captioning service used by
    the deaf and hard-of-hearing on network, cable and syndicated
    television programming. </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, an advertisers' boycott and a &quot;Turn Off
    10&quot; campaign at McGraw-Hill-owned KGTV in San Diego
    culminated in a new three-year contract for Local 54. </p>
    <p>The pact features an 11 percent pay raise over term,
    additional holiday and vacation leave for temporary workers
    -- and jurisdiction for work on video file servers, Internet
    and at the company's new cable operation, News Channel 15. </p>
    <p>Local 407 in Albuquerque, N.M., has been seeking a first
    contract for a year with Pulitzer-owned KOAT-TV, and has
    gained community support by wiring around the local broadcast
    media with news conferences, picketing and letters to
    advertisers. A federal mediator is trying to facilitate a
    settlement. </p>
    <p>In the Motor City, where newspaper workers at the Detroit
    News and Free Press also are locked in a labor struggle,
    members of NABET-CWA Local 43 are pushing aggressive viewer
    and advertising boycotts of WJBK-TV, and have distributed
    more than 10,000 buttons and bumper strips that read
    &quot;Turn-off Fox TV2.&quot; </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
