<head>
<title>Bargaining: Steelworkers strik, Peace on the rails,</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Bargaining: </strong></font><a
    href="#Steelworkers strike "><font size="4"><strong>Steelworkers
    strike</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#Peace on the rails "><font size="4"><strong>Peace on
    the rails</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>,<br>
    </strong></font><a href="#ILWU pact approved"><font size="4"><strong>ILA
    ratifies contract</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#ILWU pact approved"><font size="4"><strong>ILWU pact
    approved</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, <br>
    </strong></font><a href="#IBT gets first contract "><font
    size="4"><strong>IBT gets first contract</strong></font></a></p>
    <p><a name="Steelworkers strike ">Steelworkers strike </a></p>
    <p>Some 4,500 Steelworkers walked off the job Oct. 1 at eight
    Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel plants after the company refused to
    bring its pension plan near industry standards, sought to
    subcontract jobs and eliminate workers' current health plan. </p>
    <p>Pickets remain up at plants throughout Ohio, West Virginia
    and Pennsylvania. </p>
    <p>USWA negotiators are seeking a defined pension plan paying
    retirees $40 per month per year of service. But the company,
    which currently has pension costs about one-quarter of that
    of other steelmakers, wants a risky defined contribution plan
    with benefits based on the investment performance of its
    pension funds. </p>
    <p>While the company claims its pension proposal would pay
    retirees between $1,200 and $1,600 a month, only 200 of the
    4,500- member work force would qualify for those pension
    levels. </p>
    <p>The company also wants to outsource work, including
    production work, and eliminate all non-steelmaking jobs, such
    as crane operators, janitors and nurses. </p>
    <p>The company proposed eliminating the current health
    insurance plan and replacing it with a managed health care
    plan that not only would raise costs but would limit workers'
    choice of doctors and prescription drugs. </p>
    <p><a name="Peace on the rails ">Peace on the rails </a></p>
    <p>A dozen railroad unions and 35 major freight carriers have
    reached agreement on five-year contracts covering some
    145,000 workers nationwide, marking the first time in nearly
    a decade accord was reached without strikes or imposed
    settlements. </p>
    <p>The bargaining was far from uneventful, however, with the
    creation of three presidential emergency boards, intensive
    mediation, several voluntary agreements and an arbitration
    award. Still out for ratification is a tentative agreement
    between the National Carriers' Conference Committee and the
    Firemen and Oilers, while the American Train Dispatcher
    Department, a division of the Brotherhood of Locomotive
    Engineers, remains in negotiations. </p>
    <p><a name="ILA ratifies contract ">ILA ratifies contract </a></p>
    <p>Longshoremen on the East and Gulf Coasts approved a
    five-year master agreement Oct. 2 that calls for a $4-an-hour
    pay increase over the life of the contract. </p>
    <p>The master agreement covers wages, hours, duration and
    employer contributions to the health and pension funds.
    Workers will immediately receive a $2-an-hour increase,
    followed by $1-an- hour raises in 1998 and 2000. Employer
    contributions to the health and welfare and pension funds
    will increase by 96 cents an hour by the end of the contract. </p>
    <p>Other provisions include flextime arrangements, lower pay
    for new hires and a reduction in gang size required per
    container. Both sides agreed to move to an industrywide
    managed health system by 1999. </p>
    <p><a name="ILWU pact approved">ILWU pact approved</a> </p>
    <p>On the West Coast, Longshoremen and Warehousemen approved
    a three-year contract calling for a $3-an-hour pay raise over
    the term of the pact for 8,000 dockworkers in 26 ports. </p>
    <p>Skill rate differentials increased, as did the maximum
    pension benefit for future retirees. The ILWU held on to
    current levels of benefits including medical, dental and
    vision. The contract is retroactive to June 29. </p>
    <p>The vote was the second on the agreement. In the first
    vote, 52 percent of the members approved the contract, but
    the vote fell short of a majority in two of the eight ILWU
    voting districts, Los Angeles and San Francisco. In order to
    protect the interests of minority groups of workers, union
    rules require a second vote with a 60 percent approval rate. </p>
    <p><a name="IBT gets first contract ">IBT gets first contract </a></p>
    <p>By an 84 percent majority, more than 750 pilots and flight
    engineers at American Trans Air Inc., represented by the
    Teamsters, ratified their first contract. </p>
    <p>The agreement provides a 7.5 percent raise over four
    years, the first pay boost since 1990. It also sets up more
    clearly defined scheduling procedures. </p>
    <p>Crews voted for IBT representation in 1993, and in 1995,
    turned down a tentative agreement by a 3-1 margin. Don
    Treichler, an IBT representative, said the crews wanted pay
    and scheduling improvements. </p>
    <p>The Indianapolis-based airline serves Boston, Chicago,
    Detroit, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Seattle, Las Vegas,
    Phoenix and other cities. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
