<html>
<head>
<title>IAM seeks strength in numbers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center">&#160;<font size="4"><strong>IAM seeks
    strength in numbers<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    James B. Parks </p>
    <p>Chicago </p>
    <p>In a landmark convention, the Machinists charted an
    innovative new course for the future that includes growth and
    solidarity, more emphasis on organizing and political action. </p>
    <p>The delegates approved a resolution &quot;wholeheartedly
    endorsing and supporting&quot; the proposed unification of
    the IAM with the UAW and Steelworkers to create the
    second-largest industrial union in the world. </p>
    <p>In his keynote, IAM President George Kourpias
    distinguished the development as a unification, rather than a
    merger, noting that &quot;we will be drafting an entirely new
    constitution that will guide an entirely new union into a new
    century.&quot; The three unions already have begun
    cooperative efforts. </p>
    <p>&quot;Strength and power, that's what this unification is
    all about,&quot; USWA President George Becker told the
    convention before the vote. &quot;This is not a unification
    being forged out of weakness. Each union is a strong union;
    each is rich in resources and capabilities.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;The trade union movement is a social movement,&quot;
    said Paul Masseron, assistant to UAW President Stephen P.
    Yokich. &quot;This is about the future of our country. This
    is about whether Wall Street gets to decide everything or
    whether workers have some say in our destiny.&quot; </p>
    <p>The delegates also tackled the sticky question of how to
    improve and expand member services and how to pay for them.
    The proposal on the floor was a constitutional change
    reducing the mandated strike fund contribution from 20
    percent of monthly per capita to 5 percent in 1997 and 10
    percent in 1999. The money saved, $22.6 million the first two
    years and $7.5 million each year thereafter, would be used
    for organizing, communications, education and other services. </p>
    <p>&quot;If we want to be `The Union for the 21st Century
    (the convention motto),' we need to make some changes,&quot;
    said delegate Bob Klepper of Lodge 733. &quot;We need to do
    more organizing. We need some more staff.&quot; </p>
    <p>Ultimately, the delegates agreed with Frank Souza of Lodge
    1414, who declared, &quot;Like all unions, we are losing
    members and we're losing money. And we're running out of
    options. We can either lay off staff, reduce our programs,
    raise our dues -- or adopt this amendment.&quot; They adopted
    the amendment by a 2-1 margin. </p>
    <p>Recognizing the growing role of women in the workplace and
    in the union, the delegates unanimously approved creation of
    a Women's Department to educate members on the needs and
    problems of working women, and to train and encourage more
    women to take leading roles at all levels of the union. </p>
    <p>Earlier in the week, Coalition of Labor Union Women
    President Gloria Johnson urged the convention to organize
    women and to help all working women. &quot;It's a disgrace
    that in this country, where nearly 60 million women are
    working, only 8 million belong to trade unions or
    associations,&quot; said Johnson, a vice president of the
    AFL- CIO and the Electronic Workers. </p>
    <p>But in an election year, most of the talk was about
    politics. The delegates endorsed President Clinton and Vice
    President Gore for re-election. Appearing via satellite,
    Clinton pledged to continue to fight to protect workers'
    right to strike. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney and a host of other
    speakers urged the union to vote like workers and to win in
    November. This year is &quot;the year that we either take
    back control of our country or allow the radical right, the
    new right and the not quite right to tighten their grip on
    the soul of our nation,&quot; Sweeney said. </p>
    <p>Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka challenged the
    delegates to take the fight &quot;out of the suites and back
    to the streets&quot; to win economic justice and social
    dignity for workers and their families. </p>
    <p>House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt (D-Mo.) promised
    a worker-friendly agenda if Democrats regain control of
    Congress in November. The centerpiece of that new agenda
    would be to keep good- paying jobs in America. &quot;A good
    job lies at the foundation of everything we care about in
    this country,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich offered a &quot;simple
    solution&quot; to deal with those in Washington who
    &quot;don't want worker safety, minimum wages, education, job
    training and who don't like unions. There's a simple
    solution. Send them home.&quot; </p>
    <p>Other speakers included Federal Mediation and Conciliation
    Service Director John Calhoun Wells; Canadian Labor Council
    President Bob White; Alexa McDonough, leader of Canada's New
    Democratic Party; and Bill Press, co-host of CNN's Crossfire. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
