<html>
<head>
<title>LIUNA pledges organizing, sets election</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>LIUNA pledges
    organizing, sets election</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>Las Vegas </p>
    <p>Delegates to the Laborers 21st convention recommitted the
    union to massive organizing efforts and prepared for the
    first election of LIUNA's top officers by rank-and-file
    members. </p>
    <p>&quot;To meet the mandate of this convention in
    organizing, we will pour in reinforcements to the greatest
    organizing campaign ever waged,&quot; LIUNA President Arthur
    A. Coia told the delegates. &quot;We must ensure that all
    workers have basic human rights, dignity and respect.&quot; </p>
    <p>The convention passed resolutions calling for greater use
    of volunteer organizers, expanding a program to organize
    nonunion contractors and establishing regional organizing
    branches. </p>
    <p>Using member organizers in &quot;whole market&quot;
    campaigns in New York City, the union has signed up most of
    the asbestos abatement and demolition workers in the city.
    Member organizers also have been instrumental in providing
    union benefits to poultry workers in North Carolina and
    environmental remediation workers in California. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney applauded LIUNA's
    organizing efforts. &quot;With commitments like yours, we're
    going to keep winning contract battles and we're going to win
    at the ballot boxes in November, because labor is indeed
    back.&quot; </p>
    <p>In its first secret-ballot election, delegates nominated
    Coia and Bruno Caruso, president of Local 1001 in Chicago, to
    appear on the ballot for president, which will go to the
    general membership from Nov. 2 through Dec. 16. </p>
    <p>Secretary-Treasurer R.P. &quot;Bud&quot; Vinall was
    renominated without opposition and so won a full term in
    office to run through 2001. </p>
    <p>Secretary of Transportation Federico Pena addressed the
    delegates via live satellite link and read a message from
    President Clinton, who thanked the union members for playing
    a key role in making the nation stronger. Clinton's message
    ticked off a number of Republican efforts against working
    families that were turned back this year, including attempts
    to repeal the Davis-Bacon Act, gut the Occupational Safety
    and Health Act, and allow &quot;legal company unions.&quot; </p>
    <p>Other speakers included Bob White, president of the
    Canadian Labour Congress; Martin Maddaloni, president of the
    Plumbers and Pipefitters; Robert A. Georgine, president of
    the AFL-CIO Building and Construction Trades Department;
    former Democratic vice presidential nominee Geraldine
    Ferraro; film and television actress Pamela Reed, the
    daughter of LIUNA's secretary-treasurer; Olympic gold
    medalist Matt Biondi; Nevada Gov. Bob Miller; and Las Vegas
    Mayor Jan Jones. </p>
    <p>Addressing the convention via satellite or video were:
    Reps. Richard A. Gephardt (D-Mo), David E. Bonior (D-Mich.)
    and William Clay (D-Mo), and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy
    (D-Mass.). &#160;</p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
