<html>
<head>
<title>Labor teach-in rekindles bond with academia</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Labor
    teach-inrekindles bond with academia <br>
    Enthusiasm for issues of workers spills over<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p>A rebounding labor movement and a newly interested
    academic community bridged a chasm of two generations'
    duration with a huge, overflow crowd in attendance at a
    teach-in at Columbia University. </p>
    <p>Lines stretched several blocks as nearly 2,000 people
    gathered for the Oct. 3 opening of &quot;The Fight for
    America's Future: A Teach- In with the Labor Movement,&quot;
    packing the Law Library, a spillover hall and the area
    outside the event. </p>
    <p>During the first half of the 20th century, labor and
    intellectuals were allied on behalf of social justice,
    democracy in the workplace and the economic well-being of
    working Americans. That compact disintegrated during the
    Vietnam War years. </p>
    <p>&quot;Here's the truth: when faced with a changing culture
    as well as a changing economy, the labor movement hunkered
    down,&quot; said AFL- CIO President John J. Sweeney.
    &quot;Relationships torn apart in the 1960s and '70s went
    unrepaired. The labor movement became isolated and
    introverted, concerned more with our own deepening crisis
    than with the world around us. </p>
    <p>My brothers and sisters, workers and their unions need
    you, and you need us,&quot; he said. &quot;We need your help
    in making basic economic education available and accessible
    to every American, so everyone can understand what is
    happening to their family budget and who is doing it to them. </p>
    <p>We need your help in exposing the flaws of our
    society,&quot; Sweeney said. &quot;While it takes a village
    to raise a child, it takes a union to get a raise.&quot; </p>
    <p>Helping Sweeney open the historic convocation were
    feminist author Betty Friedan, Harvard theologian Cornel
    West, University of Virginia philosopher Richard Rorty,
    Columbia University historian Eric Foner and Columbia
    University law professor Patricia Williams. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka, Executive
    Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson, and several federation
    department leaders participated in sessions held Oct. 4 at
    the New York City campus. Workshop topics included
    immigration, the globalized economy, organizing among
    African-Americans, welfare and work, families and feminism,
    labor political action and culture, identity and class
    politics. </p>
    <p>Other teach-ins will be held throughout October. They are
    designed not only to renew ties between academe and unions,
    but also to teach students about the labor movement and get
    students and professors to use their talents to help working
    Americans. </p>
    <p>Events are planned at Wayne State University, Detroit;
    University of Cincinnati; Clinch Valley College, Wise, Va.;
    University of Nevada, Las Vegas; Eastern Illinois University,
    Charleston, Ill.; University of Texas at El Paso; University
    of Florida, Tallahassee; University of Wisconsin, Madison;
    and State University of New York-Geneseo. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
