<html>
<head>
<title>Union News: Boycott Crown Petroleum, Ohio on the</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Union News: </strong></font><a
    href="#Boycott Crown Petroleum "><font size="4"><strong>Boycott
    Crown Petroleum</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>,<br>
    </strong></font><a href="#Ohio on the march "><font size="4"><strong>Ohio
    on the march</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#Illinois rallies for votes "><font size="4"><strong>Illinois
    rallies for votes</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>,<br>
    </strong></font><a href="#Sweeney: Do right "><font size="4"><strong>Sweeney:
    Do right</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#N.Y. re-elects top officers "><font size="4"><strong>N.Y.
    re-elects top officers</strong></font></a></p>
    <p><a name="Boycott Crown Petroleum ">Boycott Crown Petroleum </a></p>
    <p>At the request of the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers,
    Crown Central Petroleum has been added to the AFL-CIO boycott
    list. </p>
    <p>Last February, Crown's managers escorted all 250 members
    of OCAW Local 4-227 from its oil refinery in Pasadena, Texas,
    while the union and the company continued to bargain. These
    workers remain locked out, with Crown citing the pretext of
    &quot;sabotage&quot; and the &quot;unsuccessful status of
    negotiations,&quot; according to the union. </p>
    <p>However, the day after the lockout began, Crown stated in
    a letter to the union that &quot;when you accept our
    proposal, we will end the lockout.&quot; </p>
    <p><a name="Ohio on the march ">Ohio on the march </a></p>
    <p>Ohio trade unionists will consider a statewide work
    stoppage and march on Columbus to protest anti-worker
    initiatives in Congress and the Ohio General assembly. The
    Ohio AFL-CIO convention approved forming a committee to draw
    up plans. </p>
    <p>Some 900 delegates to the convention capped off the
    gathering's first day in Cincinnati with a march and rally
    protesting the privatization of that city's only public
    hospital. The march was led by state fed President Bill
    Burga, AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson
    and the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson. </p>
    <p>Delegates also signaled approval of a ballot initiative
    for riverboat gambling in four locations, but only if such a
    move would not cut funding for public schools and if workers
    are allowed to exercise their rights to join unions and
    bargain. </p>
    <p><a name="Illinois rallies for votes ">Illinois rallies for
    votes </a></p>
    <p>November elections were front and center at the Illinois
    AFL- CIO convention in Chicago, as AFL-CIO
    Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka urged delegates to work
    exhaustively to elect labor- friendly representatives. </p>
    <p>&quot;We can have that workers' victory, from the
    courthouses to the statehouses to the White House, if you
    make a commitment in this important political year,&quot;
    Trumka said. </p>
    <p>Food and Commercial Workers President Douglas H. Dority
    called for using an issues-oriented approach to the election
    and beyond. &quot;We must see our efforts for victory in
    November as a starting point, as a first step in our
    long-term effort to revitalize the labor movement.&quot; </p>
    <p><a name="Sweeney: Do right ">Sweeney: Do right </a></p>
    <p>The November election is about &quot;taking back control
    of our country or giving it away to the radical right, the
    new right and the not-quite-so right,&quot; AFL-CIO President
    John J. Sweeney told the 210 delegates at the Nevada AFL-CIO
    convention. </p>
    <p>He urged delegates to pledge 30 hours of their time to
    work for candidates they believe in and who support such
    working family issues as Medicare, Social Security,
    education, workplace health and safety, labor laws and
    American jobs. </p>
    <p>The convention re-elected Claude &quot;Blackie&quot; Evans
    as executive secretary-treasurer and Walt Elliot as
    president. Delegates also approved a $5,000 donation to
    striking Frontier Hotel workers who entered their fifth year
    on the picket lines last month -- the longest-running strike
    in the United States. </p>
    <p><a name="N.Y. re-elects top officers ">N.Y. re-elects top
    officers </a></p>
    <p>New York State AFL-CIO President Edward J. Cleary and
    Secretary-Treasurer Paul F. Cole won unanimous re-election to
    new four-year terms by the 1,000 delegates to the
    federation's 28th constitutional convention. </p>
    <p>Meeting under the theme &quot;one movement, one voice, one
    agenda,&quot; the convention heard from AFL-CIO President
    John J. Sweeney, House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt
    (D-Mo.), Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-N.Y.), various state
    politicians, Transport Workers President Sonny Hall and
    several AFL-CIO department leaders. </p>
    <p>After much vociferous discussion, delegates made
    endorsements in 27 of 31 congressional races. In addition,
    participants attended a variety of workshops on such topics
    as political participation, organizing, union label, the
    economy, health care, job safety, education and retirement
    planning. </p>
</blockquote>
