<head>
<title>Newsmakers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p><strong>AWARDS </strong></p>
    <p>The National Consumers League honored Labor Secretary
    Robert B. Reich as the 1996 Trumpeter Award recipient for
    speaking out for social justice and the rights of consumers. </p>
    <p>Pharis Harvey, executive director of the International
    Labor Rights Fund, and Young Shin, executive director of the
    Asian Immigrant Women Advocates, received the
    Letelier-Moffitt Human Rights Awards for their crusades
    against child labor abroad and sweatshops in the United
    States. </p>
    <p><strong>DEATH </strong></p>
    <p>Peter J. Brennan, one of New York's most prominent labor
    leaders and U.S. secretary of labor from 1973-1975, died of
    lymphatic cancer. He was 78. </p>
    <p>Brennan, president of the Building and Construction Trades
    Council of Greater New York, was appointed by President
    Richard M. Nixon to be labor secretary after Brennan
    organized construction unions and workers to support Nixon
    and the Vietnam War. </p>
    <p>Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich praised Brennan's
    government service to workers, noting that his tenure was
    marked by laws protecting pensions and employment rights of
    the disabled, as well as strictly enforced workplace safety
    laws. </p>
    <p>In 1975, Brennan return to New York and resumed the
    presidency of the construction trades council, a post he held
    until he retired in 1992. He also served as vice president of
    the state AFL-CIO and the New York City Central Labor
    Council. </p>
    <p>Brennan is survived by two daughters, one son, one
    brother, eight grandchildren and six great-grandchildren. </p>
</blockquote>
