October 11, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p><strong>RESOURCES </strong></p>
    <p>Union Issues for Working Women at the George Meany Center
    for Labor Studies Oct. 20-25 will explore new strategies and
    approaches to tap the energy that women can bring to the
    labor movement. Session topics will include politics,
    economics, organizing, leadership, safety and health, problem
    solving and planning, effective presentations, power writing
    and working within the power structure. To register, call
    301/431-5422. </p>
    <p>The American Labor Museum/Botto House National Landmark
    will display the A. Philip Randolph Traveling Exhibit through
    Nov. 9. Visiting hours are Wednesday through Saturday 1-4
    p.m. or by appointment. The museum is located at 83 Norwood
    St., Haledon, N.J. </p>
    <p>The Chicago Federation of Labor's Union Images Art Exhibit
    will be exhibited Nov. 4-8 in the atrium of the James R.
    Thompson Center, 100 W. Randolph in the Windy City. The
    exhibit, which is the result of a juried competition
    sponsored by the federation in celebration of its 100th
    anniversary, includes works of art portraying life on the job
    and in unions. Contact Elena Marcheschi at 312/565-9431. </p>
    <p><strong>PUBLICATIONS </strong></p>
    <p>Organizing for Change, Changing to Organize! is available
    through the AFL-CIO's Support Services Department. Single
    copies of the report, published by the AFL-CIO Elected
    Leadership Task Force on Organizing, are free and may be
    obtained by calling 202/637- 5041, or FAXing 202/637-5058. </p>
    <p>Government that Works is a new book of case histories of
    multiple federal facilities that threw away the book on
    standard operating procedures and started over with
    worker-management cooperation. Contact AFGE at 202/639-6419. </p>
    <p><strong>CONFERENCE </strong></p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO Human Resources Development Institute
    conference American Workforce in Transition will be held Dec.
    7-10, 1996, at the Fairmont Hotel in San Francisco. Contact
    Carol Claggett at 800/842-HRDI (4734). </p>
