<html>
<head>
<title>Worker issues front and center</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Worker issues front
    and center Labor '96 puts stamp on political campaign</strong><br>
    </font>by <br>
    Michael Byrne</p>
    <p>Chicago </p>
    <p>More than 800 AFL-CIO union delegates to the Democratic
    National Convention helped launch President Clinton's
    campaign for a second term, putting the issues of working
    families squarely at the front of the national debate. </p>
    <p>In the first address by an AFL-CIO president to a
    political party convention, John J. Sweeney spoke plainly
    about the political aspirations of millions of working
    families. </p>
    <p>&quot;They don't want to run the Congress, or the White
    House or the political parties,&quot; he said. &quot;They
    want to be compensated and respected for the contributions
    they make. They want to send their children to decent
    schools. They want to go to a safe workplace every day. They
    want a doctor when they need one, a little rest when they are
    weary, and a pension after a lifetime of work.&quot; </p>
    <p>Delegates punctuated Sweeney's speech with chants of
    &quot;America Needs A Raise,&quot; waving signs that also
    called for Good Jobs, Secure Pensions, Health Care and
    Education. Demonstrations on these worker issues were held
    throughout the convention, which contrasted the Democratic
    Party's stands with the clearly anti-worker agenda put
    forward by the Newt Gingrich-led Congress and adopted by the
    Republican Party at its convention earlier in San Diego. </p>
    <p>At a meeting of labor delegates before the convention
    opened, Vice President Gore thanked union members for their
    support and said pointedly, &quot;We are on your side. We
    need to stick together because the stakes have never been
    higher.&quot; </p>
    <p>While national media attention was drawn here for the
    nomination of Clinton and Gore, the real story was unfolding
    in congressional districts across the country, where Labor
    '96 coordinators were mobilizing union members to get out and
    vote to reverse the anti-worker tide in Congress. <a
    href="labor96.htm">(See story, Page 3)</a>.</p>
    <p>The grass-roots effort this year is paying special
    attention to working women, who have been ignored too often
    in the past. The federation's Working Women Vote '96 project,
    organized by the Working Women's Department along with 9to5,
    a nonpartisan organization, will be reaching out to all
    working women during a nationwide action week Oct. 4-11. </p>
    <p>&quot;Women are the key swing constituency this
    year,&quot; said Karen Nussbaum, who heads the department.
    &quot;In 1992, the women's vote was a deciding factor in the
    election. But in 1994, women didn't turn out, particularly
    low-income working women. We want to mobilize these women to
    vote in 1996.&quot; </p>
    <p>The centerpiece of the campaign is reaching out to women
    where they spend most of their time -- in grocery stores or
    shopping malls, at day care centers, in union halls and at
    union worksites. Voter registration/GOTV events will be held
    in about 100 communities with about 10,000 women activists
    participating nationwide. </p>
    <p>&quot;These women are union members and their best
    friends,&quot; Nussbaum said. &quot;White-collar and
    blue-collar women. No-collar, no- income women who cook,
    clean and care for the kids so the husband can work two jobs.
    Retired, and just plain tired. They've been left out of the
    political process.&quot; </p>
    <p>Special activities by unions during Working Women Vote
    week include the Bakery, Confectionery and Tobacco Workers'
    plan to provide cake they will hand out to women during lunch
    hour if they register or sign a pledge to vote. And the
    Flight Attendants have launched an unprecedented push to
    register their members. </p>
    <p>Labor '96, which was launched at a special convention in
    March with a $35 million pledge by AFL-CIO unions, is
    underscored by television and radio ads in selected
    congressional districts aimed at persuading legislators to
    change their positions on issues of importance to working
    families. </p>
    <p>In Chicago, Sweeney unveiled a new round of ads in 27
    districts where the incumbents had voted to slash Medicare,
    and then &quot;falsely claimed Medicare benefits would
    increase under their proposals.&quot; The federation also
    launched ads in selected districts highlighting legislators'
    votes against the student loan program. </p>
    <p>These messages, combined with earlier ads on the minimum
    wage and pensions, have incensed Republican Party officials,
    who have filed a series of nuisance complaints with the
    Federal Election Commission and sent threatening letters to
    television and radio stations running AFL-CIO ads. That is a
    sure sign the federation's campaign is on target, Sweeney
    said. </p>
    <p>Five FEC complaints have been filed since the federation
    announced its campaign in March. Sweeney dismissed them as an
    effort by the Republican leadership &quot;to distract public
    attention from their poor record on working family
    issues.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;The other side is not very happy,&quot; Labor
    Secretary Robert B. Reich told labor delegates before the
    convention got under way, &quot;and it's a credit to your
    campaign to expose the voting record of the Newt Gingrich-Bob
    Dole Congress. </p>
    <p>When Gingrich's `Contract With America' was unveiled,
    unions were the only people who stood up and were
    counted,&quot; Reich said. &quot;You have reminded them that
    the paycheck is the most important family value.&quot; </p>
    <p>That was the role of union delegates to the convention,
    Sweeney said. &quot;As labor delegates and representatives
    from America's unions, our central mission will be to
    persistently and consistently raise the issues our members
    care about most -- jobs and the economy, health care,
    retirement and pension security, education, and respect and
    rewards for the work we do,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>The workers' message also was carried to the convention
    floor by AFSCME President Gerald W. McEntee, who lambasted
    GOP leaders in Congress for trying to block the Family and
    Medical Leave Act and to drastically cut the Occupational
    Safety and Health Administration. </p>
    <p>&quot;At a time when nearly half a million Americans die
    on the job each year, Republicans are working overtime, if
    you will, to exempt workplaces from just routine safety
    inspections,&quot; said McEntee, who heads the federation's
    Political Committee. </p>
    <p>Machinists President George J. Kourpias, addressing a
    progressive policy forum sponsored by the Campaign for
    America's Future, praised Clinton for standing up to the GOP
    onslaught. &quot;The labor movement could not have withstood
    the assault by GOP leaders if the president had not
    intervened to defend working families.&quot; </p>
    <p>He urged activists to &quot;dress up Bill Clinton with
    coattails,&quot; to help elect a Congress that he can work
    with in a second term. </p>
    <p>The focus of the AFL-CIO's activities as Election Day
    neared is to educate union members and mobilize them to vote.
    Candidate comparisons highlighting stands on labor issues,
    will be distributed in late September. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
