<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>IAM Mac pact secures jobs, raises wages</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>IAM Mac pact secures
    jobs,raises wages `Global competition' doesn't stand scrutiny</strong><br>
    </font>by <br>
    James B. Parks </p>
    <p>The Machinists won a major victory at McDonnell Douglas on
    issues that affect many U.S. workers -- pension, job security
    and wages -- with the help of a united labor front and a
    strategy that exposed the fallacious corporate &quot;global
    economy&quot; excuse. </p>
    <p>&quot;The McDonnell Douglas workers proved that working
    people can build a better future, if they have the
    organization and courage to make a stand,&quot; IAM President
    George J. Kourpias said. &quot;People don't have to be
    victims of job exports or low wages. This is an important
    lesson and a major victory for workers everywhere.&quot; </p>
    <p>Some 6,700 members of IAM District 837 began returning to
    work at the aerospace manufacturer Sept. 16, five days after
    ratifying a new five-year contract that makes what the union
    called &quot;sweeping improvements in job security, retiree
    benefits and wages.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;Standing up together, we won the same basic job
    security protections the Boeing machinists won in their
    strike last fall,&quot; said Jerry Oulson, president of IAM
    District 837 in St. Louis. &quot;We won the best pension
    benefits in U.S. aerospace, a `30-and-out' retirement plan
    and improved wages and insurance. Our members can be very
    proud of what they've accomplished and return to their jobs
    stronger, more united and with their heads held high.&quot; </p>
    <p>The agreement &quot;shows that even in an era of economic
    transition, labor and management can resolve tough issues
    like job security if they are willing to work together,&quot;
    Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich said. </p>
    <p>Some 2,000 temporary replacement workers hired by the
    defense contractor were terminated Sept. 11, the day the pact
    was ratified, the company said. Strikers will be credited
    with time on strike for seniority purposes. The employees
    walked out June 5 at McDonnell Douglas's St. Louis plant
    after rejecting the company's contract offer. The key issue
    in the talks was McDonnell's increasing use of outside
    contractors and the transfer of some work to nonunion plants
    in Mesa, Ariz., and Macon, Ga. </p>
    <p>The new contract, ratified by a 2-1 margin, came after
    nearly 30 hours of continuous negotiations in the Capitol
    Hill offices of House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt
    (D-Mo.), who represents many of the McDonnell Douglas
    workers. </p>
    <p>During the strike, the IAM used a broad range of
    strategies to present its case. In this strike, as in the
    Boeing strike earlier this year, a key was the union's
    ability to link the plight of the St. Louis workers to
    international issues, said Barbara Shailor, who helped
    develop that strategy before being named AFL-CIO
    international affairs director in August. </p>
    <p>Two years before bargaining began at Boeing and McDonnell
    Douglas, the union researched how much production was being
    shipped out to nonunion U.S. plants and to low-wage Asian
    countries, particularly China. When talks began, the workers
    had a clear sense of what work was in China, Shailor said. </p>
    <p>&quot;We got under the argument of many American companies
    that you have to move work outside the country to access the
    market to sell your products,&quot; Shailor said. &quot;It's
    called the half-loaf theory -- half a loaf is better than no
    loaf. We came back with, `It's a loaf being baked outside the
    U.S. for the upper crust at home.' &quot; </p>
    <p>It wasn't hard to educate the members about the
    outsourcing, she said. The worker on the shop floor knows
    work is being sent out when he sees a crate marked &quot;Made
    in China.&quot; But the union had to show that the trend
    would likely continue unless there were skids in the contract
    to prevent it, she added. </p>
    <p>The union's research also was used to generate press
    stories that alerted the public to the results of the
    outsourcing. Prior to the opening of talks The Wall Street
    Journal exposed that the aerospace company's strategy of
    exporting technology to China had backfired. After one deal,
    the company received no new business and had given away a
    generation of technology to China needlessly. </p>
    <p>The union also received significant help from the AFL-CIO
    and other unions. AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard L.
    Trumka led a mass &quot;March for American Jobs&quot; by
    10,000 people on McDonnell Douglas headquarters in St. Louis
    Aug. 11, along with Kourpias, Steelworkers President George
    Becker and UAW Secretary-Treasurer Roy Wyse. </p>
    <p>&quot;America is sick of corporate greed,&quot; Trumka
    told the crowd. &quot;America is sick of rich corporations
    sending our best jobs and technologies overseas, and taking
    huge executive bonuses while laying off loyal American
    workers.&quot; </p>
    <p>Wyse told the strikers, &quot;Labor is not going to fail
    here. This will send a message to other companies all across
    the nation and teach them something about corporate
    responsibility. Mac won't win.&quot; </p>
    <p>On the political front, the IAM asked President Clinton to
    withhold any federal payments to McDonnell Douglas related to
    the strike. </p>
    <p>In an Aug. 14 letter, Kourpias also asked Clinton to
    request an audit of the quality, cost and safety of all work
    performed for the government by the temporary replacement
    workers from across the country. </p>
    <p>But the biggest political push came from Gephardt and the
    Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service, said union
    spokesman Bob Kalaski. </p>
    <p>When bargaining stalled, Gephardt summoned the two sides
    to Washington and stressed the importance of a settlement. He
    then offered his office for the talks, and it was there that
    the final bargain was struck. In appreciation, the union and
    the company jointly bought an ad in the Sunday edition of the
    St. Louis Post Dispatch Sept. 15 thanking Gephardt and FMCS
    for their help in the strike. </p>
    <p>The new contract parallels the Boeing contract on job
    security. It requires the company to give 60 days' notice of
    subcontracting plans that would affect 50 or more union jobs,
    and to consult with the union on ways to retain jobs and
    skills. </p>
    <p>Displaced workers will be retrained and re-employed at
    available work in the company and will receive continued
    benefits. </p>
    <p>Workers will receive two wage increases totaling 4.5
    percent, plus three bonuses totaling 9 percent. Under the new
    &quot;30-and-out&quot; retirement program, workers will be
    eligible to retire as early as age 50. Defined retiree
    benefits will be set at $41 per month per year of service. </p>
</blockquote>
