<head>
<title>Local union leaders make tough choices, learn to</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Local union leaders
    make tough choices, learn to grow<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>Union representation among grocery store workers in
    Dayton, Ohio, more than doubled over the past five years,
    from 33 percent to 74 percent, from 3,500 members to 7,500. </p>
    <p>It took a lot of effort and a lot of money, recalls Lenny
    Wyatt, president of Food and Commercial Workers Local 1099.
    &quot;We had to restore viability to the local. We had a lot
    of card checks. We spent in excess of $1 million
    organizing,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>The union's presence is clearly visible in Dayton today,
    and it has paid off. </p>
    <p>When the Meijer grocery chain expanded into Dayton,
    executives cautiously eyed the pickets in front of their
    competitor, Cubs stores. Rather than fight determined workers
    like those who had maintained a three-year picket line at
    Cubs, Meijer took a neutral position and let their employees
    decide for themselves if they wanted to join the union. </p>
    <p>&quot;When Meijer saw we were aggressive, well-established
    and had community credibility, they backed down,&quot; Wyatt
    said. </p>
    <p>There are lessons in the Dayton experience that the
    AFL-CIO Organizing Department is hoping to spread around the
    labor movement. A key vehicle for that exchange is the
    AFL-CIO Elected Leaders Task Force, which met in Chicago
    recently to share ideas. </p>
    <p>Wyatt was one of the participants, as was Michael Pieti,
    who hopes to use some of Wyatt's tips to rebuild union
    membership in the faltering mill industry. Membership in
    Carpenters Local 2737, which Pieti heads, has dropped from
    28,000 members in 1985 to 15,000 today. &quot;We have a hell
    of a problem,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>&quot;We've had a lot of loss because of the constraints
    on raw material and technology. But that's not to say there
    aren't many workers out there who should be organized, and
    that's who we have to go after.&quot; </p>
    <p>Pieti realizes that the message is &quot;money, membership
    and motivation. &quot;We have people who are just glad to be
    working for $9 an hour, because that beats working at the
    Mini-Mart,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>The 53 elected union leaders at the Chicago retreat talked
    candidly about the obstacles and solutions for organizing
    workers. &quot;It was a fascinating discussion,&quot; said
    AFL-CIO Organizing Director Richard Bensinger. &quot;The
    leaders challenged each other and themselves to do more. It
    gave them the courage to go back to lead their locals in
    making plans and making tough decisions about
    organizing.&quot; </p>
    <p>One continuous topic was money -- where do you get it and
    how do you best use it for organizing. AFL-CIO President John
    J. Sweeney has urged affiliated unions to devote 30 percent
    of their budgets toward organizing by the year 2000. But that
    will require a major change in union culture at the local
    level. </p>
    <p>Flora Walker, president of AFSCME Council 25 in Michigan,
    made it happen when she left the retreat, convincing the
    executive board to put $1 million a year into organizing over
    the next four years. &quot;You have to understand that
    organizing is the savior for labor,&quot; she said. </p>
    <p>&quot;Even though we have made the commitment to allocate
    15 percent of our budget to organizing and 20 percent the
    next year, it's scary,&quot; said Kristy Semersheim,
    executive secretary for Service Employees Local 715 in San
    Jose, Calif. &quot;But we know we have to do this, because if
    we don't, we won't have a labor movement.&quot; </p>
    <p>Next year, Local 715 plans to transfer two servicing staff
    members to organizing and is allocating another $50,000 to
    pay for release time for member organizers. </p>
    <p>Member education plays an important role in the organizing
    process, said David Didier, secretary-treasurer for UFCW
    Local 135 in San Diego. </p>
    <p>The UFCW local produced an educational campaign on
    protecting the union's share of the market and the effect on
    bargaining when the share erodes. &quot;We used a short video
    and mailed it to our members. The message hit home,&quot;
    Didier said. </p>
    <p>&quot;We were also able to bargain that when our pension
    fund is fully funded, 15 cents will go back to members, who
    have agreed to give half of that to the superfund. We're
    talking $3.5 million for organizing in Southern California,
    over a four-year contract,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>&quot;The AFL-CIO must drive home the importance of
    organizing, but a lot of things must happen at the local
    level,&quot; he said. &quot;If I didn't get anything else out
    of the retreat, I got that message. There must be a
    rededication of allocated resources at the local level.&quot; </p>
    <p>To help locals restructure to foster organizing, the
    AFL-CIO Elected Leadership Task Force on Organizing published
    Organizing for Change -- Changing to Organize! The manual is
    a springboard for self-examination, discussion and action. It
    is available from the AFL-CIO Organizing Department at
    202/639-6203. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
