<head>
<title>Strawberry campaign goes retail</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
Sepmember 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Strawberry campaign
    goes retail<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO central labor councils from across the country
    took up the cause of struggling strawberry pickers from the
    fields of California, joining community and religious allies
    in a blitz of grocery stores to seek pledges of support for
    the workers. </p>
    <p>The Sept. 16 events came on the second &quot;national
    action day&quot; on behalf of the workers, and they yielded a
    bumper crop of good will in many of the 53 cities where the
    activities were scheduled. </p>
    <p>The day before, Farm Workers President Arturo Rodriguez
    and Secretary-Treasurer Dolores Huerta led 7,000 people in a
    rally and march in the Watsonville-Salinas area, where
    two-thirds of the state's strawberries are harvested by
    12,000 workers toiling 12 hours a day for $8,000 a season. </p>
    <p>The cry of &quot;Independencia Campesinas&quot; --
    &quot;Farmworker Independence&quot; -- rang out as workers
    detailed their backbreaking daily labors in fields, often
    without fresh water and bathroom facilities. </p>
    <p>&quot;We're not asking for anything the growers can't give
    us,&quot; strawberry worker David Rocha told the crowd.
    &quot;We only want what we and our families deserve and what
    is right and just. We are human beings.&quot; </p>
    <p>Even if strawberry workers' pay was increased by 50
    percent, the union estimates it would cost the industry only
    about five cents more per pound in the price of strawberries. </p>
    <p>The nationwide events the following day included news
    conferences held by the AFL-CIO central labor councils, as
    well as visits to grocery stores to ask store managers and
    consumers to sign a pledge of support for the workers, and to
    urge the state's $650 million strawberry industry to improve
    working conditions. </p>
    <p>Nine CLCs in Florida and Georgia sponsored store visits at
    96 locations and gained pledges from 17 grocery stores,
    including Winn Dixie, one of the largest supermarket chains
    in the South. In fact, the president of Winn Dixie called the
    campaign's coordinator, Paul Vasquez, and requested a
    meeting. </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, the San Francisco CLC kicked off the campaign
    with a news conference featuring Mayor Willie Brown, who
    signed the pledge card while also urging the community to
    support the workers. The CLC announced plans to target 100
    Lucky stores in the area by the end of the month. </p>
    <p>The press conference also included four members of the
    City Board of Supervisors, and officials of the A. Philip
    Randolph Institute, the Labor Council for Latin American
    Advancement and religious groups. </p>
    <p>In Los Angeles, the newly elected executive secretary-
    treasurer of the Los Angeles CLC, Miguel Contreras, held a
    news conference in front of City Hall with the support of
    four City Council members, the city controller and the city
    attorney. Contreras told reporters the CLC is planning 150
    visits to Vonn supermarket stores by the end of the month. </p>
    <p>In New York City, John Catsimataidis, chief executive
    officer of the city's largest chain of supermarkets, signed
    the pledge after meeting with Manhatten AFL-CIO Secretary Ted
    Jacobsen, UFW 1st Vice President Irv Hershenbaum and UFW
    Regional Director Sarah Johnson. </p>
    <p>&quot;I am proud to sign this pledge for the strawberry
    workers, just as I was proud to join Cesar Chavez 20 years
    ago in his effort to bring dignity to America's grape
    workers,&quot; Catsimataidis said. &quot;Men and women need
    to be treated as human beings and paid a livable wage. I
    applaud the work of the UFW and support this effort.&quot; </p>
    <p>The Denver CLC, along with Jobs with Justice and LCLAA,
    participated in a Mexican Independence Day Festival, where
    trade unionists distributed campaign leaflets and stickers. </p>
    <p>In Seattle, after visits to seven Puget Consumer Coop
    stores, management agreed to contact the CEO of the company.
    Eight CLCs in Illinois, Indiana, Michigan and Ohio also
    visited stores. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
