<head>
<title>UAW members vote on Ford pact</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
Sepmember 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>UAW members vote on
    Ford pact </strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    James B. Parks </p>
    <p>UAW members will vote Sept. 29 on a tentative three-year
    contract with Ford Motor Co. that, for the first time,
    includes a guaranteed employment floor. </p>
    <p>&quot;This agreement is a tribute to the hard work and
    discipline of the UAW-Ford membership, the negotiators on
    both sides and to the constructive relationship we have built
    with Ford in recent years,&quot; UAW President Stephen P.
    Yokich and Vice President Ernest Lofton said in a joint
    statement. Lofton heads the union's Ford Department. </p>
    <p>A contract summary distributed to the Ford workers Sept.
    18 said the new contract would &quot;overlay the existing job
    protections with a combination of innovative new incentives
    for the company to grow its business and a guaranteed minimum
    employment floor of 95 percent of the current number of&quot;
    UAW-represented jobs. The UAW represents 105,000 Ford
    employees. </p>
    <p>Following a first-year up-front lump-sum payment of
    $2,000, Ford employees would receive a 3 percent general wage
    increase in the second and third years. Along with Christmas
    bonuses and cost- of-living adjustments, the average Ford
    worker would gain $13,900 over the term of the contract, the
    union said. </p>
    <p>Retirees would gain enhanced inflation protection, and
    health care benefits would be improved. The contract also
    would provide the first-ever tuition assistance plan for
    children of Ford workers and retirees. </p>
    <p>The new agreement reflects the priorities set by UAW
    earlier this year. Rejecting the notion that better wages and
    job security are unattainable in a global economy, the union
    set those two issues as the top bargaining priorities. </p>
    <p>&quot;The UAW's commitment to the twin goals of job and
    income security is more important than ever,&quot; the union
    said in a 200-page 1996 collective bargaining program adopted
    by the union's special bargaining convention. </p>
    <p>The UAW still has negotiations with the other two Big
    Three automakers -- General Motors, where it represents
    216,000 workers, and Chrysler, where it represents about
    80,000. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
