<html>
<head>
<title>Organizing: IBT Overnite success, Try, try again,</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Organizing:</strong></font><a
    href="#IBT"><font size="4"><strong> IBT Overnite success</strong></font></a><font
    size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a href="#trytry"><font
    size="4"><strong>Try, try again</strong></font></a><font
    size="4"><strong>,<br>
    </strong></font><a href="#ALPA gets Spirit "><font size="4"><strong>ALPA
    gets Spirit</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#Musicians in groove "><font size="4"><strong>Musicians
    in grove</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>,<br>
    </strong></font><a href="#USWA's precious cargo "><font
    size="4"><strong>USWA's precious cargo</strong></font></a><font
    size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#Organizing the privatized "><font size="4"><strong>Organizing
    the privatized</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, <br>
    </strong></font><a href="#Patience paid off "><font size="4"><strong>Patience
    paid off</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#Go-go SEIU "><font size="4"><strong>Go-go SEIU</strong></font></a><font
    size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#Union turns wheel in Ohio "><font size="4"><strong>Union
    turns wheel in Ohio</strong></font></a><font size="4"><br>
    </font>Compiled by Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p><a name="IBT">IBT Overnite success </a></p>
    <p>Workers at the Overnite Transportation Co. terminal in
    Memphis, Tenn., voted 219-201 for Teamsters representation
    Sept. 16, although 23 ballots were challenged by the company. </p>
    <p>The Memphis terminal is the second-largest facility at
    Overnite, which has been the subject of a nationwide
    organizing drive by the IBT since 1994. </p>
    <p>So far, IBT has won 18 Overnite elections to represent
    2,000 workers, with 15 other elections in dispute. The
    company employs about 14,000 workers, of whom about 10,000
    are eligible for IBT representation. </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, in Los Angeles, IBT Local 572 won an election
    to represent the 467 maintenance workers employed by
    Whitewood Oriental Maintenance Co. at the L.A. Airport. The
    vote was 289-62. Most of the workers earned only $4.25 and
    received no medical insurance or pension. </p>
    <p><a name="trytry">Try, try again </a></p>
    <p>The Teamsters plucked victory from the jaws of defeat in
    two recent organizing campaigns. </p>
    <p>Flight attendants at ComAir, who in June appeared to be 11
    votes short of the majority they needed to gain IBT
    representation, celebrated a win after 15 ballots postmarked
    before the deadline, but not delivered by the U.S. Postal
    Service, finally were received, giving the union the majority
    of votes needed to declare victory. </p>
    <p>The flight attendants, based in Cincinnati and Orlando,
    Fla., cited dissatisfaction with wages and working conditions
    as their reason for seeking IBT representation. </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, in Modesto, Calif., workers at the Atwater
    Canning Co. voted 349-273 for representation by the IBT after
    falling 32 votes short of winning their union in a 1990 vote. </p>
    <p>The victory was part of a renewed drive by the workers and
    the union to improve benefits, working conditions and wages. </p>
    <p><a name="ALPA gets Spirit ">ALPA gets Spirit </a></p>
    <p>Spirit Airlines pilots have voted for representation by
    the Air Line Pilots. Of the 86 eligible pilots, 60 percent
    voted for ALPA. </p>
    <p>Spirit, based in East Pointe, Mich., provides charter
    service as well as scheduled service to markets in Michigan,
    New Jersey, Florida and Massachusetts. </p>
    <p><a name="Musicians in groove ">Musicians in groove </a></p>
    <p>After a seven-month organizing drive, musicians at the
    Green Bay Symphony Orchestra voted by mail ballot 63-18 to be
    represented by Musicians Local 205. The votes were counted at
    the end of July. </p>
    <p>The campaign was coordinated by the union's newly
    established Organizing and Education Department. </p>
    <p><a name="USWA's precious cargo ">USWA's precious cargo </a></p>
    <p>Some 450 school bus drivers in Nashville, Tenn. voted
    Sept. 3 for representation by the Steelworkers. </p>
    <p>The mostly female drivers organized around stronger safety
    measures, an end to overcrowding and unfair distribution of
    routes and fairer treatment for workers by the school
    district. </p>
    <p>The victory culminates a campaign that lasted more than a
    year, as Nashville officials repeatedly tried to stop the
    organizing effort and bus drivers refused to give up. They
    waged a legal battle for their right to organize and used
    school board meetings to rally hundreds of union supporters
    to their cause. </p>
    <p><a name="Organizing the privatized ">Organizing the
    privatized </a></p>
    <p>Service Employees Local 503 in Oregon won two organizing
    victories recently to represent workers whose jobs have been
    moved from the public sector to the private sector. </p>
    <p>Some 120 direct-care workers at the Oregon Supported
    Living Program in Eugene and 45 direct-care workers at a
    group home in Corvallis have joined the local. </p>
    <p><a name="Patience paid off ">Patience paid off </a></p>
    <p>Two SEIU units have found out that all good things do come
    to those who wait. </p>
    <p>After an organizing campaign of several months, SEIU Local
    767 won an election to represent 270 technical employees at
    Good Samaritan Hospital in Brockton, Mass. The unit also has
    filed for election to represent the hospital's service and
    maintenance unit of more than 500 workers. </p>
    <p>In took two years in Niagara County, N.Y., but 130
    technicians at the Cerebral Palsy Association finally voted
    to join Local 652. The local now is working to represent
    almost 1,000 technical employees at Children's Hospital in
    Buffalo. </p>
    <p><a name="Go-go SEIU ">Go-go SEIU </a></p>
    <p>Exotic dancers at San Francisco's Lusty Lady Theater voted
    57- 15 in early September to be represented by SEIU. The
    workers were concerned with job seniority, shift scheduling,
    working conditions, wages and health insurance. </p>
    <p>Sporting &quot;Union Yes&quot; garter belts, the dancers
    began organizing after they realized that customers were
    videotaping them from behind the one-way mirrors through
    which the dancers are viewed, and that their images were
    showing up on the Internet and in videos. </p>
    <p><a name="Union turns wheel in Ohio ">Union turns wheel in
    Ohio </a></p>
    <p>After a year of being faced with employer hostility,
    workers at Carborundum Grinding Wheel Co. in Logan, Ohio,
    voted 40-35 for Mine Workers representation. </p>
    <p>UMWA President Cecil Roberts praised the solidarity of the
    Carborundum workers, and also pointed to the effectiveness of
    the union's new organizing approach. &quot;We're taking
    advantage of our rank-and-file members who are the best
    possible people to explain to unorganized workers the
    benefits of belonging to a union.&quot; </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
