<html>
<head>
<title>Union's Southern strategy pays off</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Union's Southern
    strategy pays off <br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>Workers at Kitchen of the Ocean shrimp processing plant in
    Deerfield, Fla., voted overwhelmingly for UNITE
    representation, as the union continued marching through the
    South, racking up victory after impressive victory. </p>
    <p>The 173-18 vote for UNITE representation is the 15th win
    in 17 organizing drives in the southeastern states of
    Florida, Georgia, Alabama, North Carolina and South Carolina
    since mid-March, adding 2,500 new members to UNITE's rolls. </p>
    <p>&quot;Workers across the South are organizing for more
    empowerment in the workplace,&quot; said UNITE President Jay
    Mazur. </p>
    <p>Southern workers see themselves in the midst of a growing
    crisis as they work harder each day for less and less, said
    Bruce Raynor, executive vice president and Southern regional
    director of UNITE. They want a better future for themselves
    and their families, he said. </p>
    <p>Workers at the shrimp plant, mostly Haitian women, had to
    deal with a particularly aggressive anti-union campaign that
    included hired union busters and the firing of three
    supporters the day of the election. </p>
    <p>&quot;We were tired of being treated worse and paid less
    than non- Haitian workers,&quot; said Virginia Pierre, a
    peeler at the plant. &quot;I've been here nine years, and
    today I feel like we've finally won the respect we've
    deserved for so long.&quot; </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO Organizing Director Richard Bensinger credits
    UNITE's &quot;great strategy and dedication&quot; for the
    string of Southern victories. &quot;But they couldn't get
    there without the commitment of resources and their members.
    Their victories are directly tied in with their
    structure.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;Workers are looking for an alternative, and they see
    that our union is ready to roll up our sleeves and get in the
    trenches for the fight,&quot; said Monica Russo, UNITE's
    Southern region organization director. &quot;People are ready
    to take on their employers and win.&quot; </p>
    <p>Such was the case at the Roadmaster Corp. in Opelika,
    Ala., where workers cast a 343-150 vote for UNITE. </p>
    <p>The workers began organizing in June, citing a need for
    affordable health insurance, livable wages and respect on the
    shop floor. Workers at the plant were dismissed when
    Roadmaster bought Diversified Products in 1994 and then
    rehired for as much as $2 an hour less and with fewer
    benefits. </p>
    <p>&quot;The workers at Roadmaster have let it be known loud
    and clear that they're ready for a change,&quot; said Joe
    Gaines, a UNITE organizer. &quot;The company tried every
    trick in the book to keep the workers from forming their
    union, but this crowd stood tough and stayed focused on
    justice,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>Roadmaster workers make Thighmaster and other exercise
    equipment. </p>
    <p>Perhaps the biggest gain for UNITE has been in the nursing
    home industry in Florida, where the mostly female and
    immigrant work force is faced with low wages, lack of
    benefits and lack of respect. </p>
    <p>The union has won four out of six of those organizing
    drives, including its most recent at Miami's Dania Nursing
    Home, where workers voted by a 3-1 margin for the union. The
    unit will include certified nursing assistants and
    housekeeping, laundry and dietary workers. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
