<head>
<title>Labor '96 is pinching foes at grass roots</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Labor '96 is pinching
foes at grass roots</strong></font><br>
by<br>
Mike Hall </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>Labor '96 is in full swing, keeping the heat on wayward
    members of Congress to change their positions on issues of
    importance to working families. </p>
    <p>The latest AFL-CIO grass-roots lobbying advertisements
    focus on the votes by House members to cut education and
    college loans as part of the Republican 1996 budget plan. A
    presidential veto killed the budget, which would have cut
    college student loans by $10 billion and exacted huge cuts
    from Head Start and the Safe and Drug Free schools program. </p>
    <p>In Connecticut, Rep. Gary Franks (R) ducked 100 students
    at Western Connecticut State University in Danbury, who
    sought to confront him at a Sept. 19 forum over his votes to
    cut student loans. </p>
    <p>Justin Molito, a senior at Western Connecticut and one of
    the forum moderators, is fresh off the Union Summer Southern
    Bus Tour to help organize nursing homes in the South. After
    returning home, the 23-year-old joined Labor '96 and helped
    establish Youth for Justice on Western's campus. </p>
    <p>&quot;The response has been great, especially because of
    the student loans. It hits students right in the
    pocketbook,&quot; Molito said. &quot;They have a hard time
    believing someone would vote against education, but you show
    them the record.&quot; </p>
    <p>College tuition has jumped three times as fast as
    household income in the past 14 years, and the growing income
    gap between the rich and working families has made it a
    struggle for working families to send their kids to school. </p>
    <p>The student loan ads, which are airing on television and
    radio in 32 districts, feature Carolyn and John Friedman of
    Philadelphia. They tell viewers, &quot;Next year we will have
    two children in college and it will be very hard to put them
    through -- even with two incomes.&quot; </p>
    <p>Yet as the ad points out, &quot;Congressman _______ voted
    with Newt Gingrich to cut college loans while giving tax
    breaks to the wealthy. To take away opportunities for
    children to go to college is a crime . . . Tell him his
    priorities are all wrong.&quot; </p>
    <p>The Speaker of the House, author of the GOP &quot;Contract
    With America,&quot; continues to anger trade unionists. A
    Sept. 9 fundraiser with Gingrich and Franks drew some 500
    protesters, said Warren Gould, Labor '96 coordinator in
    Connecticut's 5th District. &quot;We were able to sign up
    nearly 200 new volunteers. It totally energized us,&quot;
    Gould said. </p>
    <p>In Western Kentucky, the Gingrich name also was a magnet.
    Trade union members have followed Rep. Ed Whitfield (R) to
    four county courthouse meetings to expose his record,
    carrying signs that claim he should earn the &quot;Best
    Supporting Oscar for Supporting Newt 91 Percent of the
    Time.&quot; </p>
    <p>In Chattanooga, Tenn., labor, community and religious
    activists made Friday, Sept. 13, an unlucky day for Rep. Zach
    Wamp (R). Some 50 people rallied in front of his office to
    criticize his votes to cut education and Medicare and allow
    raids on their pension funds. </p>
    <p>That followed a late August demonstration in which several
    dozen protestors marched in front of Wamp's downtown office
    and distributed fliers charging Wamp &quot;dropped the ball
    on education&quot; when he backed the 1996 GOP House budget. </p>
    <p>The emphasis on education follows a second round of
    television and radio ads reiterating the GOP's attempt to
    slash $270 billion from Medicare last year. The ads responded
    to what AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney called
    &quot;shamefully dishonest television commercials&quot; paid
    for by the Republicans that falsely claimed Medicare benefits
    would increase under the GOP proposals, and urged those
    members to change their positions. </p>
    <p>Activists throughout the country also are going
    door-to-door to meet with union members and their families.
    The &quot;Labor Neighbor&quot; program kicked off Sept. 14 in
    California's sprawling 1st District, which stretches north of
    San Francisco to the Oregon border and inland to the wine
    country. </p>
    <p>About 20 union members went door-to-door and were able to
    talk to about 200 union families, said Gary Greer, the
    district campaign coordinator. After telling workers about
    Republican efforts to take away hard-won gains through
    Davis-Bacon repeal, job safety cutbacks and the TEAM Act, the
    activists left with the admonition that &quot;you could sit
    out this election, but it could cost you,&quot; he said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
