<html>
<head>
<title>Racing toward adjournment, Congress cutting corners</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Racing toward
adjournment, Congress cutting corners<br>
</strong></font><font size="3">by<br>
</font>Mike Hall </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>Spending bills are the last items on the agenda for the
    104th Congress as it speeds toward a late September
    adjournment target. Several key labor issues remain in play. </p>
    <p>The Labor/Health and Human Services fiscal 1997
    appropriations bill (H.R. 3755) will be the main battleground
    for such worker issues as workplace safety, training and
    education. The Treasury/Postal spending bill (H.R. 3756)
    could threaten the rights of union representatives in two
    government agencies, and an immigration bill has an
    objectionable provision that denies education to children of
    illegal immigrants. </p>
    <p>Any unfinished appropriations measures are expected to be
    folded into one omnibus spending bill or continuing
    resolution so that lawmakers and President Clinton can avoid
    the kind of stalemate that last year caused two shutdowns of
    the federal government. It appears the Labor/HHS bill will be
    part of a continuing resolution. </p>
    <p>The Senate Appropriations Committee reported a Labor/HHS
    bill Sept. 12 that included smaller cuts and fewer
    objectionable riders than the House version approved in July.
    But it still drew criticism and a White House veto threat. </p>
    <p>The House bill eliminated funding for Goals 2000, a
    program to improve the performance of public schools, and the
    Healthy Start program that seeks to reduce infant mortality.
    It also included cuts in funding for the National Labor
    Relations Board and the Occupational Safety and Health
    Administration. A provision to ban OSHA from researching and
    issuing new ergonomic rules was stripped from the bill. </p>
    <p>The Senate version allocated money for Goals 2000 and
    Healthy Start, eliminated the 15 percent House cut for the
    NLRB and increased OSHA's funding over the House bill.
    However, funds for OSHA and the Mine Safety and Health
    Administration fall below the Clinton administration's
    requests, and the OSHA budget in fact is lower than 1996
    levels. </p>
    <p>The White House protested OSHA funding levels and the cuts
    in a Department of Labor program aimed at eliminating
    sweatshops. </p>
    <p>The funding levels for education and employment and
    training don't meet the administration's request, meaning
    some 250,000 individuals -- including 134,000 disadvantaged
    youths in the summer jobs program, 81,000 dislocated workers
    and 35,000 disadvantaged adults -- would be denied training
    and employment services. </p>
    <p>&quot;These cuts are especially shortsighted considering
    the strict new requirements in the welfare reform legislation
    to prepare welfare recipients to move into work,&quot; an
    Office of Management and Budget letter said. The OMB will
    recommend a veto if the bill remains in its current form. </p>
    <p>Senate leaders plan to seek an amendment to the bill to
    add $3.1 billion for education and training. </p>
    <p>&quot;Republicans are in a hurry to leave town, but
    school's not out until we meet the educational needs of our
    children,&quot; said Senate Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle
    (D-S.D.). </p>
    <p>While the Labor/HHS bill was reported without any
    amendments handcuffing OSHA's efforts to address new
    workplace ergonomic rules, such an amendment might well be
    offered when the measure comes up for floor action. The House
    bill attacks workers with an amendment to ban the use of
    &quot;official time&quot; -- the time union reps spend on
    labor-management programs and other representational
    activities -- at the Social Security Administration and the
    Health Care Financing Administration. </p>
    <p>&quot;This blatant anti-worker effort is another attack in
    the recent assault on unions and is in obvious retaliation
    for labor's efforts to educate both its membership and all
    working Americans on the issues most affecting their standard
    of living,&quot; Legislative Director Peggy Taylor said. </p>
    <p>Official time is used when a federal employee is acting as
    a union representative and may be used only on such things as
    contract negotiations, grievance handling and
    labor-management cooperative efforts to improve service
    quality, efficiency and delivery. It cannot be used for such
    internal union business as organizing, union elections or
    partisan politics. </p>
    <p>In the federal government, official time came about when a
    1978 law required federal unions to represent all employees
    in the bargaining unit regardless of whether they joined the
    union. At the same time, it banned the unions from collecting
    fees for the representational activities they provide to
    nonmembers. But Congress did allow unions to negotiate for
    the use of official time with federal agencies. </p>
    <p>Official and or &quot;company&quot; time is commonly
    negotiated in the private sector as well as at state and
    local government levels. </p>
    <p>House and Senate negotiators will determine what funding
    levels and other provisions will be included in the Labor/HHS
    portion of the continuing resolution, and if amendments will
    be allowed. </p>
    <p>On the immigration front, UNITE, the Service Employees and
    other unions have objected to provisions in an illegal
    immigration bill (H.R. 2202) that would deny public education
    to the children of illegal immigrants and could deny certain
    benefits to legal immigrants and their relatives. </p>
    <p>The bill also requires legal immigrants to meet certain
    income levels before they would be allowed to sponsor a
    relative, including a spouse or child, for entry into the
    United States. If that income level fell, neither they nor
    their relatives would be allowed welfare benefits. </p>
    <p>That bill is in a House/Senate conference and it is
    unclear whether an agreement will be reached that would bring
    it to the floor. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
