<html>
<head>
<title>Workers renew drive for rights in trade pact</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Workers renew drive for
rights in trade pact<br>
</strong></font>by<br>
David Kameras </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>The AFL-CIO has reiterated its demand that worker rights
    be an essential part of trade negotiations, and that the
    issue be pressed at the ministerial meeting of the new World
    Trade Organization in Singapore in early December. </p>
    <p>&quot;If we want the global economy to be a source of
    stability and growth, not chaos and division, we must address
    the pain, the anxiety and the basic needs of working
    people,&quot; AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney told the
    Advisory Committee on Trade Policy and Negotiations, the most
    prominent private-sector trade advisory panel to President
    Clinton. </p>
    <p>&quot;Trade policy and trade negotiations aren't just
    about tariffs or quotas,&quot; Sweeney said Sept. 11.
    &quot;They are about people and jobs. And they are about the
    decisions government makes that help or hurt people who are
    trying to make their way in the fast-changing and unforgiving
    global economy.&quot; </p>
    <p>The committee, which is mostly made up of CEOs of major
    U.S. corporations, but also includes AFL-CIO Vice Presidents
    Jay Mazur and Lenore Miller, was told that existing
    agreements fall far short of providing fairness to American
    workers, businesses and consumers. </p>
    <p>&quot;There are huge differences in tariff levels, labor
    and environmental conditions and government practices,&quot;
    Sweeney said. &quot;America can't accept this anymore. If we
    are going to have free trade, we must have fair trade.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;We want people to show the same concern for people
    as for property,&quot; he said. &quot;We want to empower
    workers, not just corporations. And we recognize that
    government still must help to make sure that the benefits of
    trade are widely distributed.&quot; </p>
    <p>Sweeney and Mazur, who chairs the Executive Council's
    Trade Committee, also met separately with Acting U.S. Trade
    Representative Charlene Barshefsky and her senior staff to
    press for an all-out effort to advance worker rights and
    labor standards before the WTO, which grew out of the
    long-running General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. </p>
    <p>Barshefsky reiterated that these issues are of vital
    importance, and said the administration will do its utmost to
    secure approval of a working party under the WTO's auspices. </p>
    <p>The WTO initiative was the subject earlier this month of a
    trade mission to the Southern Cone led by Luis Anderson,
    general secretary of the International Confederation of Free
    Trade Union's Latin American sector, ORIT, and including
    Barbara Shailor, AFL-CIO International Affairs Director. </p>
    <p>Meeting with labor, economic and foreign ministers in
    Argentina, Brazil and Chile, as well as with Brazilian
    President Fernando Enrique Cardozo, the group proposed that
    WTO member countries be subject to a regular review of their
    observance of international labor standards, while receiving
    assistance from a special international social fund to raise
    and implement those standards. </p>
    <p>The Latin American mission reflected &quot;the total
    consensus from workers in the hemisphere that they need to be
    represented in the talks,&quot; Shailor said, noting that the
    rights issue united workers from both industrial and
    developing nations, which have historically opposed linking
    worker rights with trade. &#160;</p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
