<html>
<head>
<title>Child labor foes making inroads</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Child labor foes making
inroads</strong></font><br>
by<br>
Muriel H. Cooper </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>Child labor continues to escalate, but the fight against
    the practice has energized a new generation of social
    activists and served to educate consumers. </p>
    <p>That was the mixed message coming out of the Child Labor
    Coalition's three-day conference in Washington. </p>
    <p>The International Labor Organization estimates that more
    than 73 million children ages 10-14 were &quot;economically
    active&quot; in 1995. </p>
    <p>&quot;The fact that so many organizations that fought for
    child labor law a century ago are now returning with renewed
    vigor to this same issue most certainly indicates that there
    is a problem,&quot; said Linda F. Golodner, co-chair of the
    coalition. </p>
    <p>The good news is that since its conference two years ago,
    the coalition of trade unionists, child and human rights
    advocates and community groups has made major inroads in
    educating consumers about the abusive nature of child labor. </p>
    <p>The organization pointed to two campaigns that are opening
    the eyes of consumers worldwide -- RUGMARK, which clearly
    identifies hand-knotted carpets made free of child labor, and
    Foul Ball, which is negotiating with the International
    Federation of Football Association to guarantee that children
    do not stitch together FIFA- approved soccer balls. </p>
    <p>&quot;You see, there's a `cause and effect' here,&quot;
    U.S. Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich told the conference.
    &quot;You turned up the heat and you got results.&quot; </p>
    <p>Conference attendees also discussed child labor in the
    agriculture industry, street trades such as domestic service
    and prostitution and how to safeguard children working
    door-to-door sales, lawn care and in the entertainment
    industry. </p>
    <p>What ties all of this together, said Neil Kearney, general
    secretary for the International Textile, Garment and Leather
    Workers' Federation, is the issue of worker rights, which is
    essential to understanding child labor. He called for a
    consistent approach in dealing with low wages, health and
    safety issues and hours of work. </p>
    <p>To effectively deal with the issue of worker rights around
    the globe, it must be a part of the discussion in
    international trade, said Greg Woodhead, an AFL-CIO
    economist. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
