<html>
<head>
<title>Safety woes dog federal contractors</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Safety woes dog federal
contractors</strong></font><br>
by<br>
Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>The federal government spent nearly $40 billion in 1994 on
    contractors with dismal safety records. </p>
    <p>A recent General Accounting Office report documented the
    practice, noting that 261 federal contractors were issued
    significant penalties by the Occupational Safety and Health
    Administration for alleged safety and health violations in
    fiscal 1994. </p>
    <p>Those contractors received more than $1 of every $5 paid
    by the federal government in contract money that year. </p>
    <p>The GAO said it considered all proposed penalties of more
    than $15,000 to be &quot;significant;&quot; OSHA said only 3
    percent of the employers it cited in that time period faced
    proposed penalties of $15,000 or more. </p>
    <p>A total of 35 workers were killed and 85 injured at work
    sites operated by the contractors, according to the report,
    &quot;Occupational Safety and Health: Violations of Safety
    and Health Regulations by Federal Contractors.&quot; </p>
    <p>Sen. Paul Simon (D-Ill.), who requested the study along
    with Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.), has proposed debarring
    federal contractors for up to three years when they violate
    job safety and other labor-related regulations, but his
    attempt to attach the proposal to GOP-sponsored OSHA
    legislation in the spring failed. </p>
    <p>The report noted that most of the contractors with the
    egregious safety records were awarded contracts from the
    Department of Defense, the Department of Energy and NASA. </p>
    <p>The GAO urged OSHA to focus on federal contractors who
    might be operating dangerous work sites -- for example, the
    agency should consider whether the presence of federal
    contracts should place the employer on OSHA's priority
    inspection list. </p>
    <p>In a statement released with the report, Simon said
    &quot;it is not unreasonable&quot; for such contractors to be
    held to a higher standard because they already are required
    to meet affirmative action and other federal requirements
    beyond those applied to nonfederal contractors. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
