<head>
<title>Unions point to struggles on Labor Day</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Unions point to
    struggles on Labor Day </strong></font></p>
    <p>Hellraising figured into this Labor Day holiday, as
    AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney and Secretary-Treasurer
    Richard L. Trumka kicked off the festivities by being
    arrested along with 19 others for blocking the entrance to
    The Detroit News. </p>
    <p>&quot;Believe me, you're going to win and you're going to
    get a good contract,&quot; he told striking Detroit News and
    Free Press employees at a rally. &quot;This strike is the
    most important strike and the most important struggle we have
    in our country today. In no way will the labor movement fail
    you.&quot; </p>
    <p>The arrests marked a shift in strategy by the strikers,
    who plan more acts of civil disobedience that will result in
    misdemeanor arrests, said Al Derey, president of the
    Metropolitan Council of Newspaper Unions. </p>
    <p>In appearances across the country, Sweeney, Trumka and
    Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson extolled
    labor's new activism and urged workers to use their power and
    vote their interests in November. </p>
    <p>Labor &quot;is building a dynamic new force for America's
    working families. We're energizing our movement, we're
    mobilizing on an unprecedented scale,&quot; Chavez-Thompson
    told a crowd at a Labor Day observance in New Jersey in honor
    of Peter J. McGuire, who helped to create the national
    holiday. </p>
    <p>Sweeney was back in Detroit two days after his arrest, on
    Labor Day, telling marchers that if they vote like workers,
    &quot;we will have a workers' victory this November. And then
    we'll keep on coming back again and again until this nation
    respects the work we do and rewards us for the contribution
    we make.&quot; </p>
    <p>Trumka delivered the same message in Chicago during the
    local AFL-CIO's 100th Labor Day celebration, urging the crowd
    to support candidates that &quot;champion the things you and
    your family need.&quot; </p>
    <p>Chavez-Thompson, in Los Angeles, told workers that the
    &quot;cruel paradox&quot; of the American economy -- high
    profits and low wages -- shows why we need unions. </p>
    <p>Sweeney also joined President Clinton for rallies in
    Milwaukee and Green Bay, Wis., two of the hundreds of
    gatherings by trade unionists across the country to mark the
    holiday. </p>
    <p>In New York City, more than 100,000 workers turned out on
    the Saturday after the holiday for the traditional Labor Day
    Parade, one of the largest in years. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
