<html>
<head>
<title>Frontier strikers: Five years and holding fast</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Frontier strikers:
    Five years and holding fast</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>Through five years of rain, sunshine, mortgage payments
    and nearby casino openings, one thing has remained constant
    for Frontier Hotel workers -- their picket line. </p>
    <p>The 550 members of Hotel Employees and Restaurant
    Employees Local 226 who were forced to strike the Las Vegas
    hotel on Sept. 21, 1991, have been buoyed by favorable court
    decisions and unshakable labor and community solidarity. But
    they remain on strike. </p>
    <p>&quot;Not one soul has gone back to the Frontier,&quot;
    said Jim Arnold, secretary-treasurer of the local. &quot;They
    took our pension away, cut wages and wanted to eliminate the
    grievance procedure,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka carried a
    message of admiration and support for the strikers at a rally
    and banquet Sept. 21-22. </p>
    <p>&quot;A five-year strike in which not one person has
    crossed the picket line deserves accolades and support,&quot;
    Trumka told the summer meeting of the Executive Council. He
    noted that Joe Daugherty, a HERE organizer, has not taken a
    day off in five years because he has been helping the
    strikers. </p>
    <p>Frontier has faced sanctions from the National Labor
    Relations Board, which has declared the dispute an unfair
    labor practice strike, and a federal court, which has ordered
    the hotel to pay more than $1.5 million to the pension fund
    for the striking workers. </p>
    <p>The court also ordered the hotel to rescind disciplinary
    findings on any employee resulting from some 64 unilaterally
    imposed work rules and to reinstate with back pay anyone
    discharged or suspended because of the rules. </p>
    <p>&quot;We're in this for the long haul,&quot; said Arnold. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
