<html>
<head>
<title>Courts: Cities can back unions, Albertson's workers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Courts: </strong></font><a
    href="#Cities can back unions "><font size="4"><strong>Cities
    can back unions</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, <br>
    </strong></font><a href="#Albertson's workers sue "><font
    size="4"><strong>Albertson's workers sue</strong></font></a><font
    size="4"><strong>,<br>
    </strong></font><a href="#Airline ordered to bargain "><font
    size="4"><strong>Airline ordered to bargain</strong></font></a></p>
    <p><a name="Cities can back unions ">Cities can back unions </a></p>
    <p>A federal appeals court ruling affirms the right of city
    and state governments to support unions in private-sector
    labor disputes. </p>
    <p>The U.S. Court of Appeals for the 9th Circuit Sept. 13
    reversed a lower court ruling that the city of Oakland,
    Calif., could not endorse a boycott of Alameda Newspapers
    Inc., owner of the Oakland Tribune. </p>
    <p>The case, ANI vs. City of Oakland, began in 1993 when ANI
    bought the newspaper, cut 400 of 600 jobs and moved
    production out of the city. The Northern California Newspaper
    Guild and the seven unions in the Conference of Newspaper
    Unions launched a boycott of ANI, which the City Council
    endorsed, canceling all city subscriptions and official
    advertising. </p>
    <p>ANI sued the city for $5 million and sought an injunction
    against the cancellations. A federal judge ruled in favor of
    ANI, saying the city illegally had tried to regulate ANI and
    had attempted to interfere with the &quot;free play of
    economic forces.&quot; </p>
    <p>The appeals court disagreed, saying the city merely was
    expressing its opinion. Cities and states have the right to
    &quot;make pronouncements about labor disputes of concern to
    their communities,&quot; the court said. </p>
    <p><a name="Albertson's workers sue ">Albertson's workers sue </a></p>
    <p>Seven current and former employees of Albertson's grocery
    chain filed a class-action lawsuit seeking back pay for work
    they performed off the clock. </p>
    <p>The suit, filed with the help of the Food and Commercial
    Workers, claims Albertson's threatens to fire employees who
    complain about working off the clock and fails to permit rest
    breaks on company time. </p>
    <p>UFCW represents 31,000 of the chain's 85,000 employees. </p>
    <p>More than 1,500 workers have given declarations that they
    worked off the clock for Albertson's. The company claims it
    has a policy against off-the-clock work, but workers maintain
    they are penalized if they don't finish their assigned tasks
    within their scheduled hours of work, forcing them to work
    off the clock. </p>
    <p>Albertson's, in a preemptive strike, filed a federal
    lawsuit in Boise, Idaho, seeking to bar union-represented
    employees from initiating suits until they have exhausted the
    grievance arbitration procedure in their own union. The union
    responded with an unfair labor practice complaint, saying the
    lawsuit is an attempt to interfere with protected employee
    rights. </p>
    <p>Several years ago, a similar UFCW investigation of
    nonunion Food Lion, an Albertson's competitor, raised 300
    claims and led to a U.S. Labor Department suit that was
    settled for $16.2 million. </p>
    <p><a name="Airline ordered to bargain ">Airline ordered to
    bargain </a></p>
    <p>A federal district judge has ordered America West Airlines
    to immediately begin contract negotiations with its
    mechanics. </p>
    <p>In a companion decision, the judge dismissed claims by the
    Teamsters and four former workers who filed a class action
    suit seeking damages over America West's decision to fire
    several hundred workers. </p>
    <p>However, Judge Roger Strand of the U.S. District Court for
    Arizona has allowed the union to proceed with its claim,
    charging that the airline's decision to contract out work had
    a negative effect on the union's organizing drive. </p>
    <p>In April, the workers voted 587-135 for IBT
    representation. However, the company challenged the win,
    charging that the nearly 400 workers fired last December by
    the airline should not have been allowed to vote. The judge
    dismissed the challenge. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
