<html>
<head>
<title>L.A. unions help tortilla drivers roll</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>L.A. unions help
    tortilla drivers roll</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    Sharolyn A. Rosier and James B. Parks </p>
    <p>After working 10 to 12 hours a day, six days a week with
    no overtime pay, more than 100 truck drivers in Los Angeles
    took on their employer, tortilla maker Mission Guerrero, and
    won. </p>
    <p>After seven weeks on strike, the truckers ratified a new
    five- year contract that gives them what they wanted: job
    security, better wages, cheaper health care and most of all,
    their dignity. </p>
    <p>The contract, ratified Sept. 18 by an 85-2 vote, provides
    for guaranteed job security, an increased base pay rate and a
    higher commission rate. At the same time, the company agreed
    to explore finding a new health care provider that would
    reduce workers' co- payments. </p>
    <p>The agreement will boost worker pay by $95 a week over the
    term of the contract. The commission rate will be raised 1
    percent, from 5 percent to 6 percent. The company also agreed
    to give up its right to unilaterally contract out the
    drivers' jobs to independent contractors. </p>
    <p>The key to the victory was community support, said Peter
    Olney, director of the Los Angeles Manufacturing Action
    Project (LAMAP), a multiunion industrial organizing program.
    &quot;We made it a communitywide issue. Mission Guerrero's
    tortillas became taboo tortillas, not to be touched until the
    strike was settled.&quot; </p>
    <p>After about five-and-a-half weeks, the company blinked at
    the boycott activity and negative publicity it was receiving,
    and started talking, Olney said. </p>
    <p>&quot;The company just wants the money to keep rolling in,
    but immigrant workers are very militant,&quot; Olney said.
    &quot;This is going to force unions to look again at the
    whole question of how to organize, at what having a union
    really means.&quot; </p>
    <p>With the help of local trade unionists, LAMAP and
    community activists, the strikers held demonstrations at El
    Pollo Loco, one of the company's major customers, and at the
    Mexican consulate. Several El Pollo Loco restaurants agreed
    to stop buying Mission Guerrero's products. </p>
    <p>On Labor Day, the workers received a big boost from the
    Los Angeles Central Labor Council. During the CLC's Labor Day
    event, Executive Secretary-Treasurer Miguel Contreras signed
    a pledge to boycott the company, along with U.S. Department
    of Housing and Urban Development Secretary Henry Cisneros,
    U.S. Reps. Esteban Torres and Maxine Waters, Lt. Gov. Gray
    Davis and several city council members. </p>
    <p>Three years ago, the workers, members of Teamsters Local
    63, organized and achieved their main goal -- health
    insurance for their families. During negotiations earlier
    this year, Mission Guerrero proposed changes that would have
    made their economic situation much worse. </p>
    <p>The company proposed a pay raise of $1.03 per day the
    first year, with smaller raises in the second and third
    years. At the same time it wanted workers to increase their
    co-payments for health care benefits, more than canceling the
    proposed wage increases, said Hector Fernandez, Local 63
    business agent. </p>
    <p>The workers also were angered by the long hours they
    worked and the system the company uses to avoid paying
    overtime. While paying its drivers only $250 a week, the
    company, in turn, sells them their trucks for $90 to $115 a
    week. To get them to hustle, the company paid a commission
    according to the value of the tortillas each customer buys,
    but only after the first $2,000 in weekly sales. </p>
    <p>For a fast driver, it usually took two to four days to
    reach the threshold, according to the union. The drivers
    routinely put in 10-to-12 hour days, six days a week, for a
    total of 60 to 80 hours. </p>
    <p>In addition, the company pays $190 a week for fuel and the
    use of the truck, but gas alone can cost $160 to $180. </p>
    <p>Mission Guerrero is the main tortilla supplier for the
    U.S. Army as well as for such fast food chains as El Pollo
    Loco, Taco Bell, Del Taco, Carls Jr. and Green Burrito. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
