<html>
<head>
<title>Communities back USWA tire campaign</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Communities back
    USWA tire campaign</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    James B. Parks </p>
    <p>The growing roar of support for the Steelworkers' campaign
    against Bridgestone/Firestone added the voices of New
    Orleans' largest tire dealer, the Atlanta City Council and a
    delegation of Japanese trade unionists. </p>
    <p>A New Orleans-style funeral, complete with Dixieland band,
    escorted Bridgestone and Firestone signs from four New
    Orleans tire stores to their &quot;final resting place&quot;
    Sept. 12 as the stores' owner, Cal Lucas, ended his family's
    three-decade relationship with the company. Lucas is the
    largest independent tire dealer in New Orleans, doing about
    $1 million in business annually with Bridgestone/Firestone.
    Now he will sell Kelly Springfield tires, which are
    union-made. </p>
    <p>&quot;Here's an international company with worldwide
    facilities that wants the workers to come to its terms,&quot;
    Lucas said. &quot;They're shipping products from Third World
    countries while American workers are out of work.
    Bridgestone/Firestone has said it wants to lower wages and
    other costs to be competitive -- it wants its workers to work
    for Third World wages. I don't like it!&quot; </p>
    <p>A crew of striking USWA members from Bayou Steel took the
    flags down from Lucas's four stores and replaced them with
    Kelly Springfield signs. </p>
    <p>The USWA and Bridgestone/Firestone have been unable to
    reach agreement on a contract since July 1994, when 4,000
    workers walked off the job. The workers, formerly members of
    the Rubber Workers, suspended the strike after 10 months.
    During the strike, Bridgestone/Firestone hired 2,300
    replacement workers. At issue is the rehiring of 700
    strikers. </p>
    <p>The union is conducting an international &quot;black
    flag&quot; campaign against the Japanese-owned tire-maker.
    The black flag is the traditional racing symbol for
    disqualifying a car for outrageous rules violations. The
    USWA's &quot;black flag&quot; campaign is asking consumers
    not to buy Bridgestone/Firestone products or service, until
    all workers are returned to work with back wages and a fair
    contract is negotiated. </p>
    <p>In Atlanta, the city council joined nearly 50 other state
    and local governments and businesses supporting the USWA
    campaign. The council adopted a resolution stating the city's
    refusal to &quot;purchase Bridge-stone/Firestone products
    until all union members are returned to work under a contract
    that provides dignity, equity and security.&quot; </p>
    <p>The resolution notes that the National Labor Relations
    Board is seeking &quot;tens of millions in back pay for
    victims of the company's unfair labor practices&quot; and
    charges that the company &quot;has no intention of
    negotiating an honorable contract with the union.&quot; </p>
    <p>A delegation of 18 Japanese trade unionists from KOKURO,
    the Japan railway union, and other independent unions spent
    six days in the United States visiting and giving support to
    striking Bridge- stone/Firestone workers. The Japanese
    unionists staged peaceful protests in Firestone Service
    Centers in Chicago and Des Moines, Iowa, visited strikers in
    Decatur, Ill., and marched on Bridge- stone/Firestone's U.S.
    headquarters in Nashville, Tenn., with strikers from the
    USWA's Camp Justice. They also marched with striking Detroit
    newspaper employees. </p>
    <p>&quot;We can't forgive the Japanese companies when they
    come to the United States and treat their workers
    badly,&quot; said Yoshiaki Jingu, one of the delegation's
    leaders. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
