<head>
<title>Northwest workers seek just rewards</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Northwest workers
    seek just rewards<br>
    </strong></font>by<br>
    David Kameras </p>
    <p>It's payback time for workers at Northwest Airlines. </p>
    <p>Three years ago, workers helped keep the then-ailing
    carrier out of the bankruptcy courts by trading concessions
    for job security provisions and payback guarantees. Now that
    talks have opened for a new contract, unionists want what's
    rightfully theirs. </p>
    <p>&quot;Flight attendants sacrificed for years to make
    Northwest Airlines a success story,&quot; said Bruce Retrum,
    president of Teamsters Local 2000, which represents the
    flight attendants. &quot;Now it's the flight attendants' turn
    to get their reward -- pay they can live on, job security and
    pension improvements.&quot; </p>
    <p>Northwest led its competitors last year in profits per
    employee, and top managers reaped the benefits in the form of
    millions of dollars in bonuses and exercised stock options. </p>
    <p>&quot;It's been a long and grueling three years,&quot;
    said Eunice DePinto, a 17-year flight attendant based in
    Seattle. &quot;We've made a lot of money for a lot of people,
    and we're ready to be rewarded for our efforts.&quot; </p>
    <p>The amount of the &quot;snap-ups&quot; -- the pay increase
    over the restoration of 1993 pay levels -- may be a point of
    contention between management and the Teamsters, as it
    already has been with the Air Line Pilots. The Machinists
    also are due snap-ups, as all three unions head into
    negotiations over the next several months. </p>
    <p>In response to a survey, more than 6,000 flight attendants
    indicated that their top bargaining priorities are
    improvements in compensation, retirement and scheduling
    flexibility. </p>
    <p>&quot;I'm not going to retire next year, but I'd like to
    see a good retirement for all of us,&quot; added M.K.
    Sagastume, a flight attendant based in Detroit. &quot;When
    the flight attendants at the top can retire, it opens up
    opportunities for everyone down the line and gives us a
    chance to bring more people in at the bottom.&quot; </p>
    <p>With fours years at Northwest, Sagastume still lacks the
    seniority to be assured of a definite advance schedule. </p>
    <p>Unity will be the watchword as the unionists brave the
    negotiating season. </p>
    <p>&quot;The concessions we've been through have shown us
    that we have to look out for each other and stick together
    and look at ourselves, not as a bunch of individual people,
    but as a union,&quot; said Carrie Trettel, an 11-year veteran
    from Boston. </p>
    <p>In other industry developments: </p>
    <ul>
        <li>The Transportation Department turned down a request
            by the Flight Attendants to investigate the
            department's conduct in tentatively finding ValuJet
            fit to resume operations following the May 11 crash
            in Miami. </li>
    </ul>
    <blockquote>
        <p>Charging that DoT has lowered the safety standard it
        expects airline executives to meet, AFA President Pat
        Friend said undue influence by the carrier and members of
        Congress pressured the department to turn &quot;a blind
        eye toward one of the most frightening safety records in
        the airline industry.&quot; </p>
    </blockquote>
    <ul>
        <li>Voting has begun for Teamsters representation of
            mechanics at ValuJet, which was grounded amid reports
            that maintenance work had been contracted out to
            poorly paid subcontractors. </li>
        <li>Flight attendants at Continental Airlines,
            represented by the IAM, ratified a
            three-and-a-half-year contract that features
            significant pay raises, job protections and improved
            vacation and sick leave. </li>
    </ul>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
