<head>
<title>Bargaining: UNITE sews up cotton deal, SEIU ends</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Bargaining: </strong></font><a
    href="#UNITE sews up cotton deal "><font size="4"><strong>UNITE
    sews up cotton deal</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>,<br>
    </strong></font><a href="#SEIU ends hospital strike "><font
    size="4"><strong>SEIU ends hospital strike</strong></font></a><font
    size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#BCT, Nabisco agree "><font size="4"><strong>BCT,
    Nabisco agree</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, <br>
    </strong></font><a href="#TCU ratifies contract "><font
    size="4"><strong>TCU ratifies contract</strong></font></a><font
    size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
    href="#Albertson pact approved "><font size="4"><strong>Albertson
    pact approved</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong><br>
    </strong></font><a href="barbrfs.htm"></a></p>
    <p><a name="UNITE sews up cotton deal ">UNITE sews up cotton
    deal </a></p>
    <p>UNITE members were voting on a tentative agreement reached
    Sept. 9 with the multiemployer association representing
    cotton garment companies. </p>
    <p>The agreement, which covers 30,000 employees in the cotton
    garment industry nationwide, was recommended by the
    negotiation committee. The ratification vote, which began
    immediately, was expected to be completed Sept. 23. The
    previous agreement expired Aug. 31. </p>
    <p>Some of the nation's largest manufacturers in the cotton
    garment industry are members of the multiemployer group,
    including Arrow Shirt, Biltwell, Pendleton Woolen Mills,
    Manhattan Shirt and The Apparel Group. </p>
    <p><a name="SEIU ends hospital strike ">SEIU ends hospital
    strike </a></p>
    <p>Members of Service Employees Local 144 in New York City
    ended a two-month strike Aug. 27 after ratifying a new
    three-year agreement with 13 hospitals and nursing homes. </p>
    <p>Some 6,700 technical, service and maintenance employees
    walked out June 24 after talks broke down over cost-cutting
    proposals by the League of Voluntary Hospitals, which
    represented management. The previous contract expired Dec. 1,
    1995. </p>
    <p>The new contract calls for lump-sum payments of $750 in
    1996 and 1997 and $1,000 in 1998. Medical care benefits and
    education benefits also were improved. </p>
    <p><a name="BCT, Nabisco agree ">BCT, Nabisco agree </a></p>
    <p>The Bakery, Confectionery and Tobacco Workers
    overwhelmingly approved a new five-year contract with Nabisco
    Biscuit Co. that raises wages and benefits by $4.61 an hour
    over it's term. </p>
    <p>The contract is a &quot;win-win&quot; for both sides, BCT
    Secretary- Treasurer and lead negotiator Gene McDonald said.
    The successful outcome is the result of a mutually productive
    relationship developed by the company and union over time, he
    said. In February, representatives from each of the 10
    Nabisco plants and the international met with company
    officials to draft a &quot;vision statement&quot; for the
    future and a &quot;road map&quot; to get there. </p>
    <p>The new contract calls for an hourly wage increase of 40
    cents the first year, followed by raises of 50 cents, 60
    cents, 50 cents and 60 cents. The company also agreed to
    increase pension fund contributions each year and to improve
    health care benefits. </p>
    <p><a name="TCU ratifies contract ">TCU ratifies contract </a></p>
    <p>Members of the Transportation Communications Union
    overwhelmingly ratified agreements with the nation's major
    freight railroads that will yield 16.9 percent wage increases
    by the end of the century. </p>
    <p>The contracts cover 20,000 clerks and 12,000 carmen, who
    voted in favor by margins of 86 percent and 76 percent,
    respectively. The pacts also provide for post-contract
    cost-of-living adjustments every six months, no rule
    concessions and, in 1999, improved health care and dental
    benefits and a new vision plan. </p>
    <p><a name="Albertson pact approved ">Albertson pact approved </a></p>
    <p>Members of Food and Commercial Workers Local 7 ratified a
    new three-year contract with Albertson's supermarkets that
    gives hourly 35-cent raises each year to entry-level
    employees. </p>
    <p>Also, workers in the top categories will receive a
    30-cent-an- hour raise each year. The contract improves
    pension benefits and maintains the current bonus program.
    About 2,500 retail workers and meatcutters in 29 stores in
    Denver, Colorado Springs, Boulder and Longmont, Colo., are
    covered by the deal. The previous contract expired May 11. </p>
    <p>Many of the provisions mirror those in contracts with the
    state's largest grocers, King Soopers and Safeway. But a key
    change, allowing management more flexibility in scheduling,
    did not appear in the Albertson's contract. </p>
    <p>Negotiations with Albertson's were put on hold this summer
    after Local 7 began a 44-day strike against King Soopers and
    were locked out by its bargaining partner, Safeway. Despite
    the delay, negotiators met 22 times trying to complete a new
    agreement. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
