<head>
<title>Union News: Pact ends vet home strike, Peerless</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4">&#160;<strong>Union News: </strong></font><a
href="#Pact ends vet home strike "><font size="4"><strong>Pact
ends vet home strike</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>,<br>
</strong></font><a href="#Peerless show crashed "><font size="4"><strong>Peerless
show crashed</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
href="#IBT backs Avis sale "><font size="4"><strong>IBT backs
Avis sale</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>,<br>
</strong></font><a href="#R.I. gets a raise "><font size="4"><strong>R.I.
gets a raise</strong></font></a><font size="4"><strong>, </strong></font><a
href="#Sweatshops pay up "><font size="4"><strong>Sweatshops pay
up</strong></font></a></p>
<blockquote>
    <p>AFL-CIO News - September 20, 1996 </p>
    <p><a name="Pact ends vet home strike "><strong>Pact ends vet
    home strike </strong></a></p>
    <p>Striking AFSCME members at the Anna, Ill., veterans' home
    ratified their first contract Sept. 12, clearing their return
    to work after walking the bricks for some five weeks. </p>
    <p>The three-year pact with ServiceMaster Diversified Health
    Services calls for increases totaling nearly $4 over term --
    from $4.60 to $4.71 an hour to $8.25 to $8.50 an hour -- and
    includes employer-provided health insurance, additional paid
    leave, holiday pay, a 401(k) program, grievance procedures
    and regular labor- management meetings. </p>
    <p>&quot;This agreement is a victory for the workers, for the
    veterans they serve and for all of Southern Illinois,&quot;
    said Henry Bayer, executive director of AFSCME Council 31.
    &quot;These workers have demonstrated the power that even a
    small group of employees can wield when they are committed,
    when they have the courage of their convictions and when they
    are united by the strength of union representation.&quot; </p>
    <p>As part of the settlement, Diversified agreed to return
    all of the striking workers to their jobs. </p>
    <p><a name="Peerless show crashed "><strong>Peerless show
    crashed </strong></a></p>
    <p>UNITE members continued to put pressure on Montreal's
    Peerless Clothing Co. as they staged a major protest outside
    the biannual MAGIC (Men's Apparel Guild in California) show
    in Las Vegas. </p>
    <p>About 500 members distributed leaflets and chanted
    &quot;Shame on Peerless,&quot; as another 50 went inside the
    convention site to do the same. </p>
    <p>Peerless is a leading men's suit manufacturer and exports
    95 percent of its line to the United States. </p>
    <p>UNITE began its national protest campaign almost a year
    ago, citing sexual and racial harassment and illegal firings
    of members of the mostly immigrant work force. Workers have
    filed 34 complaints with the Quebec government charging
    Peerless with ethnic discrimination and other civil rights
    violations. </p>
    <p><a name="IBT backs Avis sale "><strong>IBT backs Avis sale </strong></a></p>
    <p>After reaching an agreement this summer with Avis over
    employee job security, the Teamsters endorsed the $800
    million sale of the company to HFS Inc., a national
    franchiser of hotels and residential real estate brokerage
    offices. </p>
    <p>Avis employees who are participants in the car rental
    company's employee stock ownership plan will be voting over
    the next few weeks on the sale. </p>
    <p>The IBT negotiated a series of protective measures with
    Avis related to the proposed sale. IBT represents more than
    3,000 Avis employees. </p>
    <p><a name="R.I. gets a raise "><strong>R.I. gets a raise </strong></a></p>
    <p>Rhode Island's working poor got some relief Sept. 1 when
    the state's minimum wage rose from $4.45 to $4.75 an hour; it
    will rise again to $5.15 next Jan. 1. </p>
    <p>The maximum allowance for gratuities in such businesses as
    hotels and restaurants will increase from 35 percent to 50
    percent, with a minimum cash wage of $2.89 an hour. There is
    no training wage. </p>
    <p>The income boost &quot;is a step toward making sure that
    people who make minimum wage don't live in poverty,&quot;
    state AFL-CIO Secretary- Treasurer George Nee said. </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, the New York City Council voted 44-5 to
    override a veto of a bill to require city contractors to pay
    prevailing wages. Mayor Rudolph W. Guiliani (R) has
    threatened legal action. </p>
    <p><a name="Sweatshops pay up "><strong>Sweatshops pay up </strong></a></p>
    <p>The Labor Department's Wage and Hour Division recovered
    $699,323 in back wages between April and June 1996 for 2,486
    garment workers who illegally were denied minimum wage or
    overtime pay. </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, criminal charges were filed after a series of
    August raids in Brooklyn, N.Y., garment shops, including one
    linked to the celebrity Kathy Ireland label. </p>
    <p>New York led the nation in wage-and-hour violations with
    56 violations, and California followed closely behind with
    49. During the third fiscal quarter, the largest back-pay
    award -- $113,457 -- went to workers of Truong Sewing in
    Garland, Texas. </p>
    <p>The Brooklyn raids resulted from a two-month investigation
    by the district attorney's office, fire and finance
    departments and state labor department. The charges involved
    violations of the city's fire safety code and the state
    minimum wage law's prohibition on piecework. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
