<html>
<head>
<title>Young will lead Paperworkers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Young will lead
    Paperworkers <br>
    Convention concentrates on organizing, politics</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    James B. Parks </p>
    <p>Las Vegas </p>
    <p>The Paperworkers elected new leaders and set a course for
    the year 2000 that emphasizes organizing and political
    action. </p>
    <p>The convention, which retiring President Wayne E. Glenn
    called &quot;a watershed in terms of policy and
    direction,&quot; was the first since the 1994 merger with the
    Allied Industrial Workers. </p>
    <p>To lead the union, delegates elected Boyd D. Young as
    president to succeed Glenn, who had reached mandatory
    retirement age under the union constitution.
    Secretary-Treasurer James Dunn was re-elected without
    opposition. Glenn, who served 18 years as president, was
    elected president emeritus. </p>
    <p>Young, 56, was vice president for Region VI which includes
    Texas and Louisiana. He received 14,338 votes, defeating
    Gerald Johnston, who received 8,357 votes. Besides Young and
    Dunn, delegates elected three new members of the executive
    board to replace retiring members. They rejected a move to
    add two rank-and- file members, one a woman and the other a
    person of color, to the executive board. </p>
    <p>The 2,200 delegates voted to intensify organizing efforts
    by training representatives, organizers and local union
    leaders in organizing techniques. They also called for the
    union to develop a strategy for including retirees in
    organizing and political action efforts. </p>
    <p>After an emotional debate, delegates rejected a proposal
    to reduce the number of regions from 11 to 8. Supporters
    claimed it would improve union efficiency. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney, citing labor's recent
    legislative wins on the minimum wage, health care reform,
    defeat of the TEAM Act and so-called right-to-work laws,
    praised the UPIU for pioneering some of the new tactics and
    strategies that the federation is using. </p>
    <p>&quot;Instead of playing by the old political rules, we're
    lifting the lid off the House and the Senate and letting in
    some sunshine. Instead of being victimized by outmoded
    traditions of collective bargaining, we're exposing the
    actions and motives of our employers,&quot; Sweeney said. </p>
    <p>The federation has shifted its legislative focus from
    Washington into congressional districts &quot;where
    politicians have to listen,&quot; Sweeney said. &quot;We've
    taken our contract fights out of the suites and into the
    streets. When an employer or a politician crosses us, we take
    them on, aggressively and publicly. When a boss goes bad, we
    get mad.&quot; </p>
    <p>Sweeney also paid tribute to UPIU's bargaining successes.
    &quot;Don't let me forget the members of this union who took
    a stand for all of us and said `No, hell no' to Trailmobile
    and Menominee Paper Co. and Finch Pruyn. Thank you for
    teaching us to win again.&quot; </p>
    <p>Other speakers included Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers
    President Robert Wages, AFSCME President Gerald McEntee and
    AFL-CIO Political Director Steve Rosenthal. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
