<html>
<head>
<title>IBEW prepares for hi-tech future</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>IBEW prepares for
hi-tech future</strong></font><br>
by<br>
Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>Philadelphia </p>
    <p>Electrical Workers President John J. Barry and Secretary
    Jack F. Moore were overwhelmingly re-elected in a convention
    that featured electronic voting, a laser show and other
    hi-tech touches that kept delegates focused on the union's
    future. </p>
    <p>The more than 2,400 delegates used touch-screen electronic
    voting to select Moore and Barry by a nearly 5-1 margin over
    challengers Mike Lucas and Forrest Darby. Re-elected without
    opposition were Treasurer Thomas Van Arsdale and Executive
    Council Chairman Clyde Bowden. </p>
    <p>&quot;We must go beyond the parochial concerns of one
    branch or another and face squarely the larger issues that
    bind us together and will affect our common fate,&quot; Barry
    said in his keynote address. &quot;We in the IBEW want a
    world where a man can go to a safe workplace, earn a fair
    wage and use his skills to do a good day's work. </p>
    <p>We want a world where a woman can develop her talents to
    the fullest and have a wealth of opportunity before
    her,&quot; he said, &quot;where workers can retire with
    dignity, with the security of knowing that their health care
    is affordable and available . . . and where workers can
    organize and bargain collectively to achieve all these things
    in fairness and in justice.&quot; </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney vowed the federation's
    grass-roots legislative and political campaigns would help
    bring a progressive majority back into control in the House,
    pick up a couple of Senate seats and re-elect President
    Clinton and Vice President Gore. </p>
    <p>Delegates defeated a proposal to allow Canadian locals to
    hold a separate convention, reaffirmed their opposition to an
    age limit of 65 for international officers (the question had
    been defeated in a spring referendum), raised the salaries of
    some international officers and changed their pensions. </p>
    <p>Vigorous debate was held over resolutions to create an
    Electric Utility Industry Advancement Fund by increasing per
    capita of utility locals, to assess each member $1 per month
    to fight utility deregulation and to create a Utility
    Industry Advancement Fund by using current per capita funds.
    Ultimately, delegates decided to return the matters to the
    committee for further work. </p>
    <p>Another major issue that divided the delegates was a
    proposed constitutional change to require a secret ballot
    election for the top four officers. After two days of debate
    on three such resolutions, the convention approved a
    substitute amendment that requires secret ballots in the
    future. </p>
    <p>Also addressing the convention were Secretary of Labor
    Robert B. Reich, Pennsylvania AFL-CIO President William
    George, Philadelphia Mayor Edward Rendell and labor's priest,
    Msgr. George Higgins of Catholic University. &#160;</p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
