<head>
<title>GCIU looks to organizing as `lifeblood'</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>GCIU looks to
    organizingas `lifeblood'<br>
    elegates urged to embrace technology </strong></font></p>
    <p>Anaheim, Calif. </p>
    <p>Delegates to the Graphic Communications Union convention
    raised per capita to boost organizing and service to members,
    and explored ways to make technological innovation work for
    workers, not against them. </p>
    <p>Calling technology a two-edged sword, GCIU President James
    J. Norton told the nearly 500 delegates that &quot;we must
    embrace it so our employers can stay competitive. But
    technological change causes workers to be displaced.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;Staying abreast in the industry has to continue
    indefinitely, because technology will not leave us in 1996
    and is likely to impact on us in the next four years,&quot;
    he said. </p>
    <p>Delegates approved increases in the per capita tax of 75
    cents in 1997 and again in 1999, with organizing on their
    minds. </p>
    <p>&quot;Without organizing, we jeopardize our existing wages
    and working conditions,&quot; Norton said. &quot;With a
    successful organizing program, we assure a continuation of
    financial and workplace gains along with pension improvements
    that are the lifeblood of a successful union.&quot; </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney lauded the union for its
    coordinated bargaining campaign with Quebecor, the largest
    single- employer effort in the union's history, and urged
    delegates to fully involve themselves in the fall election
    campaign. </p>
    <p>&quot;Two years ago, we lost 29 congressional districts to
    `Newtie and the Blowhards' by less than 5,000 votes,&quot;
    Sweeney said. &quot;In those districts, we had two to three
    times that many union members who didn't even vote. So your
    work, your commitment can and will make a difference.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;On Nov. 5, we're going to reach down and root out
    the ugliness that has grabbed hold of our nation,&quot; he
    said. &quot;And that's a promise. That's a commitment.&quot; </p>
    <p>The convention took up a number of resolutions regarding
    such diverse topics as organizing, striker replacement and
    political action. </p>
    <p>Speakers included AFL-CIO Building and Construction Trades
    Department President Robert A. Georgine; Canadian Labour
    Congress President Robert White; Ontario Federation of Labour
    President Gordon Wilson; and Tony Dobbins, general secretary
    of Britain's Graphical Paper and Media Union. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
