<head>
<title>`Organize all farm workers'</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>`Organize all farm
    workers'<br>
    UFW plans for growth,new fights for justice<br>
    </strong></font><font size="3">by<br>
    </font>Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>Fresno, Calif. </p>
    <p>Fired up after gaining more than 35,000 new members in the
    last four years, the Farm Workers outlined new goals for the
    union and pushed its effort to organize strawberry workers to
    center stage. </p>
    <p>&quot;The organizing won't stop with the strawberry
    workers. We will organize all farm workers,&quot; UFW
    President Arturo Rodriguez told the 500 delegates to the
    union's 13th convention in Fresno, Calif., over the Labor Day
    weekend. </p>
    <p>The UFW's intensive organizing has made it the nation's
    fastest-growing union, and AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney
    held it up as a model for the rest of the labor movement. </p>
    <p>&quot;We must organize more workers as you in the Farm
    Workers union are doing,&quot; Sweeney said. &quot;Whatever
    we do, we must ask, how does this help us grow and give
    workers more power? Because if we don't grow in big numbers,
    we cannot survive.&quot; </p>
    <p>Sweeney's address was the first ever by an AFL-CIO
    president to the UFW convention. </p>
    <p>Sweeney, Rodriguez and Secretary-Treasurer Dolores Huerta,
    co- founder of the union, led about 200 strawberry workers
    from the Salinas-Watsonville area in a march around the
    convention center floor, shouting, &quot;Strawberry workers
    united will never be defeated.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;These workers are among the most exploited in all of
    agriculture,&quot; Rodriguez said. &quot;We will continue
    until they receive the benefits of a union contract.&quot; </p>
    <p>The march preceded the second national day of action in
    support of the strawberry workers in 50 cities around the
    nation on Sept. 16. (See story, Page 12). </p>
    <p>The strawberry campaign is not as difficult as the famous
    grape boycott led by the union's founder, Cesar Chavez,
    Rodriguez said. Strawberries must be picked within days or
    they become overripe and rapidly lose value, giving the union
    more leverage, he said. </p>
    <p>Political action in the form of a voter registration card
    is as important as organizing and gaining a union card,
    Housing and Urban Development Secretary Henry Cisneros told
    the delegates. &quot;If you don't have a vote, you don't have
    a voice. With the vote, we can take our children to the
    future. I want to see a Latino governor of California,&quot;
    he said. </p>
    <p>One of the highlights of the convention was a tribute to
    Chavez, who died four years ago. Delegates constantly shouted
    &quot;Si Se Puede&quot; (Yes We Can), Chavez's rallying cry.
    An emotional high point came when six-year-old Angel Noriega
    of Fresno recited Chavez's famous definition of machismo.
    &quot;Machismo is not to hit your wife and not to have a beer
    with your friends. Machismo is not to bow down to your
    boss,&quot; Noriega said. </p>
    <p>Other speakers included Jack Henning, former executive
    secretary-treasurer of the California AFL-CIO; Miguel
    Contreras, executive secretary-treasurer of the Los Angeles
    AFL-CIO; Maria Elena Durazo, president of Hotel Employees and
    Restaurant Employees Local 11; and Elisco Medina, a vice
    president of the Service Employees. &#160;</p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
