<html>
<head>
<title>Prosperity eludes hard-working U.S. families</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Prosperity eludes
hard-working U.S. families</strong></font><br>
by<br>
David Kameras </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>Despite job growth during the 1990s, the typical American
    family still faces considerable economic pain and
    uncertainty, according to several new studies. </p>
    <p>In &quot;Running in Place: Trends in U.S. Living
    Standards,&quot; the bipartisan Competitive Policy Council
    concludes that workers are toiling longer hours for less pay,
    and even the evolution of two- earner households hasn't
    helped working families keep up. </p>
    <p>The Economic Policy Institute's annual &quot;The State of
    Working America&quot; also found a continuing deterioration
    of hourly wages for all but the top 20 percent of male
    earners and most female earners between 1989 and 1995. The
    combination of falling wages and increased job loss, largely
    a blue-collar phenomenon in the 1980s, has now moved up the
    income scale at the same time that fringe benefits have
    eroded, EPI reported. </p>
    <p>&quot;For the vast American middle class and for
    low-income families, neither the 1979-89 nor the 1989-95
    business cycles have brought increased prosperity,&quot; the
    report said. &quot;American families are beset by a long-term
    erosion in wages, deteriorating job quality and greater
    economic insecurity.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;There seems to be no overall gain or efficiency
    payoff associated with all the evident pain,&quot; economists
    Lawrence Mishel, Jared Bernstein and John Schmitt wrote.
    &quot;There is no evidence that the economic squeeze on
    families is part of some sacrifice that will improve economic
    conditions in a way that will benefit families in the
    future.&quot; </p>
    <p>The researchers pointed to the weakening of union
    protections and the right to organize and bargain
    collectively, as well as such diverse factors as
    deregulation, globalization, tax inequity and weakened
    safety, health and environmental rules, as contributing to
    structural changes in the economy that place workers at a
    disadvantage. </p>
    <p>Mishel and Bernstein also conducted one of two studies on
    which the Competitiveness Policy Council based its report. In
    &quot;Trouble in Paradise: Eroding Wages and Growing Income
    Inequality,&quot; they found that median family income after
    inflation in 1993 ($36,959) was only marginally higher than
    it was in 1973 ($36,893) even though many more families rely
    on two wage-earners than 20 years ago. </p>
    <p>With more families depending on two wage-earners, there
    has been a &quot;fundamental change in the way we earn our
    income,&quot; said Howard Rosen, the council's executive
    director. This has put greater pressure on working families,
    he noted. </p>
    <p>The other study by the council, conducted by Frank Levy of
    the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, found that most
    family incomes are rising only because the women in the
    households are working more hours. </p>
    <p>The EPI's Labor Day report included several key findings
    that buttressed its analysis. </p>
    <ul>
        <li>From 1989 to 1995, hourly wages plummeted 6.3 percent
            for the typical male worker. The drop was 1.7 percent
            for the typical female worker, partially reversing
            gains made during the 1980s.</li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>Median family income was down 5.2 percent, with the
            bottom 95 percent showing a loss. Besides continuing
            wage deterioration, the decline was attributable to
            the decreasing ability of contributions by working
            wives to offset the lower earnings of their husbands. </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>Since middle-class workers pay the same proportion of
            their income in taxes as they did in the late 1970s,
            &quot;the rise in inequality and fall in living
            standards reflect what employers aren't putting into
            paychecks, not what government is taking out in
            taxes.&quot; </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>Hourly compensation, which includes fringe benefits,
            has risen only 0.1 percent faster than hourly wages
            alone since 1979, while workers receiving
            employer-provided health benefits fell in 1979- 1993
            from 79 percent to 64 percent, and pension coverage
            fell from 48 percent to 45 percent. </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>The ratio of CEO pay to that of the average worker
            rose from 60:1 in 1978 to 173:1 in 1995, a year in
            which business after-tax profit rates reached a
            30-year high, fueled by stagnant or falling wages. </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>The benefits of the booming stock market eluded most
            workers, with only 28 percent of families owning more
            than $2,000 in stock, including shares owned through
            pension plans. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Despite lower wages and standard of living for most
    Americans, &quot;there is no evidence of our economy becoming
    more competitive or having improved in the fundamentals of
    capital accumulation or economic efficiency and
    productivity,&quot; the authors said. </p>
    <p>&quot;Government policy-makers and elected leaders must be
    judged on their ability to change the economic course of the
    country, to leave the low-wage for the high-wage path,&quot;
    they said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
