<html>
<head>
<title>Real earnings rise with prices stable</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Real earnings rise
    with prices stable </strong></font></p>
    <p>Real weekly earnings rose a substantial 0.7 percent in
    August, as workers put in more hours for higher pay. </p>
    <p>Contributing to the improvement was stability in consumer
    prices, which increased only 0.1 percent in August. The
    annualized rate of 1.8 percent for the past three months
    indicates a significant slowing down of what was already a
    slim inflationary trend. </p>
    <p>The price data &quot;confirm the opinions of commentators
    who say that inflation is not a problem for
    policy-makers,&quot; said AFL-CIO economist Bill Cunningham. </p>
    <p>Nonetheless, the Federal Reserve Board has sought to use
    the recent federal minimum-wage boost as a pretext for
    raising interest rates to combat its superficial impact on
    inflation. The idea is that the higher cost of money will
    slow down business expansion and the jobs it creates, thereby
    holding down wages. The Fed will consider the possibility of
    raising interest rates Sept. 24. </p>
    <p>Ironically, current economic performance is calling into
    question the whole premise that reducing joblessness
    necessarily results in higher prices. </p>
    <p>Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich noted that the
    &quot;natural&quot; rate of unemployment is being re-defined
    downward as sustained employment levels coincide with stable
    prices. </p>
    <p>&quot;It seems to me that in making decisions about how
    vigorously we wage war on inflation, we should fully consider
    those who are most likely to be the war's first
    casualties,&quot; he said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
