<html>
<head>
<title>Jobless rate at seven-year low</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Jobless rate at
    seven-year low<br>
    Layoffs are continuingas economy expands</strong></font><br>
    by<br>
    David Kameras </p>
    <p>The unemployment rate fell from 5.4 percent to 5.1 percent
    in August, the lowest level in seven years. Still, millions
    of workers have yet to benefit from the economic recovery,
    now in its 65th month. </p>
    <p>Including underutilized and discouraged workers, the rate
    was 9.3 percent, or 12.7 million workers. </p>
    <p>Employment rose by 250,000, with 10 percent of that in
    manufacturing, led by motor vehicle and equipment
    fabrication. </p>
    <p>In addition to August's improved jobless figures, the rate
    at which workers are being laid off over the past three years
    is less than that for the previous three years. But 3.8
    million long-term employees still got pink slips between 1993
    and 1995. Long-term workers are defined as those over the age
    of 20 who have held a job for at least three years. </p>
    <p>&quot;The data from the earlier period reflected the
    impact of the 1990-91 recession and the slow labor market
    recovery that followed,&quot; said the Bureau of Labor
    Statistics, which compiled the figures. &quot;In contrast,
    the February 1996 survey covered a period of employment
    expansion and declining unemployment.&quot; </p>
    <p>Yet the layoff process continues: </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Union Pacific Railroad, which is merging with
            Southern Pacific Railroad, will cut 1,200 jobs in
            Denver over the next two years.</li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>Campbell Soup Co., which prefers buying out a German
            soupmaker to retaining its own employees, is planning
            to cut 650 jobs.</li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>Pendleton Woolen Mills is closing its
            UNITE-represented Sellwood plant at the cost of 119
            jobs, a move that even management attributes to the
            North American Free Trade Agreement and the General
            Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.</li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>On the upside, Boeing Co. is hiring 5,000 more
            workers than previously anticipated. And UNITE has
            traded wage concessions to save two-thirds of 650
            apparel jobs slated for elimination at M. Wile Co. in
            Buffalo, N.Y. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>&quot;While the decline in job dislocation is a positive
    trend, the report also confirms that some American workers
    who lose their jobs remain unemployed and, for those who do
    find new jobs, many experience a drop in earnings,&quot; said
    Joseph E. Stiglitz, chairman of President Clinton's Council
    of Economic Advisers. </p>
    <p>While 73 percent of the laid-off full-time workers were
    re- employed by February 1996, half were unable to match or
    exceed their previous earnings, and a third suffered losses
    of 20 percent or more. Those in the 25-to-54 age group had
    the highest re- employment rate, 78 percent. </p>
    <p>Manufacturing continued to take the brunt of the
    displacement (29 percent). While men were more likely to be
    laid off, they were also more likely to be re-employed. </p>
    <p>&quot;This report underscores the importance of increasing
    access to education and worker training and protecting
    dislocated workers' health and pension benefits to help ease
    job transition and reduce the cost of job loss to American
    workers,&quot; Stiglitz said. </p>
    <p>That process may be made more difficult by the huge influx
    of welfare recipients into the labor market as a result of
    the GOP welfare reform package signed by President Clinton.
    Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich has indicated that the
    administration will seek a targeted tax credit to encourage
    employers to hire those struggling to get off the dole. </p>
    <p>Specific data for July showed Washington, D.C., with the
    nation's highest unemployment rate (9 percent), followed by
    Alaska (7.6 percent), California and New Mexico (both 7.1
    percent). North Dakota had the lowest (2.8 percent), followed
    by Nebraska (2.9 percent), South Dakota (3 percent) and Utah
    (3.1 percent). </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
