<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Yawning trade gap swallows workers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Yawning trade gap
    swallows workers </strong></font></p>
    <p>America's international trade imbalance worsened
    considerably in the second quarter, with the merchandise
    deficit jumping from $12.4 billion to $19.6 billion. </p>
    <p>Imports of goods and services soared at a 14 percent
    annual rate, up from a rapid 12 percent gain in the first
    quarter. Excluding oil, imported merchandise met a record
    26.5 percent of demand for goods in the second quarter. </p>
    <p>&quot;The figures demonstrate once again that the
    continued growing deficit in trade constitutes the greatest
    area of weakness in the economy,&quot; said Mark Anderson,
    director of the AFL-CIO Task Force on Trade. &quot;That
    deficit continues to represent a drag on wages.&quot; </p>
    <p>From January to July, the goods deficit with Japan was
    $26.6 billion, 29 percent less than during the same period
    last year. However, the trade imbalance with China was $19.5
    billion. </p>
    <p>The $23 billion cumulative goods trade deficit with the
    other signatories to the North American Free Trade Agreement
    was up 26 percent from the first seven months of 1995, with a
    deficit of $13.3 billion scored with Canada, and with Mexico,
    $9.7 billion. </p>
    <p>It would be hard to blame the deficit on excessive wages.
    Once the world leader in earning power, the American factory
    worker has slipped behind his counterparts in Japan and 10
    European countries in terms of hourly compensation costs. </p>
    <p>&quot;The international comparisons of compensation costs
    show that other developed countries have industrial systems
    that value workers,&quot; said AFL-CIO economist Greg
    Woodhead. &quot;If the basis for international competition is
    low wages and low standards of worker protection, the United
    States is leading in the race to the bottom.&quot; </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
