<html>
<head>
<title>Newsmakers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/mastt.gif"
align="bottom"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Newsmakers</strong></font><br>
    Compiled by <br>
    Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>Delegates to the South Carolina AFL-CIO convention elected
    Donna DeWitt, a member of the Communications Workers, as
    president to fill the unexpired term of G.O. Smoak, who
    retired. The convention quickly adjourned on the first day so
    that delegates could return to their homes as recent
    hurricanes bore down on the state. </p>
    <p>Suzanne Granville has been appointed assistant director
    for grass-roots activity in the Legislative Department at the
    AFL-CIO. Granville, 35, worked in a similar position with the
    Letter Carriers. </p>
    <p>Karla Garland has been named the director of public
    affairs for the AFL-CIO's Housing Investment Trust. Garland
    previously served as a media spokesperson for the AFL-CIO and
    coordinator for media and marketing in its broadcast
    division. Garland, the former Newspaper Guild unit chair,
    joined the federation in 1974. </p>
    <p>Chris Woods is the new chief of staff for the AFL-CIO
    Organizing Department. Woods previously served as national
    recruitment director for the Organizing Institute. Before
    that she was an organizer for the Clothing and Textile
    Workers, now UNITE. </p>
    <p>President Clinton announced his intent to nominate AFL-CIO
    President Emeritus Lane Kirkland to the board of directors of
    the U.S. Institute of Peace. The bipartisan board was
    established in 1948 by Congress to promote international
    peace and the resolution of international conflict without
    violence, through education, training, research and public
    information. </p>
    <p>President Clinton named John E. Higgins to fill a vacancy
    on the five-member National Labor Relations Board. Higgins, a
    Republican, currently serves as the agency's acting inspector
    general. </p>
    <p>John Calhoun Wells, director of the Federal Mediation and
    Conciliation Service (FMCS) has selected C. Richard Barnes as
    deputy director for field operations. Barnes will oversee
    nearly 200 federal mediators in the country. Prior to joining
    FMCS, Barnes was a Laborers' district council manager. </p>
    <p>Two union presidents have been elected to the Railway
    Labor Executives' Association. W.D. &quot;Dan&quot; Pickett
    of the Railroad Signalmen was elected chair and Clarence V.
    Monin of the Locomotive Engineers vice chair for the
    association. </p>
    <p>Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening joined AFL-CIO President
    John J. Sweeney at the George Meany Labor Studies Center
    Sept. 13 to unveil a new program that will enable community
    college students enrolled in labor studies programs in
    Maryland to transfer their credits to four-year institutions.
    The Meany Center's Maryland Institute for Labor Education
    (MILE) program is expected to be a national model for
    community-based union leadership education. </p>
    <p>AWARDS </p>
    <p>The Letter Carriers is honoring four workers as
    &quot;Heroes of the Year.&quot; Joan Barr will receive the
    National Hero of the Year award for her actions in crawling
    under an Amtrak train to try and save victims trapped inside
    a burning commuter train in suburban Washington, D.C. Donald
    Coldwell was selected as the National Humanitarian for his
    family's commitment to provide foster care. </p>
    <p>Regional heroes include Guy A. Young from Manchester,
    N.H., who helped save an infant trapped in an overturned van;
    Mark A. Hopkins of Chicago, who saved an elderly man being
    assaulted and robbed at an ATM machine; and Carlos E.
    Tichenor of Topeka, Kan., who came to the assistance of a
    police officer overpowered by a disorderly man at a post
    office. </p>
    <p>Bricklayers Local 1 in Detroit won the &quot;Best Brick
    Project&quot; award from the International Masonry Institute
    for its construction of the new Veterans Administration
    Hospital. </p>
    <p>Farm Workers President Arturo Rodriguez will receive the
    Labor Award from the Southern California Americans for
    Democratic Action. </p>
    <p>DEATHS </p>
    <p>Jesse A. Friedman, an international labor representative
    and union educator, died of cancer at age 62. </p>
    <p>Friedman, a longtime member of the Ladies' Garment
    Workers, now UNITE, devoted all of his professional life to
    organizing and supporting workers in the United States, Latin
    America and the Caribbean. He began his career working in the
    St. John's Labor Center in Annapolis, Md., and joined the
    U.S. Labor Department in 1960. In 1962, he was appointed
    assistant Latin American representative in the AFL-CIO's
    International Affairs Department. </p>
    <p>In 1967, Friedman joined the American Institute for Free
    Labor Development and served as regional director and deputy
    executive director before being named executive director in
    1996. From 1977 until his death, Friedman was a member of the
    AFL-CIO delegation to the annual conferences of the
    International Labor Organization, where he participated on
    many committees responsible for drafting standards designed
    to protect workers' rights. </p>
    <p>He is survived by his wife, four daughters and two
    brothers. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
