<head>
<title>Labor, academic allies join forces for U.S. teach-ins</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><strong><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"><br>
September 20, 1996</strong></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>Labor, academic
    allies join forces for U.S. teach-ins<br>
    </strong></font><font size="3">by<br>
    </font>Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p>America's workers are joining their academic allies in a
    national campaign on the re-energized labor movement. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney announced the new
    alliance at a Washington news conference Sept. 18 along with
    feminist author Betty Friedan, civil rights activist and
    history professor Roger Wilkins, American Association of
    University Professors President James E. Perley and other
    academics. </p>
    <p>&quot;This new initiative, `A Teach-In with the Labor
    Movement,' proves there is no gap between young Americans and
    those who nurture, mentor and teach them,&quot; Sweeney said.
    &quot;This teach-in adds a powerful new dimension to the
    development of the new and stronger voice for working
    families we're working so hard to create.&quot; </p>
    <p>The teach-ins are designed to promote a new spirit of
    engagement and activism by serving as a way to stimulate a
    national dialogue between academics and trade unionists.
    Subjects for discussion include immigration, the globalized
    economy, organizing among African-Americans, welfare and
    work, families and feminism, labor political action and
    culture, identity and class politics. </p>
    <p>A national event at Columbia University Oct. 3-4 kicks off
    the campaign. Joining Sweeney and Friedan at Columbia the
    first night will be Harvard theologian Cornel West,
    University of Virginia philosopher Richard Rorty and, from
    Columbia, historian Eric Foner and law professor Patricia
    Williams. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka and
    Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson lead a
    distinguished group of participants that includes AFL-CIO
    Working Women Director Karen Nussbaum, Columbia
    African-American Studies Chair Manning Marable, feminist
    essayist and poet Katha Pollitt, AFSCME International Area
    Director Jose LaLuz and Yale historian David Montgomery,
    among others. </p>
    <p>Regional teach-ins are scheduled throughout October at
    Wayne State University, Detroit; University of Cincinnati;
    Clinch Valley College, Wise, Va.; University of Nevada, Las
    Vegas; Eastern Illinois University, Charleston, Ill.;
    University of Texas at El Paso; University of Florida,
    Tallahassee; University of Wisconsin, Madison; and State
    University of New York-Geneseo. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
