<head>
<title>Workers get raise as campaign rolls on</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1993</strong></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4">Workers get raise as campaign
rolls on<br>
Minimum wage raise delivered by union drive <br>
</font><font size="3">by</font></p>
<p align="center">Mike Hall</p>
<blockquote>
    <p>With two dozen minimum- and low-wage workers and their
    children looking on, President Clinton signed legislation
    giving America's lowest-paid workers a 90-cent-an-hour raise
    during an Aug. 20 ceremony on the White House South Lawn. </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO spearheaded the nationwide grass-roots drive
    that overcame deep-seated Republican hostility and all-out
    business opposition to the wage increase. </p>
    <p>That grass-roots effort continues in full swing.
    Television and radio ads, press conferences and public events
    held over the August recess let voters know about GOP moves
    to raid pensions, slash education and strip hundreds of
    billions of dollars in vital state and county aid. </p>
    <p>This followed up on earlier campaigns exposing GOP efforts
    to slash Medicare and Medicaid and block an increase in the
    minimum wage. </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO campaign to educate the public on the issues
    and mobilize members around those issues has the strong
    backing of union members, a new poll reveals, with 72 percent
    approving of television and radio ads. The survey was
    conducted Aug 2-4 by Peter D. Hart Research Associates. </p>
    <p>Prior to the White House signing, AFL-CIO President John
    J. Sweeney told the workers and their children at the
    federation's headquarters, &quot;Six months ago nobody agreed
    with us that we would have an increase in the minimum wage.
    It's the result of you and your unions pushing your members
    of Congress that brings us here today.&quot; </p>
    <p>He also urged them &quot;to remain active in your
    communities and your unions.&quot; </p>
    <p>The first 45-cent increase in the minimum wage takes
    effect Oct. 1, boosting it from $4.25 to $4.70 an hour. The
    second 45-cent step takes place Sept. 1, 1997, bringing the
    minimum wage to $5.15. </p>
    <p>Clinton thanked the labor movement for its efforts on
    behalf of the minimum wage increase, noting that &quot;there
    are very few unions in America that have minimum wage
    workers. Most of these unions did this because they thought
    it was the right thing to do.&quot; </p>
    <p>Clinton also signed the Kennedy-Kassebaum health
    portability bill, which Sweeney called a &quot;step in the
    right direction&quot; while noting the &quot;serious and
    unmet need for broad health care reform.&quot; </p>
    <p>The signings mark a high point in what has been a fruitful
    legislative season for America's working families &thorn;
    defeat of the company union TEAM Act and a national
    right-to-work-law and an easing of the GOP attack on the
    Occupational Safety and Health Administration and the
    National Labor Relations Board. </p>
    <p>Labor's success despite a hostile, Republican-controlled
    Congress can be traced to the growing grass-roots involvement
    of working families. Angry at labor's victories, GOP leaders
    have attacked the AFL-CIO's efforts, using loaded questions
    and shoddy methodology to grandly announce that union members
    don't support the federation's efforts. </p>
    <p>The new Hart poll paints a more accurate picture. It found
    that nearly three-quarters of union members say that their
    unions should either maintain their current level of
    involvement in political activity or should increase it. </p>
    <p>Sixty-seven percent of the members have a positive
    reaction to the AFL-CIO's overall campaign &thorn; the media
    push plus grass-roots mobilizing and political organizing in
    congressional districts &thorn; to educate and inform
    members, with only 11 percent negative. </p>
    <p>Contrary to Republican arguments that a significant
    minority of union members back GOP policies and object to the
    federation's campaign, only 17 percent of those surveyed said
    they would be more likely to support a candidate who has
    solidly backed Newt Gingrich's GOP agenda in Congress. </p>
    <p>A solid majority of members support the way the AFL-CIO
    campaign is being funded. By 71-25 percent, members say they
    approve of using $1.80 from their regular dues on a one-time
    basis to inform union members about issues and elections. </p>
    <p>An Aug. 20 article in The Wall Street Journal confirms the
    AFL-CIO contention that GOP congressional leaders have
    launched a calculated anti-union campaign, in concert with
    business groups, to &quot;get even&quot; with unions for
    their mobilization efforts. </p>
    <p>The article noted the $30 million the GOP is spending to
    attack the AFL-CIO's ads and their use of libel and
    regulatory threats against television stations in an attempt
    to keep the ads off the air, although few stations have done
    so. </p>
    <p>Rep. John Boehner (R-Ohio) &quot;prodded business
    lobbyists&quot; to crank up their own multimillion-dollar
    counterpunch to the AFL-CIO, the article states. </p>
    <p>&quot;Wary of Federal Election Commission rules
    themselves, the GOP leaders deny coordinating their campaign
    with the business coalition. Some coalition members attend
    regular National Republican Congressional Committee briefings
    about which candidates need help,&quot; the Journal reported. </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, in the field, a new series of ads highlighting
    targeted legislators' votes to slash millions from a vital
    student loan program will begin airing this week. </p>
    <p>Dozens of press conferences and events have been held in
    Labor '96 congressional districts since the beginning of the
    August recess, highlighting GOP stances on pension issues
    (See story, this page), celebrating the minimum wage victory
    or outlining the devastating county-by-county impact of the
    GOP's proposed 1997 budget cuts. </p>
    <p>In Irving, Texas, House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey
    (R) got a chance to eat some of his words. Armey had said
    last year, &quot;I will fight the minimum wage increase with
    every fiber of my being.&quot; </p>
    <p>Union members and minimum-wage workers presented him with
    515 boxes &thorn; the minimum wage will rise to $5.15 an hour
    &thorn; of high fiber cereal. He did not invite the
    demonstrators in for breakfast. </p>
    <p>Rep. Steven C. LaTourette (R-Ohio) was greeted by a group
    of mourners dressed in black carrying a casket at his annual
    golf fund-raiser. </p>
    <p>The casket was covered with dead vines to represent the
    withering of such vital government programs as Medicare, Head
    Start, student loans and school lunches &thorn; all
    threatened by LaTourette's votes. </p>
    <p>&quot;His votes are against seniors, children, the
    disabled, college students and working families, so I guess
    the only people he really represents are the ones who can
    afford to take a day off work and pay for the privilege of
    playing golf with him,&quot; said Don Chadwick, a retired
    Paperworker and Labor '96 volunteer. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
