<html>
<head>
<title>Labor '96 builds momentum</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4">Labor '96 builds momentum<br>
</font><font size="3">by </font></p>
<p align="center">Michael Byrne</p>
<blockquote>
    <p>Amid the hoopla of political conventions, that buzz you
    hear is union members from coast to coast massing for labor's
    ambitious drive to reclaim America for working families. </p>
    <p>Labor '96 was in full swing months ahead of the
    traditional Labor Day political launch, with 135 full-time
    coordinators mobilizing union members in 84 congressional
    districts across the country. As Republicans gathered Aug. 11
    for their convention in San Diego, the coordinators were
    mapping out get-out-the-vote strategies in a meeting with
    state federation officials and AFL-CIO staff. </p>
    <p>When the Democrats bring down the gavel for their
    convention in Chicago Aug. 26, just as the nation's attention
    turns back to school, those coordinators will be back in
    their districts explaining how some members of Congress had
    voted to drastically reduce the student loan program. </p>
    <p>The grass-roots activity keyed on student loans was
    accompanied by targeted television and radio advertisements
    on the issue, adding to the insistent &quot;air war&quot;
    volleys that have strafed anti-worker candidates throughout
    the year and raised the hackles of the extremist Republican
    leadership in Congress. </p>
    <p>&quot;The proof of the success we've been having so early
    in this campaign is the attacks that are being made against
    us &thorn; just because we have told the truth and just
    because we are mobilizing our membership,&quot; AFL-CIO
    President John J. Sweeney told the coordinators at the
    planning session held at the Maritime Institute of Technology
    and Graduate Studies in Linthicum Heights, Md. </p>
    <p>&quot;But we can't be overconfident,&quot; Sweeney said.
    &quot;The crucial part of your agenda is how the end game
    will be played out. We have to go all out. There's too much
    at stake.&quot; </p>
    <p>The stakes were raised even higher at the Republican
    convention, where delegates approved a party platform that
    embraced the company-union TEAM Act, called for the
    relaxation of labor laws including the Davis-Bacon and
    Service Contract Acts, as well as the overtime provisions of
    the Fair Labor Standards Act. It criticized teachers' unions,
    called for the privatization of government services and
    endorsed state &quot;right-to-work&quot; laws. </p>
    <p>The convention also nominated Bob Dole, who had unveiled a
    tax-cut proposal that would mostly benefit the wealthy while
    requiring massive cuts in Medicare, Medicaid, education,
    health and safety and other programs that serve working
    families. </p>
    <p>&quot;Working families have heard these promises before,
    and won't be fooled again,&quot; the AFL-CIO Executive
    Council said during its summer meeting in Chicago, pointing
    to the same kind of supply-side tax cuts in the `80s that had
    ballooned the deficit. Dole's supply- side cuts &quot;will
    only serve to widen the already obscene gap between rich and
    poor,&quot; it said. </p>
    <p>Working families were expecting to get a better hearing at
    the Democratic convention, where 795 delegates &thorn; fully
    one-quarter of the total &thorn; were union members. The
    Democratic Party platform draft embraced workers' rights to
    form unions and to bargain collectively, and rejected right
    to work and the TEAM Act. It also opposed efforts to gut the
    Occupational Safety and Health Administration and the
    National Labor Relations Board. </p>
    <p>Still, &quot;some forces within the Democratic Party would
    shrink from the commitment to make the economy work for
    working Americans,&quot; the AFL-CIO's top officers said in a
    statement that traced the traditional alliance between the
    labor movement and the Democrats. </p>
    <p>&quot;In the face of the harsh new global economy, they
    would minimize, not modernize, the institutions that offer
    working people a measure of security &thorn; an active
    national government, a social safety net and strong
    unions.&quot; </p>
    <p>The statement by Sweeney, Secretary-Treasurer Richard L.
    Trumka and Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson
    called upon the Democrats to: </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Help working families share in the gains of a growing
            economy. </li>
        <li>Reaffirm their belief that working people must have
            an independent voice on their jobs and be partners
            with their employers, enjoying a share of the benefit
            of their efforts to make their companies vital and
            productive. </li>
        <li>Demand that corporate America show some
            responsibility to our communities and our country. </li>
        <li>Advance the idea that jobs must come with living
            wages, health care, training opportunities and secure
            pensions. </li>
        <li>Support social policies that lift the most vulnerable
            into jobs, instead of abandoning them and their
            children. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>The AFL-CIO &quot;enthusiastically supports the
    re-election of President Clinton and the return of a
    Democratic Congress,&quot; the executive officers said.
    &quot;We agree with President Clinton that his economic
    accomplishments are `a record to build on, not rest on.' Too
    many working families have not yet benefited from economic
    gains.&quot; </p>
    <p>The statement also pointed out that Labor `96 &quot;is
    independent of the major parties. It's about empowering
    working families &thorn; not electing Democrats or
    Republicans.&quot; </p>
    <p>Sweeney reiterated that point in his address to the
    coordinators at their planning session. &quot;We will not
    measure our success by the numbers of this election, but by
    our ability to talk to and motivate our membership,&quot; he
    said. &quot;This is about the future of the labor
    movement.&quot; </p>
    <p>Brenda Wood, who is coordinating Labor `96 efforts in two
    Washington state congressional districts, said her work is
    concentrated on &quot;involving the membership. We are
    talking about political issues, but we are really involved in
    internal organizing. We are building our unions.&quot; </p>
    <p>Indeed, the goal of Labor &thorn;96 is to create a
    permanent grass- roots structure in every congressional
    district that will allow working families to hold
    office-holders accountable for their actions. District
    coordinators are building that network by enlisting new
    volunteers, aiming at a core of 10,000 activists working to
    get out the vote this year. </p>
    <p>Those volunteers will be reaching out to union members
    throughout September and October, explaining the issues in
    the campaign and urging them to vote for candidates who will
    stand with them and their families. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
