<html>
<head>
<title>Union Summer bears fruit nationwide</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif"
align="bottom" width="443" height="140"></font></p>
<p align="center"><font size="3"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></font></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4">Union Summer bears fruit
nationwide<br>
</font><font size="3">by</font></p>
<p align="center">Muriel H. Cooper </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>Union Summer is ending spectacularly for the AFL-CIO and
    for the young activists who lent a powerful new voice to the
    struggle for justice across the country. </p>
    <p>That voice, delivered in high volume and in theatrical
    performances, is being credited with gaining a first contract
    for workers at the plush Melrose Club resort in Hilton Head,
    S.C. </p>
    <p>Other organizing campaigns made breakthroughs as a result
    of the energy infusion of Union Summer, but the most lasting
    impact may have come in the positive impressions made in
    communities across the country, and on the young people being
    exposed for the first time to the trials of working people. </p>
    <p>&quot;We wanted to send a strong message to young people
    as well as to all working people that the labor movement is a
    strong voice for economic justice,&quot; AFL-CIO President
    John J. Sweeney told the Executive Council in Chicago.
    &quot;We have been very successful.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;This was one of the most concrete opportunities to
    do something to make the next generation of Americans
    overcome differences and diversity to unite and fight for
    justice at work,&quot; Andy Levin, director of the program,
    told the council. </p>
    <p>The Melrose win perhaps best symbolized the purpose and
    the promise of the federation's nine-week campaign. </p>
    <p>&quot;We had three goals &thorn; to get a contract, to
    gather information to set up other campaigns in the area and
    to get young people excited abut the labor movement,&quot;
    said Simon Greer, site coordinator in Charleston. &quot;And
    we did it.&quot; </p>
    <p>Three waves of activists built on the two years of work
    done by the Operating Engineers and the &quot;low
    country&quot; community surrounding the resort area to force
    Melrose into contract negotiations. On Aug. 14, workers
    celebrated a two-year contract that includes comprehensive
    health care, job security, wage increases, a grievance
    procedure and arbitration. </p>
    <p>&quot;The Union Summer activists walked into a heated
    battle,&quot; said Greer. &quot;Each wave stepped up the
    pressure, and just when it looked like Melrose was not going
    to crack, it cracked. Management said we won the war.&quot; </p>
    <p>The activists used a number of creative tactics, including
    guerrilla theater performances in various restaurants, pools
    and hotels on the resort island, running in the annual road
    race while demonstrating with signs to support the workers,
    and talking to the neighbors of Melrose's managers about
    workers' concerns. </p>
    <p>&quot;The union and Melrose employees have been fighting
    long and hard for this contract and we would not be
    celebrating this victory so early if not for the daily,
    in-your-face tactics of Union Summer activists,&quot; said
    David Miller an IUOE representative. </p>
    <p>In his report to the council, Levin noted that more than
    3,500 young people applied for Union Summer. Almost half of
    the applicants have parents who are union members.
    Fifty-eight percent of the June and July participants were
    women and 48 percent were people of color, reflecting the
    current rainbow work force. </p>
    <p>At least 26 unions put Union Summer activists to work on
    their organizing campaigns. Alliances were formed and
    strengthened with many community and religious organizations. </p>
    <p>Union Summer also has served as a union-building operation
    at the local level, said AFL-CIO Organizing Director Richard
    Bensinger. </p>
    <p>&quot;Union Summer has helped to energize local
    unions,&quot; he said. &quot;It has helped to create models
    for campaigns in which we allocate more resources to
    organizing, as well as involve rank and file and community
    allies in our efforts.&quot; </p>
    <p>Activists have worked closely with Jobs with Justice and
    ACORN (A Community Organization on Reform Now) at several
    sites, with Californians for Justice at three locations, the
    Carolina Alliance for Fair Employment (CAFE) in Hilton Head,
    the Summit County Organizing for Rights and Equality (SCORE)
    in Akron and various religious organizations on behalf of
    living wage initiatives. </p>
    <p>The interns immersed themselves in creative substance,
    distributing more than 150,000 leaflets, collecting more than
    65,000 signatures on petitions, conducting 4,088 house visits
    with workers in organizing campaigns and registering 3,237
    voters. </p>
    <p>Activists in Los Angeles leafleted Camachos Restaurant
    more than 15 times during a three-week period, convincing
    management to recognize the Hotel Employees and Restaurant
    Employees Local 814 and rehire all the workers whose status
    was disputed. </p>
    <p>Food and Commercial Workers Local 876 credited the work of
    activists with helping to wrestle a master contract and
    neutrality agreement from a Michigan drug store chain. </p>
    <p>Service Employees Local 790 said Union Summer house calls
    and work site visists were instrumental in winning a unit of
    substitutes teachers in the Oakland school district. </p>
    <p>Working with the Electrical Workers in Seattle, activists
    actually shut down a nonunion hiring hall. They showed up on
    Friday and announced they would be back on Monday at 5 a.m.
    When they arrived, the hall shut down, effectively putting
    the nonunion operation out of business for a day. </p>
    <p>&quot;For a young person to feel the power of that had a
    huge effect,&quot; Levin told the council. </p>
    <p>On Aug. 14, activists across the country leafleted grocery
    stores, seeking consumer support of strawberry farm workers
    who want a living wage, clean drinking water and bathrooms in
    the fields, health insurance, job security and an end to
    sexual harassment and other abuses. </p>
    <p>A three-weeklong Southern bus tour leafleted dozens of
    nursing homes in the deep South as part of the UFCW's
    &quot;Care For the Caregiver&quot; campaign. Several
    organizing leads came out of the effort and, in one case,
    activists helped gather signatures on union cards from the
    majority of the workers. </p>
    <p>About 200 of the participants now will go through the
    Organizing Institute. More than 50 activists were hired on
    the spot by unions to work on campaigns. </p>
    <p>&quot;The largest goal of Union Summer is to have an
    impact on the next generation, to get people to respect
    picket lines, to have unions and working people issues as
    fundamental part of their politics,&quot; said Levin. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
