<html>
<head>
<title>Organizing: UNITE scores two ways; AFTRA puts $$</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="5">Organizing:</font></p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="#UNITE"><font size="4">UNITE scores
two ways</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a href="#AFTRA "><font
size="4">AFTRA puts $$ in cable</font></a><font size="4">; <br>
</font><a href="#TEAM"><font size="4">Tripe-team workers</font></a><font
size="4">; </font><a href="#SEIU "><font size="4">Lucky seven for
SEIU</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a href="#IBT"><font
size="4"><br>
IBT wins new vote</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a
href="#VOL"><font size="4">Volunteers boost win </font></a><font
size="4"><br>
</font></p>
<blockquote>
    <p><a name="UNITE"><strong>UNITE</strong></a><strong> scores
    two ways </strong></p>
    <p>UNITE will represent workers at FDR Services in Rome, Ga.,
    following a highly successful card-check campaign, and
    workers at Dixie Kids in Fayetteville, N.C., after a
    representation election. </p>
    <p>Ninety-five percent of the workers signed union cards at
    FDR, an industrial laundry that services hospitals. The
    workers will receive free health insurance, sick days and
    wage improvements in their first contract. </p>
    <p>Poor working conditions, low wages and unaffordable health
    insurance prompted Dixie Kids workers to vote 76-62 for
    UNITE. &quot;Dixie Kids workers have joined a growing trend
    among eastern North Carolina workers to organize in the
    traditionally anti-union part of the country,&quot; said
    Bruce Raynor, executive vice president and southern regional
    director of UNITE. </p>
    <p><a name="AFTRA "><strong>AFTRA puts $$ in cable </strong></a></p>
    <p>The Television and Radio Artists have earmarked $1.25
    million to organize in the cable entertainment and news
    programming industry. </p>
    <p>&quot;We understand the size and complexity of this
    project,&quot; said Bruce York, AFTRA's national executive
    director. &quot;The recent restructuring of AFTRA with the
    locals forming a closer relationship with the national makes
    financial commitments like this possible. Our governing
    boards and members have now provided the union with the
    resources to be successful in the new broadcast and
    entertainment world in which our members work.&quot; </p>
    <p>AFTRA already has several cable contracts in place,
    including The Nashville Network, Home Box Office and E!
    Entertainment. </p>
    <p><a name="TEAM"><strong>Triple-team works </strong></a></p>
    <p>The Machinists are seeing the benefits of their
    unification talks with the UAW and the Steelworkers as the
    three joined to beat back the anti-union campaign at
    Maremount Corp. in Loudon, Tenn. The workers voted 369-272
    for the union. </p>
    <p>&quot;Here are the early fruits from our unification talks
    with the UAW and the Steelworkers,&quot; said Gary Will, IAM
    organizing director. &quot;The UAW sent in four people to
    help in the campaign. They house- called, handbilled at the
    plant gates and went one-on-one with the workers.&quot; </p>
    <p>Two UAW members from Maremount's sister plant in Alabama
    also were involved in organizing the workers. </p>
    <p><a name="SEIU "><strong>Lucky seven for SEIU </strong></a></p>
    <p>Service Employees scored another series of victories at
    worksites across the country, including a 167-104 vote by
    nurses at Los Robles Hospital in California's San Fernando
    Valley. The win by Local 535 capped an organizing drive that
    was worker-led. The nurses paid union dues and built their
    organization for more than a year before filing for an
    election. </p>
    <p>Local 236 in Chicago won card-check recognition for 180
    ushers employed by Safety Service Systems. The ushers work at
    Soldiers Field, home of the Chicago Bears, Dyche Stadium,
    where the Northwestern Wildcats play, Rosemont Theatre and
    Rosemont Horizon. </p>
    <p>A unit of 18 sterile supply technicians at the University
    of Illinois voted to join SEIU Local 73, while Local 1 won an
    election for 13 janitors at Prairie Court, a Chicago Housing
    Authority property. </p>
    <p>Health care professionals at Peoples Community Care
    Residence (PCCR) in St. Paul, Minn., voted by a 2-1 margin
    for SEIU representation, and Local 1199IN organized a unit of
    37 city- employed emergency medical service workers in Gary,
    Ind. </p>
    <p>In Seattle, District 925 won an election for 27 patient
    account reps and other workers at Children's University
    Medical Group. </p>
    <p><a name="IBT"><strong>IBT wins new vote </strong></a></p>
    <p>After the National Labor Relations Board set aside their
    first election, employees of Fiber Sales and Development
    Corp. of Urbana, Ohio, voted by a 2-1 majority for Teamsters
    representation. </p>
    <p>The NLRB determined that before the November 1995
    election, the company had offered a reduction in
    employee-paid health care premiums in order to improperly
    influence the outcome of the election. </p>
    <p>Fiber Sales is a subsidiary of the St. Louis-based Ralston
    Purina Co. The workers manufacture powdered cellulose for use
    as an additive in other products. </p>
    <p><a name="VOL"><strong>Volunteers boost win </strong></a></p>
    <p>With the help of District 7 volunteers, the Steelworkers
    won a 91-51 representation election at MEG Corp. in Cambridge
    City, Ind. </p>
    <p>The volunteer organizers helped in house calls to more
    than half of the work force. In their discussions, the
    volunteers learned that the workers were seeking respect and
    dignity and better wages. About half of the MEG employees are
    women, and many complained of sexual discrimination. </p>
    <p>The company manufactures metal shelving for businesses. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
