<html>
<head>
<title>Kmart retail union chooses UFCW</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Kmart retail unit chooses
    UFCW<br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Muriel H. Cooper </p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p>Meatcutters at a Super Kmart in Oakland, Calif., will be
    represented by the Food and Commercial Workers, which hailed
    the victory as a breakthrough against the anti-union company. </p>
    <p>&quot;It's a very important election because Kmart is
    nonunion all over America,&quot; said Charlie Fortenberry,
    UFCW Local 120 business agent. </p>
    <p>Although the Teamsters and UNITE have organized Kmart
    warehouse operations, the Oakland meatcutters were the first
    retail unit to vote union. UFCW Local 870 said the election
    will help in the drive to unionize retail clerks at the
    store. </p>
    <p>&quot;It's going to help propel us to a win,
    hopefully,&quot; said John Nunes, Local 870 business agent.
    &quot;The workers are real excited about it. We had a lot of
    confidence, too. It's going to help propel us.&quot; </p>
    <p>A large number of the 550 retail workers in the Oakland
    store have signed union cards. The union petitioned the
    National Labor Relations Board for an election in late July,
    but it was postponed at the request of the company attorneys. </p>
    <p>Kmart has reduced the work force at its Oakland store by
    half since it opened in November, a major reason that workers
    contacted the union. Workers also were harassed, accused of
    stealing and told to resign. </p>
    <p>Oakland is &quot;a strong labor town, and a lot of these
    workers came from union families, and they understand the
    importance of working under a union contract,&quot; said
    Nunes. </p>
    <p>The UFCW has joined with several community groups &quot;to
    bring to light a lot of this treatment at the store and the
    expectations of the workers,&quot; who were led to believe
    they had career opportunities. </p>
    <p>The local has filed several unfair labor practice charges
    with the NLRB claiming that Kmart fired workers for union
    activities, and spied on and threatened the workers. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
