http://aflcio.org:80/newsonline/96aug23/pensions.htm 204.127.237.106 19970215104018 text/html 5422
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 10:39:51 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 11-Feb-97 14:26:33 GMT
Content-length: 5237
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Pension raids highlighted in ads, events</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Pension raids highlighted in
    ads <br>
    New pension protection measure pending in House <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p>You work hard all your life for an honest day's work for
    an honest day's pay and the promise of secure income when
    your working days are through. </p>
    <p>Edith Thomson knows that promise is easily broken by
    ruthless employers because &thorn; after giving 41 years of
    her life to Carter- Hawley-Hale Stores Inc. &thorn; her
    401(k) money vanished when the company went bankrupt. </p>
    <p>Her story is featured in radio and television ads the
    AFL-CIO ran during the August congressional recess. Thomson's
    company had invested its workers' 401(k) funds in its own
    stock, so that &quot;when they went broke, they had used my
    retirement money already, so there was nothing left,&quot;
    she said. </p>
    <p>She lost more than $87,000. </p>
    <p>The federation's ads pointed out that Congress has
    considered pension issues several times over the last two
    years, and urged legislators to tighten 401(k) rules and
    oppose allowing company CEOs to gain control of workers'
    &quot;excess&quot; pension funds. </p>
    <p>Grass-roots activists drove the point home with picnics,
    press conferences, leafleting, picketing and the like. </p>
    <p>In North Carolina, for example, a Teamsters member
    participated in a forum at a church along with an AARP member
    and representatives of Citizen Action. In Idaho, a press
    conference at the Boise Senior Center garnered coverage from
    all the local media, who then befuddled GOP Rep. Helen
    Chenoweth's staff looking for a response. </p>
    <p>Leafleters were out in full force in Gloucester, Mass.,
    while Thomson herself participated in an event in Eureka,
    Calif. </p>
    <p>The latest round of well-founded worker anxiety over
    pension security can be traced to the serious consideration
    given a proposal on Capitol Hill last year to allow employers
    to take out of their workers' pension funds that amount
    deemed an &quot;overage&quot; &thorn; and to spend this money
    at will. </p>
    <p>Legislation was passed in 1990 to clamp down on such free
    spending by corporate officers of workers' money &thorn; but
    GOP lawmakers saw a chance to unfund workers and give the
    funds to their Big Business friends. The so-called pension
    raid of 1995 was slipped into the GOP budget reconciliation
    bill, but it was vetoed by President Clinton. </p>
    <p>Anxiety over pension funds remains strong, giving rise to
    new pension protection legislation. One such proposal &thorn;
    H.R. 3688 &thorn; would have saved Edith Thomson's money. It
    would put employees' 401(k) funds further away from employers
    by subjecting 401(k) plans to the same rules that govern
    pensions, such as a 10 percent restriction on
    employer-related real estate and securities. </p>
    <p>Currently, some 20 percent of 401(k) retirement plans are
    managed by companies, meaning the money is in the hands of
    the employer, not the workers. A disturbing number of those
    businesses are straying into risky investments with workers'
    and retirees' funds. </p>
    <p>Secretary of Labor Robert B. Reich also took on the issue
    of pensions during the August recess, announcing tighter
    standards on deposits of 401(k) money into accounts.
    Employers currently have 90 days to deposit funds in workers'
    accounts; under new rules announced in early August,
    employers will have 15 business days after the end of the
    month to square their books. </p>
    <p>Reich said his department had found employers using the
    three- month grace period as a kind of automatic float, from
    which they would benefit from interest. The DoL estimates
    that will give American workers an extra $76 million in
    interest in 1997. </p>
    <p>The rule goes into affect in six months &thorn; later for
    union members with existing contracts. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
