<head>
<title>OSHA targets worker safety at nursing homes</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">OSHA targets worker safety
    at nursing homes <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p>Nursing home workers will gain greater safety provided a
    recently announced safety and health initiative does the job. </p>
    <p>Secretary of Labor Robert B. Reich acted Aug. 8 in the
    face of mounting injuries and illnesses among workers at
    these facilities. </p>
    <p>Under the initiative, the Occupational Safety and Health
    Administration will conduct free, comprehensive seminars
    beginning this fall in Pennsylvania, New York, Missouri,
    Ohio, Illinois, Florida and Massachusetts, with the goal of
    helping employers develop safety and health programs,
    identify and prevent injuries and illnesses related to blood
    borne pathogens, tuberculosis and handling of residents, as
    well as prevent workplace violence. </p>
    <p>Those seven states all have more than 500 nursing home
    facilities. </p>
    <p>Nursing home workers suffered more than 221,000 nonfatal
    injuries in 1994 &thorn; making the industry more dangerous
    than construction, mining, electrical work and automobile
    repair, the Bureau of Labor Statistics reported. </p>
    <p>The number of lost workdays per 100 full-time nursing home
    workers increased from 98.2 in 1983 to 186.9 in 1993,
    according to the Service Employees. </p>
    <p>The goal of the new program, Labor officials say, is to
    disseminate information, give employers a chance to make
    changes, gather workers' compensation data and then focus on
    those companies with the highest rates of injury. The
    ultimate focus is training for prevention of injuries and
    illnesses, officials said. </p>
    <p>&quot;Nursing home work is one of the most dangerous jobs
    in America,&quot; SEIU President Andrew L. Stern said.
    &quot;Nearly one in five nursing home workers will be injured
    on the job this year. This initiative is a giant step forward
    in the fight to curb those injuries so that workers can
    safely provide the best possible care for their elderly
    patients.&quot; </p>
    <p>SEIU and the American Association of Homes and Services
    for the Aging are to assist OSHA in the outreach effort. SEIU
    issued a report in 1995 on nursing home safety for employees
    titled &quot;Caring Till It Hurts.&quot; </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
