<head>
<title>N.C. strikers hungry for justice</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">N.C. strikers hungry for
    justice <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>Hundreds of workers and their allies, including Union
    Summer activists from Hilton Head, S.C., joined a &quot;March
    for Justice&quot; organized by religious leaders in support
    of 450 striking Laborers at Case Farms in Morganton, N.C. </p>
    <p>The workers walked out of the poultry processing plant in
    mid- August after the company refused to recognize or bargain
    with LIUNA. In addition, two of the strikers &thorn; Luis
    Alberto Gonzalez and Roberto Mendoza &thorn; began a hunger
    strike, to &quot;Fast and Pray for Justice,&quot; outside of
    the plant. </p>
    <p>The workers voted for the union last year after
    documenting numerous incidents of abuse and exploitation by
    plant managers. Since the election, the company has fired 38
    workers for union activity. </p>
    <p>The National Labor Relations Board overruled Case Farms'
    objections and ordered the company to bargain with the
    workers. </p>
    <p>&quot;These workers are striving to provide decent lives
    for themselves and their families through hard work and
    personal sacrifice,&quot; said LIUNA President Arthur A.
    Coia. &quot;They, like so many of our ancestors, came to this
    country in search of liberty and justice. The management at
    Case Farms has done everything in their power to keep these
    workers from achieving these noble ends.&quot; </p>
    <p>In July, almost one-third of the workers walked out to
    protest the illegal firing of one worker dumped when he
    protested the increased speed of the chicken carcass
    production line. The worker was rehired and the strikers
    returned to work. </p>
    <p>The National Interfaith Committee for Worker Justice
    reported terrible conditions after a late-April fact-finding
    visit to Case Farms. &quot;We work eight-hour shifts with
    only one bathroom break,&quot; said Francisco Ramirez.
    &quot;My co-worker was forced to continue working even when
    his wrist swelled up to the size of a grapefruit because of
    repetitive stress/carpal tunnel syndrome,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>&quot;I hunger for justice,&quot; said Gonzalez. &quot;I
    am prepared to starve myself until Case Farms will sit down
    and bargain with us. I will not let the company treat us with
    such disrespect and injustice.&quot; </p>
    <p>Setting the stage for the Aug. 17 march, hundreds of New
    York City building trades workers held a rally on Wall Street
    in front of the Bank of New York &thorn; Case Farms' primary
    commercial lender &thorn; urging the bank to stop financing
    the company's abusive and illegal practices. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
