<html>
<head>
<title>Tighter rules sought to prevent workplace violence</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Tighter rules sought to
    prevent workplace violence at night <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>While commending the Occupational Safety and Health
    Administration for proposing guidelines for late-night
    workplace violence prevention programs, unions are urging
    that the guidelines be broadened. </p>
    <p>&quot;There is no definition of what constitutes
    night,&quot; the Inter- Union Workplace Physical Violence
    Coalition wrote, expressing concern that only those stores
    open 24 hours may implement preventive programs, while those
    open after dark, even until 11 p.m., will not consider
    themselves night establishments. </p>
    <p>In another comment, Food and Commercial Workers Local 770
    detailed several incidents that occurred during morning hours
    in retail supermarkets. The union recommended that the title
    be changed to &quot;guidelines for the retail industry, with
    a special emphasis on night retail establishments.&quot; </p>
    <p>The goal of the guidelines is to eliminate or reduce
    conditions that raise retail workers' chances of death or
    injury. The guidelines are to provide employers with specific
    options that could be taken to protect workers employed after
    dark. </p>
    <p>The numbers substantiate the urgency. About 1 million
    workers are assaulted and more than 1,000 workers are
    murdered annually as a result of workplace violence,
    according to a report released last month by the National
    Institute for Occupational Safety and Health. </p>
    <p>NIOSH data indicate that homicide is the second-leading
    cause of occupational death, surpassed only by motor
    vehicle-related deaths. Workplace homicides increased in the
    1990s after decreasing significantly in the 1980s, the report
    said. </p>
    <p>The greatest number of deaths during the period 1980-1992
    occurred in the retail industry, followed by public
    administration. </p>
    <p>Unions are concerned about the &quot;voluntary&quot;
    nature of the guidelines, urging the agency to make them
    mandatory. </p>
    <p>Other suggestions from the unions included greater worker
    involvement, hazard prevention, training and telephone
    access. Comments submitted by the AFL-CIO request that
    telephone access for workers be included among the
    recommended engineering controls. </p>
    <p>The deadline for comments has been extended to Sept. 30. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
