<html>
<head>
<title>Economics education puts workers in equation</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Economics education puts
    workers in equation <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">David Kameras </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO is mounting an unprecedented economics
    education program for union members. </p>
    <p>The program is being field-tested as a basic part of the
    federation's massive member mobilization campaign this
    election year, and it will become an essential part of union
    educational programs in the years to come. </p>
    <p>&quot;This is a significant step in labor education as a
    whole,&quot; said Robert Pleasure, President John J.
    Sweeney's assistant for education, at the Executive Council
    meeting in Chicago. &quot;For the labor movement to achieve
    its organizing, political, legislative and collective
    bargaining goals, we need to deepen members' understanding of
    the economic context of their union and community
    activity.&quot; </p>
    <p>He described the initial phase in which the program, as a
    corollary to Labor '96, is educating members in political
    campaigns and educating candidates about the needs and
    challenges facing working Americans. </p>
    <p>&quot;But I think this program goes far beyond the
    political process in the months ahead,&quot; Pleasure said.
    &quot;It proposes an economic education program that's
    integrated with organizing and bargaining, job training,
    apprenticeship training and worker counseling.&quot; </p>
    <p>The program is being developed with input from the
    education and research departments of all the affiliated
    unions. It will be a primary emphasis of the AFL-CIO
    Education Department and its new director, Bill Fletcher, a
    former education and field staff director at the Service
    Employees who was introduced to the council by Sweeney. </p>
    <p>&quot;We have a great opportunity,&quot; Fletcher told the
    council. &quot;We need to change things around dramatically
    in the way workers view unions and the way that unions
    influence policy. There is a certain level of urgency.&quot; </p>
    <p>The council also heard from Jeff Faux, president of the
    Economic Policy Institute, on the need to extend the workers'
    perspective onto the national scene. </p>
    <p>&quot;We need to make the economic case so that more
    people understand the importance of unions,&quot; Faux said,
    noting the prevailing myth that high wages are bad for the
    country. &quot;What we need to do is create the kind of
    movement that addresses and attacks that story,&quot; he
    said. &quot;Unless we do that, the chance of getting labor
    law reform is very low.&quot; </p>
    <p>Faux spoke about creating an army of people who understand
    the key economic facts, such as the need to create a strong
    demand for labor. &quot;There should be a hunger to
    understand what the hell is going on, to understand it in the
    context of coming in, turning on the TV and hearing only
    stock market news, not paycheck news. We need to make people
    understand there is something in this for them.&quot; </p>
    <p>To amplify labor's message, Faux talked of creating an
    &quot;echo chamber,&quot; in which the workers' perspective
    is reinforced through different media. &quot;When Gingrich
    speaks, Limbaugh echoes, and then letters to the editors with
    the same arguments come in,&quot; he said. &quot;We need to
    create our own echo chamber.&quot; </p>
    <p>Phase 1 of the economic education plan has the federation
    developing and distributing economic education curricula and
    materials to apprenticeship programs, joint labor-management
    education and training programs, counselors for displaced
    workers and community teach-ins. These activities are
    coordinated with affiliated unions, training programs,
    university-based labor centers and community groups. </p>
    <p>After the November election, the AFL-CIO will move forward
    with a multiyear, multilevel program stressing the need for
    collective action through stronger, growing unions to achieve
    a restructured economy that serves working families better.
    It is hoped the first programs of Phase 2 will be
    field-tested in early 1997. </p>
    <p>The outline also envisions a permanent national network of
    trained labor educators and economists, regular follow-up
    with program participants, debriefings to culminate in a
    seminar and workshop for union leaders, a permanent
    clearinghouse on economics education and systematic,
    comprehensive and continuing evaluations. </p>
    <p>&quot;This is a long-term process that will require
    investment and leadership to signal to the rank and file that
    this is important,&quot; Faux said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
