<html>
<head>
<title>Strategic campaign structure, leadership in place</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Corporate affairs helps
    unions with employers <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">James B. Parks </p>
    <p>Making good on the promise to revamp and revitalize the
    ability of unions to mount successful strategic campaigns for
    organizing and collective bargaining, the AFL-CIO began
    assembling the team that will provide direct help to unions
    in their dealings with employers. </p>
    <p>President John J. Sweeney drew on some of the top talents
    in the labor movement to fill key roles in the new Corporate
    Affairs Department, which will provide information and
    analysis for corporate campaigns, and the Field Mobilization
    Department, which will coordinate field activities. </p>
    <p>Ron Blackwell, UNITE's chief economist, will become
    director of corporate affairs. The department will include
    three divisions &thorn; Strategic Research, headed by David
    Chu, former Service Employees research director; Employee
    Ownership and Governance, headed by William Patterson, who
    has directed shareholder campaigns for the Teamsters; and
    Workplace Democracy, with Nancy Mills, who previously worked
    on issues of the changing workplace at SEIU, serving as
    acting director. </p>
    <p>Dick Leonard, corporate campaign director for the Oil,
    Chemical and Atomic Workers, will direct strategic campaigns
    as an assistant director in the Department of Field
    Mobilization. </p>
    <p>&quot;This is an impressive array of talent to focus on
    the critical issues facing America's working families,&quot;
    Sweeney said. &quot;It continues the exciting headway we have
    already begun with the creation and revamping of our
    activities in organizing, government affairs, public affairs,
    working women's issues, field mobilization and legal
    services.&quot; </p>
    <p>The appointments, coupled with the reorganization of the
    various field staffs, will &quot;provide affiliates with the
    best possible talent&quot; for the difficult work of
    strategic campaigns, Sweeney said. </p>
    <p>The recent rail settlement shows how effective coordinated
    actions can be, several union presidents said. </p>
    <p>The active support given by Sweeney and
    Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka, including Sweeney's
    appearance before the rail emergency board, the first-ever by
    an AFL-CIO president, helped turn the tide in favor of rail
    workers, said Transportation Communications Union President
    Robert A. Scardelletti. </p>
    <p>&quot;We needed the AFL-CIO and they were there to help.
    In the end, we reached an agreement that far exceeded what
    the industry dreamed they would be paying and anything we
    thought we could achieve,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>&quot;The railroads were going through Congress to force a
    settlement,&quot; Maintenance of Way Employees President Mac
    Fleming said. &quot;But we politicized the process by
    bringing the AFL-CIO into it. We had more votes than they
    did. It meant a lot in the end: substantial job security,
    skill differential, enhanced work rules.&quot; </p>
    <p>The campaign staff will have its hands full as soon as it
    hits the ground. Trumka, who heads the Strategic Approaches
    Committee, told the Executive Council his panel has been
    extremely busy. </p>
    <p>Coming off victories in the rail talks and in the
    Paperworkers' strike against Trailmobile, the committee has
    intensified its efforts in other ongoing disputes. </p>
    <p>In the Detroit newspaper strike, Sweeney told strikers
    last month that the federation would &quot;raise the
    visibility (of the strike) and bring this to a successful
    conclusion.&quot; </p>
    <p>Both sides have agreed to resume negotiations at the
    request of the mayor, Trumka said. But the newspaper owners,
    Gannett and Knight-Ridder, have refused to negotiate around
    the clock, opting instead for only two dates so far. </p>
    <p>The strike, which has gone on for 13 months, &quot;is
    being sustained against incredible odds,&quot; but solidarity
    is high, Trumka said. Among the strongest supporters has been
    the UAW, which recently presented $150 checks to each of the
    nearly 2,000 strikers for the fourth time since the strike
    began. The federation also has assigned two additional staff,
    George Curtin and Gary Horton, bringing to six the number of
    personnel assigned to aid the strikers. </p>
    <p>The strikers were disappointed that Gannett board member
    and former First Lady Rosalynn Carter, responding to a
    letter, would not even agree to meet with them to discuss
    their concerns. &quot;If Sadat and Begin had taken this
    approach, there never would have been a Carter Center,&quot;
    Trumka said, referring to the historic talks between the
    Egyptian president and Israeli prime minister that led to a
    peace accord brokered by then-President Jimmy Carter. </p>
    <p>Some 2,000 employees of the Detroit News and Free Press
    have been on strike since July 13, 1995, after negotiations
    failed to produce a new agreement. Management and imported
    scabs from other papers are producing the newspapers. </p>
    <p>The key issue is how to get rid of the scabs,
    Communications Workers President Morton Bahr said. The CWA
    and The Newspaper Guild-CWA are two of the striking unions,
    along with IBT and Graphic Communications. </p>
    <p>GCIU President James J. Norton announced that retail giant
    Dayton Hudson has pulled out of the Detroit scab newspapers
    and will advertise in the suburban papers. It also has cut
    its Christmas budget with the papers by $20 million, he said. </p>
    <p>The strike at the Frontier Hotel in Las Vegas is in its
    fifth year and is still going strong &thorn; not one striker
    has crossed the picket line, Trumka reported. As a result,
    the hotel is losing out on the boom on the Strip, which is
    based on a &quot;labor-management partnership that the
    Frontier is not participating in,&quot; he said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
