<head>
<title>International focus shifts to organizing,</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">International focus shifts
    to organizing and solidarity <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">James B. Parks </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO is forging ahead with an activist
    international affairs program focused on organizing,
    educating members and building a strong global union
    movement. </p>
    <p>The federation's International Affairs Committee, chaired
    by Machinists President George J. Kourpias, presented
    preliminary recommendations to the Executive Council for a
    restructuring of the federation's international activities
    &quot;to supplement the overall goals of the affiliates and
    the federation to organize and strengthen bargaining at home
    and abroad.&quot; </p>
    <p>The recommendations reflect the activist approach
    described by AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney at the World
    Congress of the International Confederation of Free Trade
    Unions in June. &quot;We must do more than talk to each
    other, pass fine resolutions and go home,&quot; Sweeney said.
    &quot;We must create clear and measurable goals and design
    campaigns to accomplish them.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;Our labor movements need to engage in a seamless
    garment of activism,&quot; Sweeney told the Trade Union
    Congress in London. &quot;We need to organize members in
    every occupation and every industry. That is the only way we
    can gain the economic power to win better wages and benefits
    at the bargaining table. That is the only way that we can
    gain the political power to enact better laws to protect
    working people's rights to organize unions and bargain with
    their employers.&quot; </p>
    <p>Sweeney announced at the council meeting that he has
    appointed Barbara Shailor, IAM's international affairs
    director, to lead the refocused international affairs
    program. She replaces Charles Gray, who will become Sweeney's
    assistant for international relations, particularly on the
    International Labor Organization, where Gray has played a
    prominent role for many years. </p>
    <p>&quot;The recommendations are consistent with other
    changes at the AFL-CIO &thorn; taking an activist approach to
    issues, much as the Organizing and Field Mobilization
    departments are doing,&quot; Shailor said. </p>
    <p>The department also will take an activist approach to
    educating union members on the international issues and how
    they affect American workers, Shailor said. She cited IAM's
    strikes at Boeing and McDonnell Douglas, both over the issue
    of outsourcing to foreign companies, as examples of the
    impact of global competition. </p>
    <p>&quot;To succeed in our struggle, union members in every
    country must develop a better understanding of how global
    forces impact their national governments, their industries,
    their unions and their place of work,&quot; Kourpias told the
    council. </p>
    <p>As part of the restructuring, the four federation
    international institutes will be combined into the American
    Center for International Labor Solidarity (ACILS) by the end
    of the year. </p>
    <p>Jim Baker, executive assistant to former President Lane
    Kirkland, is overseeing the integration of the institutes. </p>
    <p>The committee recommended that ACILS be funded without
    government supervision, foreign or domestic. Currently, much
    of the money that funds the institutes comes from the U.S.
    Agency for International Development and the National
    Endowment for Democracy. </p>
    <p>Funds for both agencies have been cut significantly by
    Congress. The report also called for focusing the efforts of
    the institutes on the organization and development of strong
    and independent trade unions at home and abroad. </p>
    <p>In addition, the report called for the IAD to cooperate
    and coordinate with affiliates and the Corporate Affairs,
    Public Policy and Field Mobilization departments by
    strengthening U.S. participation in the ICFTU, international
    trade secretariats and expanding affiliation with Asian
    organizations. It also called for a strategic political
    campaign to ratify ILO conventions on the right to organize
    and bargain collectively. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
