<html>
<head>
<title>Executive Council: State feds to capture fees;</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Executive Council: <br>
    </font><a href="#FEDS"><font size="4">State feds to capture
    fees</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a href="#DISPUTE"><font
    size="4">Dispute procedures changed</font></a><font size="4">; <br>
    </font><a href="#ENGLISH"><font size="4">Not officially
    English</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a href="#BURN"><font
    size="4">Church burnings decried</font></a><font size="4">; <br>
    </font><a href="#BOYCOTT"><font size="4">New boycott strategy</font></a><font
    size="4">; </font><a href="#STERN"><font size="4">Stern
    replaces Cordtz </font></a><font size="4"><br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p><a name="FEDS"><strong>State feds to capture fees </strong></a></p>
    <p>The Executive Council adopted a statement authorizing a
    disbursement schedule to state federations of the monies
    generated by the 1-cent penalty per capita program on state
    federation affiliation. </p>
    <p>The sliding scale disbursement calls for the largest
    allocations to go to small- and medium-sized state
    federations. Also, up to 10 percent of the funds may be
    disbursed as grants of no more than $5,000 for such needs as
    affiliation initiatives, technological enhancements or
    grass-roots development. </p>
    <p>The council also expanded AFL-CIO authority over all
    &quot;election protests&quot; in state and local central
    bodies and shifted the first appeal by a central body on
    matters regarding disciplinary action from the council to the
    Appeals Committee. </p>
    <p>In addition, protest of an officer&thorn;s election may be
    made to the AFL-CIO president within 30 days of exhaustion of
    any applicable procedures provided by the constitution or
    bylaws of the state or local central body. </p>
    <p><a name="DISPUTE"><strong>Dispute procedures changed </strong></a></p>
    <p>The council approved a series of changes in the articles
    of the AFL-CIO constitution that deal with union dispute
    settlement. </p>
    <p>A set of new procedures for handling complaints under
    Article XX were issued, including a requirement that unions
    contact each other before taking the complaint to the
    federation. </p>
    <p>The council also amended Article XX to allow independent
    unions to affiliate with an AFL-CIO affiliate even if another
    union has filed a petition with a labor board to represent
    the workers in that unit. That amendment has been approved
    each year since 1992 on a trial basis. </p>
    <p>In addition, the Article XX Review Committee was renamed
    the Committee on Article XX and Article XXI Review. </p>
    <p><a name="ENGLISH"><strong>Not officially English </strong></a></p>
    <p>English is already our &quot;common&quot; language, the
    council declared, and therefore does not have to be our
    official language, as espoused in a legislative proposal,
    H.R. 123. </p>
    <p>The council noted that the measure would
    &quot;disenfranchise, divide and disconnect millions of
    Americans from their government,&quot; and urged
    &quot;expanding public funding for adult education programs
    and English as a second language because isolating immigrants
    and American-born citizens who are not fluent in English
    leads to exploitation and discrimination.&quot; </p>
    <p><a name="BURN"><strong>Church burnings decried </strong></a></p>
    <p>The outbreak of burnings, bombings and vandalism recently
    visited on American churches was condemned by the AFL-CIO,
    which vowed to mobilize against the forces of intolerance and
    bigotry. </p>
    <p>&quot;We will work with groups from different faiths and
    with our allies in civil and human rights organizations to
    help open an honest dialogue within the communities where
    these crimes have occurred,&quot; the council said in a
    statement, &quot;and we will work to help rebuild and restore
    the houses of worship that have been vandalized by these hate
    criminals.&quot; </p>
    <p><a name="BOYCOTT"><strong>New boycott strategy </strong></a></p>
    <p>To strengthen the AFL-CIO boycott endorsement policy, the
    federation will list companies only for a period of up to one
    calendar year, at which time it would expire automatically. </p>
    <p>Before a company is listed, the national officers of the
    union seeking the boycott must meet with AFL-CIO executive
    officers or staff to discuss a strategic plan and timetable
    for the boycott. </p>
    <p><a name="STERN"><strong>Stern replaces Cordtz </strong></a></p>
    <p>The council praised retiring Vice President Richard W.
    Cordtz, who was replaced on the council by the new president
    of the Service Employees, Andy Stern. </p>
    <p>Cordtz had been a member of the council since October
    1995, when he was elected to the SEIU presidency, succeeding
    John J. Sweeney. </p>
    <p>&quot;His commitment to organizing over his 50 years of
    service to working people is a standard we hold forth to
    union activists and leaders of generations to come,&quot; the
    council said in a statement. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
