<html>
<head>
<title>Strike spotlights disServiceMaster</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Strike spotlights
    disServiceMaster <br>
    Private veterans' home shafts workers, taxpayers </font><br>
    by </p>
    <p align="center">Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p>Workers at the state veterans' home in Anna, Ill., struck
    Aug. 10 after a yearlong struggle under the AFSCME banner for
    a first contract with ServiceMaster. </p>
    <p>The ServiceMaster home is one of four veterans' homes in
    Illinois financed by the state. Unionized workers at the
    three state-operated homes in LaSalle, Manteno and Quincy
    have health insurance, pensions and earn $9.60 an hour, while
    certified nursing assistants at the privately run Anna
    facility earn only $4.67 an hour with no health insurance or
    pensions and very minimal benefits. </p>
    <p>According to AFSCME, ServiceMaster's contract with the
    state is worth nearly $2 million; yet, the company spends
    less than half of the employment costs at the other
    facilities. Given that their overall costs are only 12
    percent to 28 percent less than at the state-operated homes,
    the union concludes that &quot;ServiceMaster is making big
    profits from the veterans' home, and those profits are coming
    at the expense of the veterans, the employees and the entire
    Anna community.&quot; </p>
    <p>The federation took up the cause of the workers before the
    strike began with a statement in support of their efforts. </p>
    <p>&quot;The AFL-CIO Executive Council condemns the refusal
    of ServiceMaster to bargain in good faith with the workers at
    the Anna veterans' home. We call on the State of Illinois to
    take steps immediately to bring about a fair settlement with
    these workers, and if ServiceMaster refuses to bargain, to
    cancel its contract with the company.&quot; </p>
    <p>Several days into the strike, family members of residents
    had reported that some replacement workers were not showing
    up &thorn; and those that did report to work lacked
    qualifications and necessary skills and were administering
    poor care. </p>
    <p>Specifically, clinical tests were done late or not at all,
    meals arrived late and cold, residents had to tell the
    replacement workers how to perform lifts properly and
    residents without family nearby were not having their
    appearances tended to. </p>
    <p>Those allegations led former GOP State Senator Ralph Dunn
    to urge Gov. Jim Edgar to terminate ServiceMaster's contract. </p>
    <p>He said the treatment of the residents by the unqualified
    replacement workers had made the home &quot;a symbol, not of
    our common commitment to these veterans, but of the State of
    Illinois' indifference to their physical and mental
    well-being.&quot; </p>
    <p>No new bargaining sessions were set until after Labor Day. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
