<html>
<head>
<title>Unions fight Bell Atlantic-NYNEX hookup</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Unions fight Bell
    Atlantic-NYNEX hookup <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Colleen M. O'Neill </p>
    <p>Breaking up was hard to do, Ma Bell's offspring say. Now
    the regional operating companies are seeking new ways to come
    together. </p>
    <p>For telephone customers from Boston to Washington, that
    means a planned merger of NYNEX and Bell Atlantic. And for
    Electrical Workers and Communications Workers employed by the
    two companies, that means trouble. </p>
    <p>&quot;We have seen a preview, in the mobile phone
    operation, of what we'll see when they merge,&quot; said CWA
    spokesman Jeffrey Miller. &quot;They turned into a bunch of
    union busters.&quot; </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO joined its two affiliates in fighting the
    merger with a statement of support issued at the Executive
    Council meeting in Chicago. </p>
    <p>&quot;It is clear that Bell Atlantic's buyout of NYNEX
    would take us in the opposite direction (from the goal of the
    1996 Telecommunications Act): a bigger telecom monopoly with
    even less incentive to reverse the companies' existing
    pattern of declining service standards, ever-higher rates and
    the destruction of good jobs,&quot; the council said. </p>
    <p>The original merger plans were changed so as to sidestep
    scrutiny, CWA President Morton Bahr asserted, noting that
    &quot;in every action it takes, this company shows its
    arrogance and disregard for workers, from the six-month fight
    for a new contract last year to the end run it's trying to
    make around public oversight of the proposed merger.&quot; </p>
    <p>State regulators in the New England and mid-Atlantic
    states must approve the merger; the unions have vowed to
    fight it there and in the courts. </p>
    <p>IBEW President John J. Barry said the merging of the
    cellular operations last year gave the firms the chance to
    show how they would deal with their work force. However, Bell
    Atlantic threw out the negotiated union contracts and so far
    has refused to abide by a National Labor Relations Board
    determination that its action was illegal. </p>
    <p>&quot;Bell Atlantic continues to show its contempt for
    workers, through its refusal to acknowledge the contracts
    fairly negotiated at the mobile operation; by issuing a
    union-busting guide to supervisors; and by denying workers
    transfer rights into new jobs,&quot; Barry said. </p>
    <p>The council said &quot;both companies have allowed service
    standards to deteriorate, while steadily downsizing their
    work forces and funneling these savings into sideline
    business ventures instead of maintaining or improving their
    telecom systems.&quot; It pledged full support to the unions
    in seeking to block the alliance, and called on &quot;all
    federal and state agencies charged with reviewing the
    proposed deal to withhold approval.&quot; </p>
    <p>Bell Atlantic-NYNEX Mobile remains on the AFL-CIO's
    national boycott list. </p>
</blockquote>
