<html>
<head>
<title>Courts: UPS can't dodge NLRB; Coke contract</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="5">Courts: </font><font
    size="4"><br>
    </font><a href="#UPS"><font size="4">UPS can't dodge NLRB</font></a><font
    size="4">; </font><a href="#COKE"><font size="4">Coke
    contract upheld</font></a><font size="4">; <br>
    </font><a href="#HOSPITAL"><font size="4">Hospital injunction
    denied</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a href="#IAM"><font
    size="4">IAM charges Boeing </font></a></p>
    <p>&#160;</p>
    <p><a name="UPS"><strong>UPS can't dodge NLRB </strong></a></p>
    <p>Ruling in favor of the Teamsters, a federal appeals court
    decided that United Parcel Service Inc. is subject to the
    National Labor Relations Act, as it has been for the last 47
    years. </p>
    <p>The company had sought to bring itself under the Railway
    Labor Act, which covers airlines and railroads, and the
    National Mediation Board, which administers that law, instead
    of the NLRA and the National Labor Relations Board. </p>
    <p>The U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit ruled that
    UPS, with 300,000 employees, mainly performs ground
    transportation for small packages. Its subsidiary, United
    Parcel Service Co., with 3,000 employees, was created in 1988
    to deliver air freight and is subject to the RLA. </p>
    <p>The case, UPS Inc. vs. NLRB, arose in 1993 when the
    company was charged with violating labor laws by the IBT.
    While the case was before the NLRB, the company requested the
    board to ask the NMB whether it should be covered by the
    railway act. After an administrative law judge ruled in UPS'
    favor, the NLRB reversed the decision. </p>
    <p><a name="COKE"><strong>Coke contract upheld </strong></a></p>
    <p>A federal appeals court upheld the primacy of the
    collective bargaining contract over work rules and ordered a
    Coca-Cola employee reinstated after he was fired for being
    late to work too often. </p>
    <p>An arbitrator had decided in favor of the employee in the
    case, Midwest Coca-Cola vs. Teamsters Local 792. Coca-Cola
    argued that its work rules on tardiness superseded the
    collective bargaining agreement, but the U.S. Circuit Court
    of Appeals for the 8th Circuit rejected the argument,
    overruled a lower court and upheld the arbitrator's decision. </p>
    <p>Coca-Cola work rules require discharge for workers who are
    late four times in a 12-month period without calling in 30
    minutes before the shift begins. But the contract prohibits
    the firing of a senior employee without &quot;just
    cause,&quot; and calls for an arbitrator to determine if such
    cause existed and to order reinstatement if necessary. </p>
    <p>&quot;The fact that we, the district court, or Coca-Cola
    may disagree with the arbitrator's arguable interpretation of
    the agreement is of no consequence, because Coca-Cola and the
    union bargained for the arbitrator's interpretation,&quot;
    the court wrote. </p>
    <p><a name="HOSPITAL"><strong>Hospital injunction denied </strong></a></p>
    <p>A federal judge has denied the National Labor Relations
    Board's request for an injunction to force a Kentucky medical
    center to bargain with a union over a restructuring of
    nurses' positions and duties. </p>
    <p>U.S. District Judge John G. Heyburn of western Kentucky
    ruled that the NLRB failed to show that an injunction was
    justified and it would be too burdensome to renegotiate the
    restructuring, which was completed in February. </p>
    <p>The case, Ahearn vs. Audubon Regional Medical Center,
    began when Audubon in 1995 unilaterally changed the staffing
    levels for nurses and redesigned the physical layout without
    consulting the union. No nurses were laid off or terminated
    because of the changes. </p>
    <p>The Nurses Professional Organization, an affiliate of
    AFSCME, filed unfair labor practice charges in 1994 against
    Audubon, an acute care facility with 2,000 employees,
    including 642 registered nurses. The union claimed the
    facility threatened employees during a 1994 representation
    election, which it lost. The restructuring occurred during
    hearings on the first set of ULP charges. </p>
    <p><a name="IAM"><strong>IAM charges Boeing </strong></a></p>
    <p>The Machinists filed unfair labor practice charges with
    the National Labor Relations Board charging Boeing is
    illegally trying to entice workers out of union jobs into a
    new, nonunion classification. </p>
    <p>The union, which represents some 36,000 Boeing workers,
    claimed the company intends to move hundreds of jobs
    classified as expediters from the bargaining unit. Boeing
    recently announced that 1,100 union members who are
    classified as expediters, who track materials and parts
    through the production process, would be &quot;invited to
    move&quot; into a new unrepresented salaried position of
    &quot;material planner.&quot; </p>
    <p>The union also charged that the company has unlawfully
    threatened union members if they and/or the union refused to
    accept a new work schedule. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
