<head>
<title>Shipyard strikers in tough fight</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Shipyard strikers in tough
    fight <br>
    NASSCO takes tax funds, seeks to bust unions <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">David Kameras </p>
    <p>San Diego, Calif. </p>
    <p>Some 1,800 striking workers at San Diego's National
    Shipbuilding Co. shipyard are hanging tough against
    union-busting tactics of their employer after more than 3,000
    walked out July 17. </p>
    <p>The strikers were buoyed by separate visits from AFL-CIO
    President John J. Sweeney and Secretary-Treasurer Richard L.
    Trumka, who promised to rally the labor movement on their
    behalf. </p>
    <p>The NASSCO shipyard performs contract work for the U.S.
    Navy, which means taxpayers are subsidizing the company's
    anti-union stance. The company's chief executive enjoys fat
    raises each year while ignoring federal wage requirements for
    Navy contracts. The workers have not had a raise in four
    years. </p>
    <p>In 1992, workers struck for a month, returning when
    management agreed to bargain in good faith. But instead of a
    contract, they got suspension of the dues check-off,
    interference with shop stewards in the performance of their
    duties and refusal to discuss union security at the
    bargaining table. </p>
    <p>The unions offered to hold an independently supervised
    election to show rank-and-file support for a union security
    clause, but the company refused. </p>
    <p>Sweeney said the strike in San Diego is symptomatic of the
    nation's economic problems. Pointing to the Republican
    convention across town, he warned that workers will insist
    that &quot;America Needs A Raise.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;I hope the Republicans can hear us over at the San
    Diego Convention Center and at some of the plush parties
    going on around us,&quot; he said. &quot;I hope the Perot
    delegates can hear us up in Long Beach and that the Democrats
    can hear us next week, because they will most certainly hear
    us on Nov. 5. We will be heard.&quot; </p>
    <p>Trumka criticized Republican presidential candidate Bob
    Dole and his embrace of the core beliefs of supply-side
    Reaganomics, symbolized strongly by his selection of Jack
    Kemp as his running mate. &quot;George Bush called
    supply-side `voodoo economics.' Well, now union members know
    it's doo-doo economics,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>&quot;The 1980s were a disaster for working people in this
    country, and just about everything that was wrong with the
    1980s went by the name of supply-side economics,&quot; he
    said. &quot;We had a dose of supply- side in the 1980s, and
    it created the largest deficit in history and the widest gap
    between rich and poor. Working people may have been born at
    night, but we weren't born last night.&quot; </p>
    <p>The AFL-CIO is helping to establish a striker relief fund
    that will help striking workers make ends meet and continue
    their struggle against the shipyard's management. Monies go
    into a central fund administered by the San Diego-Imperial
    Counties Labor Council, to which workers may apply for
    assistance. </p>
    <p>The NASSCO strikers belong to the Ironworkers, Machinists,
    Electrical Workers, Carpenters, Painters, Operating Engineers
    and Teamsters. Donations to help them and their families may
    be sent to: Solidarity Fund for NASSCO Workers, c/o San
    Diego-Imperial Counties AFL-CIO, 4265 Fairmount Ave., Suite
    110, San Diego, Calif. 92105. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
