<head>
<title>ULLICO invests in new ships, jobs</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">ULLICO invests in new ships,
    jobs <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">David Kameras </p>
    <p>Newport News, Va. </p>
    <p>A labor-business partnership has resulted in a $240
    million venture to produce five double-hulled tankers,
    creating jobs for Steelworkers and, two years out, shipboard
    jobs for Seafarers and unaffiliated American Maritime
    Officers. </p>
    <p>The ships, which are designed to protect the environment
    from disastrous oil spills, are being built at Newport News
    Shipbuilding with the help of funds from Union Labor Life
    Insurance Co., one of the investors in the project. Union
    construction is expected to begin in 1997, with the vessels
    placed in service in 1998. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney joined ULLICO Chairman
    and CEO Robert A. Georgine, who is also president of the
    federation's Building and Construction Trades Department, in
    saluting the labor- management partnership that resulted in
    the venture. </p>
    <p>&quot;It means thousands of Steelworker jobs and more jobs
    for union seafarers and maritime officers after they are
    built, and it's a great demonstration of what we can do when
    there's a little respect coming from an employer,&quot;
    Sweeney said. </p>
    <p>Georgine noted that federal loan guarantees cover about
    87.5 percent of the cost and add a significant margin of
    safety to the investment, which is being made with
    Taft-Hartley pension funds. </p>
    <p>&quot;Second, we had to be sure that the other partners
    would work with us to meet fair labor employment
    standards,&quot; he said. &quot;They did, and it all adds up
    to environmentally responsible transport of petroleum in U.S.
    waters by U.S.-built, U.S.-owned and U.S.- operated ships,
    which is good news for America and good news for
    workers.&quot; </p>
    <p>ULLICO's investment objectives included achieving
    higher-than- market returns, while helping unions, their
    members and companies that are good employers. </p>
    <p>&quot;The project is living proof that jobs and profit can
    go hand in hand, and are not on a collision course, as some
    would have us believe,&quot; ULLICO said. &quot;In the
    long-run, America will have a strong economy if investments .
    . . are made to good use in real- life enterprises where
    capital and jobs are created.&quot; </p>
    <p>The &quot;Double Eagles,&quot; as the tankers are known,
    will be among the first tankers built in American shipyards
    since passage of the Oil Pollution Act of 1990, a legislative
    response to the Exxon Valdez oil spill that requires the
    phasing out of single-hull vessels entering U.S. waters. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
