<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Mariners weathering rough seas of foreign flags</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Mariners weathering rough
    seas of foreign flags <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">David Kameras</p>
    <p>Seattle </p>
    <p>Throughout the post-war period, the United States has kept
    its merchant marine afloat through a mixture of subsidies and
    other support programs to ensure that it can meet its defense
    commitments and protect its economy. </p>
    <p>But soon, the last of the operating subsidy contracts will
    be expiring, and a coalition of huge multinational grain and
    shipping interests is placing longstanding maritime policies
    under attack. Maritime unions see this fight as crucial to
    the future of the industry and maritime jobs. </p>
    <p>The showdown may come next month in the Senate, when a
    bill to earmark $1 billion a year for 10 years for maritime
    subsidies comes up. The bill, H.R. 1350, was passed by the
    House and is supported by the administration. It would allow
    U.S.-flag operators to compete globally despite the higher
    costs of the American registry, and indirectly give a boost
    to commercial shipbuilding as well. </p>
    <p>As Congress debates whether to throw a life preserver to
    the industry, regulatory agencies have granted waivers
    permitting American shipping companies to register their
    vessels under foreign &quot;flags of convenience,&quot;
    thereby evading a requirement that their crews be composed of
    U.S. citizens and the union contracts that protect them. </p>
    <p>&quot;American firms are moving foreign flag, which I
    believe our Congress could put a stop to if they wanted
    to,&quot; said Henry Jones Jr., a Seafarers chief steward
    serving on liquefied natural gas carriers operated by Energy
    Transportation Corp. The U.S. government allowed Sea-Land
    Service to re-flag a portion of its fleet at the cost of up
    to 150 jobs in Seattle, he said. </p>
    <p>Last year, a captain belonging to the Masters, Mates and
    Pilots, a Longshoremen's affiliate, was fired for hoisting a
    &quot;Don't Tread On Me&quot; flag after American President
    Lines, a major West Coast employer, won the right to use
    foreign crews on its new ships. He was reinstated only after
    pressure from his union and the AFL-CIO Maritime Trades
    Department. </p>
    <p><strong>Fighting for their livelihood </strong></p>
    <p>&quot;The companies are threatening us with foreign flags,
    which makes you feel insecure,&quot; added Dotty Hoffman, an
    SIU able-bodied seaman and splicer with Trans-Oceanic Cable
    Co., an AT&amp;T subsidiary. &quot;Plus, they use that during
    contract negotiations to keep our wages down.&quot; </p>
    <p>Jones, Hoffman and other maritime workers in Seattle
    talked recently about the decline of the U.S. merchant
    marine, and what this could mean for the next generation to
    go into the shipyards and out to sea. </p>
    <p>&quot;The young people coming into the industry now can't
    count on having a job for 20 years, or having a job they can
    settle on,&quot; Jone said. </p>
    <p>&quot;There are no more young people,&quot; said Jeff
    Engels, an able- bodied seaman for nearly 20 years, most of
    that time with the Inland Boatman's Union of the Pacific, a
    Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union affiliate. &quot;I
    would hate to be an 18-year-old today.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;The industry's in trouble, and because of that, the
    country's security and prestige are in trouble,&quot; said
    Mike Hester, another SIU able-bodied seaman. &quot;Hundreds
    of thousands of people who work in the maritime industry need
    to put bread on the table. It's scary.&quot; </p>
    <p>Still, there are some bright spots for those who ply the
    waters. </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Several tankers currently are being built in U.S.
            shipyards, carrying the promise of maintained and
            expanded jobs in domestic oil shipping. </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>Many municipalities and regions have adopted or are
            considering passenger ferry service, and
            old-fashioned paddlewheelers are once again cruising
            the Mississippi River. </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>The Ready Reserve Force of auxiliary vessels
            continues to be strengthened, reflecting the fact
            that many in the Navy, as well as many in Congress,
            continue to see the wisdom in having a privatized
            fleet available for national security purposes. </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>Prospects for the international carriage of liquified
            natural gas remain strong. </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
        <li>Thanks largely to the efforts of maritime labor, the
            World Trade Organization continues to exclude
            maritime services from its regime, protecting U.S.
            flag domestic routes from foreign operators bent on
            subjecting their crews to slave-like conditions and
            by foreign governments willing to operate below cost
            in order to gain hard currency. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Maritime in global market </strong></p>
    <p>National security always has been the guiding rationale
    for a strong merchant marine. The U.S.-built, U.S.-crewed
    requirement of the American registry is intended to ensure a
    shipyard mobilization base and seagoing manpower pool
    adequate to meet the rigors of a national emergency. </p>
    <p>Operating subsidies, meant to compensate shipping
    companies for the higher costs associated with the flag in
    what is a global marketplace, require in return a transfer of
    vessels and crews to military jurisdiction during war, saving
    the Pentagon billions of dollars in building and mothballing
    idle ships. But with shrinking federal budgets presided over
    by legislators from states and districts often far removed
    from waterborne commerce, out of sight sometimes means out of
    mind. </p>
    <p>&quot;These other countries are unscrupulous,&quot; Hester
    said. &quot;They don't care about giving their seamen safe
    working conditions or a living wage, and because of that,
    we're at a competitive disadvantage. </p>
    <p>&quot;The big question has been whether the government
    should subsidize private business, but that's really a false
    issue,&quot; he said. &quot;America needs a merchant fleet.
    Everybody wants America to be strong, Democrat and
    Republican, rich and poor. The Navy alone isn't going to get
    the job done, and without a body of merchant mariners and
    ships that are available to the American merchant fleet, it's
    not going to happen.&quot; </p>
    <p>When AT&amp;T recently bought a foreign ship, it
    registered it under the Stars and Stripes only after getting
    heat from the military, Hoffman said. &quot;When we lay
    cables, one fiber is designated a lot of times for military
    use only. So they saw that as a threat to national
    security,&quot; she said. </p>
    <p>The threat isn't limited to technology. Without adequate
    American ships and enough loyal Americans ready to risk their
    lives in crewing them in a war zone, the United States can
    become dangerously dependent on foreign powers. </p>
    <p>&quot;An example is Desert Storm,&quot; Hoffman said.
    &quot;I went on three ships to the Persian Gulf carrying
    equipment, and they actually asked foreign ships to help us,
    and they turned us down. If that happens again, who's going
    to supply our troops with the things they need?&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;If we have another Desert Storm, good luck,&quot;
    said Jim Sutton, a District 1 Marine Engineer. </p>
    <p><strong>Multinational pirates </strong></p>
    <p>Moves to repeal the Jones Act, a 1920 statute that
    restricts coastwise domestic shipping to U.S.-flag vessels,
    got a high profile on Capitol Hill this year, thanks largely
    to multinational interests hoping to include America in the
    global race to the bottom of a pool of bad wages and working
    conditions. </p>
    <p>&quot;Just seeing the conditions on these foreign vessels
    is horrendous,&quot; said IBU Secretary-Treasurer Terri Mast. </p>
    <p>&quot;Any proposal that would allow substandard foreign
    vessels into our coastwise trades would undo the work of
    generations of men and women who have labored to raise the
    safety and environmental standards of our U.S.-flag fleet to
    its current high level,&quot; MEBA President Alex Shandrowsky
    told a House subcommittee this year. &quot;It would be an
    insult to American values and traditions &thorn; and to the
    citizens of this country &thorn; should we cast aside the
    fruits of that labor.&quot; </p>
    <p>Maritime unions have been instrumental in helping their
    members meet the challenges of a rapidly changing industry. </p>
    <p>&quot;We're always upgrading our membership,&quot; said
    Jones, whose union operates a state-of-the-art training
    facility in Maryland. </p>
    <p>&quot;Joining the union was sort of like being adopted by
    a healthy family, a really good family,&quot; Hester said.
    &quot;Everything that I have, the union helped me get. It's
    an enormous opportunity for someone who doesn't have a lot of
    skills, but wants to work hard and is willing to learn. It's
    a good legacy from the working people that came before
    us.&quot; </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
