<head>
<title>USWA reaches for power in unity</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">USWA reaches for power in
    unity Pittsburgh <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">James B. Parks </p>
    <p>Talk of strength through unity and political action
    dominated the Steelworkers' convention as delegates discussed
    mergers and vowed to mobilize members to elect a pro-worker
    Congress. </p>
    <p>Meeting under the theme, &quot;Together, Tougher Than
    Steel,&quot; the convention was the first since the union's
    1995 merger with the Rubber Workers and the announcement of a
    proposed unification with the UAW and Machinists by 2000.
    Delegates also were told of ongoing merger talks with the
    Aluminum, Brick and Glass Workers. </p>
    <p>Presidents Stephen P. Yokich of the UAW and George
    Kourpias of the IAM joined USWA President George Becker in
    praising the unification of the three unions as a way to
    fight anti-worker forces such as Bridgestone/Firestone,
    Caterpillar and McDonnell Douglas, all of whom are embroiled
    in labor disputes with one of the three unions. Delegates
    approved a resolution supporting the unification. </p>
    <p>Becker and ABG President Ernie LaBaff announced the ABG
    will meet in a special convention soon to consider merger
    with the Steelworkers. If that merger is approved, the union
    would represent 95 percent of all aluminum workers. </p>
    <p>Calling this year &quot;probably the most important in the
    history of our movement,&quot; AFL-CIO President John J.
    Sweeney hailed the unification and predicted that labor's
    &quot;rising spirit and new voice&quot; will spell success in
    November, ushering in a progressive majority on Capitol Hill
    and in the White House. </p>
    <p>But he warned that unless unions match their political
    success with organizing gains, &quot;this year will be like a
    false Spring; we're going to feel really good for a while,
    and then a cold freeze is going to hit our budding
    revitalization and we will be dead.&quot; </p>
    <p>President Clinton, who was endorsed for re-election by the
    convention, addressed the delegates via satellite. He urged
    the delegates to spread the word about anti-labor measures
    supported by Republican leaders, many of which would have
    become law had the administration not vetoed or blocked them.
    Clinton cited the TEAM Act, Davis-Bacon and OSHA budget cuts
    as examples of the GOP's efforts to hurt workers. </p>
    <p>&quot;Unless we win the presidential election and change
    the composition of Congress, they will keep trying over and
    over,&quot; Clinton said. The convention voted to work for a
    new Democratic- controlled Congress. </p>
    <p>The delegates also voted to expand the union's
    &quot;rapid- response&quot; network of members throughout the
    country. The network, launched in April, is designed to
    mobilize members to respond to critical issues that face
    workers. </p>
    <p>The network has been used to generate letters and phone
    calls to legislators. On the TEAM Act alone, USWA Local 831,
    a former Rubber Workers local in Danville, Va., generated
    1,200 letters and phone calls to lawmakers; Local 2175 in
    Minneapolis produced 196 handwritten letters from its 400
    members and 91 of the 106 members of Local 690 in Auburn
    Hills, Mich., wrote personal letters. </p>
    <p>The delegates called on every USWA local to have at least
    4 percent of its total membership from all units, departments
    and locations involved in rapid response. Each local will be
    equipped with a fax machine to use in the program, Becker
    said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
