<head>
<title>Plumbers elect Maddaloni, chart aggressive path</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Plumbers elect Maddaloni,
    chart aggressive path <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">David Kameras</p>
    <p>Las Vegas </p>
    <p>The Plumbers and Pipefitters elected new leaders, who
    immediately called for expanded efforts in politics and
    organizing. </p>
    <p>&quot;There are well-funded and tough adversaries out
    there, and we cannot afford to relax our guard even for a
    moment,&quot; President Martin J. Maddaloni told more than
    3,100 delegates to the union's 35th general convention. </p>
    <p>He cited attacks on the Davis-Bacon Act, and Occupational
    Safety and Health Administration and Mine Safety and Health
    Administration regulations, limitations on workers'
    compensation and unemployment insurance, anti-labor
    amendments to the National Labor Relations Act and attempts
    to dismantle Medicare. </p>
    <p>&quot;We have learned important lessons from this
    adversity,&quot; he said. &quot;It is time to give our
    adversaries an education of their own.&quot; </p>
    <p>Maddaloni proposed a covenant with the delegates to build
    the UA's membership and strength, build and expand the
    marketplace for union contractors and fight legislators who
    would diminish members' opportunities and economic security.
    He also pledged a rededication to aggressive organizing
    efforts, including targeting areas outside traditional
    building trades, such as electronics, mechanical equipment
    service, fire protection and instrumentation. </p>
    <p>&quot;We must increase our membership if we are to stay
    strong and competitive in the years ahead,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>That view was echoed by AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney.
    &quot;Unless we get serious about organizing, this year will
    be like a false spring &thorn; we're going to feel really
    good for a while, and then a cold freeze is going to hit our
    budding revitalization, and we will be dead,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>Maddaloni, who served earlier in a number of union
    offices, replaces Marvin J. Boede, who retired after 14 years
    as president. Also elected were Michael A. Collins as
    secretary-treasurer, C. Randal Gardner as assistant
    president, a new executive board and 32 international
    representatives. Delegates also produced a revised union
    constitution and a wide range of resolutions. </p>
    <p>Other speakers included AFL-CIO Building and Construction
    Trades Department President Robert A. Georgine, Sens. Barbara
    Boxer (D-Calif.) and Arlen Specter (R-Pa.), House Minority
    Leader Richard A. Gephardt (D-Mo.), Rep. Thomas M. Foglietta
    (D-Pa.), Nevada Gov. Bob Miller (D) and National Council of
    Senior Citizens Director Steve Protulis. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
