<html>
<head>
<title>IAM makes federal case of McDonnell Douglas</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">IAM makes federal case of
    McDonnell Douglas dispute <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">James B. Parks </p>
    <p>The Machinists asked President Clinton to withhold any
    federal payments to McDonnell Douglas related to the 11-week
    strike at the company's St. Louis aerospace defense
    facilities. </p>
    <p>In an Aug. 14 letter, IAM President George J. Kourpias
    also asked Clinton to request an audit of the quality, cost
    and safety of all work performed for the government by some
    2,000 &quot;temporary replacement&quot; workers from across
    the country hired by McDonnell Douglas since the strike began
    June 5. The company also has hired a private security force
    that specializes in combating strikes. </p>
    <p>&quot;It is my understanding that the U.S. taxpayers are
    financing this,&quot; Kourpias wrote. &quot;Lacking any
    explicit prohibitions in federal law, military contractors
    can, and do, bill the Defense Department for costs they incur
    in a labor dispute,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>&quot;The practice of federal agencies subsidizing the
    strike costs of defense contractors is grossly unfair and
    discriminatory, and it should be halted at once,&quot;
    Kourpias wrote. McDonnell Douglas, the nation's largest
    defense contractor, receives about $9.2 billion annually from
    taxpayer-financed projects. </p>
    <p>Negotiations stalled when McDonnell Douglas refused to
    offer job security protections to settle the strike. </p>
    <p>Declaring that &quot;there will be no agreement without
    job security,&quot; IAM District 837 President Jerry Oulsen
    accused the company of sabotaging the talks. &quot;The union
    made new proposals to accommodate the company's need for job
    flexibility, with the clear expectation that the company
    would meet the workers' need for job security,&quot; Oulsen
    said. &quot;But the company claimed their negotiators have no
    authority to discuss job security and the subject is no
    longer even on the table.&quot; </p>
    <p>The talks broke down Aug. 16, just two days after
    negotiators had reported progress on the key issue of
    outsourcing. Bargaining had gone on for five consecutive days
    before the breakdown, the first time that had occurred since
    the strike began June 5. </p>
    <p>The talks followed a mass &quot;March for American
    Jobs&quot; by 10,000 people on McDonnell Douglas headquarters
    in St. Louis Aug. 11, led by AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer
    Richard L. Trumka and Kourpias. </p>
    <p>&quot;America is sick of corporate greed,&quot; Trumka
    told the crowd. &quot;America is sick of rich corporations
    sending our best jobs and technologies overseas, and taking
    huge executive bonuses while laying off loyal American
    workers.&quot; </p>
    <p>UAW Secretary-Treasurer Roy Wyse told the strikers,
    &quot;Labor is not going to fail here. This will send a
    message to other companies all across the nation and teach
    them something about corporate responsibility. Mac won't
    win.&quot; </p>
    <p>Some 6,400 employees walked out June 5 at McDonnell
    Douglas' St. Louis plant after rejecting the aerospace
    company's latest contract offer. The key issue in the talks
    is McDonnell's increasing use of outside contractors and the
    transfer of some work to nonunion plants in Mesa, Ariz., and
    Macon, Ga. </p>
    <p>The union is seeking the same basic job security
    provisions that already cover workers at McDonnell Douglas
    competitors, Boeing, General Electric and Pratt &amp;
    Whitney, Oulsen said. </p>
    <p>The company announced June 12 it would hire temporary
    replacement workers at the plant, which makes military
    aircraft, and temporarily transfer some production to other
    plants or to subcontractors. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
