<html>
<head>
<title>Bargaining: California employees gain; Gas workers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="5">Bargaining:<br>
    </font><a href="#California employees gain "><font size="4">California
    employees gain</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a
    href="#Gas workers settle "><font size="4">Gas workers settle</font></a><font
    size="4">; <br>
    </font><a href="#IUE in 15-year GM pact "><font size="4">IUE
    in 15-year GM pact</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a
    href="#IBT strikes Guerrero"><font size="4">IBT strikes
    Guerrero</font></a><font size="4">; <br>
    </font><a href="#Atomic workers extend"><font size="4">Atomic
    workers extend</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a
    href="#UAW, Helicopter deal flies"><font size="4">UAW,
    Helicopter deal flies </font></a><font size="4"><br>
    </font></p>
    <p><a name="California employees gain "><strong>California
    employees gain </strong></a></p>
    <p>A year of bitter negotiations ended when the California
    State Employees, an affiliate of the Service Employees,
    reached agreement with the California State University system
    on a new three-year contract. </p>
    <p>Under the agreement, some 13,000 employees will receive a
    2.48 percent raise retroactive to July 1. The contract also
    includes an increase in shift differential pay and a 2
    percent service salary increase. Workers in seven
    classifications will receive raises to bring their salaries
    in line with similar workers outside the university system.
    The contract expired in July 1995. </p>
    <p>Unit members also will receive paid maternity leave and
    family leave consistent with the federal Family and Medical
    Leave Act. </p>
    <p>The agreement covers administrative, instructional
    support, operations, health care and technical support
    employees of the CSU system. </p>
    <p><a name="Gas workers settle "><strong>Gas workers settle </strong></a></p>
    <p>The Utility Workers and Chemical Workers reached tentative
    agreement on a new two-year contract with Southern California
    Gas that would raise salaries by 3 percent for 5,100
    employees. </p>
    <p>The deal includes a 2.7 percent lump sum bonus after
    ratification and another 2.7 percent payment in 1997, the
    same year the wage increase begins. The company agreed not to
    lay off any full-time employee in the bargaining unit except
    for disciplinary reasons. </p>
    <p>In a side agreement, both sides agreed to limit to 250 per
    year the total number of layoffs, terminations and work force
    reductions in the two years after the contract expires in
    1998. </p>
    <p><a name="IUE in 15-year GM pact "><strong>IUE in 15-year
    GM pact </strong></a></p>
    <p>Electronic Workers Local 801 ratified a 15-year
    local-level agreement with General Motors that is intended to
    secure the future of the Delphi Harrison Thermal Systems
    plant in Loraine, Ohio. </p>
    <p>The agreement, which covers 3,300 hourly employees,
    establishes a two-tier wage system and provides early
    retirement incentives for senior employees. </p>
    <p>GM considered closing the suburban Dayton plant that makes
    compressors and dehydrators for automotive air conditioners,
    but kept it open after negotiations produced cost-cutting.
    The new agreement includes assurances from GM to keep the
    plant open as long as it remains profitable. </p>
    <p><a name="IBT strikes Guerrero"><strong>IBT strikes
    Guerrero</strong></a> </p>
    <p>Protesting unfair labor practices, 200 delivery drivers
    represented by Teamsters Local 63 went on strike Aug. 4 at
    Guerrero Mexican Food Products, the largest tortilla producer
    in southern California. </p>
    <p>The union charges that as a subsidiary of a huge Mexican
    corn flour conglomerate closely aligned with that country's
    ruling circles, Guerrero, which also markets under the
    &quot;Mission&quot; brand, has benefited from corporate
    welfare and has been driving independent operators out of
    business. </p>
    <p>The drivers, who are seeking a second contract with
    payment of overtime, better health insurance and a pension
    plan, joined with other labor, community, campus and
    religious groups for a rally Aug. 7 in front of the Mexican
    consulate in Los Angeles. </p>
    <p>With up to 70 percent of the local market,
    Mission-Guerrero sells to large grocery chains like Ralphs
    and Vons and smaller stores, with the remainder going to
    food-service buyers like Taco Bell and the U.S. Army. </p>
    <p><a name="Atomic workers extend"><strong>Atomic workers
    extend</strong></a> </p>
    <p>The Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers ratified a five-year
    extension of an agreement with Lockheed Martin Energy
    Systems. </p>
    <p>It covers some 800 employees at the Energy Department's
    Oak Ridge, Tenn., operations and follows the pattern set in
    contracts negotiated by the Oak Ridge Atomic Trades Council.
    Those cover 2,500 employees from 17 unions, and all apply to
    three Oak Ridge facilities operated by Lockheed for DoE. </p>
    <p>The new agreement raises wages by 3 percent each year for
    production and maintenance employees at the K-25 facility,
    which is involved in atomic waste management and
    environmental work. Employees also will receive a $500
    lump-sum bonus. </p>
    <p>Employees will have a choice between two managed care
    medical plans that will replace the preferred provider and
    health maintenance programs. </p>
    <p><a name="UAW, Helicopter deal flies"><strong>UAW,
    Helicopter deal flies</strong></a> </p>
    <p>Two UAW locals reached agreement with Bell Helicopter
    Textron on new four-year contracts at the company's Hurst,
    Texas, production plant. </p>
    <p>The separate but parallel agreements for units of
    production and maintenance and clerical and technical workers
    both call for a combination of general wage increases and
    lump-sum bonuses. </p>
    <p>The 3,200 employees, represented by UAW Locals 218 and
    317, will receive 3 percent wage increases and $1,500 lump
    sum payments in the first and third years of the contract and
    only a $1,500 payment in the second year. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
