<html>
<head>
<title>AFT: `Preserve Public Education'</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">AFT: `Preserve Public
    Education' <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>Cincinnati </p>
    <p>AFT delegates were challenged by President Albert Shanker
    to increase activism in and out of the classroom. &quot;It is
    as much our duty to preserve public education as it is to
    negotiate a good contract or defend a competent teacher under
    attack,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>Speaking to the union's 74th biennial convention, Shanker
    said there is still support for public education, especially
    when schools hold students to high standards in academic
    achievement and discipline. </p>
    <p>Shanker urged union members to become involved with AFT's
    &quot;Lessons for Life&quot; campaign, in which members,
    communities, parents and legislators push for shared goals. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney lauded the campaign and
    told delegates they have the full support of the federation.
    He also recognized the union's effort to &quot;put public
    education back in its proper place at the top of our national
    agenda.&quot; </p>
    <p>&quot;Creating strong academic standards in the United
    States is doable,&quot; said Shanker, citing the union's
    second annual &quot;Making Standards Matter&quot; report, an
    analysis of efforts to develop improved academic standards
    throughout the country. </p>
    <p>The union also released a report endorsing charter schools
    as a useful tool for school reform, provided they can
    demonstrate improved student achievement. </p>
    <p>The convention featured 16 workshops on such major
    educational issues as moving from social promotion to earned
    promotion, establishing and enforcing standards of conduct
    and college-school partnerships to raise student achievement. </p>
    <p>The delegates endorsed President Clinton and Vice
    President Gore, later hearing from the vice president. Other
    speakers included Rep. Richard A. Gephardt, (D-Mo.),
    actor/activist Richard Dreyfuss, and human rights activists
    Harry Wu and 13-year-old Craig Kielburger, who has spoken out
    against child labor. </p>
    <p>After hearing from Wu and Kielburger, the delegates passed
    a resolution pledging to put sweatshops out of business.
    &quot;It is unconscionable what these companies do to save
    money,&quot; said Shanker. &quot;We will do whatever it takes
    to get sweatshop owners to change their practices.&quot; </p>
    <p>The union will work with organizations in the Partnership
    for Responsibility, a coalition designed to end sweatshops
    and protect workers' rights. </p>
    <p>Approving continued merger discussions with the National
    Education Association, the convention passed a no-raid
    agreement between the unions. </p>
    <p>Delegates also approved a 4.4 percent per-capita increase
    over the next two years. </p>
    <p>Responding to the market-driven changes in health care,
    the convention approved a nationwide campaign &quot;to
    mobilize consumers and purchases of care, health care workers
    and the general public to promote and defend high standards
    of quality, access and choice. The AFT's Federation of Nurses
    and Health Professionals division will lead the Quality
    First&quot; campaign. </p>
</blockquote>
