<head>
<title>Fire Fighters vow war on privatization</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Fire Fighters vow war on
    privatization <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>Honolulu </p>
    <p>Delegates to the 43rd Fire Fighters convention vowed to
    use the power of the ballot box and union solidarity to stop
    privatization and other anti-worker measures. </p>
    <p>Following an address by President Clinton via satellite,
    the 1,500 delegates responded with unanimous endorsement of
    the Clinton-Gore ticket, citing Clinton's support for
    national collective bargaining for all public employees,
    among other pro- worker stances. </p>
    <p>Whitehead told delegates President Clinton is
    &quot;pro-worker, pro-family and pro-fire fighter,&quot;
    citing the administration's support for important safety
    regulations that protect fire fighters in the line of duty. </p>
    <p>To thwart state and local governments' efforts to
    privatize public service across the country, the delegates
    also earmarked nearly $250,000 for a major new initiative to
    combat privatization of the nation's fire and emergency
    medical services. </p>
    <p>&quot;If we are to meet the challenges of the future, if
    our union is to be positioned to represent the interests of
    our members in the next millennium, then we must continue to
    stay ahead of the curve,&quot; IAFF President Alfred K.
    Whitehead said. </p>
    <p>Private, for-profit corporations are an emerging threat to
    the living standards, economic security and professionalism
    of fire fighters, Whitehead declared. &quot;These
    corporations offer to provide fire and emergency medical
    services more cheaply &thorn; and still made a profit by
    cutting down wages, apparatus, staffing levels, training and
    professional standards.&quot; </p>
    <p>Delegates underscored the union's commitment to political
    action by voting for a substantial increase in funding for
    the IAFF PAC. </p>
    <p>&quot;You have one of the finest legislative and political
    operations in the American labor movement, and every time the
    bell rings, you are there,&quot; AFL-CIO President John J.
    Sweeney told the delegates. &quot;Over the past few years,
    you've demonstrated what it takes by increasing your
    political action activity tenfold and pouring resources into
    legislative fights.&quot; </p>
    <p>Delegates also re-elected Whitehead and
    Secretary-Treasurer Vincent J. Bollon to their third
    four-year terms. Fifteen district vice presidents were
    re-elected, along with a new vice president, William Taylor,
    representing the fourth district in Baltimore. </p>
    <p>Other speakers included Hawaii Democratic Sen. Daniel
    Akaka and Reps. Patsy Mink and Neil Abercrombie; and Jerry
    Lewis, entertainer and chairman of the Muscular Dystrophy
    Association. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
