<html>
<head>
<title>Union News: GMP re-elects leaders; Carpenters in</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="5">Union News:</font><font
    size="4"> <br>
    </font><a href="#GMP re-elects leaders "><font size="4">GMP
    re-elects leaders</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a
    href="#Carpenters in training pact "><font size="4">Carpenters
    in training pact</font></a><font size="4">; <br>
    </font><a href="#W.Va. talks politics "><font size="4">W.Va.
    talks politics</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a
    href="#`Tis the (political) season "><font size="4">`Tis the
    (political) season</font></a><font size="4">; <br>
    </font><a href="#Tosco reopens refinery "><font size="4">Tosco
    reopens refinery</font></a><font size="4">; </font><a
    href="#Unions boycott bridge "><font size="4">Unions boycott
    bridge</font></a><font size="4">; <br>
    </font><a href="#APALA plans organizing"><font size="4">APALA
    plans organizing </font></a></p>
    <p align="left">&#160;</p>
    <p><a name="GMP re-elects leaders "><strong>GMP re-elects
    leaders </strong></a></p>
    <p>The Glass, Molders and Pottery Workers re-elected their
    top leaders and rallied the union to meet the political
    challenge this year. </p>
    <p>&quot;America's unions are back!&quot; AFL-CIO
    Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka proclaimed as he urged
    the delegates to mobilize for the November election and
    beyond. &quot;You can feel the anger and the resentment and
    the frustration turning into hope for tens of millions of
    working Americans.&quot; </p>
    <p>GMP President Frank W. Carter told the convention that
    concerted political action could help win a better future for
    working people. The 762 delegates, meeting in Las Vegas,
    voted to raise international union dues by $2 per month per
    member and to give locals the option of raising dues by up to
    $4.50 per month. The increase was needed, Secretary-Treasurer
    James H. Rankin said, to sustain the services the
    international provides. </p>
    <p>Carter, Rankin and all other incumbent officers were re-
    elected without opposition. </p>
    <p>Other speakers included House Minority Leader Richard A.
    Gephardt (D-Mo.), Minority Whip David E. Bonior (D-Mich.),
    Rep. Robert F. Andrews (D-N.J.) and Gordon Wilson, president
    of the Ontario labor federation. </p>
    <p><a name="Carpenters in training pact "><strong>Carpenters
    in training pact </strong></a></p>
    <p>In the second major agreement of its kind this year, the
    Carpenters have joined forces with the Ingersoll-Rand
    Architectural Hardware Division to improve training and
    standards in the construction industry. </p>
    <p>Ingersoll-Rand will provide technical support and training
    materials and will certify instructors and installers upon
    completion of the training. The UBC will provide the
    apprenticeship and training programs. The union signed a
    similar agreement with Wilsonart this year. </p>
    <p>&quot;This program is a win-win-win arrangement,&quot;
    said Dudley Light, UBC technical coordinator for
    apprenticeship. &quot;The construction industry,
    Ingersoll-Rand and the UBC will all benefit from this
    innovative program.&quot; </p>
    <p><a name="W.Va. talks politics "><strong>W.Va. talks
    politics </strong></a></p>
    <p>It was politics, politics and politics at the West
    Virginia AFL-CIO convention Aug. 15-16 in Charleston. </p>
    <p>&quot;Working families and their unions are re-emerging as
    a national political force,&quot; AFL-CIO Executive Vice
    President Linda Chavez-Thompson told the convention,
    &quot;because Congress got the message that we're watching
    what they do.&quot; </p>
    <p>Some 300 delegates endorsed for re-election their
    congressional contingent of Democratic Reps. Alan B.
    Mollohan, Robert E. Wise Jr. and Nick Joe Rahall II, as well
    as Sen. John J. Rockefeller IV (D). Democratic challenger
    Charlotte Pritt garnered the group's nod for governor, while
    endorsements were made in several statewide judicial races as
    well. </p>
    <p>Resolutions concerning workers' compensation and public
    employees' right to organize were taken up. </p>
    <p><a name="`Tis the (political) season "><strong>`Tis the
    (political) season </strong></a></p>
    <p>Trade unionists meeting one state away from West Virginia
    also focused on politics, as the 29th constitutional
    convention of the Virginia AFL-CIO met in Williamsburg Aug.
    15-17. </p>
    <p>Federation President John J. Sweeney keynoted that
    gathering, warning Democrats in the state's legislature that
    labor is tired of carrying their water and coming up with a
    bucket of mud. Sweeney also went to Newport News Shipbuilding
    with AFL-CIO Vice President and Union Labor Life Chairman
    Robert A. Georgine to laud a labor- business partnership. </p>
    <p>The 350 delegates made endorsements in several
    congressional races including the Warner Senate race,
    choosing Democrat Mark Warner over incumbent Republican John
    Warner. Also up for discussion were resolutions concerning
    Bridge- stone/Firestone, federal unions, civil rights,
    community services, the Human Resources Development
    Institute, organizing, the Coalition of Black Trade Unionists
    and education. </p>
    <p>Besides Sweeney, the attendees heard from Warner, AFL-CIO
    Political Director Steve Rosenthal, Field Mobilization
    Director Marilyn Sneiderman and Evelyn DuBrow, vice president
    of UNITE. </p>
    <p><a name="Tosco reopens refinery "><strong>Tosco reopens
    refinery </strong></a></p>
    <p>The Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers Local 8-234 scored a
    win when Tosco offered to reopen the old BP refinery it
    bought, with a union work force. </p>
    <p>Tosco will rehire 215 of the 500 workers who lost jobs
    when the refinery, located near Philadelphia, was closed
    early this year. The company also will spend $50 million to
    update the factory over the next year. </p>
    <p>&quot;People are going to be real happy around here&quot;
    when the refinery reopens, said Denis J. Stephano, president
    of Local 8-234. &quot;A lot of people were completely
    convinced it would never run again.&quot; </p>
    <p><a name="Unions boycott bridge "><strong>Unions boycott
    bridge </strong></a></p>
    <p>A building trades boycott of the 17.6-mile Chesapeake Bay
    Bridge and Tunnel has resulted in nearly 9 percent less
    traffic by autos and light trucks. </p>
    <p>&quot;We believe we've hit a home run,&quot; said C. Ray
    Davenport, president of the Virginia Building and
    Construction Trades Council. He estimated the boycott, which
    is supported by the unions in the state AFL-CIO, cost the
    state about $300,000 in lost revenue in July alone. </p>
    <p>The dispute centers on the construction of a new parallel
    span connecting Virginia's Eastern Shore with the Virginia
    Beach and Tidewater areas. </p>
    <p>The $200 million job is being constructed with imported,
    nonunion labor. Davenport said PCL Civil Constructors Inc. of
    Denver refused to negotiate pre-hire agreements with the
    Operating Engineers, Laborers and Carpenters, and instead
    brought in workers from as far away as Florida and Canada. </p>
    <p><a name="APALA plans organizing"><strong>APALA plans
    organizing</strong></a> </p>
    <p>In another sign of a resurgent labor movement's commitment
    to organizing, more than 250 union leaders, organizers and
    Asian- Pacific-American union activists met in San Diego to
    develop plans to organize the millions of
    Asian-Pacific-Americans in the work force. </p>
    <p>It was the largest organizing conference in recent
    history, Service Employees President Andy Stern said, telling
    the cheering audience that the union movement &quot;must stop
    talking about organizing and start funding.&quot; </p>
    <p>Richard Bensinger, head of the AFL-CIO Organizing
    Department, agreed, and applauded Asian Pacific American
    Labor Alliance for calling on labor unions to allocate 30
    percent of their resources to organizing. </p>
    <p>A joint organizing proposal was developed and announced by
    Guy Fujimura, secretary-treasurer of the Longshoremen's and
    Warehousemen's Local 142. Under the proposal, APALA and the
    unions would develop a national network of
    Asian-Pacific-American organizers, train and hire new
    organizers, reach out to more Asian- Pacific-American workers
    in campaigns, and develop Asian-Pacific- American leaders. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
