<html>
<head>
<title>APWU vows fight to keep jobs</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">APWU vows fight to keep jobs <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>Delegates go to streets to help hotel workers </p>
    <p>Los Angeles </p>
    <p>Delegates to the 13th biennial Postal Workers convention
    took to the streets in support of a local organizing drive
    and vowed to stand and fight against efforts to privatize
    their jobs. </p>
    <p>The nearly 3,000 delegates emptied the convention hall and
    joined a huge demonstration with the Hotel Employees and
    Restaurant Employees at the New Otani Hotel. Despite the
    searing heat, the APWU and HERE members met at City Hall and
    walked a seven-block circuit to the hotel, shouting and
    chanting slogans. </p>
    <p>HERE Local 11 called for an international boycott of the
    nonunion New Otani Hotel on Jan. 24 and has been picketing
    regularly since. The hotel illegally fired three pro-union
    housekeepers with 16 years of service in order to thwart a
    union organizing drive. The boycott is endorsed by 11 of 15
    members of the L.A. City Council, as well as dozens of labor,
    religious and community groups. </p>
    <p>In the convention hall, delegates participated in an
    interactive live video to dramatize the anti-worker agenda of
    right-wing politicians like Newt Gingrich and managers like
    Postmaster General Marvin Runyon. </p>
    <p>APWU President Moe Biller called on the union members to
    fight in every way necessary all efforts to destroy postal
    jobs through privatization, outsourcing and all other means
    of stealing work from postal workers. &quot;We're now
    fighting for our future. That's our theme, and solidarity is
    what's essential.&quot; </p>
    <p>Delegates also passed more than 50 resolutions addressing
    labor-management issues, including the staffing of contract
    stations, wages and weekend and overtime work. </p>
    <p>House Minority Whip David E. Bonior (D-Mich.) said a
    change to Democrats in control of Congress would end
    anti-worker proposals at the USPS. &quot;This election isn't
    about unfunded mandates and the line-item veto,&quot; he
    said. &quot;It's about jobs and wages and pensions and
    working conditions and health care and education for our
    kids.&quot; </p>
    <p>In a videotaped message, Senate Minority Leader Thomas S.
    Daschle (D-S.D.) promised to fight USPS privatization
    proposals. </p>
    <p>The fight must continue at the ballot box, said Electronic
    Workers Vice President Gloria Johnson, who is also president
    of the Coalition of Labor Union Women. &quot;If President
    Clinton isn't re- elected and we don't recapture the House
    and Senate, we can say goodbye to the hard-won rights of
    workers,&quot; she said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
