<html>
<head>
<title>NALC says Clinton, Yes; Runyon, No</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">NALC says Clinton, Yes;
    Runyon, No <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>Orlando, Fla. </p>
    <p>Political action and the fight against privatization took
    center stage at the Letter Carriers convention as 8,100
    delegates endorsed the re-election of President Clinton and
    voted &quot;no confidence&quot; in the postmaster general. </p>
    <p>Prior to the endorsement vote, Vice President Gore
    addressed the convention via satellite, noting the
    accomplishments of the administration that have benefited
    Letter Carriers and other working men and women. </p>
    <p>&quot;Many on the other side say privatize,&quot; Gore
    said. &quot;Reform yes. Make it work even better, you bet.
    But privatize? Not on your life because, like you, we support
    the Postal Service.&quot; </p>
    <p>NALC President Vincent R. Sombrotto also reminded the
    delegates of the union's position on supporting candidates
    regardless of party. &quot;If the representatives support us,
    we support them. If they don't support us, we don't support
    them.&quot; </p>
    <p>Delegates unanimously voted &quot;no confidence&quot; in
    Postmaster General Marvin Runyon, who has demonstrated his
    lack of support for workers with efforts to privatize and
    restrict rights, the NALC declared in a resolution. </p>
    <p>The resolution also noted that mail processing automation
    continues despite serious problems, that communications
    between the NALC and USPS have deteriorated because of
    abandonment of the Employee Involvement process and that
    Runyon's policies have undercut carriers' efforts to provide
    superior mail service. </p>
    <p>Numerous speakers in the jammed Orange County, Fla.,
    convention center called for action at the ballot box and at
    the post office. </p>
    <p>Rep. Neil Abercrombie (D-Hawaii) told delegates that in
    order to have a worker-friendly Congress next year,
    &quot;everyone must work hard in the November
    elections.&quot; </p>
    <p>Reps. Gene Green (D-Texas) and Karen Thurman (D-Fla.) said
    the current Congress has been the most anti-worker since
    1947, and the only remedy is to send the GOP-controlled body
    home. </p>
    <p>Former Labor Secretary Ray Marshall told the delegates
    that elected officials should be forced to adopt a high-wage
    strategy. Without it, Americans are &quot;going to stay on
    the same path (in which) the rich get richer, workers will be
    less well off&quot; and the country's institutions will be
    weakened. </p>
    <p>Philip Bower, general secretary of the Postal, Telephone
    and Telegraph International, said that unions in Europe are
    resisting privatization, and that unions in Great Britain are
    fighting management efforts to have &quot;team working,&quot;
    which is designed to reduced the influence of unions in the
    workplace. </p>
    <p>Delegates also elected seven union members to serve as
    delegates to the AFL-CIO convention next year. </p>
    <p>Other speakers included former Steelworkers President Lynn
    Williams; Jeff Faux, president of the Economic Policy
    Institute; and radio commentator Jim Hightower. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
