<head>
<title>Labor rallies 'round berry pickers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Labor rallies 'round berry
    pickers <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">Sharolyn A. Rosier </p>
    <p>As the Farm Workers' black eagle flag waved above 15
    cities, thousands of trade unionists and community activists
    from San Jose, Calif., to New Haven, Conn., rallied Aug. 14
    with shouts of &quot;Si Se Puede&quot; (Yes We Can). </p>
    <p>The national day of action to support strawberry workers
    was organized by the UFW and AFL-CIO central labor councils
    during last month's national CLC conference. The strawberry
    workers endure unsanitary conditions, no health insurance,
    slave-like wages and 12-hour work days. </p>
    <p>In San Jose, more than 300 trade unionists, religious and
    community organizations joined in the demonstration in front
    of the downtown federal building. &quot;This is just the
    beginning,&quot; said San Jose CLC Executive Officer Amy
    Dean. &quot;We're going to make sure the injustices
    strawberry pickers endure become common knowledge.&quot; </p>
    <p>In Watsonville, Calif., the UFW strawberry campaign's
    headquarters, some 800 trade unionists, strawberry workers
    and their supporters turned out for the third in a series of
    protests at local berry coolers. &quot;Consumers and the
    public are tired of seeing workers being exploited. There
    hasn't been a wage increase in 10 years,&quot; said UFW
    President Arturo Rodriguez as the crowd chanted in Spanish,
    &quot;We see it, we feel it, the union is here.&quot; </p>
    <p>In downtown San Francisco, workers waved UFW flags, formed
    a human billboard during lunch hour and chanted,
    &quot;Strawberry growers, you're no good, treat your workers
    like you should.&quot; </p>
    <p>During a protest evoking memories of the Cesar Chavez-led
    grape and lettuce boycotts of the 1960s and 70s, more than
    100 Denver trade unionists launched their campaign with a
    rally in front of Our Lady of Guadalupe Church. In Chicago,
    chanting workers were confronted by managers of the Whole
    Foods Market and were asked by the police to leave. </p>
    <p>Following each demonstration, participants passed out
    literature asking consumers to &quot;please tell your grocer
    to support strawberry workers' basic rights.&quot; They also
    visited grocery stores and asked store managers to sign a
    pledge form stating their support for &quot;strawberry
    workers' rights, including a living wage, health insurance
    and clean drinking water and bathrooms in the fields.&quot; </p>
    <p>The workers received additional resources when the AFL-CIO
    Executive Council voted Aug. 6 to provide matching funds to
    the strawberry campaign from the federation's organizing
    campaign fund. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
