<head>
<title>UMWA pact gains on wages, pensions</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">UMWA pact gains on wages,
    pensions <br>
    </font></p>
    <p>The Mine Workers won significant improvements in pension
    benefits, health insurance and wages for its members and
    retirees in a renegotiated agreement with the Bituminous Coal
    Operators Association. A reopener option in the 1993 contract
    paved the way for the gains. </p>
    <p>&quot;The solidarity our members showed on the picket
    lines in 1993 and the growth of our strike fund placed the
    union in an excellent position to negotiate these
    improvements,&quot; UMWA President Cecil Roberts said.
    &quot;I am pleased to say we reached this agreement without
    having to strike any BCOA companies.&quot; </p>
    <p>The pension provisions apply to about 100,000 members in
    the union's 1950 and 1974 plans. The other improvements cover
    40,000 miners employed by BCOA companies or firms with
    &quot;me too&quot; agreements. </p>
    <p>The new agreement eliminates a huge penalty for miners
    laid off before they turn 50 and who choose to retire at 55
    under the terms of the deferred vested pension program. </p>
    <p>Any laid-off miner, regardless of age at time of layoff,
    who has at least 20 years of service covered by the 1974 plan
    and who has worked after Dec. 16, 1993, would receive a full
    pension if he or she retires at 55. </p>
    <p>The agreement also raises pension credits and extends and
    increases annual bonuses until 1997. The UMWA also won a 25
    percent reduction in the annual family health insurance
    deductible, dropping it from $1,000 to $750. </p>
    <p>The 1993 contract expires Aug. 31, 1998, and both sides
    agreed to early negotiations in 1997. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
