<head>
<title>Iron Workers plan to build for future</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996<br>
<br>
</strong><font size="4">Iron Workers plan to build for fortune </font></p>
<blockquote>
    <p align="left">Las Vegas</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="left">Delegates to the Iron Workers' centennial
    anniversary convention approved the addition of a new
    classification of workers to the union's official name
    &thorn; reinforcing iron workers. </p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p>Now 100 years old, the new International Association of
    Bridge, Structural, Ornamental and Reinforcing Iron Workers
    was urged by President Jake West to &quot;honor the heroes of
    the past and build a brighter future for ourselves and for
    all the Iron Workers who will come after us.&quot; </p>
    <p>The union's past could be seen at the Historic Display
    Area, which included thousands of such items as photographs,
    tools, clothing, official records, convention memorabilia,
    dues/membership books dating back to 1896 and a hot rivet
    display. </p>
    <p>The future of the union, and of the entire labor movement,
    depends on vigorous organizing activity, said AFL-CIO
    Building and Construction Trades Department President Robert
    Georgine, who announced plans for a multicraft organizing
    campaign. </p>
    <p>&quot;The open-shop movement is like a virus,&quot; he
    said. &quot;We have an antidote &thorn; organizing &thorn;
    that is the vaccine against this open-shop disease.&quot; </p>
    <p>Sen. Chris Dodd (D-Conn.), chairman of the Democratic
    Party, urged the delegates to look to the near future and
    this year's election. He denounced Republican presidential
    candidate Bob Dole for voting against Medicare and said,
    &quot;Comparing the candidates, the choice is clear &thorn;
    President Clinton.&quot; </p>
    <p>Other speakers included Nevada Gov. Bob Miller (D);
    Occupational Safety and Health Administration Director Joseph
    Dear; and Steve Protulis, director of the National Council of
    Senior Citizens. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
