<html>
<head>
<title>Worker rights in Mexico will get U.S. hearing</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p align="center"><font size="3"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></font><font
        size="4"><br>
        <br>
        Worker rights in Mexico will get U.S. hearing <br>
        </font>by </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p align="center">David Kameras</p>
    <p>The Labor Department has agreed to review charges that
    Mexican labor law discriminates against federal workers who
    try to organize and register independent unions. </p>
    <p>Acting on a petition filed by three labor and human rights
    groups, the U.S. National Administrative Office, an agency
    created to monitor the labor side accord of the North
    American Free Trade Agreement, will recommend whether the
    charges warrant ministerial consultations. The report by the
    NAO will be released within 120 days. </p>
    <p>Under the Mexican process, workers trying to form an
    independent union must first get clearance from a panel that
    includes representatives of the Confederation of Mexican
    Workers (CTM), a union with close ties to the ruling party,
    the subject of earlier complaints in the private sector. </p>
    <p>Human Rights Watch/Americas, the International Labor
    Rights Fund and the National Association of Democratic
    Lawyers contend that Mexico's union certification process is
    biased. They charge that efforts to register independent
    unions are &quot;arbitrarily&quot; rejected, thereby denying
    federal workers their right to associate and organize freely. </p>
    <p>The petition was filed in the wake of a number of Mexican
    Supreme Court decisions striking down a long-standing
    practice of prohibiting union registration by public workers
    where another union is already present, and scrapping
    extension of state contracting schemes at privatized
    businesses, including no-strike clauses. These decisions may
    prove to be valuable tools in breaking the hegemony of the
    pro-government CTM. </p>
    <p>The issue of union registration came up two years ago when
    workers at a Sony Corp. plant in Nuevo Laredo attempted to
    form an independent union. Further declaring their
    independence last May, a million workers defied a parade ban
    imposed by CTM and marched in Mexico City's main square to
    protest their government's economic policies. </p>
    <p>The lack of strong independent labor organizations has
    helped to keep wages depressed in Mexico, making that country
    more attractive to U.S. employers like General Electric,
    which has joined the exodus of manufacturing taking place
    under NAFTA. </p>
    <p>Electronic Workers Local 162 President Gary Hefner thinks
    that Mexican wages under $1 an hour was a big factor in GE's
    Aug. 1 closure of a residential transformer plant in Hickory,
    N.C. &quot;At those wages, the workers are practically paying
    the company to come to work,&quot; he told a &quot;Families
    First&quot; hearing held by congressional Democrats. </p>
    <p>&quot;We have 343 hourly workers and 250 salaried workers
    losing their jobs,&quot; Hefner said. &quot;We gave GE all
    they demanded. We worked with them in their labor-management
    cooperation schemes, even though the benefits all accrued to
    the company. We gave them everything they asked us to give,
    in the hope of keeping our jobs in Hickory. They took it all,
    and then they took our jobs too.&quot; </p>
    <p>Other American employers are playing the Mexico card. Ford
    Motor Co. barred Canadian and U.S. union officials and human
    rights group members from observing an Aug. 13 union election
    at one of the company's plants near Mexico City, although the
    group spent the day in front of the plant interviewing
    workers. Ford kept the Cleto Nigmo Committee of Independent
    Observers out in deference to the existing union, a section
    of the CTM, which Ford said could decide all union matters. </p>
    <p>The group called for invalidation of the election because
    a slate of dissident candidates was refused inclusion on the
    ballot, despite having collected sufficient signatures to
    qualify. </p>
    <p>Postal Workers President Moe Biller charged the Postal
    Service with helping a San Diego firm use Mexican workers
    earning $4 a day to prepare letters for large-scale U.S.
    mailing companies, in effect sending postal jobs south of the
    border. </p>
    <p>Meanwhile, the United States is running into opposition
    from its trading partners as it tries to get the World Trade
    Organization to agree to linkage between trade and labor
    standards. </p>
    <p>The United Kingdom has been a leading voice in the
    European Community against the proposal, joined by developing
    countries, many of whom rely on a submissive domestic work
    force to expand their markets. </p>
    <p>The governments of many developing countries have cozy
    relationships with multinational corporations like Nike and
    Reebok, resulting in minuscule wages and outrageous working
    conditions, Rev. Jesse L. Jackson told the Executive Council
    in August. </p>
    <p>&quot;I am convinced that unless we address this, the vast
    body of oppressed workers can swallow up our labor market and
    not even have indigestion,&quot; he said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
