<html>
<head>
<title>Widest U.S. trade gap with China</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Widest U.S. trade gap with
    China <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p>For the first time, the bilateral deficit with China
    exceeded that with Japan, reflecting a continued but largely
    unreported surge in imports from a country that uses forced
    and low-wage labor. </p>
    <p>The U.S.-China deficit reached $3.3 billion in June, up
    from $3 billion a year ago. The deficit with Japan, by
    contrast, narrowed significantly over the 12 months, from
    $5.3 billion to $3.2 billion. The deficit with the Pacific
    Rim narrowed too, thanks largely to the decline with Japan. </p>
    <p>The gold rush south by U.S. corporations helped to create
    a bilateral merchandise trade deficit with Mexico of $8.3
    billion for the first six months of the year, $600 million
    greater than in the same period in 1995. </p>
    <p>Overall, the merchandise trade deficit was $12.3 billion
    in June, a decrease from $13.2 billion a month earlier. </p>
    <p>For the first half of the year, deficits were scored in
    vehicles ($26.4 billion), clothing and footwear ($20.2
    billion), data processing and office machinery ($11.6
    billion), electrical machinery ($9.6 billion), home
    electronics ($5.5 billion), toys and sporting goods ($3.9
    billion), iron and steel products ($3.7 billion), furniture
    and bedding ($2.9 billion) and paper and paperboard ($1
    billion). Airplanes and parts ($10.3 billion) and general and
    specialized machinery ($3.8 billion) yielded surpluses. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; 1996 AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
