<html>
<head>
<title>As layoffs mount, backlash grows</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">As layoffs mount, backlash
    grows <br>
    </font>by </p>
    <p align="center">David Kameras </p>
    <p>In the wake of AFL-CIO efforts to inform Americans of the
    consequences of low wages and job insecurity, evidence of a
    backlash against the mania of corporate mergers and
    downsizing that has marked this decade appears to be growing. </p>
    <p>One example can be seen in the obscure government
    procurement regulations that actually encourage armsmakers to
    merge into megacorporations, costing thousands of jobs. This
    situation brought together Independent Rep. Bernard Sanders
    (Vt.) and Republican Rep. Christopher H. Smith (N.J.) to
    sponsor an amendment to the defense appropriations bill to
    stop &quot;payoffs for layoffs.&quot; </p>
    <p>Already, the American taxpayer is slated to foot the bill
    for some $300 million in merger expenses, on the absurd
    premise that closing plants increases productivity that will
    result in cost savings some time in the future, courtesy of
    an even more concentrated defense establishment. </p>
    <p>When Lockheed and Martin Marietta merged, thousands of
    union workers at an assembly plant in Marietta, Ga., were let
    go. Yet &quot;contrary to the facts of an increasing stock
    value and skyrocketing executive compensation, our members
    did not receive any compensation or retraining
    assistance,&quot; said James M. Carroll, president and
    directing business representative of Machinists Local Lodge
    709. </p>
    <p>The Sanders-Smith amendment was passed in the House but
    rejected by the Senate. Still, conferees may move for a study
    of the problem. </p>
    <p>&quot;At a time when real wages in this country for
    working people are in decline, at a time when people are
    scared to death about whether or not they are going to have
    their decent-paying jobs, they do not want to see their tax
    dollars going to large multibillion-dollar corporations so
    that these companies can then merge and lay off American
    workers,&quot; Sanders said. </p>
    <p>Polls show that Americans increasingly believe that
    corporate greed is the source of their economic insecurity,
    putting corporations on the defensive. </p>
    <p>Briggs &amp; Stratton Corp., for example, sued the
    National Catholic Reporter, an independent nonprofit
    religious newsweekly, for $30 million over an article almost
    two years old that asserted the company was &quot;in either
    denial or moral blindness&quot; when it acted to shift 2,000
    union jobs in Milwaukee to nonunion plants in the South. </p>
    <p>Corporate prickleness, however, has not been matched by
    corporate responsibility. The Bureau of Labor Statistics
    reported that 232,713 workers lost their jobs as part of mass
    layoffs during the first quarter of this year. </p>
    <p>And private-sector figures have the number of layoffs in
    July pegged at 41,843, 4.2 percent higher than in June and
    almost 80 percent more than a year ago. </p>
    <p>In July, the jobless rate edged up 0.1 percent, to 5.4
    percent, remaining in the range of 5.3 percent to 5.8 percent
    where it has languished since the fall of 1994. </p>
    <p>In addition to 7.3 million officially jobless, 4.4 million
    were working involuntary part time and 1.4 million wanted
    work and were available, but had stopped looking for jobs.
    That left a total of 13.1 million unemployed or
    underemployed. The alternative rate used by BLS to evaluate
    labor underutilization held steady at 10 percent. </p>
    <p>The economy added 193,000 payroll jobs in July, but that
    was less than the 273,000 monthly average increase registered
    in the second quarter of the year and far less than that
    needed to meet the objectives of legislative mandates already
    in place, according to AFL-CIO economist Frank Parente.
    &quot;If the jobless rate had been 4 percent, the goal of the
    Humphrey-Hawkins full employment law, there would have been
    almost 2 million fewer jobless people,&quot; he said. </p>
    <p>&quot;In the 64 months since the end of the last
    recession, the economy has added 11.4 million jobs, compared
    with 15.7 million additional jobs in a similar period
    following the recession of the early 1980s and 13.2 million
    following the recession of the mid- 1970s,&quot; Parente
    said. </p>
    <p>Job growth in July was led by a jump of 89,000 in retail
    trade, the fourth consecutive large gain, while construction
    added 25,000 jobs, and business services, 35,000. But
    manufacturing lost another 20,000 jobs, a total of 282,000
    since its most recent peak in March 1995. Federal employment
    also declined. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
