<head>
<title>Household gains responsibility for union credit</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">Household gains
    responsibility for union credit card </font></p>
    <p>The Union Privilege MasterCard portfolio now is in the
    hands of Household International. </p>
    <p>Bank of New York (Delaware) turned over the assets Aug.
    19, making Household responsible for all customer service,
    mailing all bills and notices and making credit decisions
    using its own approval criteria. </p>
    <p>Current cardholder notification began Aug. 22, with a
    welcome package to follow in October and quarterly mailings
    beginning in January. </p>
    <p>In an effort to improve on the card, Union Privilege and
    Household plan a series of product tests beginning in
    October, including what types of offers and telemarketing are
    best and how to tailor a card for members with credit
    problems or no credit history. </p>
    <p>Household also is developing a benefit to allow
    cardholders to transfer balances from other, higher-interest
    cards to pay them off at the prime rate. The company also is
    exploring the development of a money-saving
    &quot;rewards&quot; type of program. </p>
    <p>Additionally, Household plans to make available to unions
    its HOMEBASE database to better understand and communicate
    with members and the general public. </p>
    <p>The company has retained the scholarship program, skip
    payment and strike benefits. </p>
    <p>Union Privilege made the switch in administration of its
    card to provide better service for union members and gain the
    payment of royalties to the AFL-CIO and its affiliates. That
    money &thorn; some $300 million in royalties over the first
    five years &thorn; will finance organizing and national
    outreach to benefit the entire labor movement. It will be
    split between the federation and international unions. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
