<blockquote>
    <p align="left"><font size="4">Resources</font></p>
    <p>This Labor Day weekend, We Do the Work presents Heroes, 3:
    Profiles from the American Workplace. The one-hour public
    television special pays tribute to ordinary people who take
    action in times of adversity and make extraordinary
    contributions to society through their work. Check local
    listings for air times. </p>
    <p>UNITE has released a compilation from Local 1077's
    Whiteville Apparel Choir, featuring a blend of gospel and
    labor music. Cassette tapes are $10. Contact UNITE Choir
    Project, 1010 Tucker Street, Greensboro, N.C. 27405. </p>
    <p><font size="4">Conferences</font></p>
    <p>The biennial Child Labor Conference, Children at Work:
    Exploitation Escalates, will be held Sept. 8-10 at the
    Embassy Row Hotel in Washington. The conference will include
    sessions on domestic and international issues on
    school-to-work programs, corporate responsibility,
    international strategies on trade and development and
    occupational safety and health. Contact the National
    Consumers League, 1701 K St., N.W., Suite 1200, Washington,
    D.C. 20006; or via FAX at 202/835-0747. </p>
    <p>Union Issues for Working Women, sponsored by the George
    Meany Center for Labor Studies Oct. 20-25, will explore new
    strategies and approaches to tap the enormous energy that
    millions of women can bring to the labor movement. The
    program will be held at the center's Silver Spring, Md.,
    campus. Contact Diana Linton at 301/431-5420. </p>
    <p>Dealing with Workplace Violence Institute will be
    sponsored by the George Meany Center for Labor Studies Oct.
    13-18. Registration and room and board are $670. The cost for
    commuters is $110. Contact David G. Alexander at
    301/431-5408. </p>
</blockquote>
