<html>
<head>
<title>Newsmakers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<p align="center"><img src="../images/aflnews.gif" align="bottom"
width="443" height="140"></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="center"><strong>August 23, 1996</strong></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font size="4">News Makers<br>
    </font>Compiled by Muriel H. Cooper </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney announced a major round
    of staff appointments during the summer Executive Council
    meeting in Chicago. </p>
    <p>Ron Blackwell, chief economist at UNITE, will head the
    Corporate Affairs Department. Bill Fletcher leaves the
    Service Employees to become director of the Education
    Department and Barbara Shailor, international affairs
    director for the Machinists, will assume the same position at
    the federation. </p>
    <p>Other key appointments in the Corporate Affairs Department
    include David Chu, former research director of SEIU, who will
    become director of strategic research. Nancy Mills, formerly
    of SEIU, will be acting director of the Center for Workplace
    Democracy, and Bill Patterson, corporate affairs specialist
    at the Teamsters, will direct the Center for Worker Ownership
    and Governance. </p>
    <p>Dick Leonard, currently at the Oil Chemical and Atomic
    Workers, will direct strategic campaign field operations as
    an assistant director in the Department of Field
    Mobilization. (See stories, Pages 5-6). </p>
    <p>Elmer Chatak, president of the Industrial Union Department
    since 1992, retired on Aug. 5. IUD's Executive Council
    elected Secretary-Treasurer Peter diCicco to succeed Chatak
    as president and Joseph B. Uehlein, executive assistant to
    the president, as its secretary-treasurer. </p>
    <p>Chatak, whose four-year term was not due to expire until
    November, stepped down early to give the new officers an
    early start with the ongoing department reorganization. He
    began his union career in 1951 when he was hired by Phillip
    Murray as a CIO organizer. After the AFL and CIO merger, he
    was transferred to the Steelworkers District 7 and became the
    district's key organizer. In 1968 he became the first
    director of the USWA's new organizing department. </p>
    <p>DiCicco, who was elected secretary-treasurer in 1992,
    previously served as vice president of the Electronic Workers
    and IUE's New England District. </p>
    <p>Uehlein previously served as IUD's director of Strategic
    Campaigns. He is also president of the Labor Heritage
    Foundation. </p>
    <p>Robert F. Harbrant has retired as president of the
    AFL-CIO's Food and Allied Service Trades Department, a
    position he has held since 1979. He will be succeeded by
    Secretary-Treasurer Jeffrey L. Fiedler on Sept. 1. </p>
    <p>Harbrant served as secretary-treasurer and first executive
    director of FAST as well as executive assistant and assistant
    to the secretary-treasurer in the Union Label and Service
    Trades Department. He will continue working with the Bakery,
    Confectionery and Tobacco Workers. </p>
    <p>Fiedler began his career at FAST as director of corporate
    affairs in 1980 and was appointed secretary-treasurer in
    1990. </p>
    <p>President Clinton celebrated his 50th birthday by blowing
    out his candles on a union-made cake from famed Greenberg
    Bakery in New York City. The employees have been members of
    the Bakery, Confectionery and Tobacco Workers since the shop
    opened in 1946. The huge butter cream-frosted pound cake,
    which was donated to the president by the bakery, took two
    days to prepare. </p>
    <p>AFL-CIO economist Greg Woodhead was elected to the
    executive board of the Industrial Relations Research
    Association for a three- year term, beginning in 1997. The
    IRRA gives professionals interested in all aspects of
    industrial relations and human resources the opportunity to
    share ideas and learn about new developments, issues and
    practices in the field. </p>
    <p>Ken Orsatti, national executive director of the Screen
    Actors Guild, was elected president of the California State
    Theatrical Federation, the entertainment arm of the
    California state federation. Marjo Bernay of the Theatrical
    Stage Employees Local 790 was named vice president, and
    Edward Powell from IATSE was elected secretary-treasurer. </p>
    <p>DEATH </p>
    <p>Lillian Clark, national treasurer of the Television and
    Radio Artists since 1991, died in New York City after
    battling cancer for many months. She was 70. </p>
    <p>Clark was one of the original Ray Charles Singers and also
    appeared on the Perry Como show in the 1950s. She also
    recorded with Count Basie, Ella Fitzgerald, Tommy Dorsey,
    Louis Armstrong, Sammy Davis Jr. and other musical legends. </p>
    <p>She is survived by a son and a brother. </p>
</blockquote>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
