<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 1</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Grass-roots mobilization in high gear <br>
Unions not intimidatedby Republican threats <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Michael Byrne and Mike Hall</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>With Republican congressional leaders flailing wildly at
unions in the final days before recess, the AFL-CIO was keeping
the pressure on with advertising on worker issues while preparing
to move into an intensive get-out-the-vote phase of Labor '96. </p>
<p>More than 100 trained coordinators were directing grass-roots
activity in congressional districts across the country, and many
were planning recess activity. They were backed by a new round of
television and radio ads on pension security that will replace or
augment ads showing House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.)
describing Republican plans to let Medicare &quot;wither on the
vine.&quot; </p>
<p>On the ground, the federation's unprecedented member
mobilization campaign already has enlisted 3,000 rank-and-file
unionists to assist the electoral push, with a goal of training
10,000 union members this year. They will be part of the
permanent grass-roots network of at least 100 activists in each
congressional district. </p>
<p>The campaign, subtitled &quot;Building to Win, Building to
Last,&quot; will enable the federation to &quot;support men and
women who will respond to the needs of working families, and then
hold those candidates accountable once they are elected,&quot;
said AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney. </p>
<p>Thus far, the AFL-CIO campaign to highlight attacks on working
families and publicize those voting records has &quot;hit some
raw nerves,&quot; Sweeney said. &quot;The depths to which they
are going is just unbelievable.&quot; </p>
<p>Through threats of legal action and federal investigations,
Republican leaders have tried to strong-arm television and radio
stations into blocking the federation's issues advertisements,
which have focused on opposition to raising the minimum wage and
efforts to cut Medicare and give tax cuts to the rich. Only a
handful of stations have yielded to the pressure. </p>
<p>The attacks on unions have taken a shrill, almost hysterical
tone. In a scene reminiscent of the 1950s McCarthy-era communist
witch hunt, Republicans on July 24 staged a phony show hearing on
labor, leading in a hooded &quot;secret&quot; witness to testify
behind a screen. </p>
<p>Sweeney called it a &quot;naked political payback for labor's
success in telling it like it is.&quot; </p>
<p>The GOP and its allies in the business community, under the
guise of a Chamber of Commerce &quot;Coalition,&quot; have
launched their own ad campaign attacking the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>The GOP's massive disinformation campaign also includes an
eight-minute attack video distributed to media outlets;
orchestrated phone bank operations generating negative calls to
state and local AFL-CIOs and a constant barrage of overheated and
hysterical anti-union rhetoric from such party leaders as
Gingrich and House Majority Leader Richard Armey (R-Texas.) </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO has not backed down, turning many Republican
claims on their head while keeping up the drumbeat about how the
Gingrich-led Congress has put workers at risk while rewarding
rich benefactors. The new TV spots highlight votes last year to
allow corporations to spend pension funds, endangering many
workers' retirement security. </p>
<p>The Labor `96 push has had a strong economic focus, following
on the coast-to-coast &quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; town hall
meetings in May and June. That message was explored during July
in 22 &quot;kick- off&quot; events in congressional districts,
which drew as many as 130 rank-and-file workers in many areas.
Participants were asked to turn in pledge cards to volunteer to
join the growing legion of union election workers. </p>
<p>Some 200 district coordinators, union staff and state
federation officers will gather Aug. 9-11 at the Masters, Mates
and Pilots training center to develop state and district
coordinated campaign strategies. That session will effectively
launch the electoral phase of Labor '96, which is several months
and thousands of union volunteers ahead of what the labor
movement has accomplished in past elections. </p>
<p>&quot;We are determined that union members this election will
understand the important issues that affect their economic
security and living standards,&quot; said AFL-CIO Political
Director Steve Rosenthal. &quot;If we do our job, we can reverse
the anti-worker tide of the current Congress and make sure we
have a friend in the White House.&quot; </p>
<p>The federation also held its first-ever &quot;candidates
forum&quot; in Washington, introducing 75 congressional
candidates and campaign managers to AFL-CIO unions and their
fight for working families. They also heard reports from
pollsters on union members' views on crucial issues and from
Karen Nussbaum, director of the AFL-CIO Working Women's
Department, on the importance of women's vote in 1996. </p>
<p>Candidates are listening because the AFL-CIO's message for
working families is resonating across the country. The
federation's Medicare ads were greeted enthusiastically by
labor's allies in Congress, including Minority Whip David Bonior
(D-Mich.), who organized a series of floor speeches by Democrats
defending the ads and lambasting Gingrich. </p>
<p>Embarrassed by the ads, Republicans sought to backpedal,
claiming that Gingrich actually was talking about the obscure
Health Care Finance Administration. </p>
<p>But Gingrich's words are clear. &quot;But we believe it's
going to wither on the vine because we think people are
voluntarily going to leave it - voluntarily,&quot; he said. </p>
<p>&quot;People could not `leave' the financing administration as
they could `leave' the traditional Medicare program,&quot;
AFL-CIO General Counsel Jon Hiatt wrote TV stations, claiming
that the Republican objections were &quot;groundless and
deceptive.&quot; </p>
<p>He also noted that after the Oct. 24, 1995, speech, Gingrich
press aide Tony Blankley confirmed the speaker was talking about
fee-for-service Medicare. </p>
<p>Those ads aired on 176 stations in 33 districts. </p>
<p>The GOP's two-day House &quot;show&quot; trial in front of the
Judiciary's Crime Subcommittee, also left egg on the faces of
organizers. The hearings were designed to attack a 1995 agreement
between the Laborers and the Justice Department to institute
reforms as a &quot;sweetheart&quot; deal, while trying to tie the
union to organized crime. </p>
<p>But a former FBI agent and a Justice Department witness
described how LIUNA is working with the government to effectively
clean its house, and dismissed accusations of favoritism. </p>
<p>Sweeney called the hearings &quot;bogus (and) nothing more
than retaliation for the new voice America's unions are creating
for working families . . . their bully tactics will not fool the
public or deter us from exposing their attacks on working
families.&quot; </p>
<p>The credibility of the GOP's mystery guest witness was
completely destroyed. He testified behind a screen, even though
he previously testified publicly, and his identity is common
knowledge. He also was unmasked as a paid government informant
who had sold information to tabloids. </p>
<p>July 24 staged a phony show hearing on labor, leading in a
hooded &quot;secret&quot; witness to testify behind a screen. </p>
<p>The GOP and its allies in the business community, under the
guise of a Chamber of Commerce &quot;Coalition,&quot; also
launched their own ad campaign attacking the AFL-CIO - part of a
massive disinformation campaign that includes an eight-minute
attack video distributed to media outlets, orchestrated phone
bank operations generating negative calls to state and local
AFL-CIOs and a constant barrage of anti-union rhetoric from such
party leaders as Gingrich and House Majority Leader Richard Armey
(R-Texas.) </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO has not backed down, turning many Republican
claims on their head while keeping up the drumbeat about how the
Gingrich-led Congress has put workers at risk while rewarding
rich benefactors. The new TV spots highlight votes last year to
allow corporations to spend pension funds, endangering many
workers' retirement security. </p>
<p>The Labor '96 push has had a strong economic focus, following
on the coast-to-coast &quot;America Needs A Raise&quot; town hall
meetings in May and June. That message was explored during July
in 22 &quot;kick- off&quot; events in congressional districts,
which drew as many as 130 rank-and-file workers in many areas.
Participants were asked to join the growing legion of union
election workers. </p>
<p>Some 200 district coordinators, union staff and state
federation officers will gather Aug. 9-11 at the Masters, Mates
and Pilots training center to develop state and district
coordinated campaign strategies. That session will effectively
launch the electoral phase of Labor '96, which is several months
and thousands of union volunteers ahead of what the labor
movement has accomplished in past elections. </p>
<p>&quot;We are determined that union members this election will
understand the important issues that affect their economic
security and living standards,&quot; said AFL-CIO Political
Director Steve Rosenthal. &quot;If we do our job, we can reverse
the anti-worker tide of the current Congress and make sure
workers have a friend in the White House.&quot; </p>
<p>The federation also held its first-ever &quot;candidates
forum&quot; in Washington, introducing 75 congressional
candidates and campaign managers to AFL-CIO unions and their
fight for working families. Candidates also heard reports from
pollsters on union members' views on crucial issues, and from
Karen Nussbaum, director of the AFL-CIO Working Women's
Department, on the importance of the women's vote in 1996. </p>
<p>Candidates are listening because the AFL-CIO's message for
working families is resonating across the country. The
federation's Medicare ads were greeted enthusiastically by
labor's allies in Congress, including Minority Whip David E.
Bonior (D-Mich.), who organized a series of floor speeches by
Democrats defending the ads and lambasting Gingrich. </p>
<p>Embarrassed by the ads, Republicans sought to backpedal,
claiming that Gingrich actually was talking about the obscure
Health Care Finance Administration. </p>
<p>But Gingrich's words are clear. &quot;But we believe it's
going to wither on the vine because we think people are
voluntarily going to leave it - voluntarily,&quot; he said. </p>
<p>&quot;People could not `leave' the financing administration as
they could `leave' the traditional Medicare program,&quot;
AFL-CIO General Counsel Jon Hiatt wrote TV stations, claiming
that the Republican objections were &quot;groundless and
deceptive.&quot; </p>
<p>He also noted that after the Oct. 24, 1995, speech, Gingrich
press aide Tony Blankley confirmed the speaker was talking about
fee-for-service Medicare. </p>
<p>The two-day House show trial in front of the Judiciary's crime
subcommittee also left egg on the face of the GOP. The hearings
were designed to attack a 1995 agreement between the Laborers and
the Justice Department to institute reforms as a
&quot;sweetheart&quot; deal, while trying to tie the union to
organized crime. </p>
<p>But a former FBI agent and a Justice Department witness
described how LIUNA is working with the government to effectively
clean its house, and dismissed accusations of favoritism. </p>
<p>The GOP's mystery witness was unmasked as a paid government
informant who had sold information to tabloids. </p>
<p>Sweeney called it a &quot;naked political payback for labor's
success in telling it like it is.&quot; </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
