<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 2</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Rail workers get historic agreements <br>
<font size="3"><i>By David Kameras</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Conrail last week finally relented in its bilateral dispute
with the Maintenance of Way Employees, ending a two-year struggle
to achieve labor agreements between rail labor and the nation's
major freight carriers. </p>
<p>With tentative agreements with 13 unions now in place, the
national rail industry has survived a bargaining process without
strikes or imposed settlements for the first time in at least 30
years. </p>
<p>&quot;BMWE members asked for real wage increases, better
working conditions, increased away-from-home expenses and job
protection,&quot; union President Mac A. Fleming said. &quot;I am
pleased that we were able to deliver on all those goals through
negotiations and without any service disruption.&quot; </p>
<p>The prospect of a disruption was imminent. BMWE had reached
agreement with the 34 other railroads belonging to the National
Carriers Conference Committee, but Conrail stood alone and
intransigent, even after BMWE and the Transportation
Communications Union extended a no-strike pledge for seven days
beyond the July 23 expiration of a 30-day cooling-off period
imposed under the Railway Labor Act. </p>
<p>TCU later settled with all the carriers. The BMWE pact was
reached less than 24 hours before the end of the time extension. </p>
<p>The BMWE conflict stemmed from proposals by a presidential
emergency board regarding &quot;work force stabilization,&quot;
affecting workers who are furloughed or reassigned. Conrail
maintained that its interpretation of the proposals differed from
that of the union's, and it wanted an arbitrator to weigh in, a
move the union called delaying tactics. </p>
<p>Fleming said management's need to accept job security items
and a production-gang definition were in exchange for concessions
already made by labor in negotiations, and declared that his
union would not enter into a national agreement with one carrier
refusing to comply with key provisions. </p>
<p>Five days before the agreement was reached, AFL-CIO President
John J. Sweeney warned that with hundreds of millions of dollars
in profits and top executives getting more than $1 million in
salary, &quot;Conrail's insistence on keeping the cash in the
corporate suites (threatened) to unravel a national agreement for
145,000 rail workers and 34 other railroads.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;Nearly a decade ago, Conrail employees helped save the
company from bankruptcy by forgoing benefits that ease the pain
of a layoff - a benefit given to nearly all other rail
workers,&quot; Sweeney said. &quot;Now it's time for the workers
to reap a share of the profits they helped create.&quot; </p>
<p>Fleming thanked the AFL-CIO's leadership, noting that the
federation &quot;stood beside the BMWE in solidarity as we fought
for a strong contract, and made invaluable contributions to
keeping the negotiating process moving forward.&quot; </p>
<p>The ratification process is expected to take several weeks. </p>
<p>The history of contract talks in the rail industry has long
been marked by carrier inflexibility and stalling tactics, as
management has relied on a sympathetic Congress to achieve what
could not be secured at the negotiating table. </p>
<p>In 1991 and 1992, Congress intervened to impose settlements,
stemming from a round of bargaining started in 1988. The AFL-CIO
denounced that government interference in the collective
bargaining process. </p>
<p>Three presidential emergency boards were appointed by
President Clinton in the current round. Sweeney testified before
two of the boards on behalf of rail workers. The tentative
agreements followed recommendations from those boards. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
