<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Southern bus tour links civil rights, economic
justice <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Muriel H. Cooper</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Mobile, Ala. </p>
<p>The link between the civil rights movement and the struggle
for economic justice took on a human face for 30 Union Summer
activists who traveled throughout the South helping to organize
nursing home workers, one of the nation's most dangerous and
poorly paid professions. </p>
<p>The three-week Southern bus tour is a part of the AFL-CIO's
Union Summer campaign deploying 1,500 students and young
activists across the country to work in union organizing drives. </p>
<p>Unlike the rest of Union Summer, where activists were assigned
to work in one city, the bus tour is traveling more than 850
miles from July 24 to Aug. 11, beginning in Memphis, Tenn. It was
stopping in Jackson, Miss., and Mobile, Selma, Montgomery and
Birmingham, Ala., before ending up back in Memphis. </p>
<p>The tour is retracing some of the paths taken 30 years ago by
an earlier generation of young activists during Freedom Summer,
which served as the model for Union Summer. </p>
<p>&quot;You are launching a new movement . . . a movement that
connects the struggles of the past for civil rights with the
hopes for a future with economic justice,&quot; Food and
Commercial Workers President Douglas H. Dority told the activists
as they gathered in Memphis at the site of Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr.'s assassination. </p>
<p>Dubbed the &quot;care-a-van,&quot; connecting to the
&quot;Care For The Caregivers&quot; nursing home organizing
campaign by the UFCW, the Union Summer activists got an up-close
and personal view of the realities of organizing nursing home
workers. </p>
<p>Southern nursing home operations are among the lowest-paying
in a low-wage industry. Workers have one of the highest injury
rates, with no health care or pension benefits, giving the
industry the infamous reputation of being the most dangerous in
which to work. </p>
<p>&quot;The workers need justice and fairness. They need a
union,&quot; Linda Chavez-Thompson, executive vice president of
the AFL-CIO, told the students during an intensive training
workshop held in Memphis July 21-23. </p>
<p>&quot;I learned that the conditions are just horrible,&quot;
said Gussie Bowen, an activist from Florida. &quot;You have to be
certified to do the job, but they don't pay you enough money to
feed your family.&quot; </p>
<p>The mission was not one for the weary. By 6 a.m., most of the
activists were up and out of the motel to handbill at nursing
homes, only to return at midday in muggy, 90-degree heat to greet
the second shift. </p>
<p>&quot;You have to let the workers know that they have nothing
to fear,&quot; said Vanessa Scott, one of seven nursing home
workers traveling with the activists. &quot;You have to let them
know that no one will see the authorization card. The card just
says that they are interested in having a union come in. It
doesn't mean you're in the union.&quot; </p>
<p>Deep into the night, the activists - fueled with the emotions
of the day - plotted strategy on how to get around the workers'
all-too-real fear of being identified with a union, tossing out
ideas like so many balls bouncing off a wall: trace workers'
license plates to get addresses and set up home calls; convince
other local unions to help in the organizing; reach out to the
local media; pass out brochures asking the workers questions that
end with the tag line, &quot;if you answered yes, you need a
union.&quot; </p>
<p>They talked with four nursing home workers from Cogburn
nursing home in Mobile, who were fired when they expressed an
interest in organizing. The union lost the election. </p>
<p>&quot;I was mad,&quot; dietary aide Alma Hayward said of the
election. &quot;When we tried to talk about the union, we were
disciplined or fired. But the administrator could talk against
the union as much as he pleased. But we are taking them to court
(on federal labor law violations), and what is done in the dark
will come to light. So, we really didn't lose,&quot; she said. </p>
<p>&quot;Just listening to the workers talk about being fired
from their jobs helped to motivate me to help them get
justice,&quot; said Diallo Brooks from Washington. &quot;My
energy level is high and I get excited about making a difference
in peoples' lives.&quot; </p>
<p>For many of the activists, the trip marked their first time in
the South, a battleground for social change - and the beginning
of a living lesson in the connection between civil rights and
economic justice. </p>
<p>Under the hotel balcony where Martin Luther King died, they
heard the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson explain how King saw the fight by
Memphis garbagemen to gain respect by joining AFSCME as the next
logical step in the civil rights movement. </p>
<p>They heard mostly female African-American workers from the
Delta Pride catfish processing plant in Indianola, Miss., explain
the hardships and triumphs of the successful union organizing
drives at three of the company's plants. </p>
<p>They walked in front of the Greenwood, Miss., grocery store
where black teen-ager Emmett Till stood and was later killed for
allegedly whistling at a white woman in 1955. </p>
<p>They listened as Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) described how he
survived a 1965 police riot at Selma's Edmund Pettus Bridge,
where marchers were beaten and firehosed for seeking the right to
vote. And they reflected on King's poignant message of commitment
to justice in his letters from the Birmingham jail. </p>
<p>&quot;We are showing that my generation cares,&quot; said
Allen Bozeman from Prattville, Ala. &quot;We are doing something
good. We want to contribute to our communities. We may not
accomplish everything, but we did stand up for caregivers,&quot;
he said. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
