<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Unions reach out to women <br>
Organizing, leadershiptop department goals <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Sharolyn A. Rosier</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The AFL-CIO's fledgling Working Women's Department is up and
running full throttle in its mission to represent women and make
their concerns a part of labor's agenda. </p>
<p>&quot;The department will be injecting concerns of working
women into every nook and cranny of the labor movement,&quot;
said Karen Nussbaum, the department's director. &quot;It's a very
big mandate, but it's what we need to do. We will make sure that
every major program and all departments do their work keeping
working women in mind.&quot; </p>
<p>Organizing is a key priority of the department, said AFL-CIO
Vice President Gloria Johnson, who was named by President John J.
Sweeney to chair the Executive Council's Working Women's
Committee. </p>
<p>Women currently comprise almost 40 percent of total union
membership and are more than 60 percent of all service workers,
the fastest-growing segment of new members. Studies show they
also are more likely to join a union than men. </p>
<p>&quot;We have made strides, but the majority of working women
still don't belong to unions. Only about 16 percent of all
working women belong to unions,&quot; said Johnson, who is
president of the Coalition of Labor Union Women and vice
president of the Electronic Workers. </p>
<p>&quot;Unions have a moral responsibility to working
women,&quot; Sweeney told the Institute for Women's Policy
Research. &quot;Because working women are desperately squeezed
for time and money, they are urgently in need of union
representation.&quot; </p>
<p>Representation of working women is very important for unions
when one considers the numbers. The U.S. Census Bureau projects
the number of male workers will increase by only 8 percent by
2005, while the number of female workers will increase 17
percent. These numbers are strikingly important to every aspect
of unions' existence - organizing, political action and
legislation, Nussbaum said. </p>
<h4>The union advantage</h4>
<p>No matter what color collar they wore, women who testified at
the federation's &quot;America Needs A Raise&quot; town hall
meetings said they experienced similar hardships in the workplace
- sexism, low wages, temporary employment, sexual harassment and
unequal pay. </p>
<p>But union women often stated in the meetings that they
benefited from having a union contract and the support of their
union when they faced these problems. </p>
<p>The union advantage extends also to pay. Female union members
earn 38 percent more than their nonunion counterparts - and the
advantage is even greater for women of color. In 1995, union
African-American women earned an average of $473 weekly, compared
with $325 for nonunion African-American women. Latino women
represented by unions had median weekly earnings of $423,
compared with $291 for nonunion Hispanic women. </p>
<p>Unions also narrow the wage gap between women and men from 32
percent for nonunion women to 25 percent for union women,
according to the Institute for Women's Policy Research. </p>
<p>&quot;We've worked hard to reduce it and we're proud of the
progress we've made so far, but we're not going to rest until the
gap disappears,&quot; said AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda
Chavez-Thompson. </p>
<h4>Female leaders needed</h4>
<p>Another sign of progress is a growing representation of women
in top union leadership positions. In 1979, when women made up 30
percent of the labor movement, there were no women on the AFL-CIO
Executive Council and no female department directors or executive
staff members. The next year, Joyce Miller of the Clothing and
Textile Workers, now UNITE, became a member of the Executive
Council and Dorothy Shields was named Education Director. </p>
<p>It took 40 years before the federation had its first female
executive officer, Barbara Easterling of the Communications
Workers, who served as secretary-treasurer for two months in
1995. </p>
<p>The 1995 AFL-CIO convention brought significant progress for
women, including additional seats on the Executive Council.
Today, in addition to Chavez-Thompson, there are six women on the
council and nine female directors of AFL-CIO departments. </p>
<p>But the hard fact is that the movement is not nearly where it
should be, Chavez-Thompson declared. &quot;The challenge to
unions is three-fold - transform the culture of unions, recruit
more women leaders and establish more networks and relationships
of union women helping union women.&quot; </p>
<p>Changing the culture in unions to provide more of those role
models will be difficult, Chavez-Thompson said. &quot;For
example, many of my union brothers in the San Antonio Public
Employees Council assumed I was the boss's secretary, even after
I was business manager and ultimately executive director of the
local unions.&quot; </p>
<p>More attention also has to be paid to developing and training
new and young female workers, Johnson said. &quot;We must help
them understand it's more than paying dues, negotiating a
contract and job security. It's an opportunity to stand with
people in a common cause . . . and an opportunity to get
involved. The local is only as strong as their involvement.&quot; </p>
<p>The department's other priorities include politics and
outreach to all women, union and nonunion. &quot;We are the
biggest organization for women, and we intend to act like we
are,&quot; Nussbaum said. That is particularly important this
year, when &quot;it will be working women's votes that determine
the next election,&quot; she said. </p>
<p>The department also is putting together a network for women,
which all union members are welcome to join, and will be issuing
a quarterly newsletter and establishing a resource clearinghouse. </p>
<p>CLUW and the women's departments of affiliated unions also
will work closely with the department. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
