<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Workers stop Oregon `right to work' <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Sharolyn A. Rosier</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Workers in Oregon thwarted a petition drive to place a public
employee right-to-work measure on the November ballot. </p>
<p>Oregon Taxpayers United, headed by the anti-union lobbyist
Bill Sizemore, filed more than 108,000 signatures, but only
86,000 were validated July 18 by the state's secretary of state -
not enough to qualify for the ballot. The announcement &quot;was
a great moment for our campaign to block that,&quot; said David
Gregory, the AFL-CIO regional director. </p>
<p>The ballot initiative would have prohibited the mandatory
payment of union dues by public employees and banned the
government from deducting union dues from employees' pay checks. </p>
<p>&quot;Even with their purported budget of $672,000, Sizemore
and his millionaire backers were unable to buy their way onto the
ballot,&quot; Oregon AFL-CIO President Irv Fletcher said in a
statement. &quot;The Oregon public was able to see past the empty
rhetoric and reject this attempt to tinker with the state
constitution.&quot; </p>
<p>Sizemore's group also led the 1994 ballot initiative that
required public employees to pay part of their pension. An
appellate court overturned that measure last month. Sizemore said
he would try again in 1998 to get the &quot;right-to-work&quot;
measure on the ballot. </p>
<p>Gregory credited union solidarity with defeating the
initiative, including early planning and funding by the state
AFL- CIO, which raised per capita at its convention, as well as
assistance from the national AFL-CIO beginning early this year. </p>
<p>Over the past few months, the AFL-CIO dispatched five
additional staff members to assist in the campaign. </p>
<p>During one campaign activity - a July 2 rally at the state
Capitol - more than 100 public employee union members brought the
message home to legislators that Sizemore did not speak for them. </p>
<p>Oregon is among 29 &quot;fair share&quot; states that require
dues payments by employees who work in a union shop - whether
they join the union or not. The law is designed to prevent
&quot;free-riders,&quot; workers who benefit from union
bargaining but do not pay dues. </p>
<p>&quot;The message is clear,&quot; said Oregon Public Employees
Union/SEIU Local 503 President Karla Spence. &quot;Voters are fed
up with Bill Sizemore's attacks on working Oregonians. The
right-to- work initiative he circulated would have hurt more than
public workers - it would have hurt families and communities
throughout the state.&quot; </p>
<p>OPEU represents more than 22,000 public employees, and AFSCME
represents 17,500 public employees in the state. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
