<html>
<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 6</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Lights on at Sylvania <br>
</h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The Electronic Workers were able to break a 40-year union
drought when workers at the Osram Sylvania facility in St. Marys,
Pa., voted 251-227 for IUE representation. </p>
<p>The workers decided they'd had enough of the company's
shenanigans after Sylvania tried to implement continuous shifts
and permanently laid off 100 workers, sending their jobs to
Mexico. </p>
<p>The union effort was pushed by defunct Local 291 workers who
worked in Sylvania's Salem, Mass., plant until about four years
ago, when the company closed the plant to consolidate with the
St. Marys facility. </p>
<p>IUE used more than 50 radio commercials and a full-page
newspaper ad explaining what was at stake for the workers and the
community. The victory is being pegged as one of the biggest for
the union in recent years. </p>
<h4>IUE rolls the bumpers on</h4>
<p>American Roll Form and Manufacturing Co. in Angola, Ind.,
granted IUE recognition for 206 workers after 124 signed
authorization cards. </p>
<p>Another 77 probationary workers will be part of the unit when
they become permanently employed. The workers make auto bumpers. </p>
<h4>SEIU scores seven times</h4>
<p>The Service Employees scored seven organizing wins in the past
few weeks, gaining about 575 new members. </p>
<p>Three of the wins came in health care facilities. SEIU Local 4
won an election July 11 to represent 85 workers at the St. Paul
nursing home in Chicago. Local 79 won a July 12 election for a
unit of 80 nursing home workers at Friendship Manor in Detroit. </p>
<p>Local 250 survived a vicious anti-union campaign to win a unit
of non-professionals at Catholic Healthcare West's St. Joseph's
Behavioral Health Center in Stockton, Calif., by a 39-20 margin. </p>
<p>In Chicago, Local 236 signed a contract with a new employer,
Argenbright International Services, covering 250 workers at
O'Hare International Airport. Two Chicago janitorial units at CHA
properties also voted for SEIU by 26-0 and 18-2 votes. </p>
<p>And in Orlando, Fla., SEIU Local 750 won the right to
represent workers at National Car Rental on a 38-18 vote. </p>
<h4>Union wins at Red Cross</h4>
<p>Red Cross nurses, professionals and technicians at the South
Jersey-Penn Region of American Red Cross Blood Services will be
represented by AFT's Hospital Professionals and Allied Employees
(HPAE). </p>
<p>The unit will include two bargaining units of 300 employees,
who voted by a 4-1 margin for the union. </p>
<p>&quot;We fought for our right to be union because we wanted
fairness and consistent standards,&quot; said Laura Power, a
donor collector with the Red Cross. &quot;We intend to use our
voice on behalf of employees and the blood donors and patients we
serve.&quot; </p>
<p>The victory represents a growing trend at Red Cross Blood
Services around the country, where 2,000 of the 14,000 workers
are now unionized. </p>
<h4>UMWA is workers' answer</h4>
<p>Workers at the Long Airdox mining equipment plant in
Saltville, Va., wanted security and respect - so they voted 49-20
for Mine Workers representation. </p>
<p>&quot;They refused to be intimidated by management's threats
and illegal discharge of a union supporter,&quot; said UMWA
President Cecil E. Roberts. &quot;And they saw through the
company's false promises and its illegal 11th-hour pay
increases.&quot; </p>
<p>The Saltville plant is the third plant to vote for the union
among the six plants owned by Long Airdox. More than 200 workers
are represented by the UMWA at the company's Cedar Bluff, Va.,
facility, and workers at the Pulaski, Va., facility long have
been represented by the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers. </p>
<h4>UFCW has the beef</h4>
<p>After a long struggle, Food and Commercial Workers Local 22
was recognized at Monfort Inc.'s Grand Island, Neb., beef plant.
The agreement, announced July 22, was worked out by the NLRB and
resolves all outstanding unfair labor practices complaints
involving the plant. </p>
<p>&quot;This is a tremendous first step for the workers,&quot;
said Local 22 President Rick Sallfeld. &quot;We look forward to
negotiations with the company and building a positive working
relationship.&quot; Contract negotiations are set to begin August
5. </p>
<p>Monfort, based in Greeley, Colo., employs more than 10,000
people at four major beef processing plants. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
