<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Strawberry fields forever tough <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Sharolyn A. Rosier</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Life is hard for strawberry pickers, who labor 10- to 12-hour
work days in California's million-dollar strawberry industry,
with exposure to pesticides the order every day. </p>
<p>But there is hope in a union. The Farm Workers have taken on
the entire industry to bring the social and economic justice of a
union contract to every worker in the fields. The campaign that
began last April intensified with pledges from almost 200 AFL-CIO
central labor councils during last month's national CLC
conference to give their time and resources. (See story, Page 5). </p>
<p>Union Summer activists also are assisting the UFW. </p>
<p>&quot;Until the organizing began this year, there had not been
a wage increase in 10 years,&quot; said UFW President Arturo
Rodriguez at the CLC conference. &quot;Pay is among the lowest in
agriculture - often below the minimum wage - and most workers
have no benefits.&quot; </p>
<p>Fighting back tears, 18-year-old Griselda Ruiz held her
daughter as she explained how she was forced to work in the rain,
and many times through lunch. &quot;With the campaign, we've seen
some changes, because they are trying to look good,&quot; she
added, &quot;but I was fired for wearing a union button.&quot; </p>
<p>Some 20,000 men, women and children work in California's
strawberry fields for an average wage of $8,000 per year. </p>
<p>On such paltry salaries, the workers are forced to share small
apartments with three or four families, according to the union.
Other workers live in caves, shacks and old cars. </p>
<p>Eighty percent of the strawberries consumed in the United
States and Canada are grown in California, where the state's
Central Coast boasts 65 percent of the total strawberry crop
value. The season lasts from March to October. </p>
<p>Some growers already are retaliating against the union. Last
June, anti-union workers assaulted two union organizers after
they visited workers at Gargiulo Farms in Watsonville. Within
hours of the incident, more than 100 farm workers and supporters
gathered outside the grower's office to protest the company's
anti-union violence and intimidation. </p>
<p>But the power rests with the &quot;coolers,&quot; who exert
great control over the more than 270 growers. </p>
<p>Coolers provide growers with loans and plants from their
nurseries, set the price and package and market growers' crops,
according to the UFW. </p>
<p>&quot;Our strategy is to organize the entire strawberry
industry t instead of one grower at a time,&quot; Rodriguez
explained. &quot;That means getting the coolers to cooperate by
pressuring growers to do the right thing.&quot; </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
