<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 8</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Veto kills company union bill <br>
Minimum wage, health bills to be signed into law <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Mike Hall</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Delivering on his promised veto, President Clinton sent the
misnamed TEAM Act to the sidelines July 30. The company union
bill had been high on the Republican leadership's business
agenda. </p>
<p>Two other major victories for labor were assured when Congress
settled differences between House and Senate versions of a long-
overdue minimum wage increase and a health insurance portability
bill. Clinton will sign both measures. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO-led drive to give America's lowest-paid workers
their first raise in seven years will boost the minimum wage from
$4.25 per hour to $5.15 in two 45-cent steps, Oct. 1, 1996, and
Oct. 1, 1997. </p>
<p>The House and Senate also put finishing touches on welfare
reform legislation opposed by the AFL-CIO. Clinton said he would
sign the bill. </p>
<p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney commended Clinton for his
veto of the TEAM Act, a &quot;damaging and unnecessary piece of
legislation (that) would have given management the say-so over
who speaks for workers on issues such as wages, hours and other
terms and conditions of employment.&quot; </p>
<p>In his veto message, Clinton noted the bill would have allowed
&quot;employers to establish company unions where no union
currently exists and permitted company-dominated unions where
employees are in the process of determining whether to be
represented by a union.&quot; </p>
<p>Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.) said the measure was unneeded
because 30,000 employers already have established worker teams,
and the National Labor Relations Board rarely objects to these
arrangements. </p>
<p>The bill passed the Senate July 10 by a margin of 53-46. The
House passed it 221-202 last September. Neither margin approaches
the two-thirds needed in each house to override a presidential
veto. </p>
<p>Labor's fight against the TEAM Act in the Senate was two-
pronged, with rank-and-file members rallying back home and
calling their representatives on the AFL-CIO's toll-free
congressional hotline, and with the federation's top officers and
affiliated union presidents scouring the Senate hallways to lobby
against the bill. </p>
<p>At the same time, several large business groups staked their
legislative success or failure on the TEAM Act, but never were
able to gather enough support to come close to veto-proofing the
company union bill. </p>
<p>Earlier this session, political observers gave the minimum
wage increase almost no chance of passage in a Republican-
controlled Congress where some party leaders not only vowed to
halt an increase but even said the minimum wage should be
abolished altogether. </p>
<p>But the AFL-CIO, along with a coalition of progressive
organizations, began to drum up massive public support through
media campaigns and public events. A series of 29 America Needs A
Raise town hall meetings nationwide dramatized the growing wage
gap between the rich and the rest of us, as well as obscene
executive salaries and soaring corporate profits in a time of
layoffs, downsizing and plant shifting. </p>
<p>The health insurance reform bill makes it easier for workers
to carry their insurance from job to job and harder for insurance
companies to deny coverage for pre-existing conditions, among
other reforms. While a good first step, labor will continue to
fight for major health care reform. </p>
<p>In the welfare battle, despite some improvements in the bill
made in conference, the AFL-CIO urged Clinton to veto the
measure. The legislation would end a 61-year-old federal
guarantee of cash assistance for families and children by giving
annual block grants to states that will set their own rules and
regulations for welfare. </p>
<p>The conference did strengthen provisions protecting current
and laid-off workers from replacement by welfare recipients, who
now will be required to work under the bill's workfare provision.
But it does not require a minimum wage or benefit floor, and that
greatly intensifies competition in the low-wage labor market. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
