<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 9</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Capitol Digest <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Mike Hall</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The House continued the attack on the 40-hour work week July
30 when it passed a bill allowing employers to replace overtime
pay with compensatory time. </p>
<p>But the measure (H.R. 2391) faces a Senate fight, and the
Department of Labor has recommended that President Clinton veto
it. </p>
<p>Like many Republican initiatives, the bill carries a
deceptive, worker-friendly title, &quot;The Working Families
Flexibility Act.&quot; </p>
<p>The bill &quot;will not give workers increased control over
their lives. It will give them a reduced paycheck and standard of
living for their families,&quot; AFL-CIO Legislative Director
Peggy Taylor said. </p>
<p>A recent Peter Hart poll showed that workers, by a 64-22
percent margin, prefer overtime pay to comp time. Backers of the
bill tried to paint it as a voluntary arrangement between the
boss and workers, but most of the control is in the hands of the
employers. </p>
<p>The so-called worker protections in the bill are &quot;weak
and virtually meaningless,&quot; Taylor said. &quot;The concept
of a `voluntary arrangement' in most workplaces is a cruel hoax.
If the employer wants to `pay' for overtime work in compensatory
time, not cash, the employer will find a way to exert his
considerable influence over the workers to accept that
arrangement.&quot; </p>
<p>Proponents of the legislation claim it would give workers a
chance to use their comp time for various family functions and
other needs at the workers' discretion. But the bill essentially
gives the boss veto power over the workers' use of earned comp
time. </p>
<p>The bill now goes to the Senate. </p>
<h4>Elsewhere in Congress:</h4>
<p>CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM - What do you call a bill that lets
rich fat cats give even more big political donations, halves what
worker-financed political action committees can give and attacks
unions, too? If you're Newt Gingrich, you call it &quot;campaign
finance reform.&quot; But this bill was so out-rageously weighted
to the wealthy it fell 259-162. It also would have imposed a
bureaucratic nightmare of regulations on unions' political
activity. </p>
<p>DAVIS-BACON - The Senate was expected to turn back what one
labor lobbyist called one of the &quot;most venal and
mean-spirited&quot; amendments he had seen - a move to suspend
the Davis-Bacon Act for reconstruction of the Oklahoma City
federal building. On April 19, 1995, an explosion there killed
168 workers, and in the hours, days and weeks following, building
and construction trade workers toiled tirelessly and sometimes
voluntarily to save survivors, remove victims and stabilize the
destroyed building. Oklahoma BCTD Secretary Jimmy Fish called the
move &quot;a slap in the face to the hundreds of skilled
construction men and women who worked so admirably in the
aftermath of the blast.&quot; </p>
<p>MANDATES - A move that could have undermined such basic labor
laws as the Fair Labor Standards Act, the Occupational Safety and
Health Act, the Davis-Bacon Act and the Family and Medical Leave
Act, along with core environmental laws, was defeated July 23.
The federal Advisory Commission on Intergovernmental Relations
voted down its own final report on so-called unfunded mandates,
thanks to pressure from organized labor, the environmental
community and the Clinton administration. The ACIR had been
charged with reporting recommendations under unfunded mandate
legislation passed in 1995. A White House letter outlining
objections to the report said it ignored &quot;the views of
working men and women who benefit from these laws.&quot; </p>
<p>PESTICIDES - A fight started with a 1989 AFL-CIO lawsuit to
ban the use on fresh foods of pesticides suspected of causing
cancer is coming to a successful end. Already, such agents are
banned from processed foods, but a House-passed bill would apply
uniform standards to fresh and processed foods. It also creates
higher standards for certain foods and chemicals that affect
children and calls for screening for chemicals that raise the
risk of breast cancer. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
