<html>
<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 10</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Teens limited on machines <br>
<font size="3"><i>Compiled by Colleen M. O'Neill</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The Senate has approved a narrowly worded measure to allow
teen-agers to load cardboard paper balers in retail
establishments meeting certain industry standards. </p>
<p>The House passed a similar measure last October. While 16- and
17-year-old workers will be allowed to load the machines, they
may not operate or unload them. In addition, the Senate measure
calls for stepped-up reporting of accidents involving teens and
the machines, with Congress retaining the ability to modify the
law if injuries increase. </p>
<h4>Lockout/tagout challenge</h4>
<p>A federal appeals court has ruled that a warning of machine
start-up invalidates OSHA's lockout/tagout rule regarding
&quot;unexpected&quot; activation. </p>
<p>The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed a decision by
the Occupational Safety and Health Review Commission vacating
citations against General Motors Corp., rejecting the Department
of Labor's interpretation that &quot;unexpected&quot; meant
&quot;unanticipated&quot; or &quot;unplanned for.&quot; The court
said &quot;unexpected&quot; contained an element of surprise that
would be lacking if a worker had advance notice of start-up. </p>
<p>OSHA may appeal the ruling or might have to reissue the rule
to change its wording to conform with the court's language. </p>
<p>Michael Wright, director of health and safety for the
Steelworkers, said of the ruling that reliance on warning signals
eliminates the necessary margin of safety for workers, citing as
an example the possibility of alarm failure or a worker's
inability to hear an alarm because of a noisy workplace. </p>
<h4>Silica dangers targeted</h4>
<p>OSHA announced plans for a nationwide effort to begin this
month to protect workers from exposure to crystalline silica dust
through stepped-up training, education and outreach programs. </p>
<p>The special emphasis program - a collaboration of labor,
government and business - seeks to aid workers in maritime,
agriculture, construction and general industry. Workers
performing sandblasting, drilling or tunneling are especially at
risk. </p>
<p>Nearly 14,000 deaths were attributed to exposure to the dust
from 1958 to 1990, while 300 more people die each year from
silicosis. Inhaling silica dust also has been associated with
other diseases, such as tuberculosis and lung cancer. The
National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health estimates
some 2 million workers are exposed annually. </p>
<h4>Lead violator fined</h4>
<p>A Michigan demolition contractor faces a $742,000 fine for
numerous alleged willful and serious violations of OSHA
regulations protecting construction workers against overexposure
to lead. </p>
<p>The exposures occurred during demolition at a Trinidad, Texas,
power plant last fall, when 25 of 30 workers were found to have
blood lead levels above the OSHA threshold for medical attention.
Eight of those 30 had levels requiring removal from the work
site; one required extensive treatment. </p>
<h4>Crackdown on egg farm</h4>
<p>DeCoster Egg Farms faces $3.6 million in proposed penalties
levied by the U.S. Department of Labor for safety and health
violations - and criminal charges are being considered. </p>
<p>DeCoster employs 800 workers in three states. </p>
<p>Secretary of Labor Robert B. Reich said the company operates
an &quot;unsanitary and dangerous workplace,&quot; provides
&quot;inhumane living quarters&quot; of cramped trailers and
treats workers deplorably - as in the case of a worker who
severed several fingers and was forced to wait hours for medical
aid. </p>
<p>OSHA cited unguarded machinery, violations of housing
requirements for temporary labor camps, exposed electrical parts
and ungrounded equipment, overexposure to air contaminants,
failure to provide protective equipment, noise overexposure, lack
of medical care and lack of hazard communication training. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
