<html>
<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 11</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Ergonomic work is spared cuts <br>
Ban lifted on protectionsagainst workplace crippler <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Colleen M. O'Neill</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Working families scored another big safety and health victory
when the House voted to repeal a ban on the development of a
standard addressing repetitive stress injuries. </p>
<p>By a 216-205 vote, the House July 11 deleted language that
denied the Occupational Safety and Health Administration the
ability to develop an ergonomics standard - or, indeed to even
gather information on ergonomic-related hazards. </p>
<p>Workers and their allies pushed hard on Capitol Hill to get
the language removed from the Labor/Education/Health and Human
Services appropriations measure, and were rewarded for their
efforts when 35 Republicans joined 180 Democrats and one
independent in voting against the provision. </p>
<p>&quot;We were surprised at the vote, given the history on this
issue,&quot; said Peg Seminario, the federation's job safety and
health director, &quot;but there's been a swing of opinion away
from the extreme Republican proposals they've been putting
forward in the past.&quot; </p>
<p>Simply put, ergonomics considers the fit of the job to the
anatomy of the worker. Hazards include repetitive motion, awkward
positions and heavy and awkward lifting. With poor job design or
poorly designed equipment, the increased stress on workers'
bodies often leads to injury. </p>
<p>Workers know too well the toll of jobsite ergonomic hazards.
Over the past decade, the numbers and rates of disorders
associated with repeated trauma have increased by epidemic
proportions - more than 800 percent. In fact, in 1994, more than
705,000 workers suffered serious injuries related to ergonomic
hazards. </p>
<p>Workers at highest risk for injury and illness labor in meat
processing plants, nursing homes and hospitals, at keyboards, on
assembly lines and in grocery stores. </p>
<p>The economic costs of these disorders are huge, with workers'
compensation and other related costs associated with the
crippling injuries estimated at more than $20 billion a year. </p>
<p>For example, workers with carpal tunnel syndrome lose a median
of 30 days of work annually, compared with a median of five days
lost for all injuries. By comparison, amputations - well
recognized as serious injuries - result in an average of 24 days
away from work. </p>
<p>GOP Rep. Henry Bonilla of Texas championed the restrictive
language, employing an ostrich-like approach to the sprains,
strains and crippling effects of RSI suffered by thousands of
workers. His measure took the approach that if an injury is not
reported, it didn't happen - so if you ban the reporting of
injuries, they don't exist, and therefore no standard is required
to deal with them. </p>
<p>Bonilla blamed &quot;the strong arm of labor&quot; for his
provision's defeat, and Republicans vowed to bring the measure up
again. </p>
<p>Rep. Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.) led the effort against Bonilla's
amendment. </p>
<p>&quot;I want to thank the 216 members of Congress who put the
health and safety of American workers ahead of partisan
politics,&quot; said Secretary of Labor Robert B. Reich. &quot;If
injuries are occurring in the workplace, it's up to the Labor
Department to find a way to prevent them. That's our job.&quot; </p>
<p>Even while workers rejoiced at turning back the ergonomic
language, there was a downside to the appropriations measure. </p>
<p>Funding was cut for OSHA and Mine Safety and Health
Administration programs, specifically in enforcement. The House
bill also failed to provide funds for important mine safety and
health research activities signed over to the National Institute
for Occupational Safety and Health with the demise last year of
the Bureau of Mines. </p>
<p>In addition, the House approved an amendment banning the use
of any Social Security or Medicare Trust Fund money to pay Social
Security Administration workers who perform legitimate union
activities during work hours. These workers, somewhat like shop
stewards, comprise less than 0.3 percent of the SSA's work force,
and have been performing these &quot;official time&quot; duties
for decades. </p>
<p>When the bill goes to the Senate in September, activists
should contact their senators (1/800-LABOR21) to urge them to
oppose restrictive ergonomic language, restore funding to federal
job safety agencies and programs and remove the SSA provision. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
