<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">IBEW: Utility deregulation would shock <br>
<font size="3"><i>By David Kameras</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Federal legislation introduced by a Colorado congressman to
impose restructuring and deregulation on electric utilities would
threaten American jobs and communities, the Electrical Workers
say. </p>
<p>&quot;Proponents of this bill are using words like `choice,'
`cost savings' or `elimination of restrictions' in describing its
provisions,&quot; said IBEW President John J. Barry. &quot;We
believe that, despite the good intentions of some of its backers,
the bill as it stands would cause chaos and disruption in an
industry already undergoing massive changes. </p>
<p>&quot;The hard fact of the matter is that every American has a
stake in the outcome of this issue,&quot; he said.
&quot;Electricity is vital to the security and the very
functioning of our country. We believe that all members of
Congress and indeed every concerned citizen must engage in a full
and vigorous debate before anything affecting such a vital
service is adopted.&quot; </p>
<p>The measure was put forth by Rep. Dan Schaefer (R-Colo.). </p>
<p>Barry charged that House members, led by Speaker Newt Gingrich
(R-Ga.), are claiming benefits based on &quot;the rosy but
erroneous findings&quot; of a report issued by Citizens for a
Sound Economy. </p>
<p>Although the 1992 Energy Policy Act already has opened up the
industry to deregulation, new measures like Schaefer's seek to
usurp the right of the states to set the pace in introducing
competition through their own regulatory authorities. </p>
<p>&quot;Should Washington solve a problem that doesn't
exist?&quot; asked an IBEW position paper that notes: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Threatened retail competition or direct access has caused
        utility companies to bolster stock prices by slashing
        their work forces, negatively affecting the lives of
        thousands of workers and their communities. </li>
    <li>Job loss places a great strain on the reliability of the
        electric utility system and threatens yet another source
        of decent, fairly compensated jobs in the United States. </li>
    <li>A scaled-back work force negatively affects the safety
        and reliability of an electric system that has been the
        world's best and most affordable to all consumers. </li>
    <li>Small businesses and individual consumers will be in a
        much weaker position to obtain lower rates if
        mega-companies dominate a region's power supply, provide
        deep discount rates to energy- intensive industrial
        customers and shift costs to remaining consumers. </li>
    <li>Most legislative proposals seek a direct connection
        between power production and delivery costs and consumer
        rates, which is largely irrelevant to real costs and
        benefits and would shift costs to small businesses and
        individual consumers. </li>
</ul>
<p>&quot;The need for further radical federal restructuring of
the electric utility industry is simply not there,&quot; said
Barry. &quot;We will do all in our power to convince Congress
that oversight of the nation's power supply rightly belongs
intrastate, a system that has worked well for everyone in our
society for decades.&quot; </p>
<p>Barry told his union's utility conference in January of
efforts in various states to roll back regulation, much of it
prompted by the momentum gathering steam at the federal level,
and the struggle of locals to hold the line. </p>
<p>&quot;The trend in utilities towards mergers, job cutting and
hard- line bargaining is worldwide,&quot; he said. &quot;The
proponents of the free market, whose consciences are untroubled
by such `annoyances' as job security, community well-being or
social concerns, have turned their attention to utilities. </p>
<p>&quot;We must face up to the forces on the right wing that
want to promote rapid and irresponsible change in the utility
industry,&quot; Barry declared. &quot;They are attempting nothing
less than to destabilize the industry for their own gain.&quot; </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
