<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 13</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Energized central labor councils explore new
roles <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Sharolyn A. Rosier</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Denver </p>
<p>Walking the walk and talking the talk, 175 central labor
council officers attending the first national CLC conference took
to the streets to rally for justice in the community. </p>
<p>An impromptu group began singing the song of labor as well,
giving voice to &quot;Rise Again,&quot; &quot;Solidarity
Forever&quot; and other worker standards as the officers took
Denver by storm. They shared ideas and recommendations on how
they could take that creative energy and become the bedrock of
labor's efforts to rise again. </p>
<p>The CLC officers took immediate action on strategic campaigns
by participating in a July 12 rally in support of striking
Detroit News and Free Press newspaper workers. More than 300
people t including CLC officers, union members and federation
staff t rallied in front of Gannett-owned KUSA Channel 9 on the
day before the strike's one-year anniversary. </p>
<p>Chanting as they entered the lobby, their noise deafened the
panic-stricken station executives, who called the police and
reported a &quot;riot.&quot; Following an exhortation by Farm
Workers President Arturo S. Rodriguez, the demonstrators engaged
in informational picketing (See story, Page 8). </p>
<p>Back at the conference, the CLC officers also rose to the
occasion when Rodriguez and two UFW members who were fired for
union activity gave striking accounts of the slave-like
conditions of the California strawberry fields. (See story, Page
2). </p>
<p>The conferees donated their own money to the campaign and in
turn pledged their councils to donate time and resources to the
campaign. After working sessions on CLC support for the
strawberry campaign, the officers also agreed to organize two
national days of action in support of the workers and offered
numerous recommendations for the campaign. </p>
<p>Other working sessions focused on the role of the CLC,
building membership participation and encouraging legislative and
political action. Dialogue during working sessions and question-
and-answer periods showed that CLCs are indeed rising again. </p>
<p>Amy Dean, business manager of the South Bay Labor Council in
San Jose, Calif., said her council has established a nonprofit
organization called Working Partnerships USA and a campaign
management institute. </p>
<p>&quot;Community as well as labor leaders need to be at the
table as we formulate and fight for all working people,&quot;
Dean explained. &quot;The labor council set up WPUSA to
institutionalize this crucial relationship and to provide a
vehicle to reach the widest possible constituency.&quot; </p>
<p>In less than a year, WPUSA has become a player in the regional
debate over economic development policy, persuading the County
Board of Supervisors to approve tax abatement guidelines that
protect the rights of working people and taxpayers and provide a
guaranteed number of good-paying jobs. </p>
<p>Other councils, including the Omaha (Neb.) Federation of
Labor, have formed nonprofit organizations. President Terry Moore
agreed that such groups expand labor's organizational and
political clout in the community. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO Department of Field Mobilization sponsored the
conference to forge just such innovation. </p>
<p>&quot;There's no one more vital to the labor movement than you
are t no one,&quot; AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda
Chavez-Thompson told the CLC officers. &quot;For our movement to
succeed, it needs for you to succeed.&quot; </p>
<p>Although the labor movement is in a time of colossal
challenges, Chavez-Thompson said, those challenges also provide a
window of opportunity - a chance to help set the agenda for the
nation. </p>
<p>&quot;But a larger movement is needed,&quot; she stressed.
&quot;That's why we're aiming to create a culture of organizing
throughout the union movement . . . and CLCs can and will be the
center of that culture.&quot; </p>
<p>Several CLC officers reminded Chavez-Thompson, who oversees
state and local AFL-CIO activities, and AFL-CIO President John J.
Sweeney, that building these extensive organizing and political
programs at the local level are limited by low levels of local
union affiliation and a lack of resources. </p>
<p>Sweeney promised the officers the AFL-CIO would &quot;work
harder, spend more money and campaign smarter than we ever have
before.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;But the bulk of the resources for reorganizing the
American work force and rebuilding the American labor movement
must come from international and local unions,&quot; he
explained, &quot;while the coordination and community support for
such efforts must come from our central labor councils.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;We need to make the work of central labor councils so
important and essential that local unions feel it would be
foolish not to affiliate,&quot; said Marilyn Sneiderman, the
federation's field mobilization director. &quot;We must
simultaneously activate our councils and increase affiliation of
locals so we have the resources that we need to get the job
done.&quot; </p>
<p>Another key focus of the national conference was coalition-
building in the community. In adopting a new slogan,
&quot;Organizing for Justice in the Community,&quot; conference
attendees spent many hours in workshops and plenary sessions
developing strategies about how best to build progressive
networks back home. </p>
<p>Radio commentator Jim Hightower praised labor as &quot;the
force that rallies people whether they are union or not. That's
what this is all about.&quot; </p>
<p>The officers also elected four members to the CLC Advisory
Committee from a field of 20 who sought election. They are Jeff
Crosby of Lynn, Mass.; Ernie Esposito of Johnstown, Pa. ; Warren
Gould of New Haven, Conn.; and Ernie Grecco of Baltimore. Dean
was elected to chair the committee. </p>
<p>Formed by Sweeney with the appointment of 20 officers from
small, medium and large councils, the committee's charge is to
set priorities and the direction for labor councils. As part of
their work, every council is being surveyed via telephone, with
320 surveys completed, said Fernando Gapasin of Penn State
University. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO plans to use the work of the Advisory Committee,
the conference and the telephone survey to lead the national CLC
mobilization effort to unite and magnify the work of each council
into one program that offers workers a real opportunity to start
fighting back and winning, Sneiderman said. </p>
<p>Other speakers included Sweeney's Executive Assistant Bob
Welsh; Arlene Holt, executive assistant to Chavez-Thompson;
Richard Bensinger, director of the AFL-CIO Organizing Department;
Steve Rosenthal, director of the federation's Political
Department; and Peggy Taylor, director of the federation's
Legislative Department. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
