<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 14</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">$20 million award reversed <br>
</h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>A federal appeals court has reversed a $20 million lower court
damages award against the Carpenters and the Paperworkers. </p>
<p>BE&amp;K, a nonunion construction firm based in Birmingham,
Ala., alleged that the unions conspired to have the company
removed from a $500 million Potlatch Corp. paper mill
construction project in 1991. The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals dismissed claims against the UBC because of insufficient
evidence, and dismissed a state claim against UPIU because it was
pre-empted by a pending federal suit. The case is BE&amp;K
Construction vs. Carpenters. </p>
<p>&quot;This is not just a great decision for us,&quot; said UBC
President Douglas J. McCarron. &quot;The court's ruling also
defends the rights of all unions to work together in
solidarity.&quot; </p>
<p>UPIU President Wayne E. Glenn praised the unanimous appeals
court decision, calling the jury finding &quot;unjustified&quot;
and the award &quot;outrageous.&quot; </p>
<p>BE&amp;K charged that the two unions threatened Potlatch with
violence if BE&amp;K was not removed from work on its Cypress
Bend mill in McGehee, Ark. The appeals court found that the UBC
was not even present at the meeting in question and that UPIU,
which represents Cypress Bend workers, did not threaten Potlatch,
but had peacefully and legally tried to convince the company to
change its mind. </p>
<h4>No `paycheck electioneering'</h4>
<p>The National Labor Relations Board unanimously banned
companies from using workers' paychecks and the way they are
distributed to influence union elections. </p>
<p>Citing its rules against last-minute speechmaking by either
side to a &quot;captive audience&quot; and late campaigning near
polling places, the board laid down these prohibitions on
employers: </p>
<ul>
    <li>No splitting of paychecks as an anti-union tactic. Some
        employers would give employees two checks, one containing
        what the employer says the worker would earn, less union
        dues, and the other representing what the employer claims
        would be the union dues. </li>
    <li>No changing the time, location or method of paycheck
        distribution. </li>
</ul>
<p>The case stemmed from a complaint by the Operating Engineers
against Kalin Construction Co. in Sodus, Mich., over a 1994
election. The board ordered a new election. </p>
<h4>California wage law upheld</h4>
<p>A federal appeals court has upheld California's prevailing
wage law that sets a two-tiered payment system. </p>
<p>Two nonunion contractors had argued that the federal
Employment Retirement Income Security Act pre-empted the law.
ERISA sets guidelines for the protection of employee benefit
plans. </p>
<p>The California law requires contractors on state-funded public
works projects to pay prevailing wages without crediting higher-
than-prevailing benefit contributions. The contractor can pay
workers the total amount of the prevailing wage and benefits in
cash wages, or pay a combination of at least the prevailing cash
wage plus employee benefit plan contributions that together
amount to at least the total amount of the prevailing wage. </p>
<p>The contractors, WSB Electric Inc. and J.R. Roberts Corp., had
appealed a similar ruling by the U.S. District Court. In its
ruling, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said ERISA
exemptions did not apply to the California law, which regulates
wages in general, nor wages that are part of a specific benefit
plan. </p>
<p>The case is WSB Electric vs. Curry. </p>
<h4>Court curtails company</h4>
<p>The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit
has issued an order enjoining the cleaning company United States
Service Industries Inc. from retaliating against employees
because of their union activities and from otherwise violating
the National Labor Relations Act. </p>
<p>The Washington-based janitorial firm has been the focus of an
ongoing organizing drive by Service Employees Local 82. The order
enjoins the company from, among other actions, transferring and
discharging employees because of their union activity; engaging
in surveillance of employees; interrogating employees; and
threatening employees with reprisal. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
