<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">UNITE's Kmart pact `excellent' <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Colleen M. O'Neill</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The community of Greensboro, N.C., again rallied around civil
rights and human rights, helping to produce a top-notch contract
for Kmart distribution center workers after a bitter struggle. </p>
<p>Religious leaders and activists gave vigorous support to the
workers at the facility, who voted for union representation in
September 1993. As the months passed, workers learned they earned
by far the lowest wages of all Kmart's &quot;hard-line&quot;
distribution workers, and they built their case for justice and
dignity with patience and confidence. </p>
<p>In fact, the predominantly white work forces at the chain's
other hard-line centers were making hourly wages an average of $4
higher than those of the mostly minority Greensboro workers. </p>
<p>The battle grew to include a community-sponsored boycott,
civil disobedience demonstrations and other actions. Workers'
persistence paid off with a three-year contract covering some 550
workers that went into effect July 28. It includes: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Pay increases ranging from 22 percent to 52 percent over
        the next 24 months. </li>
    <li>Two new paid holidays. </li>
    <li>Increases in paid sick leave. </li>
    <li>Nondiscrimination language. </li>
    <li>New job-bidding, grievance procedures and work standards
        language. </li>
</ul>
<p>&quot;This is an excellent new contract,&quot; said Bruce
Raynor, executive vice president and southern regional director
of UNITE. &quot;It was a long, tough battle, but the Kmart
workers, with the tremendous support from the Greensboro
community, were able to force the company to agree to a contract
that offers them the highest wage increases that any hard-line
distribution center has ever received.&quot; </p>
<p>In addition to actions in the Triad area of North Carolina,
protests against Kmart's treatment of its workers took place in
Atlanta, Houston, Chicago, Cleveland, Memphis, Tenn., and
Norfolk, Va. </p>
<p>In real terms, the pact provides an hourly wage boost of 50
cents this year, 75 cents next July and 75 cents in July 1998.
Workers also received a 50-cent-per-hour raise last March, during
negotiations. The current base rate of $9 an hour will go to $11
by the third year. The starting rate in the warehouse of $7.25 an
hour will advance to $9 an hour. </p>
<p>In addition to the wage and sick leave gains, other benefits
remain unchanged, such as major medical insurance coverage for
employees and dependents, a disability income plan and dental
plan t all fully paid by the company - and a retirement savings
plan. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
