<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 16</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Coalitions tailor sweatshop campaign <br>
<font size="3"><i>By Muriel H. Cooper</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Two recent Washington events showcased the continued efforts
of labor unions, the Department of Labor, celebrities and
retailers to eradicate sweatshops throughout the world. </p>
<p>The &quot;Fashion Industry Forum&quot; and congressional
hearing were followed up by a New York demonstration July 30 by
the &quot;Stop Sweatshops&quot; Coalition against jeans maker
&quot;Guess?&quot; for allowing sweatshop conditions in the
manufacture of its garments. </p>
<p>UNITE President Jay Mazur outlined steps that would help
eliminate sweatshops during the fashion forum sponsored by the
Labor Department. </p>
<p>These measures include manufacturers and retailers taking
responsibility for how their products are produced, new industry
standards that recognize the growing trend of giant retailers who
also are manufacturers, increased resources and powers for the
Labor Department, international trade agreements linked to worker
rights and corporate codes of conduct. </p>
<p>During a July 15 congressional hearing, Rep. Christopher H.
Smith (R-N.J.) called for the United States to block the
importation of goods made with exploitative child labor and to
cut off foreign aid to countries that tolerate sweatshops using
child labor. </p>
<p>The International Labor Organization estimates that some 73
million children between the ages of 10 and 14 are employed
worldwide. American consumers began to focus on the issue of
child labor and the resurgence of sweatshops last summer, when
almost 70 workers were found toiling in slave-like conditions in
California. </p>
<p>&quot;The shocking revelations from El Monte, Calif., last
year t followed by The Gap and Kathie Lee Gifford episodes - have
awakened the country to the return of the sweatshop,&quot; Mazur
said. This past spring, UNITE exposed a New York City sweatshop
that produced clothing for the Kathie Lee Gifford line. </p>
<p>&quot;This is more than an economic problem for a particular
industry, firm or group of workers,&quot; Mazur said. &quot;The
injustice and inhumanity of the modern sweatshop constitute a
moral challenge for our society - a challenge to some of the most
basic democratic and human values.&quot; </p>
<p>Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich affirmed the Clinton
administration's support for ending child labor, and called for
such efforts as an international labeling system like the
&quot;RUGMARK&quot; tag, which is affixed to hand-knotted carpets
certifying that they are not made with child labor. </p>
<p>Nearly 300 garment industry professionals were represented at
the DoL forum in Arlington, Va. </p>
<p>Many of the retail representatives said they were working to
monitor factories here and abroad that produce clothing for the
U.S. market to ensure they are adhering to labor laws. </p>
<p>Also appearing at the forum was sweatshop worker Nancy
Penaloza, who described how she worked at least 56 hours a week
sewing women's suits for $6 each. The suits are sold for more
than $120. </p>
<p>&quot;The factory is very dirty, &quot; she said. &quot;When
I'm working, I'm afraid because the rats and mice crawl on my
feet. There is only one bathroom for 150 people, and it is very
dirty. . . . I hope this forum today will help to make conditions
better for garment workers,&quot; she said. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
