<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">USWA: No dealwith Bridgestoneif workers out <br>
<font size="3"><i>By James B. Parks</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Steelworkers President George Becker said he is willing to
meet anywhere at anytime to settle the two-year strike against
Bridgestone/Firestone, but only if replaced workers are returned
to work. </p>
<p>&quot;I would be willing to meet with appropriate officials of
Bridgestone/Firestone as soon as one condition is met,&quot;
Becker said. &quot;That condition is the return to work of all of
the workers whom the company has illegally replaced at its
facilities. Until that condition is met, any meeting with me
would be pointless,&quot; he said. </p>
<p>Becker's statement was in response to reports that in a
meeting with Rev. Jesse L. Jackson, Bridgestone officials said
they wanted to meet with Becker and that Becker should be
involved in future negotiations. </p>
<p>&quot;While the Steelworkers carry out a worldwide campaign to
publicize Bridgestone/Firestone's anti-union, anti-worker
conduct, we have amply demonstrated our sincerity in wanting to
negotiate a fair contract that will meet the needs of both the
company and the union,&quot; Becker said. &quot;I urge the
company to make a similar show of sincerity by immediately
restoring all of the illegally replaced workers.&quot; </p>
<p>On the second anniversary of the strike, the USWA ratcheted up
the pressure on the Japanese tiremaker with an impressive show of
international solidarity during the &quot;Days of Rage,&quot;
July 12-13. </p>
<p>From Nashville, Tenn., to Sao Paulo, Brazil, to Tokyo, workers
around the world sent an unqualified message to
Bridgestone/Firestone: Settle the strike with the Steelworkers
quickly and fairly. </p>
<p>Bridgestone even lost support in its own backyard when
Nashville's Metro Transit revoked the company's contract for bus
tires. Lucas Tire Co., New Orleans' largest independent tire
dealer, also dropped Bridgestone's tires. </p>
<p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney and Becker led a march by
2,000 workers and strike supporters in Nashville, the tiremaker's
U.S. headquarters. &quot;The only way to cope with corporate
lizards is to lift the rocks they hide under and turn their
bellies up to the sun,&quot; Sweeney told the crowd. The strikers
have &quot;13.1 million brothers and sisters who will walk before
they drive an automobile, or ride a bus, or operate an earthmover
that slithers down the street on Bridgestone/Firestone
tires,&quot; he said. </p>
<p>The USWA and Bridgestone/Firestone have been unable to reach
agreement on a contract since July 1994, when 4,000 workers
walked off the job. The workers, formerly members of the Rubber
Workers, suspended the strike after 10 months. During the strike,
Bridgestone/Firestone hired 2,300 replacement workers. At issue
is the rehiring of 700 strikers. </p>
<p>RENGO, Japan's labor federation, held a press conference in
Tokyo condemning the management of Bridgestone and issuing a
strong statement supporting the USWA and demanding a fair
settlement. </p>
<p>In Argentina, 2,000 workers staged a three-hour rally and work
stoppage in solidarity with the USWA and to show Bridgestone
officials that they would strike if there is no progress in their
talks. Bridgestone has threatened to eliminate 150 jobs there if
the union does not accept its last offer. </p>
<p>In Brazil, workers staged one-hour work stoppages at each of
three shift changes, and all shifts engaged in a work slowdown
that they called &quot;working like turtles.&quot; </p>
<p>In Europe, union representatives from every Bridgestone plant
met with top company officials in Brussels and demanded that a
just agreement be reached. </p>
<p>For the two weeks prior to the meeting, European workers
handbilled at all Bridgestone plants on the continent and
displayed black flags on all union bulletin boards. </p>
<p>In addition to the rallies, the USWA ran a 30-minute
television program in 20 cities July 13 exposing the activities
of the company Becker calls &quot;a poster child for corporate
irresponsibility.&quot; </p>
<p>Meanwhile, Nashville city officials denied the USWA's request
to extend the permit for Camp Justice, the tent city occupied by
replaced workers located just outside Bridgestone/Firestone
headquarters. The 90-day permit expired July 15. The union has
appealed the decision, and an Aug. 13 hearing has been set. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
