<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 18</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Teamsters nominate Carey, Hoffa for membership
vote <br>
<font size="3"><i>By David Kameras</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The Teamsters completed their 25th international convention in
Philadelphia July 19 after nominating President Ron Carey and
challenger James Hoffa for the top post of the AFL-CIO's largest
union. </p>
<p>A direct ballot election is set for November. </p>
<p>In his candidate acceptance speech, Carey pointed to the
reversal of a 16-year membership decline, development of grass-
roots and educational programs, anti-corruption efforts and
achievement &quot;of some of the best contracts our members have
ever worked under&quot; as evidence of a track record of fighting
&quot;to put our members first.&quot; </p>
<p>In accepting his nomination, Hoffa proposed a new future for
the union, &quot;one with respectable contracts and with a new
general president who won't take orders from outsiders,&quot; an
allusion to the federal consent decree under which the union
currently is functioning. </p>
<p>While in Philadelphia, the IBT sought to resolve a dispute
with May Department Stores, which is shuttering a Strawbridge
&amp; Clothier warehouse occupied by protesting workers and
moving operations out of the area. Those efforts were praised by
AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney, who also lauded the union as
&quot;one of the brightest lights on the organizing
horizon.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;We need to get ourselves a new organizing attitude and
begin treating anti-union bosses like we treat anti-union
politicians,&quot; Sweeney said. &quot;If a boss fires somebody,
we should get the boss fired. If a boss takes us on, we take the
fight public. If the boss breaks the law, we break their bank
account, sit in their offices and get in their faces.&quot; </p>
<p>Delegates voted to establish a code of ethics for pension and
health fund trustees, add the president of Teamsters Canada to
the international's general executive board, bar members and
officials from associating with organized crime and uphold the
suspension and expulsion of a number of officials accused of
corruption. </p>
<p>But spirited and sometimes raucous debate between the two
presidential camps held up action on a number of proposals
affecting electoral procedures, area conferences, officer
compensation and the union's strike fund, prompting Carey to call
for a special convention after the election. &quot;That's the
only way we can complete our business, to take it out of politics
and have an orderly convention.&quot; </p>
<p>The commotion in the hall frequently disrupted the course of
business and prevented Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Pa.) from addressing
the delegates, who nonetheless united to cheer Labor Secretary
Robert B. Reich, there to credit the Clinton administration for
having &quot;finally put in place a National Labor Relations
Board that understands that collective bargaining is a right and
not a privilege.&quot; </p>
<p>Reich pledged use of the president's veto authority to block
Republican efforts to gut workplace safety, scrap overtime and
allow the establishment of company unions. &quot;What's good for
American workers is good for America,&quot; he said, &quot;and
that is why we need strong unions in this country.&quot; </p>
<p>A poll of rank-and-file Teamsters by Peter D. Hart Research
Associates indicates that members prefer Bill Clinton over Bob
Dole 58-30, and 65 percent approve of Clinton's performance.
However, the convention declined to endorse a specific candidate
for the White House, indicating instead that local unions will
promote voter registration and education. </p>
<p>&quot;We don't tell our members how to vote,&quot; Carey said.
&quot;We provide them with the facts, and they will make up their
own minds. On the major economic issues facing working families,
it's clear that most of our members believe that the Clinton-Gore
ticket is a better choice than Bob Dole.&quot; </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
