<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 19</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">West Coast ports hum <br>
</h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The Longshoremen reached a tentative three-year contract with
the Pacific Maritime Association that would provide wage
increases of $3 per hour for 8,000 workers at 26 ports on the
West Coast. </p>
<p>The ILWU's Longshore Division Caucus ratified the pact July 22
and sent it to the membership for a vote sometime in August. The
contract would be retroactive to July 1, when the previous
contract expired. </p>
<p>Under the agreement, the workers would receive a $2 raise in
the first year and $1 in the second. The increases would be the
first since 1993 for the workers. </p>
<p>Skill rate differentials also increase for longshore equipment
operators and marine clerks. The highest differential of 6.75
percent will increase to 20 percent over term. Pension benefits
also would increase for future retirees from $2,415 per month to
$2,520 in the third year. </p>
<h4>Janitors in tentative pact</h4>
<p>After turning up the heat on San Francisco building owners and
managers with a 99 percent strike vote, 4,000 janitors were
voting Aug. 3 on a contract that would increase wages and
pensions by 25 percent. </p>
<p>The Building Owners and Managers Association and the San
Francisco Contractors' Association had proposed dismantling the
union hiring hall, reducing health and welfare coverage and
eliminating seniority rights, even while building owners are
reaping record profits. </p>
<p>The janitors, who are mostly immigrants, minorities and women,
are represented by Service Employees Local 87. </p>
<h4>Victory in Grayson, Ky.</h4>
<p>A two-year fight for dignity and decent wages by the Service
Employees at Cook Family Foods ended when the workers ratified a
new contract. </p>
<p>The new contract doubles current pay levels, exceeding
industry standards, the union said. While the contract does not
include a union shop clause, some 188 of the 200 workers who
voted in the election joined the union. </p>
<p>The employees, formerly members of the Firemen and Oilers,
struck for more than a year at the Grayson, Ky., plant. About 100
employees returned to work after a federal court in Cincinnati
overturned an NLRB decision certifying the union as bargaining
representative for the workers. </p>
<h4>IBEW in Georgia pact</h4>
<p>About 5,000 Electrical Workers at Georgia Power will receive a
7 percent pay raise after ratifying a new three-year contract. </p>
<p>The deal, approved June 28, covers power plant operators,
linemen, meter readers and maintenance and repair workers. They
will receive a 3 percent wage increase in the first year,
followed by hikes of 2 percent in 1997 and 1998. </p>
<p>Shift differentials and per diems also increased, and the
amount workers must pay for long-term disability benefits
declined. </p>
<h4>Supervisors back workers</h4>
<p>The San Francisco Board of Supervisors passed a resolution in
support of the California Professional Employees, an affiliate of
the Painters that represents workers at the city's Economic
Opportunity Council. </p>
<p>The resolution urged the council to negotiate and reach a
collective bargaining agreement. The union has been attempting to
bargain a new contract to replace one that expired July 1, but
agency officials refuse to negotiate. </p>
<p>The agency also is fighting union efforts to organize
employees in three other departments at the agency. The union,
which represents 70 employees who provide day care for poor
children and home weatherization services, has filed unfair labor
practice charges with the National Labor Relations Board over the
negotiations and organizing roadblocks. </p>
<p>San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer and
U.S. Rep. Tom Lantos, all Democrats, already have made public
statements in support of the workers. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
