<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 20</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">`We will win Detroit strike' <br>
Sweeney boosts strikers as solidarity actions grow <br>
<font size="3"><i>By James B. Parks</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Organized labor intends to turn up the heat as high as
necessary to win the Detroit newspaper strike, AFL-CIO President
John J. Sweeney said. </p>
<p>&quot;We're going to win those strikes. That's a promise and a
commitment,&quot; Sweeney said, referring to the strikes in
Detroit and at Bridgestone/Firestone. &quot;To really scare (the
Detroit newspapers), we have to have an even stronger impact on
profits, circulation and advertising,&quot; he said. &quot;That
is what we are planning to do. </p>
<p>&quot;First of all, we have to win this for the strikers.
Second, we have to win this for the labor movement. I'm not sure
if you appreciate how much focus there is on this strike in other
parts of the country. This is just an example of the corporate
greed we see,&quot; Sweeney told a crowd of strikers during a
visit to Detroit. </p>
<p>Some 2,000 employees of the News and Free Press, owned by
Gannett and Knight-Ridder, respectively, have been on strike
since July 13, 1995, after negotiations failed to produce a new
agreement. Management and imported scabs from other papers are
producing the newspapers. Hired union-busting security goons from
Vance and Huffmaster are delivering the papers. </p>
<p>Striking unions include the Teamsters, Communications Workers,
Graphic Communications and The Newspaper Guild. </p>
<p>The strikers settled an unfair labor practice charge July 12
by agreeing not to coerce current newspaper employees by making
threats, gathering in crowds to picket or blocking driveways. </p>
<p>The settlement agreement was spurred by a National Labor
Relations Board threat to seek an injunction against alleged
misconduct, and by the fuel such proceedings might add to the
newspapers' racketeering suit against the unions, said Samuel
McKnight, attorney for the striking unions. </p>
<p>&quot;The real violence here is the company's effort to
destroy the working lives of 2,000 decent employees,&quot;
McKnight said. &quot;We'll continue to do everything we've been
doing to inflict on them huge economic losses until they bargain
in good faith.&quot; </p>
<p>The strikers repeated their desire to negotiate a fair
settlement. In an editorial in the striker-produced Sunday
Journal, the unions urged management to &quot;make us an offer.
Respond to one of ours. `Drop dead' or `Go away' is not a useful
response. Get off the dime and begin serious negotiations about a
contract. </p>
<p>&quot;If the absentee owners choose not to negotiate, however,
they shouldn't kid themselves that the strike is over or that
they are going to win back the trust and readership and dollars
of the community they have so egregiously insulted with their
arrogance and union-busting,&quot; the unions said. </p>
<p>The strikers continue to get strong support from other unions.
The Locomotive Engineers, meeting in Detroit, donated $20,000 to
help the strike. Gwend Johnson, an assistant to CWA President
Morton Bahr, announced that all of the families on the
Adopt-A-Family list had been adopted as of July 1. But donations
still are needed to keep the fund solvent. Contributions can be
mailed to: Adopt-A-Family, c/o Gwend Johnson, CWA Headquarters,
501 Third St. N.W., Washington, D.C. 20001, phone: 202/434-1115. </p>
<p>On the first anniversary of the strike, the strikers rallied
at the Sterling Heights printing plant where the scab papers are
produced. In San Jose, Calif., more than 100 people rallied and
raised $500 for the strikers. </p>
<p>In Washington, some 200 delegates to the A. Philip Randolph
Institute's annual education conference joined Newspaper Guild
President Linda K. Foley, striking Detroit newspaper employees
and Washington Metropolitan AFL-CIO President Joslyn N. Williams
in front of the National Press Building to protest the presence
of the Detroit News and Knight-Ridder bureau offices in the
building. </p>
<p>&quot;We don't want union busters in our town,&quot; Foley
said. </p>
<p>Strikers Meka Murphy and Gean Odroniec, both members of IBT
Local 372, told the crowd they had not received an adequate raise
since 1989. &quot;All we want is a decent contract and a decent
wage and to go back to work,&quot; Odroniec said. </p>
<p>&quot;We made this company,&quot; Murphy said. &quot;We built
this company, and this is what they do to us.&quot; </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
