<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 21</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">New leaders for California <br>
</h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The California AFL-CIO charted a new course with an expanded
executive council and two new leaders. </p>
<p>Art Pulaski, secretary-treasurer of the San Mateo Labor
Council, was elected executive secretary-treasurer July 31 by
some 800 delegates, replacing the retiring Jack Henning. Tom
Rankin, state federation research director and lobbyist, was
elected president, succeeding Albin J. Gruhn, who also retired. </p>
<p>Delegates approved the expansion of the council from 36 to 46
to increase representation by women and people of color. </p>
<p>State federations must set a higher standard for organizing,
and unions must adopt a more aggressive organizing attitude, AFL-
CIO President John J. Sweeney told the delegates. In order to
reverse union membership losses, Sweeney called on state
federations &quot;to roll out the big guns&quot; and shift more
of their resources to organizing. </p>
<p>AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson also
addressed the convention. </p>
<h4>No to harassment</h4>
<p>Women's, labor, legal, religious and community organizations
have pledged their support for expand protections for sexual
harassment victims. </p>
<p>&quot;We stand solidly with those supporting this legislation
that will serve to hold responsible parties accountable when
perpetrators of sexual harassment are negligently hired or
retained in the workplace,&quot; said Massachusetts AFL-CIO
President Joseph Faherty. </p>
<p>Boston 9to5, National Association of Working Women, was
instrumental in gaining a broadened interpretation of the state's
sexual harassment statute. The measure would allow victims of
sexual harassment to file cases directly in Superior Court within
three years of the incident or file with the Massachusetts
Commission Against Discrimination. </p>
<p>It also would extend the statute of limitations from six
months to three years for all forms of workplace discrimination. </p>
<h4>County runs sweatshop</h4>
<p>The Los Angeles County Labor Federation announced that Los
Angeles County and its Home Supportive Services program has
received the &quot;L.A.'s Biggest Sweatshop&quot; award. </p>
<p>The Home Supportive Services program pays sub-poverty wages
and regularly denies workers payment for hours worked, raises and
opportunities for advancement. Workers don't receive health
benefits either, despite the fact that many are injured on the
job providing care for others. </p>
<p>The award was presented by an exploited Thai worker whose
story focused attention on the resurgence of sweatshops in
America. Last summer during a raid, almost 70 Thai workers were
discovered working in El Monte, Calif., in slave-like conditions. </p>
<h4>Privatization panned</h4>
<p>Postal unions testifying before the House subcommittee on the
Postal Service said they supported some provisions in the Postal
Reform Act of 1996, but they adamantly oppose privatization and
the dilution of bargaining rights. </p>
<p>Postal Workers President Moe Biller said the APWU supports
provisions on competitive mail, changes in USPS financing and law
enforcement improvements. Letter Carriers President Vincent R.
Sombrotto also favored those provisions, but challenged a
proposal that rate adjustments could be used to restrict the
financial component of collective bargaining agreements. </p>
<p>Mail Handlers President William H. Quinn also testified. </p>
<h4>Web clean-up campaign</h4>
<p>Service Employees Local 82, home of the Justice for Janitors
campaign in the nation's capital, has unveiled its World Wide Web
site, Toxin Watch. </p>
<p>The site includes information on toxic spills, releases and
other environmental problems of select oil, gas and chemical
companies. </p>
<p>The web address is <a
href="http//www.seiu.org/local/82-dc/toxin.htm">http//www.seiu.org/local/82-dc/toxin.htm</a>. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
