<html>
<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 22</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">BLE elects new leadership <br>
<font size="3"><i>By David Kameras</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>By a 320-276 vote, delegates at the Locomotive Engineers'
convention in Detroit elected a new president, Clarence Monin,
formerly the union's first vice president. </p>
<p>Monin defeated incumbent Ronald McLaughlin. A third candidate,
Paul Morrison, chairman of the union's California legislative
board, received 23 votes. Also elected to five-year terms were
Edward Dubrowski, first vice president and Russell W. Bennett,
secretary-treasurer. </p>
<p>Monin pledged to &quot;mobilize, energize and organize the
Locomotive Engineers and the other employees we represent.&quot;
He indicated that he wants to make BLE, which joined the AFL-CIO
in 1989, 133 years after its founding, a larger and more
aggressive part of the labor movement &quot;in concert with the
AFL-CIO and the Transportation Trades Department.&quot; </p>
<p>While in the union's No. 2 position, Monin served as U.S.
national chairman of the BLE safety task force, helping the
National Transportation Safety Board investigate major rail
accidents, was vice chairman of the union's U.S. national
legislative board and directed BLE's education and training
department. He also assisted in on-site negotiations during the
most recent round of contract talks. </p>
<p>In an example of the union's emphasis on solidarity, a
thousand members, officers and family members joined with
striking Detroit News and Free Press workers in a march to demand
that management bargain in good faith, and passed the hat to
raise $20,000 to help out strikers and their families. </p>
<p>BLE's show of unity went &quot;above and beyond the call of
solidarity,&quot; said Margaret Trimer-Hartley, an activist who
before the strike was an education writer for the Free Press, and
who was asked to address the convention. &quot;I felt
particularly proud to be there because my father was a railroad
man.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;I think what we saw in Detroit is an awakening of what
can be done between sister unions of the AFL-CIO,&quot; union
spokesman Steve Fitzgerald said. </p>
<p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney told delegates that labor's
recent successes in getting the Senate to approve a minimum-wage
increase and defeat a national right-to-work bill, as well as
blocking the so-called TEAM Act and efforts to eliminate new
repetitive stress injury regulations, have triggered efforts by
business lobbies and anti-worker forces in Congress to target
unionists with lies and half-truths. </p>
<p>&quot;Well, I don't know about you, but I'm ready,&quot; he
declared. &quot;I'm delighted to take my place beside all their
other targets: the young, the old, working families, the disabled
and the poor. I stand before you today and say I'm proud to be a
target. </p>
<p>&quot;Will you stand with me?&quot; he asked. &quot;Will you
stand with me and (Secretary-Treasurer) Rich Trumka and
(Executive Vice President) Linda Chavez-Thompson as we take back
our country?&quot; The convention responded with a standing
ovation. </p>
<p>Sweeney warned of the consequences that would result if Bob
Dole, &quot;the `Darth Vader' of American politics,&quot; wins
the presidency in November, and outlined the federation's
grass-roots legislative and political education program with
which &quot;we're going to win, from the courthouse to the White
House.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;Why am I so sure? Because America's workers are fed up
with seeing their wages keep falling while the stock market and
productivity and executive salaries and corporate profits keep
skyrocketing,&quot; he said. </p>
<p>Other convention speakers included Railroad Signalmen
President W.D. Pickett, Canadian Labour Congress Secretary-
Treasurer V.M. &quot;Butch&quot; Speakman, labor member of the
Railroad Retirement Board, Rep. David E. Bonior (D-Mich.),
Detroit Mayor Dennis W. Archer and Federal Railroad Administrator
Jolene Molitoris, whose reception was characterized as
&quot;restrained and polite.&quot; </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
