<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 23</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">AFA: Ground Valujet's executives <br>
</h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Citing continuing safety concerns, the Flight Attendants asked
the Transportation Department to give the boot to top officers at
ValuJet Airlines. </p>
<p>Charging that management is either incapable or unwilling to
run a safe airline, the union, which represents the airline's 600
flight attendants, said chief executive Robert Priddy and chief
operating officer Lewis Jordan &quot;should not be trusted with
the public safety.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;This management team bears full responsibility for
ValuJet's horrendous safety record,&quot; said AFA President
Patricia Friend. &quot;They have proven they cannot run an
airline safely, and the DoT must take action.&quot; </p>
<p>ValuJet's fleet was grounded on June 18 after numerous
inspections by the Federal Aviation Administration turned up
serious safety problems at the cut-rate carrier in the wake of a
May 11 crash in Florida that killed all on board. Since beginning
service in 1993, the airline has had six accidents, been
investigated for an additional eight safety &quot;incidents&quot;
and garnered 340 service difficulty reports at the FAA. There
were 59 unscheduled landings in the first five months of this
year alone. </p>
<p>Despite this ghastly record, management is seeking permission
to get airborne again. The AFA said the carrier's filing seeks to
keep certain records secret and to gain an exemption from DoT
procedural rules governing public notice and comment. </p>
<p>The AFA also is pushing for passage of legislation that would
give &quot;whistleblower&quot; protection to aviation workers
reporting safety violations in their workplace. </p>
<p>In another aviation development: </p>
<ul>
    <li>The Air Traffic Controllers, an affiliate of the Marine
        Engineers, has provided initial funding for creation of
        the National Aviation Research Institute, which is
        intended to improve air safety through the development of
        new technology based on the input of the workers who
        actually operate the resulting equipment. </li>
</ul>
<p>Noting that the technology of the present air traffic control
system is 10 to 15 years behind, Acting Executive Director Mike
Connor said the new group will be listening to those &quot;able
to talk about what their needs are within the system, rather than
people who cannot make it happen when they worked with the
FAA.&quot; </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
