<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 24</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Wage fight on national track <br>
Congressional vote is just part of the story <br>
<font size="3"><i>By David Kameras</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>Congress has voted to raise the minimum wage from $4.25 to
$5.15 an hour over two years, but that amount is considered
hardly enough for workers in many states and localities, who have
forged &quot;living wage&quot; campaigns from coast to coast. </p>
<p>Through its America Needs A Raise campaign, the AFL-CIO has
been working with coalitions throughout the nation to champion
the notion that people who work full time ought to earn enough to
support their families. </p>
<p>The most recent breakthrough in the effort to give America a
raise occurred in Oregon, where 114,494 signatures were collected
t many more than the number needed - to mandate a ballot
initiative for November that seeks to raise the state's hourly
minimum wage from $4.75 to $6.50 over three years. </p>
<p>&quot;This is the first step on the long road to give our
lowest- paid working families the raise they justly
deserve,&quot; said Oregon AFL-CIO President Irv Fletcher, who
worked with a coalition of more than 50 labor, religious, social
justice and environmental groups to get the initiative qualified
three days after the U.S. Senate approved an increase in the
federal minimum wage. </p>
<p>A similar success was scored just to the south, where an
initiative to put on the ballot a measure to raise California's
minimum wage by $1.50 qualified with almost 550,000 signatures.
AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney was on hand to help submit the
qualifying ballots. </p>
<p>Voters in Denver and New Orleans will see the fruits of local
initiatives to boost wages on their ballots. Other citywide
initiatives are on the move in Albuquerque, N.M., Boston,
Chicago, Houston, Milwaukee, New York and Washington. </p>
<p>Fletcher said that Congress &quot;is just catching up to where
we've been for the past five years. We intend to continue the
proud and progressive Oregon tradition of setting superior
standards for basic worker protections and quality of life for
our families.&quot; </p>
<p>Those standards are more than an abstraction to Jeanie Taylor
of Salem, Ore., a single mother, full-time student and
minimum-wage worker. &quot;I'm not a teen-ager flipping
hamburgers for pocket change,&quot; she said. &quot;I'm a working
mom who is struggling to provide for my family, while attending
school full time - and $4.75 an hour just doesn't cut it. </p>
<p>&quot;If we increase the minimum wage in Oregon, I may not
have to choose between buying shoes for my son and putting food
on the table,&quot; Taylor said. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO's &quot;America Needs A Raise&quot; campaign goes
beyond the minimum wage. It seeks to spotlight what has been a
decades-long slide in the buying power of American workers, which
in terms of hourly earnings fell 12 percent between 1978 and
1995. It draws attention to the 8 million workers who have to
work two jobs to make ends meet, and the longer hours they put in
on those jobs. It points to the drop in median family income
despite an explosive growth in multiearner families. </p>
<p>Real average weekly earnings did receive a boost in June,
rising 2.2 percent, the Bureau of Labor Statistics reported. </p>
<p>Much of that increase was due to a 1.5 percent growth in
average weekly hours, and average hourly earnings rose 0.8
percent. For the 12 months, real average weekly earnings grew by
1.7 percent. </p>
<p>Median real weekly earnings actually fell slightly in the
second quarter, from $301 to $300 in constant 1982 dollars. </p>
<p>Contributing to the positive real earnings in June was the
continued low inflation rate, with consumer prices (CPI-W)
registering a tiny 0.1 percent increase. Decreases in the costs
of apparel and upkeep and transportation helped to offset a large
run- up in food and beverage prices. Producer prices, which help
predict future performance, rose 0.2 percent. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
<hr>
