<head>
<title>AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996 -- Page 25</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO News - August 3, 1996</h3>
<h3 align="center">Top U.S. export continues to be jobs <br>
<font size="3"><i>By David Kameras</i></font></h3>
<hr width="80%">
<p>The U.S. merchandise trade deficit widened in May, from $12.4
billion to $13.2 billion, as the nation continued to increase its
export of jobs, notably to the Pacific Rim. </p>
<p>The goods deficit with China jumped from $2.3 billion to $3.1
billion, and stands at $12.4 billion for the year - a 7.3 percent
increase over 1995. Although a weaker yen has helped narrow the
bilateral gap with Japan, that trend may change in the coming
months because of a recent appreciation of the dollar that made
U.S. products more expensive. </p>
<p>The five-month total merchandise deficit was $57.7 billion,
close to the $60.4 billion record set in 1995. </p>
<p>&quot;The U.S. trade deficit continues to expand, despite the
fact that unit labor costs continue to decline relative to most
of our trading partners,&quot; noted Mark Anderson, director of
the AFL-CIO Task Force on Trade. &quot;It is clear that lower
wages are not the way to improve the international trade position
of the United States.&quot; </p>
<p>Merchandise shortfalls with America's trading partners in the
North American Free Trade Agreement also have grown, with
year-to- date totals reaching $8.7 billion with Canada, up from
$6.5 billion in 1995, and $6.8 billion with Mexico, up from $6.2
billion. </p>
<p>The troubles for American workers created by the ill-advised
pact continue to materialize, as evidenced by the certification
for NAFTA transitional adjustment assistance of 250 laid-off
Pacificorp utility workers, bringing the total of those eligible
to more than 72,000. That total represents a mere fraction of
those actually affected by displacement. </p>
<p>Some 95 percent of imported electricity comes from Canada. </p>
<p>Meanwhile, at the southern border, Department of
Transportation officials succumbed to pressure from trucking
firms and agreed to weaken a truck safety inspection program on
the Texas-Mexico border. </p>
<p>Under the new plan, companies can self-certify that their
trucks have no safety problems, despite DoT findings that 51
percent of the trucks crossing into Texas were found too
dangerous to operate on U.S. highways. DoT found 34 percent of
trucks entering California to be unsafe, along with 44 percent of
trucks entering Arizona and 78 percent entering New Mexico. </p>
<p>With the certification, Mexican drivers - who earn as little
as $10 a day - can travel without restriction in those states,
and throughout the United States and Canada by 2000. Trucking
deregulation is a provision under NAFTA that the Teamsters and
several Mexican driver groups want renegotiated. </p>
<p>In addition, NAFTA has been roundly criticized for its weak
and unenforceable labor and environmental side agreements. Chile,
which has been considered for membership in an expanded NAFTA,
has agreed to join the Southern Cone Common Market, or Mercosur,
increasing pressure on the United States to grease the skids
toward new trade agreements, regardless of their potential flaws. </p>
<p>Trade performance in the first five months of the year was
particularly dismal in motor vehicles ($21.9 billion deficit),
clothing and footwear (16.5 billion), data processing and office
machinery ($9.6 billion), electrical machinery ($8.3 billion),
consumer electronics ($4.6 billion), toys and sporting goods
($3.1 billion), iron and steel products ($3 billion), furniture
and bedding ($2.3 billion) and paper and paperboard ($1 billion).
Surpluses were scored in airplanes and parts ($8.1 billion) and
general and specialized machinery ($3 billion). </p>
<p>On a balance-of-payments basis, May's combined trade deficit
in goods and services was $10.9 billion, $1.3 billion more than
in April and the worst monthly figure recorded this decade. </p>
<p>Provided by the AFL-CIO Publications Division. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm" target="index.htm">AFL-CIO
Home Page</a> | <a href="/newsonline/news-archive.html">News
Archives</a> | <a href="/newsonline/newssearch.htm">Search News
Archives</a></p>
