<TITLE>STATE KEY LABORATORY OF FUNCTIONAL POLYMER MATERIALS FOR ADSORPTION AND SEPARATION </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>STATE KEY LABORATORY OF FUNCTIONAL POLYMER MATERIALS FOR ADSORPTION AND SEPARATION </H2>
<P><U><B> </B>
<H4></H4>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.nankai.edu.cn">Nankai University </A>
</UL>
<P></U>
<HR>
<H3>Director of Lab: <A HREF="director.html"><B>Prof. Huang Wenqiang </B></A><BR>
 </H3>
<HR>
<H3>Chairman of Academic Committee: <A HREF="chairman.html"><B>Prof.He Binglin </B></A><BR>
 </H3>
<HR>
<H3>Main Research Fields: </H3>
<P>
<P>Studies on the design, synthesis, structure, performance and inter acion mechanism of new type of functional polymer for specific adsorption and separation. 
<P>
<P>Studies on the synthesis and application of clinical polymer materials with function of adsorption and separation and biomedical materials. 
<P>
<P>Studies on reactive polymer materials 
<P>
<P>Studies on analytical and characteristic methods for the micro structure of functional polymer materials. 
<HR>
<H3>Main Academic Staff in the Laboratory:</H3>
<P><A HREF="/disk2/WWWserver/cnkeylab/LOAN/B010/staff1.html "><B>Prof. He Binglin</B></A><A HREF="/cnkeylab/LOAN/B010/staff1.html "> </A>
<P><A HREF="/disk2/WWWserver/cnkeylab/LOAN/B010/staff3.html "><B>Prof. Huang Wenqiang</B></A> 
<P><A HREF="/disk2/WWWserver/cnkeylab/LOAN/B010/staff4.html "><B>Ma Jianbiao,Research Fellow</B></A> 
<P><A HREF="/disk2/WWWserver/cnkeylab/LOAN/B010/staff5.html "><B>Prof. Guo Xianquan</B></A> 
<P><A HREF="/disk2/WWWserver/cnkeylab/LOAN/B010/staff6.html "><B>Li Chaoxing, Research Fellow</B></A> 
<HR>
<H3><A HREF="/cnkeylab/LOAN/B010/equipment.html ">Main Instruments and Equipment </A></H3>
<HR>
<H3>Main research fields of the lab. </H3>
<P><BR>
 * Studies on the design, synthesis, structure, performance and inter action mechanism of new type of functional polymer for specific adsorption and separation.<BR>
 * Studies on the synthesis and application of clinical polymer materials with function of adsorption and separation and biomedical materials. <BR>
 * Studies on reactive polymer materials * Studies on analytical and characteristic methods for the micro structure of functional polymer materials. 
<HR>
<H3>Present Research Projects </H3>
<P>(1)Studies on biomedical polymer materials, including: Blood-cleaning polymer materials Biofunctional polymer materials Polymer materials for drug controlled releasing <BR>
 (2)Synthesis and application of new type of polymer materials for adsorption and separation, including: Separation, extraction and purification of natural products; Concentration and separation of noble metals; Adsorption and separation of harmful components from waste water and gas; Column packing materials for high performance liquid chromatography.<BR>
 (3)Studies on polymer catalysts including: Polymer supported transition metal complexes Polymer supported colloidal metallic catalysts Super acidic resin catalysts Polymer catalysts with high temperature resistance. Research Project Undertaken: <BR>
 1. major projects: 2<BR>
 . Blood-cleaning polymer materials<BR>
 . Biofunctional polymer materials <BR>
 2. Key project during the Eighth Five Plan<BR>
 . Chelating resin materials <BR>
 3. &quot;863&quot; project<BR>
 . Bio-active materials for adsorption <BR>
 4. International academic collaborating project<BR>
 . Biosorption Heavy Metals (with McGill University of Canada)<BR>
 5. Project on fund of natural science for youth scientists: 16<BR>
 6. projects on fund of national natural science: 16<BR>
 7. Projects from ministries and commissions: 22 <BR>
 8. Projects from companies and industries: 2 <BR>
 9. Projects from other sources: 8 
<HR>
<H3>Representative Achievements </H3>
<P>1. Studies on crosslinking reaction, the relationship between structure and performance of its products(1991)<BR>
 2. Design and synthesis of new polymeric materials for separation and their sorption selectivity for natural products(1992)<BR>
 3. Characterize of swelling property of resins(1991) <BR>
 4. Fractionally geometric method for the study of polymeric gelatin(1994) <BR>
 5. Flame-retardant alloy of ABS/PVC for injection molding(1993)<BR>
 6. Synthesis, structure and clinical application of HA macro-porous adsorbemt(1993)  7. Synthesis of chiral polymeric ligands and their application for the resolution of DL-amino acids(1993) <BR>
 8. Synthesis, structure and clinical application of IA immnoadsorbent(1993) 9. Biomimetic design and synthesis of oxygenaffinitive polymeric complexes and the properties for enrichment of oxygen(1993) <BR>
 10. Preparation and development of new materials for the separation and purification of chlorophyll copper(1992)<BR>
 11. Studies on the structure and property of crosslinked polystyrenedivinylkenyene by means of fluoresence(1994) <BR>
 12. Development of polymer supported super acidic catalysts(1994) <BR>
 13. Preparation of weakly anion adsorbents for CO2(1994) <BR>
 14. New process for separation and purification of Letinan(1994) <BR>
 
<HR>
<H3>Guidance to Subjects opened</H3>
<P> <B>1.</B><CITE> Application of Chiral  Ligand Polymers In Resolution of Optical Isomers</CITE><BR>
 <B>He Binglin</B><BR>
 Institute of Polymer Chemistry, Laboratory of Functional Polymer Materials for Adsorption and Separation, Nankai University, Tianjin 300071, PRC. <BR>
 <TT>Progress in Natural Science, 1991(6), 501-514</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Resolution of unmodified DL-amino acid enantiomers by chiral polymer ligand-copper complexes is a valuable and practical new technique. We have prepared over ten kinds of chiral polymer-ligands and their Cu(II) complexes, and investigated the reaction mechanism of the ligand exchange reaction and the conditions of the chromatographic process by using these polymer-Cu(II) complexes in the resolution of DL-amino acids. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>2. </B><CITE>The Synthesis and Properties of Some Porous and Highly Cross-Linked Resins with Moderate Polarity as the Adsorbents for Gypenosides</CITE><BR>
 <B>Ma Jianbiao Li Jianmin Shi Zuoqing He Lanling He Binglin </B><BR>
 (Institute of Polymer Chemistry, Nankai University) <BR>
 <TT>Acta Polymeric Since No. 6 1991</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Several porous and highly crosslinked resins with moderate polarity were synthesized by the suspension copolymerization of divinylbenzene respectively with methyl methacrylate, methyl acrylate, dimethyl maleate , ally acetate, acrylonitrile, vinyl methyl ketone, and N-vinyl pyrrolidone. The resins were characterized and their capacities in adsorbing gypenosides were then determined by HPLC method. The results showed that the polarities of these resins had an important influence on their physical structures and adsorbing capacities. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>3.</B><CITE> </CITE><CITE>Preparation of Microparticles of Narrow Distributed Diameter and Their Usage in Amino Acid Analysis </CITE><BR>
 <B>Wang Busen Zhang Yuge He Binglin</B><BR>
 (Institute of Polymer Chemistry, Nankai University)<BR>
 <TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese universities Vol. 12, No. 4, 1991</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>The narrow distributed polymeric microparticles with diameters of 3-10 um were prepared by suspension when PVA and DBS-Na were used as the mixed dispersing with the stirring rate of 1500-2000r/min. The effects of the conditions of the polymerization reactions on the diameters and distributions of the microparticles were examined. Thereafter, the authors studied the properties of the sulfonated polymeric microparticles which were used as the stationary phases of an amino acid analyzer. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>4</B>. <CITE>Polystyrylsulfonyl Chloride: A Useful, Reactive Intermediate for Preparation of Functionalized Polymers</CITE> <BR>
 <B>Huang Wenqiang He Binglin</B><BR>
 (Institute of polymer Chemistry, Nankai University) <BR>
 <TT>Chinese Journal of Reactive Polymers Vol. 1, No. 1, 1991 </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>This paper describes the preparation of polystyrylsulfonyl chloride, a useful, reactive intermediate, and its application in syntheses of functionalized polymers which can be used in organic chemistry as polymeric reagents, supports and in controlled release systems.<BR>
 <BR>
 <B>5.</B> <CITE>Polymer-supported Ammonium Fluoride: </CITE><BR>
 <CITE>A useful Reagent for Si-O bond Cleavage</CITE> <BR>
 <B>Li </B><B>Chenxi Lu Yu Huang Wenqiang He Binglin</B><BR>
 (Institute of polymer Chemistry, Nankai University) <BR>
 <TT>Synthetic Communications Vol. 21, No. 12 and 13, 1991 </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Polymer-supported ammonium fluoride(1) is a convenient reagent for Si-O bond cleavage. Resin 1 is inexpensive, easy to prepare from commercial amine-containing anion exchange resins and aqueous hydrofluoric acid, easy to store. The product is easily separated from the reaction mixture by filtration. The used resins can be regenerated and reused without losing its reactivity.<BR>
 <BR>
 <B>6.</B> <CITE>Studies on the Adsorption of Middle Molecular Substances from the Plasma of Uremic Patients and Severe Burnt Patients in Vitro</CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Guo Xianquan Yu Saner He Dan etc. </B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of polymer Chemistry, Nankai University)<BR>
 <TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese University No. 8, 1991 </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>It was studied that the middle molecular substances(MMS) were removed with macroporous resins from the plasma of uremic patients and severe burnt patients in vitro. The MMS were analyzed with Sephadex G15. The simulated plasma-perfusion was carried out. The efficiency of the clearance of the MMSwas investigated. the mechanism of adsorption of the MMS by macroporous resins was discussed. It is helpful for finding and preparing a way to treat the patients with hemoperfusion. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>7.</B><CITE> </CITE><CITE>The Investigation of the Pore Structure of Macroporous Ion Exchange Resin and Polymeric Adsorbent by Mercury Porosimetry. Effect of Hysteresis on the Pore Structure</CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Guo Xianquan, Ge Dejin, HeBinglin </B><BR>
<B> </B><TT>Ion Exchange and Adsorption Vol. 7, No. 5, 1991.</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Many authors have observed volume hystersis in the mercury intrusion. After the final reduction of to atmospheric presure, various amounts of mercury remain irreversibly trapped in the samples, depending on the structure of the porous material of the macroporous ion exchange resin and polymeric adsorbent or polymeric catalysts.<BR>
 <BR>
 <B>8.</B> <CITE>Synthesis of the Polystyrene-type Adsorbents Containing Polar Groups and Their Capacities in the Adsorption of Stevioside and Gypenosids </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Ma Jianbiao Fan Yunge Zhao Fenzhi Yu Zhanru Shi Zuoqing He Binglin </B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of polymer Chemistry, Nankai University)<BR>
 <TT>Science in China(Series B)Vol. 35 no. 2, 1991</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Seven polystyrene-type adsorbents(I-VII) were synthesized by the modification of styrene-divinylbenzene copolymer respectively with hydroxymethyl, aminomethyl, methoxymethyl, (4-hydroxy phenoxy)methyl, (4-acetylphenoxy)methyl, and acetyl groups. their structures were characterized with chemical methods and physical techniques. The adsorption capacities of the adsorbents to stevioside and gypenosides were determined via batch test in which the HPLC method was used for the analysis of saponin concentration of solution. The results showed that all the adsorbents could adsorb these saponins to a certain extent, but VI and VII had large capacities owing to their moderate polarities.<BR>
 <BR>
 <B>9</B>. <CITE>Effects of Chemical Modification of Supports on Properties of Tertiary Amino Resin Dispersed palladium Catalysts for the Hydrogenation of Methyl Acrylate </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Chunfu Chen Juntan Sun Hong Li Binglin He</B><BR>
<B> </B><TT>Markromol. Chem. , Marcromol. Symp Vol. 59, 1992 </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Tertiary amino resins(TAR) were chemically modified by quaternization with methyl iodide. By this route six partly quaternized tertiary amino resins(PQTAR) with different I/N mole ratio were synthesized. Four different reducing agents, I. e. , NaH, LiALH4, CH4OH-NaOH and NaBH4, were tested for the preparation of palladium catalysts dispersed on TAR or PQTAR. The rate of hydrogenation reaction were found to be dependent not only on the type of reducing agent but also on the structure of polymer support. Both the rate of hydrogenation and the amount of Pd eluted closely relate to the I/N mole ratio of the polymer supports. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>10</B>.<CITE> Properties of High Dispersed Palladium Catalysts on Poly N-Vinyl-2-Pyrrolidone </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Sun Juntan Chen Chunfu Li Hong He Bing lin </B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of Polymer Chemistry, Nankai University)<BR>
 <TT>Chinese Journal of Reactive polymers Vol. 1, NO&gt;1, 1992</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Four kind of palladium catalysts dispersed on poly-N-pyrolidone were prepared by using CH3OH-NaOH, NaBH3, H2O, or CH3OH-h2O as the reducing agent in the process of catalysts preparation. The catalystswere characterized by XPS, TEM, XRDand used for the hydrogenation rate of methyl acrylate. It was found that the valence state of palladium and distribution of palladium patricles as well as the hydrogenation rate were gently affected by the reducing agent. The best evenly dispersed palladium catalyst showing high hydrogenation activity was prepared using CH3OH-NaOH as the reducing agent. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>11.</B> <CITE>Kinetics of Copolymerization Methyl Methacrylate andEthylene Dimethacrylate</CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Chen Weizhu Zhao Fenzhi Lin Xue Song Zhenzi </B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of polymer Chemistry, Nankai University)<BR>
 <TT>Acta polymeic Sinica No. 2, 1992</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Kinetic behavior of MMA-EGDM copolymerization was investigated in the presence of toluene and 2-ethylbutanol. Effect of monomers ratio, properties and amounts of porogenic agent is discussed for the kinetics of copolymerization. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>12</B>. <CITE>Preparation of polymeric Microparticles by Improved Microsuspension Polymerization </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Zhang Yuge Wang Busen Chen Hong bin Ning Jun He Binglin </B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute OF Polymer Chemistry, Nankai university) <BR>
 <TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese Universities Vol. 13, No. 11, 1992 </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>The present paper represents the improved microsuspension polymerization for the preparation of polymeric microparticles. The effects of several factors on the stability of the system were studied. The results show that it could be carried out in a wide range of reaction conditions. The method may be applied to batch production of polymeric microparticles. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>13. </B><CITE>Studies on Immobilization of B-Cyclodextrin onto Polymeric Carrier(II) </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>He Binglin Zhao Xiaobin </B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of Polymer Chemistry, Nankai University) <BR>
 <TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese Universities, 13(11)1472-1475(1992)</TT><BR>
<TT> </TT><BR>
<TT> </TT>A novel b-cyclodextrin polymer was prepared by immobilization of b-cyclodextrin onto chlorosulfonated and crosslinked polystyrene carrier via chemically bonding Experimental results show that the B-cyclodextrin polymers made by the two systems of NaH/DMF and Et3N/DMAP/DMF have high immobilization amounts. the influence factors were studied in detail. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>14. </B><CITE>Studies on Immobilization of Aminoacylase From Aspergillus Oryzae on Macroprous Carriers</CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Li Minqin Wang Daobin Zhou Juyan He Binglin</B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of Polymer Chemistry, Nankai University) <BR>
 <TT>Science in China(series B) Vol. 36, No. 7, 1993 </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Synthesized macroporous cross-linked copolymers of methyl acrylate-divinyl benzene(MA-DVB), acrylamide-N, N'-methylenebisacrylamide(AAM-BIS)and their functionalized products were used for immobilization of aminoacylase from Aspergilus oryzae. Effects of the carrier properties on the activity of immobilized aminoacylase were investigated and effects of substrate concentration, PH, phosphate buffer concentration and temperature on the immobilized aminocylase were compared with those of the soluble aminoacylase. A column of immpbilized aminoacylase was prepared and used for continuous resolution of N-acyl-DL-methionine; the operational stablity of immobilized enzyme was also investigated.<BR>
 <BR>
 <B>15</B><CITE>.</CITE><CITE> Study on Poly(Methyl Methacrylamide)-Type Ligand Exchange Chromatographic Supports </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Yan Husheng Cheng Xiaohui He Binglin</B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of Polymer Chemistry, Nankai University) <BR>
 <TT>Acta Polymeric Sinica, 1993(2), 220-224 </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Crosslinked poly(methyl methacylate) was first reacted with ethlenediamine or polyethylenepolyamine and then reacted with chloroacetic acid to from hydrphilic poly(methyl mithacrylamide) resins containing a-amino acetic acid groups. The resins coordinated with Cu2 were used as chromatographic supports to separate the neutral amino acids. The effect of the chromatographic conditions such as composition of the eluent, flow rate and column temperature on the separation was studied. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>16.</B> <CITE>Studies on Immobilization of Aminoacylase on Functionalized Polymethyl Acrylate </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Lin Minqin He Binglin</B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of Polymer Chemistry, Nankai University)<BR>
 <TT>Chinese Journal of Biotechnology, 9(3), 282-286(1993)</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Functionalized polymethyl acrylate was used for immobilization of aminoacylase from Aspergillus oryzae. Effects of degree of cross-linking, amount of porogenic agent and mixed porogenic agents on the activity of immobilized aminoacylase were the highest when the carrier was 25% cross-linking and 100% porogenic agent. Effect of substrate concentration, ionic concentration, temperature and PH on immobilized amminoacylase were compared with those on soluble aminoacylase and effects of some organic solvents and protein denaturants on immobilized aminoacylase was used to resolve continuously N-acry-DL-phenylalaine for a mouth, and 90% activity of immoblized aminoacylase was retained. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>17.</B> <CITE>Preparation of Polystyrylsulfonyl Chloride Resin and Its Application in Synthesis of Nitrogen-Containing Basic Resins</CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Huang Wenqiang Li Chenxi Men Aiju Pan Tongtong He Binglin </B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of polymer chemistry, Nankai University)<BR>
 <TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese University, 14(7), 432-435(1993)</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>A new method for preparation of polystrylsufonyl choride resin(I) is described in which the commercially available sulfonated ionic exchange resins(H+from) were treated in ethanol with pyridine to convert into pyridinium polystylsufonate, the latter was refluxed with thionyl choride to give resin 1. A number of nitrogen-containing basic resins were obtained by the reaction of resin 1 wit polyethylenepolyamines, a-aminopyridine, 1, 2, 4-triazole and 2-aminothiazole, respectively. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>18.</B><CITE> </CITE><CITE>The Synthesis of Some Polymeric Diethyletriamine/Cu(II) Complexes Supported by Porous Crosslinked Poly(methyl Acrylate) and Their Sorption </CITE>Properties for Urea<BR>
 <B>He bnglin Ma Jianbiao Zong Fang</B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of polymer chemistry, Nankai University) <BR>
 <TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese University, 14, (7), 1023-1027(1993)</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Some polymeric diethylenetriamine/Cu(II)complexes supported by porous crosslinked poly(methyl acrylate) were synthesized as the adsorbents for urea and their properties in adsorbing urea were staid. The results showed that the polymeric complexes adsorbed urea through coordinate bond of urea to the centric ion. The largest capacity of the complexes was determined as 71. 5mg/g when the adsorption was performed at 28C in the urea solution with concentration of 130mg/dl in a buffer of NaHPO4-NaH2PO4(PH=7. 0). <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>19.</B><CITE> </CITE><CITE>Synthesis and characterization of polymer-immobilized B-cyclodextrin with an inclusion recognition functionality </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Xiaobin Zhao Binglin He </B><BR>
<B> </B><TT>Reactive polymers 24(1994)9-16 </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>A series of b-cyclodextrin(b-CyD) was immobilized onto the crosslinked styrene/divinylbenzene copolymer which embedded polyglycidylmethacrylate. The resulting B-CyD polymeric possesses a specific inclusion recognition with the aromatic compounds. the structures and properties of the grafted copolymer were characterized in detail. Their application for the adsorption of phenol and its derivatives was also assessed. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>20.</B><CITE>Determination of the Inclusion Between B-Cylodextrin and Bilirubin </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Zhao Xiaobin He Binglin</B><BR>
<B> </B><TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese University, 15(8), 1994</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>In this paper, a kind of cyclic oilgosaccharides, B-cyclodextrin was found to possess inclusion abilirubin which is a metabolite of heme in senescent red blood cells. The structure of inclusion complex of B-cyclodextrin/bilirubin was determined by UV-VIS spectra and X-ray powder diagrams. Experimental results indicate that 2 moles of B-cyclodextrin include one mole bilirubin to form the inclusion complex by Van der waals'force, hydrophobic interaction and hydrogen bonds. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>21. </B><CITE>Study on Catalysis of Complex Superacid from macroporous Sulfonated Resin and Fluoboric acid for Esterificaion of Acid With Alcohol's </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Luo Jiazhong Huang Wenqiang He Binglin </B><BR>
<B> </B>(Institute of polymer chemistry, Nankai University)<BR>
 <TT>Ion Exchange and Adsorption, 10(6), 539-542(1994)</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>A novel complex superacid resin prepared from aqueous fluoboric acid and macroporous sulfonated resin shows considerably high catalytic activity for esterification of acetic acid with isopropanol or n-butanol. It was found that esterification of acetic acid and isopropanol(mole ratio 1:3)catalyzed by the complex resin is a second-order reaction, the apparent activation energy Ea is 56. 19KJ/mole. The relative catalytic activity of the complex resin in the reaction of acetic acid and n-butanol(mole ratio 1:3) at 80'C is much higher than that of macroporous sulfonated resin. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>22.</B><CITE> Studies on the New Complexing Adsorbents(IV)-The Memorial of Complexing Adsorbents Containing Polyethylene Polyamine and Copper(II) or </CITE>Nickel(II) used as Template Ions <BR>
 <B>He Binglin Wang Busen Li Wenlan Ding Zeren Guo Zhenliang</B><BR>
<B> </B><TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese Universities, 15(1), 132-135(1994) </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>The behavior of Kinetic adsorption and desorption of two kinds of complexing adsorbents containing polyethylene polyamine, with Cu(II)or Ni(II) as the template ion for Cu(II) and Ni(II)respectively, was studied. The results of five operating cycles show that the complexing adsorbents possess stationary sorption capacities for Cu(II) or Ni(II). Its saturated sorption capacities for Cu(II) and Ni(II) are 4. 357 mmolCu(II)/g and 3. 153 mmol Ni(II)/g respectively. The relative errors are 1. 5% and 2. 2% respectively. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>23</B><CITE>. Investigation of Interpenetrating Polymer Network Chelate Resin(I)---Syntheses of Crosslinked Polystyrene-Polyacrylonitrile Interpenetrating Polymer Network</CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Wang Yongjian Lin Xue Yang Yizhong He Binglin </B><BR>
<B> </B><TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese University, 15(9), 1408-1411</TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>In this paper, crosslinked polystyrene--polyacrylonitrile interpenetrating polymer networks(IPN) have been prepared. The relationship between the interpenetrating percentage of resin and crosslinked percentage, weight fraction, pore structure and solvents were discussed. for the gel type resin, when the crosslinked percentages of the two networks are the same, the interpenetrating percentage is the best. For the macroreticular type, the effect of pore structure is remarkable. The results show that solvent is the most important factor for the IPN synthesis. <BR>
 <BR>
 <B>24.</B><CITE> Studies on Adsorption of the Dioxin with the Macroporous Resin </CITE><BR>
<CITE> </CITE><B>Li Li Ji Ang Guo Xianquan He Binglin</B><BR>
<B> </B><TT>Chemical Journal of Chinese University, 15(12), 1861-1865(1994) </TT><BR>
<BR>
<TT> </TT>Digoxin was selected as digitoxin adsorbed with HA-2 and HA-3 macroporous resins screened from 7 kinds of resins. The physical properties such as specific surface area, pore volume and average pore diameter of the resins were investigated. The factors that affect the adsorption of digoxin are discussed. <BR>
 
