<HEAD>

<TITLE>Case Study / February 3, 1997</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, October 23, 1996  11:31 AM -->

</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">



<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<IMG SRC="images/CS.gif"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=0 ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Multimedia LCD Projectors Bring Internet <br>
Instruction to University Students</FONT><br>
<P>
The growth in demand for World Wide Web access has outpaced many educational institutions ability to fulfill students desire to learn about surfing the net.  Using a multimedia projector to teach students about the Internet gives more students exposure to this information.  By using Sharp LCD projection systems, Florida State University has advanced both its Internet teaching capabilities and general course instruction.
<BR>
Media Specialist Bruce Meintjies, Office of the Dean, instructs university staff members about how to use LCD multimedia projectors in the classroom to visually enhance course work and more effectively reach the students.  By connecting Sharp's XG-E1100U multimedia LCD projectors to a Macintosh or PC-based computer, teachers can reach a larger audience of students to help them learn more about multimedia and the Web in the classroom.  The projectors are also used for video presentations and have replaced overhead projectors as instructional tools.   The university  projects images from the XG-E1100U onto screens with a maximum measurement of 10 feet (measured diagonally).   
<BR>
 "The biggest benefit of using Sharp LCD projectors is that professors find them easy to use, so they can concentrate on teaching," says Meintjies.  "They require very little maintenance.  Currently, we have 27 Sharp projectors around the university.  The majority of auditorium classrooms have the projectors ceiling mounted, while smaller classrooms use A/V and multimedia carts."
<BR>
With the Sharp multimedia projector, professors can "point and click" their way through Web pages, deliver high-resolution presentations, or show video with an image that is bright enough to keep the lights on in the classroom.
<BR>
"The high brightness technology offered by Sharp gives the instructors the added benefit of keeping the lights on while teaching," says Meintjies.  "Previously, students were unable to take notes due to low-level lighting required with other projection systems.  The Sharp projectors deal with this problem beautifully."
<BR>
According to Ron Colgan, general manager of Sharp's Professional LCD Products Group, multimedia projectors are the necessary next step in educational instruction tools. "Using bright, easy to see images in a classroom while teaching gives the instructors more teaching power," says Colgan.  "The decrease in LCD production costs and the relative ease of adapting  hardware platforms allows schools to become a part of the ever-growing world of multimedia." For more information, contact: Bruce Meintjies, Florida State University College of Arts and Sciences, Office of the Dean (904) 644-5264.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="images/home_house.gif" border=0 alt= home HSPACE=10 ALIGN=MIDDLE> SyllabusWeb Home</A>



</BODY>
</HTML>
