<HEAD>

<TITLE>February 3, 1997</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Monday, August 5, 1996  11:46 AM -->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#AEEEF0">


<IMG SRC="images/ntr.gif"  ALIGN=TOP>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>February 3, 1997</FONT>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B> Data Confirms Shift to PCs in Education Market </B>
<MENU>
<LI>
New market data released by IDC/LINK, Framingham, Mass. reports that the Windows platform is sweeping the K-12 education market nationwide. Results of the data indicate that 56 percent of new computer purchases during the 1996-97 school year will be PCs running Windows. IDC/LINK also reports that Windows-based PCs are preferred across all schools, regardless of enrollment size. The main reasons for the shift reportedly are greater availability of software for that platform, lower prices, and influential parents who use Windows at home or at work.<A HREF="http:// www.microsoft.com/education/k12">www.microsoft.com/education/k12</A>
</MENU>
<P>
<B> Computers Go to the Forefront of Architectural Education at Rensselaer </B>
<MENU>
<LI>
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute is revamping its architectural curriculum to include more computing. First-year students will become familiar with computers as an integral part of architecture education; second-year students will progress to animation and interactivity; and third-year students will learn how to generate 3D prototype models from their CAD drawings. In addition, at the graduate level, the school offers three new post-professional master's degree programs, including Computer-Based Design Research. Beyond courses, the school also recently opened a new Architectural/Urbanism Simulation Lab in which architecture students can create virtual reality models of their projects. <A HREF="http:// www.rpi.edu"> www.rpi.edu</A>
</MENU>
<P>
<B> MIT Aids Web Environmental Searches </B>
<MENU>
<LI>
MIT's Global System for Sustainable Development (GSSD) is an adaptive intelligent-agent interface for the Internet that makes it easier to analyze multidimensional aspects of environmental problems. Researchers using GSSD can access environmental information sites that have been gathered and organized by MIT. The project is a collaborative effort of MIT's Department of Political Science and the Technology and Development Program, along with the Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, the Laboratory for Computer Science and the Center for International Studies. GSSD is currently in beta, but is scheduled to go on the Web by June 1997. The URL will be gssd.mit.edu/application.html. For additional information, access <A HREF="http://www.mit.edu
">www.mit.edu
</A>
</MENU>
<P>
<B> Newbridge ATM-Based Products Deliver New Options for Distance Education </B>
<MENU>
<LI>
Newbridge Networks recently released an integrated MPEG2 card for the Newbridge 36150 MainStreet Access Switch that increases bandwidth efficiency for ATM-based video services. Newbridge Networks offers a complete range of high performance ATM networking solutions, including the 36150 and 36170 MainStreet ATM switches that enable video-based solutions for distance education programs. <A HREF="http://www.newbridge.com
">www.newbridge.com
</A>
</MENU>
<P>
<B> AirMedia Announces Special Pricing Plan for College and University Students </B>
<MENU>
<LI>
AirMedia announced a special pricing plan for its AirMedia Live Internet Broadcast Network designed for students at universities and colleges in the U.S. The offer will make AirMedia's Premiere Plus E-mail Service Plan available for $5.95 per month for the duration of each student's university enrollment. Using AirMedia Live, a student receives a wireless alert within 30 seconds after the arrival of new mail on the campus mail server. AirMedia E-mail Message Center integrates arriving campus mail alerts with multiple accounts on services such as CompuServe, AOL, and others. Additionally, university mail administrators can enroll their schools in a program where the school receives $5.00 for each new student activation.<A HREF="http://www.airmedia.com">www.airmedia.com</A>
</MENU>
<P>
</MENU>
<P>
<p>
