<TITLE>Miami Workshop '97</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Monday, February 10, 1997  10:57 PM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

| <A HREF="miami97_cvr.htm">Workshop Agenda</A> | <A HREF="miami97_fri.htm">Friday</A> | <A HREF="miami97_sat.htm">Saturday</A> | <A HREF="miami97_sun.htm">Sunday</A> |<br>
| <A HREF="miami97_lodg.htm">Fees, Lodging and Transportation</A> | <A HREF="miami97_reg.htm">Registration Form</A> | 

<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/miami97.gif"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=LEFT>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>South Florida </FONT></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Fort Lauderdale area</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<BR>
<FONT color=red SIZE=5><CENTER>March 7 - 9, 1997</CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<BR>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Co-Sponsored by</FONT><BR>
<FONT color=red SIZE=5>Syllabus Press</FONT> <BR>
publishers of Syllabus Magazine<BR>
with<BR>
Broward Community College and<BR>
Florida Atlantic University joint campus</CENTER>
<P>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>Choose from the following <BR>
full-day workshops and seminars:</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=3>Hands-On Workshops</FONT></B>
	<P>
<LI> The World Wide Web in Education<BR>
<LI> Developing Courses for the World Wide Web	<BR>
<LI> Managing Courses on the World Wide Web	<BR>
<LI> Presentations and Multimedia in the Classroom	<BR>
<LI> Introduction to Multimedia Tools 	<BR>
<LI> Multimedia Authoring <BR>
<P>
<B>Technology Seminars</B>
<P>
<LI> Issues in Distance Education<BR>
<LI> Institutional Support for Technology Programs <BR>
<LI> Evaluating Effectiveness in Instructional Technology Programs <BR>
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><FONT color=red SIZE=5>Two full days of intensive seminars and hands-on instruction</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT color=red SIZE=5>Appropriate for high school, college, and university-level faculty and administrators</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>S</FONT> yllabus Workshops began as an extension of the popular full-day technology workshops given as pre- and post-conference sessions at the annual Syllabus conferences. Now, Syllabus Workshops are offered throughout the academic year in many different geographic locations.
<P>
In South Florida, all of the courses which make up the Syllabus Core Curriculum will be available during the weekend of March 8-9. Each of these courses covers technology in the context of education and has been designed through a collaboration among experienced workshop leaders and teaching faculty chosen as Syllabus Scholars for their leadership in education technology.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Who should attend?</FONT><BR>
Syllabus Workshops are designed for college-level faculty and department chairs, college administrators, high school teachers, and education technology professionals. Hands-on workshops on Multimedia and on the World Wide Web are sequenced to accommodate different skill levels. Classroom seminar sessions provide in-depth examinations of important issues for all educators involved in technology programs.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>A full weekend of instruction</FONT><BR>
The conference begins Friday, March 7, at 5:00 p.m. with an opening general session and keynote followed by an evening reception. On Saturday and Sunday, attendees will enjoy full-day workshops or seminars of their choice. 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Academic and continuing education credit </FONT>
Attendees have the option to earn 1 academic unit @ $35 or 1.5 continuing education units (CEUs) @ $30 for their participation in two days of workshops or seminars. Please indicate your interest on the registration form.
<P>
<B>BEG</B> =Beginner. Courses with a (BEG) designation will accommodate beginning-level participants.
<P>
