<HEAD>

<TITLE>February 1997</TITLE>
<!-- Date: 5/1/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Highlights from Syllabus Magazine</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>February 1997</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Volume 10, No. 6</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Personal Computer/Workstation Technologies</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
If you are not a subscriber <a name="syllsub" href="syllsub.html">Click here</a> to receive a free subscription to Syllabus magazine, the definitive magazine for high schools, colleges, and universities.
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<IMG ALT="graphic" SRC="images/feb97cvr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>
Personal computers are becoming increasingly necessary for students to both function effectively in colleges and universities and to compete in the job market upon graduation. Our feature article, "Universal Student Access to Information Resources Technology,"  examines how institutions are responding to the challenge of "universal access" for their students: ensuring that each student can "own" a computer. 
<P>
The February issue also focuses on Windows computing. We include case studies and a Product Guide that covers a wide range of Windows software for the curriculum. A Buyer's Guide includes some of the latest desktops, workstations, notebooks, and palmtops available today. Our Multimedia column contains information on how the application Authorware can help courseware designers employ sound pedagogical strategies. 
<br>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

Some highlights and short excerpts follow:
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>Universal Student Access to Information Resources Technology</B> <BR>
<P>
Mark Resmer, Vice President of Information Technology at Sonoma State University, examines the issues surrounding universal access and reviews what institutions are doing to make student ownership of personal computers the rule rather than the exception.
<P>
<MENU>
As Information Technology becomes an increasingly central part of the learning experience for students throughout all disciplines, universities and colleges face a major challenge in ensuring that all students have access to the technological resources that will enable them to realize its full potential to transform their education.
Traditional computer labs simply cannot scale to the point where every student has unlimited access to a computer. Quite apart from issues of cost and physical space, not to mention obsolescence, the quality of access that can be provided in a lab does not equal that which comes from ownership of a computer.
<P>
Let us assume that you currently have a computer on your desk. If someone were to ask you if you would be willing to exchange that computer for one located in a lab at the end of the corridor where your office is located, would you agree to the trade? Even if you were guaranteed access to a machine any time you needed it, a grossly unrealistic expectation at most of our institutions, the answer is almost certainly "no," because of the degree to which you have customized your computer to meet your particular needs and because of the personal information it contains.</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>

<B>Personal Computer and Workstation Technologies: Buyers Guide</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/feb97_01"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>
<B>SGI 02</B><BR>
The O2 desktop workstation line from Silicon Graphics features Unified Memory Architecture (UMA) and integrates advanced 3D graphics, image processing, video and compression capabilities with a 64-bit MIPS RISC microprocessor. The O2 includes Silicon Graphics' new version of UNIX-based operating system IRIX 6.3, which is background compatible, as well as a graphical user environment that integrates Internet and intranet publishing and file transfer capabilities. The O2 supports Microsoft Windows 3.1 or Windows 95 applications. Contact: Silicon Graphics Computer Systems, Mtn.View, CA; (415) 960-1980.
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<B>Apple eMate 300</B><BR>
Designed as a companion to the Mac OS and Windows-based PCs in a distributed learning environment, eMate offers educators an affordable way to make technology accessible to more students. Weighing less than four pounds, the eMate provides dual input methods of a stylus and keyboard. It includes built-in menus that can be operated by touching the screen or through keyboard shortcuts. The eMate 300 features the Newton operating system and comes Newton Works, a set of applications that includes a word processor, drawing program, spreadsheet, and graphing calculator. Contact: Apple Computer, Inc., Cupertino, CA; (408) 996-1010.
<P>
<B>HP Palmtop PC</B><BR>
HP's new palmtop PC, expected to be available in mid-1997, will feature an 80-column, 640x240 LCD display, providing a comfortable view of documents with pages of standard width. It will support Microsoft Windows CE, a scalable Windows operating-system platform that enables users to access and share documents with their Windows-based notebook computers and desktop PCs. The new palmtop PC will feature automatic file synchronization with Windows 95 and Windows NT, which would make it possible for users to carry anywhere the same appointment calendar, phone books and Microsoft Office files that are kept on a full-sized PC. Contact: Hewlett-Packard Co., Palo Alto, CA; (415) 857-1501.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>Technology Across the Campus</B><BR>
<P>

CUBE, a three-dimensional matrix of subjects, themes, and real world examples is part of a new framework at The Pennsylvania State University; More than 20 electronic multimedia classrooms outfit the University of Toronto; and students at Chatham College electronically file writing assignments that are graded by professors through voice annotation.

<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>The Pennsylvania State University</B><BR>
Business College Develops CUBE Multimedia Curriculum
<P>
Smeal College of Business at The Pennsylvania State University is revamping its undergraduate business curriculum with a new program being developed called CUBE (Curriculum for Undergraduate Business Education). CUBE links and integrates areas of business school study with a multimedia and 3-D interactive technology intended to update, expand, and vary content. The program incorporates digital video, audio, graphics, and interactivity that integrate lecture, lab and print. The CUBE program curriculum began last fall with two related, but different products for each of the four courses. Each textbook will be developed into modules, differing from traditional textbooks, using only select chapters. These modules are authored by Smeal College development teams.
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/feb97_04"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>University of Toronto</B><BR>

The Electronic Multimedia Classroom Improves Learning Environments for Students and Faculty
<P>
With more than 20 electronic multimedia classrooms at the University of Toronto, professors who give lectures can manage and control all elements of a presentation by touching the screen. By using Adcom Electronics' iRoom software, "the instructor doesn't have to become an acrobat," says Michael Edmunds, Director of Information Commons at the University of Toronto. Professors can stand in one place during the entire lecture without moving all around trying to control the lecture presentation. iRoom's touch-screen feature gives professors a certain amount of confidence because everything is planned.<P>
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<B>Chatham College</B><BR>
Electronic Filing of Papers By Students Graded Online By Professors
<P>
Chatham College, located in Pittsburgh, Penn., recently experimented with new teaching technologies that allow students to electronically file writing assignments that are graded online by professors with voice annotation. Last spring was the first semester students used their PCs to file writing assignments using Microsoft Word and Microsoft Mail to be graded and recorded by faculty members online.<BR>

"The dynamic nature of the network and technology in general has accelerated innovative uses into the curriculum, and has greatly enhanced technology-based teaching and learning," says Anne Steele, Vice President of Academic Affairs.
<P>
 <HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Multimedia Column</B><BR>
<P>

Simon Hooper, of the Instructional Systems and Technology program at the University of Minnesota, introduces Authorware, the icon-based authoring language used by faculty for cross-platform multimedia development.<BR>
<MENU>
In his book, <I>A Different Kind of Classroom: Teaching with Dimensions of Learning </I>(ASCD, 1992), Robert Marzano suggests that to foster deep and flexible learning, students should engage in activities that will both extend and refine their thinking. Marzano suggests employing strategies that require students to compare and contrast information, to induce principles and deduce consequences, to examine errors and build proofs, and to analyze from personal perspectives and abstract general principles. Yet, how many multimedia products show evidence of such activities? In contrast, many products I have examined do little more than present information to students. Designers seem to be attempting to transmit information into students' minds as effortlessly as possible.<BR>

The causes for the conflict between teaching and learning theory and contemporary multimedia design practice are complex. However, the availability of tools with only limited development capabilities has probably exacerbated the problem. Multimedia developers generally choose from three classes of development tools: programming languages, authoring systems, and authoring languages.<BR>

</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
<B>Windows Product Guide</B>
<P>
<B>DERIVE for Windows</B><BR>

DERIVE is a mathematical assistant for Windows that applies the rules of algebra, trigonometry, calculus, and matrix algebra used by students, educators, engineers. It includes a command toolbar, substitution dialogs, file menu commands, and context sensitive help capabilities. Other features include preview before printing, printer support for all types of color, and black and white printers, and the capability to customize the page setup of DERIVE printouts. Contact: Soft Warehouse, Inc., Honolulu, HI; (808) 734-5801.
<P>
<B>The Java Multimedia Cyber Classroom</B><BR>
The Java Multimedia Cyber Classroom for Windows 95 and Windows NT teaches Java with more than five hours of audio, live code, exercises and programs. Java Programming for the Internet: A Multimedia Cyber Classroom for Windows 95 and Windows NT covers Java programming for Internet applications with more than 100 live Java applets, audio clips, exercises, and software such as Symantec Cafe Lite development environment, Aimtech's Jamba Java authoring tool, and the Java Development Kit 1.1. Contact: Prentice Hall PTR, Upper Saddle River, NJ; (800) 382-3419.
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/feb97_03"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Fractal Design Detailer for Windows</B><BR>

Fractal Design Detailer for Windows is a graphics application that allows users to paint on the surface of 3D models in real-time. Detailer allows users to create bump and texture maps for objects and characters in 3D animations and create colored, textured, rendered 3D objects for use in image-editing composition. Once text is imported, models can be given color by creating Texture maps; relief by making Bump maps; shininess, reflectivity or glow by using Highlight, Reflection, or Glow maps. $449. Contact: Fractal Design Corp., Scotts Valley, CA; (800) 846-0111.
<br>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<IMG SRC="images/feb97_02"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>KaleidaGraph</B><BR>

KaleidaGraph for Windows is a data analysis and graphing application that can transform complex data into attractive visual displays. KaleidaGraph features flexible data entry by using the keyboard or by opening a data file. KaleidaGraph has the ability to handle large data sets, and curve fitting. Works on Windows 95, NT, 3.1 & WFW 3.11. $249. Contact: Synergy Software, Reading, PA; (610) 779-0522.
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<ol>
<FONT SIZE=5>Back to SyllabusWeb <A HREF="index.html">Home Page</A></FONT>
