<HEAD>

<TITLE>February '97 Buyer's Guide</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Thursday, August 1, 1996  12:11 PM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Personal Computer/Workstation Technologies</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5><CENTER> A Buyer's Guide </CENTER></FONT>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<CENTER>A guide to the latest desktops, notebooks, and palmtops for the education market</CENTER>
<p>
<CENTER><A HREF="RS_list.html">click</A> here for free product information</CENTER>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<!-- Want RS numbers?? -->
<FONT SIZE=5>Computers and Workstations</FONT>
<P>
<B>Apple Power Macintosh 5400/120</B><br>
The Power Macintosh 5400/120 features the 120MHz PowerPC 603e processor and comes standard with 16MB of DRAM (expandable to 136MB), an internal 1.6GB hard disk drive, and Ethernet connection for high-speed networking. The Power Macintosh system features the Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) expansion bus architecture. It includes a built-in 15-inch color monitor, capable of displaying 32,000 colors, an AppleDesign keyboard, and mouse. $2,299 (education price). Contact: Apple Computer, Inc., Cupertino, CA; (408) 996-1010. Reader Service #30
<P>
<B>Compaq Presario ES</B><br>
The Presario ES, a multimedia PC for the education market, is the only Windows-based PC line sold standard with HyperStudio, a tool used by students and educators to create, design, and share multimedia projects and presentations. The Presario 4104ES includes the choice of a 14-inch or 15-inch multimedia monitor, featuring JBL Pro audio speakers and visual technology. The Presario 4406ES is easy to install into networked environments and upgrades to Fast Ethernet. Contact: Compaq Computer Corp., Houston, TX; (800) 88-TEACH. Reader service #31
<br>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<B>MicroFLEX-PCI/200</B><br>
The MicroFLEX-PCI/200 PC runs at 200MHz and is based on the Intel P200 CPU. It includes 16MB of EDO RAM, a 6X CD-ROM drive, a 1.2GB hard drive, and 16-bit sound speakers. The MicroFLEX includes the Award PnP Flash BIOS offering password protection and selectable shadowing of both systems and video BIOS. Plug-and-play BIOS allows autoconfiguration of all plug-and-play add-in cards, with Windows 95 and IBM compatibility. Contact: Micro Express, Irvine, CA; (800) 989-9900. Reader Service #33
<P>

<B>SGI 02</B><br>
The O2 desktop workstation line from Silicon Graphics features Unified Memory Architecture (UMA) and integrates advanced 3D graphics, image processing, video and compression capabilities with a 64-bit MIPS RISC microprocessor. It  includes Silicon Graphics' new version of UNIX-based operating system IRIX 6.3, which is background compatible, as well as a graphical user environment that integrates Internet and intranet publishing and file transfer capabilities. Contact: Silicon Graphics Computer Systems, Mtn.View, CA; (415) 960-1980. Reader Service #34
<P>
<B>Sony PCV-90</B><br>
The Sony PCV-90 is a high-end multimedia PC with audio and video capabilities. It is a constructed PC mini-tower that features a door that slides up and down to reveal the floppy disk and CD-ROM drives inside. The PCV-90 features a 200MHz Pentium processor, 32MB RAM, 2.5GB hard disk drive, a 28.8kb DSVD modem, "Sony Tuned" MPEG decoding, 8X CD-ROM drive and software. Contact: Sony Electronics, Park Ridge, NJ; (800) 472-SONY. Reader Service #35
<P>
<B>Sun Ultra Workstations</B><br>
The Sun Ultra Workstations' visual computing performance provides capabilities comparable to specialized graphics workstations costing twice as much. The Ultra architecture's graphic performance is due to the UPA and VIS technology, which is tightly integrated with Creator graphics. Creator graphics, the first graphics architecture based on 3D-RAM, provides high-performance graphics, and new media (video, 2D, and 3D imaging) capability. Contact: Sun Microsystems Computer Co., Mtn View, CA; (415) 960-1300. Reader Service #36
<P>

<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Notebooks and Palmtops</FONT>
<P>
<B>Apple eMate 300</B><br>
Designed as a companion to the Mac OS and Windows-based PCs in a distributed learning environment, eMate offers educators an affordable way to make technology accessible to more students. Weighing less than four pounds, the eMate provides dual input methods of a stylus and keyboard. It includes built-in menus that can be operated by touching the screen or through keyboard shortcuts. The eMate 300 features the Newton operating system and comes with Newton Works, a set of applications that includes a word processor, drawing program, spreadsheet, and graphing calculator. Contact: Apple Computer, Inc., Cupertino, CA; (408) 996-1010. Reader Service #37
<br>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<B>IBM ThinkPad 760</B><br>
The new ThinkPad models offer a 150MHz Pentium processor, 2.1GB, 6X CD-ROM 
drive, 12.1 TFT XGA color screens, and Microsoft's Windows NT 4.0 Workstation preload and support. The ThinkPad 760 series is designed as a desktop alternative notebook offering advanced multimedia features and high-end performance. The UltraBay allows for the addition of a second hard drive, second battery, or wireless communication device. Contact: IBM Corp., White Plains, NY; (800) 426-8322.   Reader Service #38
<P>
<B>Sharp PC-9030</B><br>
The 120MHz Intel Pentium-based PC-9030 includes 256 KBytes L2 cache and built-in math coprocessor. Equipped with high-brightness and low-power consumption Super High Aperture screen technology, modular 6X speed CD-ROM drive, and 16-bit Soundblaster PRO compatible sound card and stereo speakers. It ships with 1.1GB hard disk drive and 8MB of EDO memory, expandable to 64MB. Contact: Sharp Electronics Corp., Mahwah, NJ; (800) BE-SHARP. Reader Service #39
<P>
<B>HP Palmtop PC</B><br>
HP's new palmtop PC, expected to be available in mid-1997, will feature an 80-column, 640x240 LCD display, providing a comfortable view of documents with pages of standard width. It will support Microsoft Windows CE, a scalable Windows operating-system platform that enables users to access and share documents with their Windows-based notebook computers and desktop PCs. The new palmtop PC will feature automatic file synchronization with Windows 95 and Windows NT. Contact: Hewlett-Packard Co., Palo Alto, CA; (415) 857-1501. Reader Service #55
<P>
<B>Sparc64</B><br>
The SPARC64 is a part of the HALstation 300 series of workstations that are ideally suited for computer-intensive applications such as engineering analysis and design, scientific research, and financial modeling. With the 64-bit SPARC V9 architecture, the instruction unit can issue four instructions per cycle to eight functional execution units that operate in parallel. Runs on existing 32-bit Solaris binaries without modifcations; and supports all major open systems standards. Contact: HAL Computer Systems, Campbell, CA; (408) 379-7000. 
<P>
<B>Z-Station VP</B><br>
The Z-Station VP is a multimedia configured desktop computer and monitor with educational software. All Systems come with Windows 95 or Windows for Workgroups, Netscape Navigator, ten educational software titles, a 3.5-inch 1.44MB floppy drive, PCI local bus, a 64-bit video graphics controller, 1MB video DRAM (upgradable to 2MB), and an integrated multimedia kit including a 4X CD-ROM, 16-bit Soundblaster audio card, speakers, and microphone. Contact: Zenith Data Systems, Buffalo Grove, Ill; (847) 808-5000. 
<P>
<B>WinBook LM</B><br>
The new LM is the first WinBook with a 64-bit video accelerator and 128-bit graphics. It features a 150MHz Intel Pentium processor, 16MB EDO RAM, 256K synchburst cache, PCI-bus architecture, 1.0GB hard drive, 12.1-inch SVGA active-matrix color display, and 6X CD-ROM drive. The unit is designed with a dual-button touchpad centered in the palmrest and comes with a Windows 95 specific keyboard. Contact: WinBook Computer Corp., Hilliard, OH; (800) 468-2162. 
<P>
