<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>case studies</TITLE><!-- Date: Tuesday, June 4, 1996  1:20 PM --></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Case Studies</FONT></CENTER><P><CENTER>Following are case studies that illustrate the use of technology on campus.</CENTER><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><br><FONT SIZE=5>Asbury Theological Seminary</FONT><P>Full-Motion Video in the Classroom<BR><P><IMG SRC="images/asbury.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>The Asbury Theological Seminary in Wilmore, Kentucky is merging traditional missionary training with the latest video technology. Full-motion video is being used to teach theology and train future ministers and missionaries. The school incorporates distance learning, video, production studios, and laptop computers to deliver education. Every classroom includes a video information system control unit and monitor or projection system. All of the systems are connected via optical fiber to the video information system in a building dedicated to electronic creativity. An instructor can access DOS or Macintosh CD-ROM applications, VHS recorders, VCR equipment, still video and laser disc players, 16mm and 35mm slide to video machines, and satellite and CATV tuners.<BR>The school operates 48 electronically-equipped classrooms for distance learning that is spread over 14 buildings. The electronic creativity building houses tools for creating video content, a broadcast-quality video studio for local and distance learning, and specially-equipped graduate student study carrels allowing connections to campus resources and external information sources. In addition, notebook computers are used by practicing ministers and missionaries working as far away as Estonia and India who can access the network at any time.<BR><P>For more information, contact: Dr. Kenneth Boyd, Seminary College, Professor of Instructional Media Systems, Asbury Theological Seminary, (606) 858-2310.<BR><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Brigham Young University</FONT><P>Humanities Tutorials<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/BYU.GIF"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Professor Jon D. Green, in the humanities department at Brigham Young University, needed a new way to reach his humanities students. Green saw how most students would plow through a literary work without really deriving any pleasure from what they were studying. He observed that because the students did not directly experience what they were learning, they never really retained the material, and they didn't seem to get any lasting benefit from their courses.<BR>To help address this problem, Green introduced software-based instruction into his classroom. He began to offer his students software tutorials in order to stimulate their enjoyment of the humanities curriculum. Green has designed nine tutorials to help students understand the humanities in the areas of poetry, dance, music, opera, film, drama, sculpture, painting, and architecture. The tutorials are intended to help students develop the perceptual skills necessary to make sense of the works of art they learn about in his classes. The modules also give students access to additional information that can enhance their appreciation of a work of art.<BR>One of Professor Green's tutorials covers ballet, allowing students to review ballet steps by name and definition. Students are shown the steps and can creatively manipulate the moves of a given ballet sequence and create their own dance. Then, they can then actually see the dance performed. Once a student practices recognizing different ballet steps the whole dance comes alive. Professor Green says, "It's like learning a foreign language; it gradually makes sense as you learn the vocabulary." And that is Professor Green's goal: to make sense of the senses involved with experiencing the arts directly. Green recently completed a pilot disc to teach film editing techniques. It involves on-screen definitions and examples of the techniques (e.g., fade, dissolve, match cut) as well as opportunities for linking two shots on screen using different transition devices and actually linking together a series of different shots to create different narrative sequences. Green's film tutorial examines Alfred Hitchcock's classic thriller, The Birds. In the tutorial, students can drag and drop sequences from the movie in different order and combinations, creating their own film, and then compare it to Hitchcock's original by simply pressing a button. <BR>"This kind of learning, in which the terminology and definitions are linked to immediate on-screen examples, and where these new recognition skills can be applied in personally creative ways, opens up a whole new dimension of learning," Green says. <BR>Professor Green and his colleagues are developing the modules for publication, taking advantage of the cross-platform capabilities of Authorware as a development tool. They plan to publish the modules under the title: Exploring the Arts Interactively.<BR><p>For more information, contact: Professor Jon Green, Brigham Young University; (801) 378-2346 or access <A HREF="http://www.byu.edu">http://www.byu.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>California Polytechnic State University, San Luis Obispo</FONT><P>The MultiMedia Research Project has provided a venue for several innovative projects developed by students<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/calpoly.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>The MultiMedia Research Project (MMRP) is a student-organized project at California Polytechnic State University in San Luis Obispo. The Project, which has been on-going for the past six years, grew out of students' needs to bridge the gap between themselves and industry. A number of multimedia projects has emerged under the umbrella of MMRP. Students working on special multimedia projects relating to college course work now have access to a centralized lab, well-stocked with the latest equipment either donated or loaned from various corporate sponsors such as Gerber, NEC, Radius, Epson, Mitsubishi, and PowerComputing among others.<BR>Currently, the MMRP is pursuing three projects. One of them is the 3Dinitiative Project, which will demonstrate virtual applications with spatial sound and 3D approaches. By incorporating sight and sound, the viewer will participate in an immersive and realistic 3D experience via a head mounted display (HMD) with head tracking, a three-space input device and real-time 3D sound.<BR>Another project in place is the Universal Access Map Project. This interactive mapping system project will introduce a kiosk on-screen computing system. The kiosk will provide the most efficient and time saving directional information to the general public. This system will be used in areas such as schools, public buildings, amusement parks, museums, and airports. By incorporating the use of computer animation and video footage, the system will give a 3D orientation of proposed routes.<BR>The third project is the Sustainability Project. Since its inception in the Spring of 1995, the project has accumulated much attention for presenting a holistic methodology of designing structures that would conceivably never have a heating, cooling, or electrical bill and recycle 78% of all water used. The second phase of the project was completed in August that focused on exploring and enhancing the interface. The members of the Sustainability Project are currently working on the implementation of the third phase that will have a much improved interface structure and an increased level of complexity.<BR>In addition to a vast array of multimedia resources, the MMRP also showcases students' projects at various trade shows each year. The projects that have been created at the MultiMedia Research Project lab have been showcased at 42 trade shows including TeleCon, New Media, A/E/C, COMDEX, and INFOCOMM. Through this kind of exhibition, students are able to acquire not only hands-on experience with multimedia, but are able to showcase their ideas to others outside the university.<BR><p>For more information on the MMRP, contact Steve O'Driscoll-Packard or Shawn Jackman, Leadership Committee Members at (805) 756-1494, or access <A HREF="http://www.mmrp.calpoly.edu">http://www.mmrp.calpoly.edu</A>.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Case Western Reserve University</FONT><P>University Network  Instrumental Several Projects<BR><p>At Case Western Reserve University, the implementation of CWRUnet, a strictly fiber optic cable from the main wiring system, has enabled data, voice, and video transmissions. Some key CWRUnet projects have emerged, for example, first- and second-year medical students receive Macintosh PowerBooks as part of their tuition. The students can use their laptops to access the school's electronic syllabus and interactive educational software including A.D.A.M. <BR>Japanese language students have used the network to communicate with students in Waseda University in Japan. The program includes network-transmitted student profiles, complete with brief audio greetings in Japanese. <BR>The university also has CWRUnet-connected multimedia classrooms that allow faculty to activate off-site VCRs, slide viewers, film projectors, laser discs, audio tapes, or other devices with an infrared remote control. Cameras and microphones in one room enable two-way video conferencing. The incoming and outgoing signals pass through CWRUnet cables. In addition, many professors use the network to provide homework hints, with many files containing complex formulas and diagrams. Some faculty use CWRUnet to send video clips of "help sessions" to students who own a personal computer. Students and faculty also use e-mail, course-specific bulletin boards, and Web pages to continue class discussions. CWRU also uses its World Wide Web page as the main electronic gateway to campus information services, which offers one entry point to access to all campus information resources, including a software library, CD-ROM server, library servers, course evaluations, and event listings. The network offers access to the campus' on-line library catalog system, containing information on more than one million holdings, and more than 200 other electronic library catalogs. <br><p>For more information, contact Dr. Raymond Neff, Vice President for Information Services, (216) 368-2000 or access <A HREF="http://litwww.cwru.edu">http://litwww.cwru.edu</A> <P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Cogswell Polytechnical College</FONT><P>Music Engineering Technology Program<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/cogswell.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Many colleges offer Music Technology programs, but Cogswell Polytechnical College has a Music Engineering Technology (MusET) program, which is one of the first of its kind in the country. In 1989 the program began based on feedback from companies in the music industry that indicated a growing need for workers that are trained in electrical engineering and in music. The music engineering technology curriculum was designed in conjunction with a number of companies involved in the production of musical instrument manufacturing such as Yamaha and computer software companies including Apple Computer Inc. Most of the faculty had their start in music and then pursued careers focusing on the technology side. Many are from local companies within Silicon Valley. <BR>The MusET program focuses on understanding the mechanics of the technology used to produce the music rather than on producing the music with the technology. In addition, the idea behind the program is that students have a much easier time learning the electronics and digital theory when they see a direct connection to how electronic devices affect sound. Facilities at the school include 24-, 16-, and 8-track recording studios, using MIDI and digital audio systems for synchronous tape, digital recording, and audio for video post production. Students also have access to a 1,800 square-foot performance room with a stage. Individual classroom MIDI stations and sound design labs are also available. <BR>The nearly 70 students currently enrolled receive training in sound design, audio recording, digital signal processing, and MIDI (musical instrument digital interface) specification as well as in traditional electrical engineering training. The music technology component of the MusET program begins with a course in MIDI and then evolves to a series of courses covering the manipulation of sound. Courses in sound design explore traditional forms of music such as frequency modulation as well as new and experiemental forms of music. A series of audio recording courses exposes students to the problems encountered in the analog and digital recording studio environments. In conjunction with understanding the technology and its design, students also create and record music. Courses are also offered in Music Theory, Music History, and Music Literature. <BR>The majority of courses revolve around electronic engineering technology, including courses in Electronic Devices, Electronic Circuits, and Direct and Alternating Currents. In addition, students study computer science with classes in C, Pascal, and others languages. A series of courses in Digital Principles and Applications are offered in which students learn about binary data. Required electronics courses focus on the theory and design of computer cards that record, play back, and manipulate sound. Physics classes are also part of the curriculum and cover topics ranging from Newton's Laws to the Principles of Acoustics. The MusET students also have a variety of electives, from music business to sound reinforcement. <BR>For a senior project students are required to design and construct either a hardware device or a software program, depending on their degree specification. Past projects have included wireless MIDI systems, computer programs linking MIDI to graphics, and one recent projectin which the student designed a digital signal processor for a guitar.<BR><p>For more information, contact: Ted Henderson, Chair of the Music Engineering Technology Program, (408) 541-0100 or access <A HREF="http://www.cogswell.edu">http://www.cogswell.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Davidson County Community College</FONT><P>Nursing Education with Multimedia<BR><p>Prof. Patricia Shoemaker is using multimedia presentations to teach her nursing students at Davidson County Community College how to care for their patients. "We're trying to take a lecture format and change it into something that is more interactive," said Prof. Shoemaker. By incorporating a variety of images and sounds, she has taken the lecture beyond the traditional. <br>Prof. Shoemaker finds multimedia technology to be an effective teaching tool, especially in trying to convey complex information to non-traditional learners. "Some of us are auditory learners while others are visual learners, and by incorporating sounds and images the visual learners are given a greater opportunity to understand and enjoy the material," she says.<BR>For her multimedia lectures, Prof.  Shoemaker uses Intel's Smart Video Recorder technology, which allows her to capture images from either video tape or video disks. The images can then be edited and imported into Microsoft's PowerPoint presentation program. The presentations are then transferred to disk and displayed on an LCD projector. <BR>In a class section about the eye, Professor Shoemaker's students view videos that show pupils of differing sizes, illustrating normal and abnormal pupil sizes. Shoemaker also uses video of otoscope images to demonstrate the diagnosis of an ear infection. She uses digitized audio to identify and compare varying degrees of abnormality in heart rhythms.<BR>Prof. Shoemaker will do further work with digitized video and plans to digitize the voice of the instructor so that students can listen to the entire lecture at their own pace. She hopes to produce the course on CD-ROM so that students can individually review the areas for which they need more study or be able to move on after they have mastered a topic. <br><p>For more information, contact: Professor Patricia Shoemaker, Chair, Health Technology Division, Davidson County Community College, Lexington, N.C.; (704) 249-8186.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>University of Delaware</FONT><P>FOCUS-Distance Learning Program Involves 28 Academic Departments<BR><p>At the University of Delaware, several projects have grown out of the university's FOCUS distance learning program. The program has involved 28 academic departments, produced nearly 100 distance learning courses, offered two degree programs, and received 1,722 enrollments in 12 states. Its use of multiple technologies includes videotable, cable, satellite, compressed video, and interactive television. Each semester, more than 10 percent of the university's faculty teach in video and distance learning environments in the Colleges of Nursing, Arts and Science, Engineering and Human Resources, and in University Media Services, and the Division of Continuing Education. <BR>UD has utilized video in a variety of ways. It has established two-way, interactive connections among the campuses of Newark, Lewes, and Georgetown. Videotape course delivery is available to off-campus students and is used in video broadcasts over the Mind Extension University (ME/U) cable channel and a variety of satellite links. Classes, seminars, conferences, and meetings are available to students at work sites, other universities, and other facilities.<BR><p>For more information, contact Dr. Richard Fischer, associate provost, continuing and distance education, (302) 831-2795,<A HREF="mailto:Richard.Fisher@mvs.udel.edu">Richard.Fisher@mvs.udel.edu</A> or access <A HREF="http://www.udel.edu">http://www.udel.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University</FONT><P>Optical Storage of Student Records<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/EMBRYRIDDLE.GIF"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University, a leader in aviation and aerospace education, typically enrolls 5,500 students at residential campuses in Daytona Beach, Fla., and Prescott, Ariz. More than 12,000 students pursue courses in the evening and on weekends through 114 off-campus locations throughout the U.S. and Europe, as well as through computerized instruction linked to the residential campuses. <BR>In an effort to implement a more cost-effective method for storage and retrieval of student registration and flight data records, and to reduce the use of paper, two departments at Embry-Riddle's Daytona Beach campus and one at its Extended Campus headquarters have implemented optical storage solutions. This will replace antiquated microfiche and paper records-systems that used to reside in an 80' x 80' room. "With the same staff, we're able to give better customer support and quicker turnaround time when records are requested. With the old paper system it would take a clerk or student assistant at least 10 minutes to retrieve a student's file," said Danette Moorhead, Manager of User Services and Information Technology. <BR>Last Year, Embry-Riddle's Flight Training Department turned to an optical storage solution to improve compliance with Federal Aviation Administration regulations, which require that each student's records be readily available for review while the student is enrolled, and for two years after graduation. The FAA also requires that every hour of a student's training, both in the classroom and in the air, be documented. In addition, the school keeps flight records on file for up to two years for students who have attended the university but have since left.<BR>Flight records, which are requested daily, contain information such as the flight instructor's evaluation for each flight, comments about student test scores, and information and comments from instructors on the more than 20 different flight courses required for graduation.  <BR>Embry-Riddle chose to organize its vast collection of flight records using a system comprised of a Hewlett-Packard SureStore Optical 20xt LAN Jukebox, a Fujitsu 3096 scanner, a Kofax 9250 card, ImageFiler software from Optika Imaging Inc., and a high-speed laser printer. With the old paper-based storage system, numerous documents for every currently enrolled flight student, and for graduates or released students for two years, were housed in individual hard files. At the end of a student's training a typical file would contain 50 documents. <BR>Using optical jukeboxes has simplified retrieval of records for both the clerks and the flight instructors who utilize the jukeboxes daily. Instructors can now access and quickly browse records right from their workstations by typing in a student's ID number. In the future, the university has plans to use optical jukeboxes for the registration process as well. <BR><p>For more information, contact: Danette Moorhead, Manager of User Services and Information Technology, Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University, Daytona, FL; (904) 226-6407 or access <A HREF="http://www.db.erau.edu">http://www.db.erau.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Georgia Institute of Technology</FONT><P>Interactive Media Technology Center<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/cseye.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>A number of multimedia projects have emerged under the umbrella of Georgia Tech's Interactive Media Technology Center (IMTC). IMTC is a research center under Georgia Tech's Office of Interdisciplinary Programs. Under the direction of Mike Sinclair, Senior Research Engineer, the center has many projects underway incorporating technology, including multimedia medical simulations and research in the study of human movement.<BR>Collaborating with the Medical College of Georgia and the Bioengineering Research Center, IMTC has developed a 3D simulation of surgery on an organic-looking eyeball. Eye Surgery Simulator is a device incorporating virtual reality to simulate the look and feel of eye surgery. The simulator incorporates photo-realistic images of the anterior segment of the eye derived from photographs of bank eyes. The simulator has linear tactile feedback for real-time feel of tool-tissue interaction. The haptic information was based on a model derived from data gathered by monitoring surgical tool forces during procedures performed on a bank eye at the Medical College of Georgia. According to Sinclair, "With the Eye Surgery Simulator, students can practice an operation, such as cataract removal or lens replacement, many times a day; whereas, before students could practice such surgery only a few times a week."<BR>A primary benefit of the simulator is to provide medical students and practicing surgeons with an environment for recursive and time-critical training. The simulator will be used to practice eye surgery in time-critical scenarios and give users the opportunity to learn how to perform under intense pressure. The simulator will also enhance anatomical navigation skills and hand/eye coordination. <BR>The Eye Surgery Simulator consists of a Silicon Graphics Onyx computer, an ophthalmic workstation, a three-axis tactile system, 3D stereoscopic viewer, and virtual instruments including a scalpel, scissors, forceps, and phaco emulsifier. The operating station for the simulator has the viewer interacting with a 3D virtual eye using a virtual surgical instrument controlled by a handheld 6D tracking stylus. Information concerning position and orientation is provided to the computer. The tip of the stylus is connected by thin rigid bars to three torque motors that generate component force feedback in response to the instrument's interaction with virtual tissue. <BR>"The new technology has an array of benefits to medical students including reduced use of cadavers and animals, rare surgical complications can now be part of routine training, and especially difficult surgery can be rehearsed before operating on a patient," says Sinclair. <BR>In addition, the technology gives students the capability to view or review a procedure from several perspectives, including from inside the eye to see if cuts were made at the correct depth and proper angle.<BR>Another application in collaboration with the Bioengineering Research Center and MCG is the Endoscopic Retrograde Choloangio-Pancreatography (ERCP) Surgical Simulator, which replicates an endoscopic procedure in a virtual environment. This application allows medical students to use virtual reality to simulate looking inside a patient's body. The simulation consists of a virtual patient, into which an endoscope is inserted and its position tracked. "It gives students a birds-eye view that would otherwise not be possible with a cadaver or mannequin," says Sinclair. The simulator provides tactile feedback, including both pressure and motion. A real-time view from the endoscope and a view from inside the organ are then rendered on a graphics-intensive computer and presented on a monitor, much like that used in an operating room.<BR>Another project currently underway is the Remote Palpation Simulator. The project will allow doctors to examine patients in remote locations via telecommunications. It employs a six-axis robot arm with a tactile input sensor as the end-effector and a virtual abdomen consisting of skin and a tactile output matrix.<BR>IMTC also is involved in the technology of human motion capture, analysis, modeling, and visualization. A software tool developed at IMTC called Motion Interactive is being used to study dance, and a variety of sports such as diving and the study of various offensive and defensive maneuvers in team handball and hockey. Sinclair explains, "The application provides a time-ordered list of 3D coordinates as if you were documenting a puppet's movement." Researchers can observe any form of human movement to study optimal scenarios such as documenting the power of impact and velocity of a tennis racket when striking a tennis ball.<BR>The Dance Technology Project, a collaboration among IMTC, Georgia Tech Theater, and the Atlanta Ballet, is researching new and innovative ways to integrate technology and the arts, specifically dance. The project's premier performance entitled "Non Sequitur" featured a ballerina performing a dance with an animated virtual dancer. Another project, entitled "Springing Grass," consisted of dancers who wore infrared emitters that were detected by infrared cameras. The results were animated particle trails of the dancer's hand movements on a nearby scrim that illustrate the precise hand and arm positions of the dancer. Future developments will include real-time dancer costuming via projected computer animation onto the live dancers at the Olympic ceremonies this summer.<BR><p>For more information, contact Mike Sinclair, Director of the Interactive Media Technology Center and Senior Research Engineer,<A HREF="mailto:michael.sinclair@oip.gatech.edu">michael.sinclair@oip.gatech.edus</A>. The home page of the Georgia Institute of Technology can be accessed at <A HREF="http://gatech.edu/TechHome.html">http://gatech.edu/TechHome.html</A> and IMTC can be accessed at <A HREF="http://www.oip.gatech.edu/imtc.html">http://www.oip.gatech.edu/imtc.html</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Indiana University</FONT><P>Compaq Testing Lab Simulates University's Conditions To Determine Computer Network Needs	<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/IU.MUSIC.GIF"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>The Bloomington campus of Indiana University was confronted with a problem common to today's computer-rich campuses: its University Computing Services department needed to grow its computer network to better serve the school's faculty, staff, and students.<BR>Part of the enormous growth in computer automation can be attributed to the university's innovative Student Locker system, which gives students access to a home directory service. In their home directories, students can store electronic data rather than carry files around on floppy disks. Each of the 35,000 undergraduate and graduate students can access this service via the university's Public Computing Facilities sites, some 1,000 workstations throughout the campus.  Students with their own PCs can also access the Student Locker home directory service through network connections in many of the student residence halls.<BR>In addition, about 6,000 faculty and staff access a variety of network services through an additional 10,000 network-connected devices located across the campus. "We were stretching our old timesharing systems to meet the computer needs of students, faculty, and staff," says Indiana's principal hardware engineer, John Naab.  <BR>Interested in evaluating the Compaq ProLiant 2000R server, Naab and network systems engineer, Lance Speelmon traveled to the Compaq LAN Test Facility at the company's headquarters in Houston, Texas, where ProLiant servers were tested under Indiana campus configurations.<BR>The simulation helped predict networking needs. "We learned that we needed to split the faculty/staff system in two: one server for messaging support, another for general-purpose file and applications serving," says Speelmon. "By using Novell NetWare 4.1 Directory Services, we can consolidate the staff and faculty needs into one shared Virtual LAN environment, which reduces overhead support requirements."<BR>Both Naab and Speelmon envision a future network that, in addition to the Bloomington campus, connects all eight Indiana University campuses to these services.<BR><p>For more information, contact John Naab, Principal Hardware Engineer, (812) 855-4848 or access <A HREF="http://www.indiana.edu">http://www.indiana.edu</A>.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Indiana University, Bloomington</FONT><P>Multimedia Music Library<BR><p>Indiana University's School of Music will open a new multimedia library in December. Called the Variations Music Information System, the library will make all of the resources reserved for music courses available via digitized audio and full-motion video to all students and faculty on the campus. Users can access information on library resources as well as play back and edit musical scores. Currently under construction, the 55,000-square foot library will include digitized analog sound files which users will play on local workstations and over the campus network.<BR>Already ranked as one of the top music libraries in the country, Indiana University at Bloomington has an extensive collection that includes more than 600,000 books, microfilms, periodicals, and recordings. Scores include 8,000 orchestra scores, 14,000 chamber music scores and parts, and 5,000 opera scores, including some of the first or early editions of these forms of music.Through the project, 140 faculty members and a student body of more than 1,400 students will have complete access to 300 items on course reserve in a digital format as well as full-motion video associated with some music works.  Users can access and interact with the system using workstations equipped with piano keyboards at the library's Media Lab. The lab currently houses 10 workstations, but eventually will have 130, all equipped with piano keyboards. <BR>The Variations project will also have databases of sound and score files that can be retrieved by 100 workstations located throughout the library for the public, with the future capability for 250 additional workstations. The system uses full-motion video and CD-quality audio.<BR>The Variations project will have editing room facilities for creating multimedia projects that support the creation of music notation and the manipulation of sound. The editing room will give students a means to create multimedia projects and have better access for research purposes. Students can insert their own works or the works of others into multimedia presentations consisting of text, sounds, graphics, and full-motion video.In addition to distributing course reserve materials, the project is intended to develop score databases, and provide real-time digitization of analog sources for each student's individual request, allowing them to interactively control the multimedia resources. The project allows retrieval of data sources in all information formats including, text, sound, full-motion video, and graphics.<BR>Currently, the project, in beta, is set-up in the Music Library and Recital Hall Building, but soon the high-speed audio/video network will be distributed to all parts of the Bloomington campus, and  by December 1995 at Indiana University's Purdue campus. Instructors will be able to access materials for classroom use right from their computers.<BR><p>For more information, contact: Dr. David Fenske, Chief Librarian, School of Music, Indiana University, Bloomington; (812) 855-2970 or access <A HREF="http://www.variations.edu">http://www.variations.edu</A>. <A HREF="http://www.-iub.indiana.edu">http://www.-iub.indiana.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Iowa State University</FONT><P>Revitalizing the Undergraduate Biology Curriculum<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/ISU.GIF"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>A little more than four years ago, a commitment was made at Iowa State University to redesign the undergraduate core biology curriculum, and a large part of this effort included the development of a variety of ways to utilize technology in instruction. <BR>The first step in developing a technology infrastructure to support proposed changes in curriculum was the creation of microcomputer facilities. The facilities, staffed with undergraduate assistants, currently house 55 Macintoshes and 21 DOS machines, and are open 60 hours per week. The project received financial support from a Howard Hughes Medical Institute (HHMI) undergraduate grant.<BR>Warren Dolphin, Biology Project administrator in the biology department at Iowa State, explains how faculty built a strategy for using the new technology to solve teaching problems: "As experience was gained in operating the computer labs, giving computer assignments in courses, and teaching the new curriculum, faculty began to ask why students had difficulty in introductory biology." While lecturers in biology traditionally use audiovisuals as well as verbal descriptions of processes, such presentations are ephemeral, lasting only for the lecture period with the students' notes and the textbook as the only records for later study, Dolphin explains. "Several faculty thought that there should be a provision for allowing students to review materials, especially diagrams and pictures. What they needed was a system that could be adopted to allow a thousand or more students to access different lectures at virtually any hour of the day with the possibility of simultaneous access for multiple users from several campus sites."<BR>Iowa State has a highly developed ethernet capability. The solution was to create a large file of biological images on a server where they would be accessible over the network for lecturers to use in creating lectures. The same sytems could be used to make the lectures network-accessible for students.<BR>An image capture facility allows faculty to take a photograph, Kodachrome slide, microscope slide, or any video image and from it create a digital image. An animation development group was also formed, and has produced approximately 40 animations of biological concepts. Being produced in-house, these animations are developed with guidance from content-expert faculty, and are customized for easy use in lectures and in computer labs. <BR>The images are stored on 2.4GB hard drive, which will hold 15,000 images. Currently, there are approximately 5,500 stored images which are indexed by Kudo software. The drive is connected to a restricted server computer which is network accessible 24 hours per day, seven days per week. Any instructor with access privileges can download these images into a Macintosh computer from any network location on campus. This allows teaching staff, scattered throughout five different buildings, to have unlimited access to resource materials for lecture development. Because participating faculty often contribute personal slide collections and other visual materials, the common image bank fosters sharing of teaching materials among a number of lecturers in the beginning courses. <BR>With funds from the HHMI grant, seven PowerBook computers were purchased and loaned to biology instructors. PowerPoint presentation software was installed on the laptops and the instructional technologist conducted workshops to train faculty. With these tools, faculty create visually attractive electronic "slide shows" with images imported from the image bank on the file server and integrate the images with text and tables entered through the keyboard. <BR>Completed lectures are sent over the AppleShare campus network to a built-in computer in the lecture hall. Instructors go to the lecture hall without carrying cumbersome audiovisual materials, simply turn on the ceiling RGB projector, and boot up their materials for lecture delivery. Because the file server is permanently networked, lecturers can also use the Internet in class to call up data sets, or they can intersperse dynamic simulations with the slide show software. <BR>After class, instructors download their lectures to the biology file server. Once deposited, lectures are available for the rest of the semester through any of the hundreds of Macintosh computers on campus that are connected via ethernet. The storage capacity allows banking of about 12 sets of 40 lectures for an entire semester. Instructors adopted the system in general biology, embryology, medical entomology, microbiology, genetics, and general zoology. At the end of a semester, lectures are removed from the hard drive and stored on an archival data tape. When an instructor teaches the course again, lectures can be removed from the archives, modified as needed, and then placed back on the server. This also provides a mechanism for lecturers to share materials. Over time, the department expects to accumulate a set of model lectures that can be modified by individuals who teach the core courses for the first time, thus reducing the tedious side of teaching while allowing for individual creativity. <BR>Computers are also being incorporated into the labs. Students use spreadsheets and graphing programs to analyze data, and all lab reports must be prepared with a word processor. The department uses simulation programs that model complex phenomena such as food chains in aquatic ecosystems, microevolution, and photosynthesis. Students also complete assignments in which they use the Internet. For example, 350 students were asked to use the Internet (via Mosaic) to access a server at the Australian National Botanical Gardens. From a computer on a distant continent, freshman biology students in Ames, Iowa accessed and printed information about the flora of Australia. In fifteen minutes, not only did these students learn a few botanical facts, they also learned how small the world can be using the powerful connectivity facilitated by technology. <BR>Mark Windschitl, the instructional coordinator for biology, comments on how the teaching of biology at Iowa State has changed with the introduction of technology: "We have found that the new technologies have forced us to re-examine what, for decades, has been the norm in how we communicate with students. Our experience clearly demonstrates that as technology becomes integrated into the academic culture, what was once experimental evolves into a highly effective design for productive and powerful learning."<BR><p>For more information, contact: Mark Windschitl or Warren D. Dolphin, 201 Bessey Hall, Iowa State University, Ames, Iowa 50011; (515) 294-4911 or access <A HREF="http://www.iastate.edu">http://www.iastate.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Ithaca College and the University of Georgia</FONT><P>Students at Two Institutions Focus Their Attentions on the 1996 Campaign<BR><p>A moderated electronic National Issues Forum, entitled "How Do We Want to Govern America?" is planned for the 1996 campaign season in the fall term at Ithaca College and the University of Georgia. This e-forum is the second experiment connecting students in New York and Georgia by Dr. Jill Swenson at Ithaca College and Dr. Margaret Holt and Dr. Pam Kleiber at the University of Georgia. In Fall 1994, their classes came together in cyberspace to deliberate "People and Politics: Who Should Govern?" <BR>Dr. Swenson remarks, "There is a tremendous sense of disconnection between the public and politics, between the politicians and the press, and between the press and the public. The electronic forum will give student-citizens and student-journalists an opportunity to deliberate in discussions about how we want to govern ourselves."<BR>At Ithaca College in upstate New York, junior and senior journalism students will enroll in a special topics course about campaign coverage with Prof. Swenson this August. Students will critique campaign coverage and consider the methods of public journalism, sometimes called civic journalism and community journalism. An additional seminar of 15 students enrolled in "Issues and the News" will build partnerships with co-curricular and community news media. Students will explore how to improve news coverage of the campaigns. The electronic forum will be used to help students develop new techniques for reporting campaign issues for the college community. The electronic forum will serve as an easily accessible instructional supplement to the classroom via its widely available technology and software.  Swenson says, "With easy and inexpensive access to a computer terminal where students can retrieve e-mail messages, a simple listserv provides the necessary support for moderators and participants who wish to participate in electronic study circles."<BR>The National Issues Forum-Listserv will be organized around a set of readings prepared by the National Issues Forum for August 1996 publication release and titled, "How Do We Want to Govern America?" The non-partisan materials spell out several choices and present various perspectives and positions in debate about the issue or topic. And as Prof. Swenson asserts,  "The point is not to debate about candidates but instead talk about the issues. Issues are more than personalities, policies, partisan conflicts, and events." <br><p>For more information, contact Jill Swenson, Associate Professor, Department of Television-Radio, (607) 274-3632 , e-mail <A HREF="mailto:swenson@ithaca.edu">swenson@ithaca.edu</A>, or access <A HREF="http://www.journalism.wisc.edu/cpn/sections/tools/manuals/electronic_handbook1.html">http://www.journalism.wisc.edu/cpn/sections/tools/manuals/electronic_handbook1.html</A> or access <A HREF="http://www.ithaca.edu or http://www.ug.edu">http://www.ithaca.edu or http://www.ug.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Mary Washington College</FONT><P>Internet Instruction by Example<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/mwc.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Dr. Ernest Ackermann, a professor in the Department of Computer Science at Mary Washington College in Fredericksburg, Va., teaches classes and workshops in how to use the Internet. After reviewing all the textbooks on the market, Ackermann found many good books on using the Internet, but did not find one that stressed step-by-step examples and exercises. So, he wrote a book, Learning to Use the Internet; An Introduction with Examples and Exercises, published by Franklin, Beedle, and Associates, to support his classes.<BR>The book features simple "how-to" instructions on the basics of using the Internet, including highlighted sections showing what users would see on the screen, as well as abundant examples and exercises for students to try. The book contains engaging examples and illustrations to keep students' interest.One problem Ackermann anticipated was that with the rapid pace of change on the Internet, much of the information in any printed book about the network can become quickly outdated. So, instead of including supplementary materials on a CD-ROM, Ackermann maintains a Web site to provide updated information for the book. The Web site mirrors the organization of the book, so that users can easily locate information pertinent to a given section of the book.<BR>The book, available since this past spring, has been used  for classes in more than 100 colleges and universities. Ackermann has also developed a teacher's manual to help faculty design tests and assignments, but it will probably not be available on the Internet, given the possibility that students might be able to locate answers through the network.<BR><p>For more information, visit Ackermann's Web site at <A HREF="http://www.mwc.edu/ernie">http://www.mwc.edu/ernie</A> or contact: Dr. Ernest Ackermann, Mary Washington College, (540) 654-1320; e-mail <A HREF="mailto:ernie@oregano.mwc.edu">ernie@oregano.mwc.edu</A>. The College's Home page is <A HREF="http://www.mwc.edu">http://www.mwc.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Mississippi State University</FONT><P>Computer Visualization within the Design Studio<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/msstate.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Architecture students at Mississippi State University enjoy state-of-the art virtual walkthroughs of their design projects. Established in late 1993 in collaboration with the MSU/National Science Foundation Engineering Research Center for Computational Field Simulation (ERC), the thrust of the Visually-Coupled Architectural Walkthrough Program is to provide students with the ability to visually experience moving through and around the building and site designs they produce on their laptops, as though these models were actually constructed.<BR>The current implementation of the program calls for students to regularly transfer their 3D CAD models over the campus computer network to an online storage facility at the ERC. This is most frequently accomplished using the network "docking stations" provided within the architecture building. Then, at a scheduled time, the students and design studio instructors gather in the computer visualization classroom at the ERC.<BR>One by one, a member of the project staff imports the student models into a custom-written, high-performance simulation program. This program, which is run on a Silicon Graphics ONYX graphics supercomputer, generates the real-time, high-resolution stereo imagery of the students' CAD models. These images are presented to the students through a display device known as the BOOM (Binocular Omni-Orientation Monitor). As opposed to a standard desktop or laptop computer monitor, this device allows the user to physically move through the design while looking up, down, side to side, and so on, as though he or she were actually  inside of the building or structure. With simple on-the-fly adjustments to the software controlling the simulation, one can vary the scale of the model, lighting characteristics, and numerous other features that affect the visual appearance of the simulation.<BR>The stereo imagery of a student flythrough is concurrently displayed on an 8' x 10' wall screen using a large, full-color, ceiling-mounted projection system. These stereo images are viewed by the other students and faculty  through inexpensive stereo glasses. These full-motion stereo images are also recorded on VHS videotape for evaluation at a later time, as well as in stereo snapshots of particular views found during a flythrough.<BR>These simulation capabilities are used throughout the entire course of a design project, from concept to final design inspection and presentation. Observations by the faculty and project staff, as well as directly from the students, show that in many cases students have gained a higher understanding of their designs, resulting in better thought out, more refined, end products.<BR>In order to further exploit the usefulness of this visualization technique, researchers have developed a lower-end, PC-based visualization system which can be signed out of the architecture library by students and used at their desks in the design studio. Such a system allows students to rapidly evaluate their early conceptual designs without the burden of having to go across campus to the ERC just for a quick look. As the design project progresses and model complexity grows beyond the capabilities of the low-end system, the students can move up to the high-performance system currently in use.<BR><p>You can visit the MSU VR program web page at <A HREF="http://www.erc.msstate.edu/scivi/vr">http://www.erc.msstate.edu/scivi/vr</A>. For more information, contact Steven Aukstakalnis, Department of Architecture, Mississippi State University, (601) 325-2131 or <A HREF="http://www.msstate.edu">http://www.msstate.edu</A>.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>North Carolina School of Science and Mathematics</FONT><P>Advanced High School Students Learn Calculus via Distance Learning<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/vimscs.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Last fall, the mathematics department at the North Carolina School of Science and Mathematics in Durham, N.C., began offering calculus to advanced high school students at two remote sites. The distance learning course, which was launched by Professor John Goebel, was designed to provide advanced placement students with an education matching their capabilities. Among the 20 students who were qualified to take upper level courses, eight students chose the distance learning calculus course offered at North Carolina School of Science and Mathematics, and a handful chose to commute to attend a college course. Two chose to not take any mathematics at all, resigned to accept a curriculum that didn't match their capabilities for mathematics.Students attending the calculus course via the Internet participate in labs and carry out investigations that lead to the discovery of the important calculus concepts needed in order to solve real problems.<BR>Mathcad mathematics software from MathSoft Inc. is used in the course. Prof. Goebel chose the software for its numerical, graphical, and symbolical capabilities, as well as for its interactive e-mail and Internet connectivity. Students turn in assignments that incorporate integrated text, equations, and graphics capabilities. "The students do a lot of writing in the course to explain how they reached particular solutions to assigned calculus problems. Mathcad software provides a way for students to turn in text, files, and graphs all in one document," says Goebel. <BR><p>For more information, contact Professor John Goebel, Mathematics Department, (919) 286-3366 or access <A HREF="http://www.ncssm.edu">http://www.ncssm.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>North Carolina State University</FONT><P>Cyberspace Study Aid for Materials Science<BR><p>Beginning students in materials science at North Carolina State University's engineering department are using an interactive Web site as a virtual laboratory to help them visualize concepts. The project is the brainchild of Dr. John Russ, a visiting professor and research associate in materials science and engineering, and grew out of his belief that students need a more visual approach to understanding difficult scientific concepts. In the past, students had to rely on their imaginations to visualize a 3D molecule from a 2D textbook rendition or chalkboard display. But Dr. Russ says that better alternatives are available in the computer age.<BR>The project originated in 1991 as a  self-paced study aid and supplemental tool for materials engineering students. Dr. Russ later developed Macintosh and Windows CD-ROM versions entitled "Visualizations in Materials Science" (ViMS). As the modules increased, Russ and some of his students developed an accompanying textbook and used HyperCard to facilitate access to the modules. A second version of ViMS was created in 1994 that integrated Theorist from Waterloo Maple Software in Waterloo, Canada to add interactive math capabilities.<BR>In the summer and fall of 1995, with interest in the World Wide Web on the rise, Dr. Russ and his students converted the original HyperCard script to HTML. Today, ViMS has evolved into a cyberspace study aid available to all students taking introductory engineering classes as well as anyone visiting the Web site at NCSU. ViMSweb contains more than 300 worked problems, 700 movies, and 1,500 document pages with hundreds of QuickTime movies, cartoons, animations, simulations, and digitized video clips combined with a highly interactive interface.<BR>The ViMSweb is laid out textbook-style, with chapters and tutorial explanations in the form of interactive notebooks for use with the Maple's "Click & Solve" mathematics package, Theorist. Students can view text, work out problems, and see real-time video clips and animations covering topics in materials science. With the Theorist application, students have the capability to enter values of variables, substitute variables by clicking and dragging, and solve and plot equations. The study aid focuses on the key concepts and methods of solving a problem, rather than presenting rote procedures for attaining a correct response. This allows students to proceed with a strong theoretical background through a difficult course.<BR>Brent Neal, a student who helped with the project, says, "Engineering concepts are so difficult that if a student falls off the train, it's hard to get back on." The ViMSweb study aid is self paced and can be accessed at any time. "There is a strong feeling of having a private tutor available as you use the materials," says Prof. Russ. Comments in the problems help students understand how to approach new situations and avoid common pitfalls. A "Pop-Up Professor" icon liberally sprinkled throughout the various pages offers interesting insights and comments designed to keep student interest high.<BR>A CD-ROM version is also available, containing an interactive hypertext guide that has cross-references to six of the principal textbooks most commonly used in introductory-level materials sciences courses. The CD-ROM is available from PWS Publishing Co. in Boston, Mass.<BR><p>For more information, visit ViMSweb at <A HREF="http://vims.ncsu.edu">http://vims.ncsu.edu</A>, or contact Dr. John Russ, adjunct professor in materials science and engineering, North Carolina State University; e-mail:<A HREF="mailto:john_russ@ncsu.edu">john_russ@ncsu.edu</A>.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Ohio State University</FONT><P>Faculty are developing multimedia applications to help students learn difficult engineering and architectural concepts<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/csohio.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>At Ohio State University (OSU), instructors are developing applications that teach a variety of engineering and architectural concepts. Professor Brooks Breeden from the department of architecture developed MacLARCH for Macintosh and WinLARCH for Windows using Macromedia's Authorware Professional. The courseware modules were designed to help students learn how to solve construction problems in civil engineering and landscape architecture. The application illustrates topics such as road alignment, property traverse surveying, and earthwork cut and fill. Each subject features an interactive presentation with color animation and diagrams, followed by sets of questions about the topic. Short QuickTime movies are used to animate elements such as contour definition. The content is presented in several different formats. One format is a self-test "drill and practice" in which the program randomly generates exercises about a particular topic, and allows the student to choose: "work one for me" or "let me work one."<BR>Another project emerged out of OSU's participation in the NSF-funded Gateway Coalition, Breeden teamed up with Professor George Staab to produce a set of tutorials that focus on engineering mechanics. Their work has resulted in the software that accompanies McGraw-Hill's recent publication of Beer and Johnston's Vector Mechanics for Engineers: Statics. They are now working on software to accompany the companion volume: Vector Mechanics for Engineers: Dynamics, scheduled for publication in Autumn, 1996.According to Breeden, "the programs are especially adept at accurately displaying problems in terms of size and scale." Using Authorware's intuitive display tools, instructors can easily set up and animate a problem, using more than one display if necessary.<BR>Breeden says the increasing ease of use of multimedia products is leading more faculty to participate more closely in the development process. "In the past, multimedia presentations and computer-assisted instructional courseware were programmed by graduate students. Now that more powerful development tools are available, we're seeing more faculty participation in the actual creative development process. With Authorware, we can design applications as we develop them. It's a perfect example of object-based programming-you can fine-tune parts of a course, and stop and start the portion you're working on without having to recompile the program between runs."<BR>Breeden and Professor John Simpson, who teaches landscape architecture at the university, also used Authorware to create "Ethical Dilemmas in Environmental Stewardship," which explores issues such as overfishing, the arms race, and feeding starving populations as well as other social dilemmas related to the environment.<BR><p>For more information, contact Professor J. Brooks Breeden,<A HREF="mailto:breeden.1@osu.edu">breeden.1@osu.edu</A> or (614) 292-8338; or contact Professor George Staab,<A HREF="mailto:staab.1@osu.edu">staab.1@osu.edu</A> or (614) 292-7920 or access <A HREF="http://www.acs.ohio-state.edu">http://www.acs.ohio-state.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Oklahoma State University</FONT><P>      German by Satellite<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/oklacs.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Many high schools, especially in rural areas, face a dilemma: how to give their students the kind of rich German language instruction that is required to meet legislative demands without having specially trained instructors on the faculty. Providing a solution to the problem is the German by Satellite (GBS) program, which uses distance learning techniques combined with computer-based and computer-assisted instruction that is designed to give students at high schools without a German teacher a college preparatory education that otherwise would not be possible.<BR> GBS, created by Professor Harry Wohlert of Oklahoma State University, stretches one semester of college German into a one-year high school course. Schools participating in the program receive twice-a-week broadcasts from Wohlert that stress student-teacher interaction. The broadcasts are a fast-paced sequence of lecture, speaking, and listening practice based on authentic German material and cultural vignettes. To accommodate the fact that an audience loses concentration periodically-even a class that is interested in the subject material-the broadcasts include frequent breaks that consist of German commercials and cultural material. These breaks provide a mental pause for students, while continuing to focus on the subject matter.Hundreds of schools across the country participate in the broadcasts, with one or two schools volunteering as hosts for each session, working interactively with Professor Wohlert either at the television studio at Oklahoma State, or through a two-way audio system.  <BR>On the three weekly non-broadcast days, the GBS program calls for students to work with computer programs, textbooks, vocabulary quizzes, chapter tests, and other instructional materials. Students are continually involved in language practice, far longer than is possible in a conventional classroom setting, says Wohlert. Instruction can be delivered by teachers who do not know how to speak German. For assistance, students at participating schools can call a toll-free number, eight hours a day, to reach a native German-speaking instructor.<BR>GBS integrates computer technology into the curriculum in several ways. For vocabulary practice, GBS uses Macintosh computers with digitized speech. To check pronunciation, students use a speech recognition program that compares their input with that of native German speakers.<BR>To deliver instruction to advanced students and to those needing extra help, Professor Wohlert uses a Macintosh computer with Creative Technology Ltd.'s ShareView Plus collaborative computing system, which allows transfer between computers of audio, video, and data over normal copper wire telephone lines. With the system, Professor Wohlert can interact with his students as if they were in the same room with him, allowing him to use one-on-one teaching methods.<br><p> For more information contact: Professor Harry Wohlert, Oklahoma State University, Stillwater, OK; (405) 744-7109 or <A HREF="http://pio.okstate.edu">http://pio.okstate.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Old Dominion University</FONT><P>TELETECHNET<BR><p>At Old Dominion University in Norfolk, VA, students can take part in one of the largest distance learning programs in the U.S. The program entitled TELETECHNET is a satellite, interactive television network through which Old Dominion transmits 80 live and interactive courses to approximately 2,000 students across the state through the Virginia Community College System. Implemented in 1994, TELETECHNET is now accessible to 16 community colleges. Students take the first two years of their college education through the community colleges and the final two years of their college education through TELETECHNET. Students can receive baccalaureate degree programs in areas such as nursing, business management, and engineering technology. The program also has far reaching economic implications in areas where residents have not had opportunities to access higher education. Not only do these students receive bachelor's degrees, but their home areas now have more highly skilled workers.<BR><p>For more information, contact Dr. Anne Raymond-Savage, associate vice president for lifelong learning and academic television services, (804) 460-1076 or access <A HREF="http://www.odu.edu">http://www.odu.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Princeton University</FONT><P>Medieval Studies Program is Enhanced Through Multimedia<BR><p>A collaborative project taking place at Princeton University entitled Mappamundi is providing students with an interactive multimedia environment for studying the Middle Ages. Led by Professor Michael Curschmann, Mappamundi has engaged a dozen or more faculty members from several departments in building an extensive online collection of maps, images, and audio materials related to medieval culture. The project provides a database complete with images, examples, and links to related collections of artwork, portraits, texts, and translations, recordings, maps, original graphics, video clips, bibliographies, and course syllabi.<BR>Initially, Mappamundi will be used by students studying the middle ages, but as the collection grows, it will be used by students studying religion, art, architecture, Near Eastern Studies, and literature courses. <br><p>For more information, contact Professor Michael Curschmann, Director of the Mappamundi Project, (609) 258-3000 or access <A HREF="http://www.princeton.edu">http://www.princeton.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute</FONT><P>Studio Calculus<BR><p>At Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute many courses are taught in a studio environment with computers and interactive software. Learning is facilitated by collaboration and interaction among students and instructors.<BR>A course called Workshop Calculus is based on the premise that students learn more by doing and talking about calculus than by listening and watching. Joseph Ecker, a professor in the department of mathematics, previously taught calculus only in a traditional lecture, lab, and recitation format. It became evident to him that most of the learning was going on in the computer lab setting, so Ecker asked, "Why not extend this mode of learning to all aspects of this course?"<BR>The new studio calculus class incorporates Maple software, Waterloo Maple Inc.'s symbolic computation product. Ecker says, "Students in the computer lab talk about and do calculus instead of just listening and watching. They are arguing about and trying different problem solving approaches as well as peer teaching and collaborative learning." In addition, students interactively explore the visual aspects of calculus and develop graphs using Maple. The instructor receives constant feedback on each student's understanding and can provide immediate help.<BR>The studio calculus course accommodates approximately 100 students and meets twice a week. Students work together in pairs or small groups and bring their own notebooks loaded with the software. The school plans to open a new notebook computer lab for use in this course as well as in studio physics and in introduction to engineering analysis.<BR>Homework and projects in the studio course incorporate Maple software. "Students are becoming sophisticated Maple users," says Ecker. "They are learning how to develop good judgment."<BR>Faculty at Rensselaer appreciate the interactive aspects of teaching in which students actively participate in their education. "We want the students to be involved, interacting with each other, interacting with the faculty, and interacting with the topics being covered in the course," says Ecker. He comments that one of the most exciting results of teaching in the studio setting is the enthusiasm he sees in his students. "Suddenly the students are more inquisitive and eager to ask questions. Every day I see the differences in how students respond in the lecture and studio settings. In the lecture room, they are passive. In the studio, they are participating."<BR>A Studio Calculus text published by HarperCollins College Publishers will be released this spring. The text will provide faculty with a pedagogical framework and materials to teach calculus in the studio setting.<BR><p>For more information, contact Professor Joseph Ecker, Department of Mathematical Sciences; (518) 276-6383 or e-mail:<A HREF="mailto:eckerj@rpi.edu">eckerj@rpi.edu</A> or access <A HREF="http://www.rpi.edu">http://www.rpi.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Salve Regina University</FONT><P>New Multimedia Lab Leads to Diverse Projects<BR><p>Salve Regina University, located on Aquidneck Island in Newport, R.I., recently implemented a Multimedia Production Area. Complete with state-of-the art equipment, faculty and students have used the facility for classroom projects and to create interactive courseware.<BR>The area has helped many undergraduate and graduate students prepare in-class multimedia presentations. These can be as simple as scanning pictures onto a CD-ROM for playback later or as complex as the projects worked on by Professor Robert Kulo's communication class.<BR>Working with Mr. Vincent Integlia, the Multimedia Supervisor, the class produced presentations involving writing and editing scripts, filming the content, taping voice-overs, selecting appropriate music, and using multimedia technology to create fade-ins and multiple images.<BR>According to student Patricia Austin `97, an English major who is hoping to pursue a career in broadcast journalism, the project has provided her with a greater insight into the technical aspects of production, and valuable career experience that would have been impossible without the facility.<BR>"With multimedia, it's almost a disservice to students if you don't integrate it into your curriculum," says Mr. Integlia. "The area is for students to come explore, as Dr. Kulo's class did, and really see what multimedia is."<BR>The facility is comprised of equipment that includes computers with CD-ROM drives, scanners, laserdisc players, recordable CD-ROM players, mixers, VHS recorders, stereo equipment, microphones, speaker systems, projection equipment, and digital cameras as well as a plethora of multimedia authoring software.<BR>Once multimedia presentations are authored on the recordable CD-ROM player, faculty and students can access the materials from multimedia carts,  available to faculty and students.<BR>The ten multimedia carts have the capability to transport everything necessary for showcasing a multimedia presentation. Included in each cart is a computer, a set of stereo speakers, a laserdisc player, and projection equipment. <BR>Projects that have emerged from the facility include a CD-ROM tour of the University's McKillop Library. Users can look at maps of all floors and click on icons to find out more information on departments or rooms within the structure.  <BR>Another project grew out of Salve Regina's annual Global Fun Day. The cultural diversity project on CD-ROM allows students to click on different countries to learn more about the various cultures. The project, which was nominated for George Washington University's Jere Trout Award that recognizes multimedia excellence, was produced in cooperation with local elementary school students of various cultural backgrounds and experiences. To create the project, Salve Regina University students worked with thirteen children to present two-minute documentaries of their heritage. The audio portion of the CD-ROM was created by students studying music at Salve Regina. <BR><p>For more information, call Vincent Integlia, Multimedia Supervisor, (401) 847-6650, ext. 2167.<BR>The Multimedia Production Area Web Site can be accessed at the URL <A HREF="http://198.49.179.4/pages/integlia/multi.html">http://198.49.179.4/pages/integlia/multi.html</A>.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>San Francisco State University</FONT><P>Fiber Optic Video Transmission System<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/sfsu.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Shortly after officials at San Francisco State University learned that First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton wished to deliver a commencement speech to their 1995 graduating class last May, they realized that they would have to make special preparations for her visit.<BR>The First Lady's SFSU appearance, one of only three commencement addresses made by Ms. Clinton in 1995, created two primary problems. First, how would the university accommodate everyone expected to attend the graduation ceremony? And second, if the university set up remote viewing sites in conference rooms and theaters to solve the first problem, how would they get the video feed to those locations?<BR>Typically, the university has very large graduating classes and, for that reason, holds commencement ceremonies across campus at Cox Stadium. Though the football stadium has a capacity of about 13,000, it quickly became evident that more than 20,000 people were interested in attending, including a particularly large throng from the media. To make the situation even more challenging, engineers wanted to enhance the commencement production by adding three additional cameras.<BR>At the time, SFSU had six fiber  optic cables in place, of which only four were in working condition. Four were not enough to handle all the required connections, but engineers decided not to add more, because it was too expensive and they didn't have enough time.<BR>The decision was made to use a four-channel fiber optic video transmission system from Physical Optics Corp. of Torrance, Calif. For a total cost of about $5,000, video engineers at SFSU employed the plug-and-play multiplexer to simultaneously transmit four separate video signals over one multimode fiber optic cable, thereby eliminating the need for additional fiber. Because the system needs no optical or electrical adjustments, the installation was done quickly and easily.<BR>Using this approach, four camera signals were routed through coaxial cable from the field up to the stadium press box. From the press box, the signals went into the POC transmitter box and onto fiber optic cable. They then traveled across campus to the audio/visual instructional television center and into the POC receiver box, where the signals were converted back to coaxial cable. Next, the video signals were sent to frame synchronizers and then to the production switcher where they were mixed and captioned. At that point, the video signal was recorded, sent to five remote campus viewing locations (three theaters, the student union, and main gymnasium) and back to the stadium for display on rented Sony Jumbotrons. The signal also was sent by microwave to Viacom Cablevision in San Francisco so that it could be televised on cable.<BR>Audio was sent through existing dry telephone pairs but, because the phone lines are noisy and limited in number, SFSU recently ordered a POC eight-channel digital audio transmitter/receiver pair to replace them. Unlike other video and audio links, the POC units can be switched between different fibers without any adjustment, dramatically reducing down-time in the event of a fiber failure or reconfiguration.<BR>In addition to commencement ceremonies, the video extenders are being used in other campus capacities as well, including television broadcasting and distance learning. In the television broadcasting program at SFSU, students learn writing, producing, directing, newscasting, and sportscasting, as well as the behind-the-scenes technology.<BR>During the soccer season, students used the POC boxes on a field at the far end of campus. It was the first time television broadcast students had ever covered soccer, and it was made possible largely because engineers were able to feed multiple television signals down one optical fiber. This was particularly important at the soccer field because very few fiber cables are located on that part of campus.<BR>The POC video multiplexers are also useful for distance learning. San Francisco State University currently trades courses with most other CSU campuses and with many UC campuses. As SFSU continues to develop in this area, the POC units will be used for sending video and audio signals from classrooms back to the switching facility where they can be transmitted to the distance learning network.<BR><p>For more information, contact: Doug Smith, television engineer, Audio/Visual Center, San Francisco State University; 1600 Holloway Avenue, San Francisco, CA 94132; (415) 338-2639; Fax (415) 338-7255; e-mail:<A HREF="mailto:dsmith@sfsu.edu">dsmith@sfsu.edu</A> or access <A HREF="http://www.sfsu.edu">http://www.sfsu.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Seattle University</FONT><P>Training Counselors with Video Technology<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/seattle.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>The department of counseling and school psychology at Seattle University has been training counselors for nearly four decades. During the 1950s and 1960s, the emphasis was on training candidates for school counseling positions. Now many additional areas of have emerged, ranging from addiction studies to pastoral counseling. The school uses video technology as a means to train counselors in all of these diverse areas.<BR>Prior to using video technology, students in training had to depend on tape recordings as a means to perfect their verbal skills. The audio tapes provided feedback on content and tone of voice, but of course lacked the important visual elements such as body language, eye contact, and overall presentation. But by the mid-1960s, videotaping was initiated and all but took the place of one-way mirrors. The practice of hooking up a video camera to a monitor in another room enabled viewing without interaction and class observation. Now the level of communication is completely interactive, and students can view, hear, ask questions when appropriate, and tape sessions for further analysis. The counseling department currently uses 10 Canon VC-C1 communication cameras in its eight clinical rooms: three large rooms and five small rooms. Two of the cameras are placed in smoked, glass domes on the ceilings of the larger rooms, and the smaller rooms are configured exactly the same way, but with only one camera. A central location accommodates the main viewing center for counseling instructors to monitor each of the eight clinical rooms.The viewing center contains a 42-inch video monitor, an LCD touch panel control system, and two VCRs. The instructor can initiate discourse with the students in clinical rooms by using the touch panel. Within this central location are eight viewing stations connected to each of the clinical rooms, and students can monitor sessions and observe instruction that is given to other students in any given clinical room. The touch panel can be used to control volume, movement of the VC-C1, and the functions of the VCR. Each of the eight student viewing stations has a 27-inch video monitor, two VCRs, an LCD touch panel control system, and three audio headsets. The VCRs are used to tape sessions in progress that can be analyzed later in detail by the instructor and student. The entire facility was made to resemble a professional office, complete with a waiting room for clients.<BR><p>For more information, contact Hutch Haney, Department of Counseling and School Psychology, (206) 296-5751 or access <A HREF="http://www2.seattleu.edu">http://www2.seattleu.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Southern Methodist University</FONT><P>New A/V Systems at the Cox School of Business<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/smu.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>At Southern Methodist University Cox School of Business this past spring, a natural disaster prompted the decision to quickly upgrade the school's audio-visual facilities. On the night of May 5th, 1995, a record-breaking rain and hailstorm swept across Dallas, destroying millions of dollars worth of property. A flash flood swept through the bottom floor of the Business School, leaving several classrooms and teaching theaters submerged. The administration decided to totally revamp and upgrade the school's classroom audio visual and distance learning systems.<BR>"In a way the flood was, for the school, a blessing in disguise," remarked Tom Barry, formerly Associate Dean For Academic Affairs at the Edwin L. Cox School of Business, and now Vice President for Academic Affairs at SMU. "It prompted us to undertake, in one fell swoop, what would have undoubtedly been done piece-meal had the flood not wreaked so much damage in one night."The Georges Auditorium, on the bottom floor of the business school building was completely destroyed by the flood. So contractors gutted and  redesigned the room from the ground up. The new auditorium now provides students and professors state-of-the-art video, Internet, and Distance Learning capabilities.<BR>Essential to the design of the new auditorium was the hardwiring of each of the 156 desks in the room for AC, with computer network connections to follow, so that each student in the classroom can be online when the need arises. Despite a certain concern that students in the back row would be Net-surfing through entire lectures, student interaction through network connections was one of the goals of the room redesign. <BR>Key to the auditorium's projection system is a Sony VPH-1292Q video/data projector, set up in a rear-projection format behind a 9 x 12 acrylic rear-projection screen. The podium houses a computer and touch-panel Control system, as well as a Sony VID-P 100 Document Camera- one of the room's new Distance Learning tools. The document camera sits in a large slide-out compartment, and, when not in use, slides into the unit and is out of view. Another Distance Learning tool is the SoftBoard, from Microfield Graphics Inc. The SoftBoard converts the analog handwriting of the instructor into digital information. <BR>During the month before the flood, the school had already completed installation of audio-visual systems in six of the SMU business school classrooms. Each of these classrooms-all  untouched by the flood-is outfitted with a Sony VPH-1252Q Data Projector suspended from the ceiling with a monitor mount, a single Soundsphere speaker, and a custom-designed lectern that houses all of the computer, video, and control systems. The classroom systems were designed by Dallas-based Bauer Audio Visual.<BR>John Criswell, Director of SMU's Business Information Center and a member of the university's Distance Learning Committee, pointed out the importance of the new educational systems. "This equipment is essential to Distance Learning because we can capture, with tools like the SoftBoard or the document camera, all of the presentation, just as a student or professor in the room experiences it, and we can send the entire presentation to any other site, anywhere in the world."<BR><p> For more information, contact: John Criswell, Director of the Business Information Center or Philomena Jones, Assistant Director, SMU Cox School of Business, (214) 768-2000 or access <A HREF="http://www.smu.edu">http://www.smu.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Southwestern Oklahoma State University</FONT><P>Distance Education Over an Optical Fiber Network<BR><p>Southwestern Oklahoma State University has implemented an optical fiber network for distance learning between its two campuses that are 60 miles apart. The network also links sites at two high schools, a junior college, and a vocational technical center.<BR>"We implemented the fiber optic network to virtually stabilize the population of Oklahoma. We felt we needed to do something because the population here has seen a major dip. That's because now one farmer can do what it took 20 farmers to do 10 years ago," says Dr. Lessley Price, director of tele-learning at the university.<BR>Population has declined as much as 10 percent in the last year, and the university is finding it difficult to fill teaching positions. But with distance education, the schools are being sustained by sharing resources such as teachers. "We felt we needed to give the people an opportunity to have an education, and through distance learning, students in rural areas save commuting time," Price says. Some of the classes offered include Teaching in the Secondary School, and Teaching in the Elementary School.<BR>Classroom components of the system include a camera at the front and rear of the classroom, an overhead camera, and camera controls located at the host and remote facilities. The controls can be manipulated by a portable infrared control panel that enables tilt, pan, zoom capabilities at the facilities. In addition, four large monitors are located at each facility.<BR><p>For more information, contact: Dr. Lessley Price, Southwestern Oklahoma State University, (405) 774-3149.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>St. Petersburg Junior College</FONT><P>Exploring Poetry with Virtual Reality<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/stpete.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Assistant Professor David Hartman, who teaches in the communications department on the St. Petersburg/Gibbs campus of St. Petersburg Junior College in Pinellas Park, Fl., faced a dilemma: how to teach poetry to students who essentially are non-readers. Having been faced with indifference from students on a subject he loved, he felt it was time to create a project that would allow students to experience the feeling of the poem. <BR>Hartman wanted students to virtually experience the process of drafting a poem by viewing a sampling of critical responses and adding their own critical responses. The experience could stimulate students to write poems themselves, he hoped. Hartman and computer graphics specialist Tim Brock have combined efforts to create a virtual reality project with the working title Petals, which is an interactive exploration of Ezra Pound's poem "In a Station of the Metro." <BR>Currently in progress, the project provides students with an interactive approach to reading the poem. It combines studying the etymology of key words, visually experiencing the key words, understanding the hidden meanings and implications of literary images, and learning about Ezra Pound's life and his creative process when drafting this particular poem. Students can select different words to explore, and see how they change the meaning of the poem. <BR>To navigate to different sections of Petals, students use a HyperCard stack created by Brock, that has a subway metaphor. The stack includes a location in which critics give their views of the poem. Using a HyperCard link to an Internet web browser, the stack allows students to access the Ezra Pound home page on the World Wide Web.   <BR> From the HyperCard stack, students can link to a Virtus WalkThrough Pro application. In the application, also created by Brock, students can enter a virtual environment where the poem comes to life with graphic images and QuickTime moves. The virtual environment consists of a path students can travel down where they see key words in the poem broken down into their main grammatical units and view images associated with each word. For example, if the student selects the word "face," Virtus WalkThrough Pro displays a face on one portion of the virtual path and shows the Latin roots of the term. Hartman says that by viewing images evoked by the words in the poem, students can see what may have triggered Pound's imagination.In addition, for each key word in the poem, students can substitute four or five other words. Students could, for example, replace the word apparition with phantasm or spirit. When students have replaced all the key words, they are combined into a new poem. The images associated with the new words then are combined in the virtual environment, which students can travel through and see how the meaning of the original poem changed.Assistant Professor Hartman will begin testing Petals in his composition classes this fall.<BR><p>For more information, contact: Assistant Professor David Hartman, Communications Department, St. Petersburg/Gibbs Campus, (813) 341-4754, or Tim Brock, Instructional Technology, St. Petersburg Junior College, Allstate Center, (813) 341-4517.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>State University of New York, Stony Brook</FONT><P>Ecology, Conservation Biology, and Wildlife Management<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/ramas.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Teaching ecology students population equations is difficult by itself. But any attempt to convey the complexity of predicting the future of endangered and threatened species is much more difficult. To instruct students in this area, Dr. Lev Ginzburg, a professor at the State University of New York, Stony Brook, uses RAMAS ecological software that provides population-based simulations that can predict outcomes for endangered species based on various factors. Since 1982, he and two former graduate students, Dr. Scott Ferson and Dr. H. Resit Ak&ccedil;akaya, have combined efforts to develop RAMAS, a software library for building population and metapopulation models. The product consists of six models for understanding population growth.RAMAS is used as part of the curricula of three courses at the State University of New York at Stony Brook, in undergraduate and graduate ecology, and in computer programming and modeling for biological problems. The application enables students to build their own population models, simulate the impact of various complex interactions within given parameters, and compute the results. Students can calculate the expected population based on varying factors, determine the reliability of the estimate, and calculate the probability that a given population will fall below a specified threshold during or after a particular time period. <BR>At the undergraduate level, the program is used as a guided simulation to teach the fundamentals of population dynamics. Possible behaviors exhibited by natural populations are illustrated with sample data sets on spotted owls, gorillas, and brook trout. For example, students study the spotted owls' chance of recovery from its current threatened status. Students could also study the impact of actions such as captive breeding and re-introduction to natural habitat patches, and whether such actions would have more success with one large habitat patch or two smaller ones.<BR>One of the projects taught by Dr. Ginzburg analyzed the effect of crocodile farming on the crocodile population. Students were required to write a paper on how they would set up a crocodile farm. Using  RAMAS, students could determine which method was the least harmful and which method would be detrimental and lead to extinction of the crocodile. By calculating various factors affecting population growth, it was determined that harvesting adult crocodiles actually had a minor effect compared to the devastating  impact of harvesting baby crocodiles. Students were required to set up model simulations and determine the best way to run a crocodile farm and then write a paper on how they would manage the farm using RAMAS in the computer laboratory. <BR>Computer technology has greatly enhanced the curriculum. Dr. Ginzburg points out that most realistic models are too complex, so we are forced to use computer simulations. Students can easily simulate population growth and fluctuations on a computer. Ginzburg still believes in studying symbolic mathematics on a blackboard, but that isn't so much in the forefront now, with the advent of software for the curriculum. Students at the undergraduate level are much more interested and receptive when computers are used in the classroom, and showing simulations on a computer makes the information more immediate and realistic.<BR>RAMAS models incorporate species-specific data to predict future changes in population and assess the risk of population extinction or explosion,  and the chances of recovery from a disturbance. RAMAS/age models fluctuations in simple age-structured populations. RAMAS/stage is stage-based modeling of species with complex life histories, such as plants or insects. RAMAS/GIS is used to link geographic information system software to a metapopulation model, and RAMAS/metapop and RAMAS/space are used for building spatially structured metapopulation models for species that live in multiple patches. RAMAS/ecotoxicology and RAMAS/time models are being developed.RAMAS is currently used in approximately 70 courses in 25 countries in wildlife management and conservation biology: courses which were non-existent two or three years ago.<BR> Drs. Ak&ccedil;akaya, Ferson, and Ginzburg plan to focus on undergraduate teaching with RAMAS, with the soon-to-be-released book/disk package covering an entire semester of ecology called Introduction to Population Ecology: Principles and Computer Exercises. Students exposed to RAMAS early on will be at an advantage when they enter the work force, since RAMAS is a widely used tool in research and management today.<br><p>For more information contact Applied Biomathematics; (800) 735-4350 or fax (516) 751-3435. The SUNY at Stoney Brook Web site can be accessed at <A HREF="http://www.sunysb.edu">http://www.sunysb.edu</A>. The RAMAS Web site can be accessed at <A HREF="http://gramercy.ios.com/~ramas">http://gramercy.ios.com/~ramas</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><B><FONT SIZE=5>Tufts University</FONT></B><P>New Software Tests Students on Bias in the Courtroom<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/cstufts.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>A new application designed by political scientists at Tufts and Northwestern Universities provides a multimedia approach to studying the American Justice System. The application, entitled Crime and Punishment, simulates a real-life courtroom through digitized video of actors playing the roles of prosecutor, defense attorney, defendant, and victim. By tracking the sentencing decisions of users, who play the role of the judge, the software helps determine whether cases that are identical can result in different sentences. <BR>The students are presented with a total of six different cases ranging from a sexual assault on a minor to a case involving grand larceny shoplifting. According to one of the developers, Prof. Kent Portney, the application allows students and instructors to analyze whether there are patterns of bias within a given group of students. Portney began using the software in a course entitled "Judicial Politics." Portney observes, "The application is an experiment in human bias. When we first began using it this past semester, we clearly saw bias in the classroom and it was quite a learning experience for the students." <BR>The simulation involves students taking a seat on the bench and judging a case in which the instructor can manipulate case characteristics including the defendants' race, gender, appearance, or manner of speaking. In any given case, a defendant could be black or white, male or female, dressed in street clothes or a prison jumpsuit, animated or subdued.<BR>The CD-ROM application, which currently runs on a Power Macintosh will be available for Windows later this summer. A World Wide Web version is also planned. <p>For more information, contact Professor Kent Portney, Political Science,<A HREF="mailto:kportney@pearl.tufts.edu">kportney@pearl.tufts.edu</A>. To reach the Tuft's University home page access <A HREF="http://www.tufts.edu">http://www.tufts.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>University of California, Irvine</FONT><P>Executive MBA Program in Health Care<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/ucics.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>The University of California at Irvine recently began offering an executive MBA in health care to medical professionals. The program grew out of a need for health care professionals to develop a business sense and to be able to use statistics to analyze and accommodate future trends affecting the health care field. In the past, health care professionals simply needed a medical degree to succeed in their chosen field. But Dr. Carlton Scott, a professor at the Graduate School of Management at U.C. Irvine, observes that the times have changed for health care professionals.<BR>The program is attended by physicians, nurses, and administrators. In Prof. Scott's health care statistics course, offered as part of the program, students learn statistics covering topics such as the survival rate of hospitals, or what effects budget cuts will have on the health care industry. All students are given the latest Toshiba notebook computer, along with the SPSS Graduate Pack for statistical analysis from SPSS Inc. in Chicago, Ill. They study a broad range of statistics with the more than 50 high-resolution graphs supported in the software. The software guides students through specific procedures, including "how to enter data" and "which statistic to use."<BR>In one activity in Prof. Scott's class, students plot HMO versus private insurance claims to analyze how different types of insurance affect the industry. The SPSS Graduate Pack, specifically designed for students, comes with a spreadsheet-style Data Editor to make data management easier.Prof. Scott points out that before the computer packages were used, students merely looked at the data prepared on paper by the instructor. Now students can instantly develop their own charts and graphs. They can immediately see how a change in one number will effect the graph. The students can calculate health care statistics using pictorial statistics, histograms, and regression displays.<BR>The software is integral to Prof. Scott's course and is used in all statistical calculations by the students each day class is in session. Typically, students begin the class by downloading files from the server.<BR>Students conduct various other investigations. In a study of waiting room time, they plot out the numbers on a histogram, comparing the waiting times patients must endure at various clinics, and they generate various pictorial displays and forecasts. The class then engages in a discussion on the effects of waiting time on the industry as a whole. Prof. Scott and his students use the software to forecast and analyze variables affecting surgical services. Students plot out the numbers to determine what effect, if any, the seasons have on surgical procedures and how hospitals can prepare for and accommodate patient demand. In the past, the health care industry had no easy way to prepare for changing trends. Any attempt at forecasting would take mounds of paper and large amounts of time. Prof. Scott points out, "It would have been far too tedious and would have taken an enormous amount of grunt work."<BR>Students also analyze which areas in the country are going to need additional health care workers, hospitals, or additional beds. They can use SPSS to generate statistics including logistic regression, MANOVA, loglinear, hiloglinear, unconstrained nonlinear regression, constrained nonlinear regression, GLM-type loglinear, probit, Kaplan-Meier, and Cox regression.Prof. Scott sees relevance for the MBA Health Program as something that is necessary due to potential economic shifts. "All of a sudden, health care professionals must be cognizant of the costs involved in providing health care," says Prof. Scott. U.C. Irvine's MBA in Health Sciences is one of only three such programs offered in the U.S., but other schools may follow suit as the demand grows for medical professionals to balance their medical education with a knowledge of business and marketing.<BR><p>For more information, contact Dr. Carlton Scott, Graduate School of Management, University of California, Irvine, (714) 824-5336 or access <A HREF="http://www.uci.edu">http://www.uci.edu</A><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>The University of Georgia's College of  Veterinary Medicine</FONT><P>Neurologic Examination of the Dog and Cat<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/ugv.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Dr. Craig Greene of the University of Georgia's College of Veterinary Medicine in Athens, Georgia, in conjunction with Allison Lucas Wright, medical illustrator and Dr. John Oliver, created an interactive, computer-assisted videodisc tutorial designed to teach neurologic examination of cats and dogs. Used in a course entitled Veterinary Neurology, third-year undergraduate students study material that includes selected aspects of neurologic findings using motion video from 20 cases seen at the University Veterinary Clinic. In addition, animated motion sequences of neurologic pathways and still images of neuroanatomy and neuropathology are used as well. <BR>Prior to using the videodisc series, graduate students studying to become veterinarians were constrained on many levels. First was the limited and random availability of diseased dogs and cats for students to examine. Second, the instructor's ability to thoroughly assess each student's neurologic interpretation individually was limited to only one instructor and one set of audiovisual resources for an entire class of 80 students. Examinations on neurologic localization involves the student being given a set of signs and clinical history; then they are asked to localize the lesion. "It is difficult to evaluate the thought process of each individual student used in reaching their conclusion," says Dr. Greene. And third, these two problems together left Dr. Greene with the opinion that students may be entering the workforce unprepared. <BR>In the first year, students are introduced to neural anatomy. By the third year, veterinary students are taught to localize nervous system lesions in diseased patients. Due to the time lapse between the first and third year, Dr. Greene's concern were forgetting and not integrating what was learned in the first year. Prior to the use of interactive technology, a 25-contact-hour course was the only formal instruction in the use of the neurologic examination in the clinical setting. Subsequent application of these techniques occurred in the senior year rotation on medicine and surgery. <BR>Realizing he needed a solution to better prepare veterinary students, Dr. Greene authored an interactive tutorial that would enable students to become adept at examining and assessing neurologic findings on dogs and cats. The tutorial, entitled "Neurologic Examination of the Dog and Cat: An Interactive Videodisc Autotutorial," allows students to see spontaneously diseased animals and the neurologic deficits created by naturally occurring lesions. Students can observe movement and responses to sensory and motor stimulation which can then be recreated over and over again. <BR>The program is divided into eight sections: Introduction, Mental Status, Gait and Posture, Postural Reactions, Spinal Reflexes, Cranial Nerves, Sensation, and Help. Essential topics are highlighted for students, the grading scheme for each of the six components of a neurological exam are explained, and terminology is defined. <BR>Case materials consist of 8mm movies and videotape of dogs and cats with naturally occurring neurologic disorders, transferred to a master videodisc. Allison Lucas Wright using Macromedia Director enhanced the videodisc further by incorporating animated displays, motion sequences of neurologic pathways, graphic illustrations, as well as still images.<BR>The interactive tutorial depicts movement disorders and responses of the patient to neurologic testing, reviews nervous system pathways and neurologic function, and reinforces some of the course objectives of the third-year course in small animal veterinary neurology. <BR>Using interactive videodisc technology, students are able to learn the essentials of neurologic examination and then have those new skills reinforced. Instead of lecturing to a large hall of students, Dr. Greene has broken the course down into independent study sessions of four groups of 20 students each. The college presently has more than 150 videodisc workstations for Macintosh and IBM. <BR>Students are taught how to interpret abnormalities of the various components of the neurologic examination including mental status, gait, postural reactions, reflexes, cranial nerve, and sensory examinations. In addition, the module teaches the principles of localizing lesions in the nervous systems of diseased dogs and cats. <BR>With the tutorial, students are able to run through menu-driven modules at their own pace as well as perform experiments on dogs and cats in a clinical setting shown on the computer. "We show individual animals that have neurologic deficits and then students are able to consider the possible causes for the lesion which would include inflammatory, neoplastic, degenerative, traumatic, and anomalous causes." <BR>The Macintosh and IBM-compatible program was funded through the Office of Instructional Development at the University of Georgia. It is currently in use in the classroom to teach junior students clinical neurology at UGA. Other veterinary schools that have requested the tutorial include Auburn University, Ohio State University, Iowa State University, University of Tennessee, Tuskegee University, North Carolina State University, and Washington State University.<BR>The videodisc module has benefited the students in their development to become adept veterinarians, and also has saved animals.<BR>Instructors no longer have to research and do experiments such as creating lesions on live animals for teaching purposes. Dr. Greene is currently working on an additional tutorial for veterinary students. <BR><p>For more information contact Dr. Craig Greene,<A HREF="mailto:greene.c@calc.vet.uga.edu">greene.c@calc.vet.uga.edu</A> or access <A HREF="http://www.vet.uga.edu">http://www.vet.uga.edu</A>. <P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>The University of Kansas</FONT><P>Virtual Theater<BR><p><IMG SRC="images/kansas.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>At the University of Kansas, in Lawrence, Kansas, Associate Professor of Theater and Film Mark Reaney uses virtual reality software called Virtus Walkthrough Pro not only to plan sets for plays, but in the actual presentations of the plays. During a presentation, video devices are used to display sets and other images on a large screen behind the actors. An offstage computer operator, monitoring the play, shifts the scenery around on the screen so that it is in line and synchronized with the actors. <BR>"With Walkthrough pro," Reaney explains, "You can build a structure, or as in this case, a theater set and move freely throughout the model." Although it is possible to prerecord a navigation path with Virtus software, the scenery needs to be reactive to the actors for a live theater production, so the role of the offstage computer operator is an important one.<BR>Reaney has used the technique to produce Elmer Rice's play The Adding Machine, rendering the sets on his Macintosh and simulating the scenery, props, and some of the characters. As the play unfolds, audience members equipped with polarized 3D glasses see dual images that converge, enabling the illusion of 3D space. The images projected in The Adding Machine are controlled from backstage, ensuring that illusion is not lost by shifting an image too far to the left or right. <BR>The projection equipment used includes an nView LCD panel and Dukane overhead projectors. Off-stage cameras are used to create 3D images of some of the actors. The signal is then chroma-keyed into the computer-generated virtual worlds by video mixers. <BR><p>More information about the production is available at Mark Reaney's World Wide Web home page: <A HREF="http://kuhttp.cc.ukans.edu/~mreaney/">http://kuhttp.cc.ukans.edu/~mreaney/</A>. Contact: Mark Reaney, Associate Professor of Theater and Film, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045; (913) 864-3944.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>The University of Minnesota, Crookston </FONT><p>ThinkPad University<br><p>Many colleges and universities have struggled with how to implement computer technology for academic and administrative purposes. A growing trend within academia has been the implementation of notebook computers. The University of Minnesota, Crookston, was the first university to implement the purchasing of notebook computers for all full-time students. According to Dr. Donald Sargeant, chancellor of the university, "The university's focus has been on the use of technology to support key organizational goals versus just promoting technology itelf." The main reason for notebook computers at this university according to Dr. Sargeant was the growing need of computer literacy in the workplace and the difficulty of financing computer laboratories. In addition, there was a desire for all of the students to be afforded the same access to computer resources across the board and throughout the day, night, and weekend. <br>Numerous discussions involving the entire campus took place to evolve the university into a technologically-savvy one. When first discussing the issue, a number of faculty were apprehensive and thought that the technology itself might lead to the demise of the school. Today, nearly everything on the campus is electronic. "There is very little physical mail initiated within the campus. Instead, most internal university mail is electronic, including course outlines and materials, meeting agendas and minutes, and information items and questions. The Web is available for accessing information in and out of the classroom. The computer has moved to the forefront in teaching and learning as have the terms anytime and anywhere," says Dr. Sargeant.<br>Every faculty and service office and every building is connected to the LAN, from the library to residential facilities. Today, over half of the classroom seats have power and LAN outlets for notebook computers, every student in residential life facilities has individual LAN access, and faculty enter the classroom with their notebook computer which they connect to the overhead projection system and LAN.<br>The notebook computer solution stemmed from the need to not only acquire knowledge about computer technology in the workforce, but also to provide a campus where students have instant access to all the materials they need daily. "The notebook computers brought students access like they had never experienced before," says Dr. Sargeant, "Students now have access to their course instructors and their academic advisor, support offices, and other information resources." <br>All computers have built-in modems; therefore, off-campus residents can study and complete assignments or ask questions from their homes, reducing the need to come to campus. In addition, professors at Crookston noticed an increase in student motivation, and they observed that with computers they were able to cover more material in class. The notebook computer solution placed more responsibility for learning on the learner and provided equal access to all resources on campus.<br>According to Dr. Sargeant, the notebook computer, bundled with software solution has provided students with increased access to the library and other on-line resources, enhanced communication capabilities with faculty and other students both on and off campus, increased opportunities for cooperative and collaborative projects, and intensified experiences for dealing with constant change and advanced skills for employment in the "information age." <br><p>For more information contact Dr. Donald Sargeant, Chancellor,<A HREF="mailto:Sargeant@mail.crk.umn.edu">Sargeant@mail.crk.umn.edu</A> or access <A HREF="http://www.crk.umn.edu">http://www.crk.umn.edu</A><p>www.crk.umn.edu<p><FONT SIZE=5>Vancouver Film School</FONT><p>Students Enjoy State-of-the-Art-Facilities<br><p><IMG SRC="images/vancuvr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>The Vancouver Film School, located in  Vancouver, Canada, has a cutting-edge program dedicated exclusively to multimedia training. Designed in collaboration with industry representatives, the multimedia program consists of an intensive 40-week course that school officials believe to be equivalent to 10 months of experience in multimedia production.<br>The curriculum includes courses in 2D and 3D graphics and animation, video production, digital video editing, digital audio and MIDI, music production, storyboarding, HTML World Wide Web publishing, and CD-ROM creation, as well as planning, budgeting, scripting, and marketing. A multitude of labs focusing on different media are outfitted with state-of-the-art equipment designed to immerse the student into the same environment they will work as professionals.<br>The labs are designed to represent real-world multimedia production environments. Courses are taught on a range of platforms, including Silicon Graphics Inc. workstations, Pentium-based PCs, and Apple Computer Inc. Power Macintosh computers. All students have access to a workstation, and all machines are fully networked and can link to the Internet and the World Wide Web through a high-speed connection. Students can audition their projects on sophisticated systems and utilize a large theater with customized acoustics.<br>The Pentium Lab is used primarily for graphics and animation. The equipment consists of 27 Pentium 90 workstations, each with a pressure-sensitive Wacom drawing tablet. The software applications used are Adobe Photoshop, Macromedia Director, Fractal Design Painter, Autodesk Animator Pro, and Autodesk 3D Studio. The Power PC Lab has 27 Power Macintosh 6100 computers. Other labs include a ProTools Audio Lab, anAvid, nine station Non-linear, Digital, Video Editing Lab, and the Alias Computer Animation Lab, which offers 3D graphics training with Alias Animator Pro 6.0 on Silicon Graphics Iris Indigo XS24Z Workstations. The Alias program runs as a part-time in addition to the multimedia program.<br> A MIDI lab gives students the opportunity to work with a computer-based music sequencing environment that is dedicated to digital sound and scoring for movies. The lab is equipped with 14 Power Macintosh 7100 computers with Opcode Studio Vision A/V sequencing  software, Digidesign Audiomedia II digital audio cards, and an Alesis Quadrasynth keyboard synthesizer.Students are trained in the marketing and business side of multimedia and are required to create a project to develop business knowledge associated with commercial production. They can create and orchestrate original music or produce a multimedia presentation that demonstrates how multimedia can help a particular corporation enter the digital age of communication. Students get hands-on learning in marketing by having to develop and pitch their interactive projects to the business community. Companies that have been involved in some of these projects include B.C. Telecom, the Vancouver Board of Trade, and the Vancouver Aquarium.<br> Students are required to take a structured core program and are given the opportunity to explore personal projects or areas of specialization. The Core Program follows the production process and students begin assembling elements and acquiring skills that will culminate in an electronic presentation given in the large multimedia presentation theater at the end of their stay. <br>The theater is dedicated to critical evaluation and presentation using laserdisc, video, multimedia, high-resolution computer graphics, and five channel surround sound. The sound system includes digital and analog sound tracks for Dolby Surround sound and other digital formats for cinema and presentations. It was specifically designed and customized to fit the room and its acoustic capabilities. Among the other theater features are large-screen video projection capabilities through a Sony projector.<br>Students graduate from the Vancouver Film School with a full range of skills as well as an interactive portfolio of multimedia projects and an interactive personal resum&eacute;. The resum&eacute; resides on a Web page that the student has created in the Internet lab. The Web page will remain posted on the school's Web site for interested employers.<br><p>For more information contact: Dana Morin, Managing Director, (604) 685-6331 or <A HREF="http://www.multimedia.edu">http://www.multimedia.edu</A>.<p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Virginia Commonwealth University</FONT><p>A Virtual Classroom Model<br><p><IMG SRC="images/vcucstwo.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Like many institutions, Virginia Commonwealth University has long been involved in classroom uses of technology and distance education endeavors (delivering one- and two-way audio and video conferencing). But today, these efforts have moved beyond the traditional, and VCU has found itself on the frontier-mastering rapidly developing Internet technologies and working to adapt them to non-traditional instructional uses both for on-campus students and distance learners.<p>VCU is currently developing several projects in which the Internet provides a diverse toolset and a rich environment for instructing, interacting, discovering and learning. These Internet technologies include the World Wide Web, electronic mail, Usenet newsgroups, and telnet. Each of the three examples cited here have developed a Virtual Classroom model that can be used both in and out of the classroom.<br>In the School of Allied Health's Health Administration Department, the newest class of students in the Executive Masters' Program are using the World Wide Web and e-mail as the primary modes of communicating with faculty during their two-year program. Most students in the program are mid-career professionals who work full-time jobs and live in geographically different areas of the country-from Maine to Texas. During the two-year curriculum, students spend five 1-2 week sessions on the campus in Richmond, Virginia. For five-and-a-half months each semester, students continue course work at their place of residence, meeting with faculty and other students on the Internet.<br>The World Wide Web serves as the framework which easily and seamlessly links information about the program, faculty, students, and course materials. Locally created Usenet newsgroups, which are linked into WWW pages, provide a bulletin board-like capability for faculty to post assignments and for students to post responses. Chat areas provide opportunities for student collaboration and informal discussion. In addition, access to university library services and databases is provided through the integration of telnet links from course Web pages. And, e-mail provides additional enhanced communication capabilities for both students and faculty.<br>In a typical online session, students use Netscape Navigator (a Web browser program by Netscape Corporation) to access their daily assignments, post completed work, chat with their instructor, send e-mail to colleagues, and peruse the library catalogue database and employment opportunities. "The World Wide Web provides an integrated interface to all the various components of our system. This really helps students and faculty navigate the systems quickly and easily," says Jeff Lodge, Webmaster for the Health Administration Program.<br>In the College of Humanities and Sciences' departments of English and Foreign Languages, faculty are experimenting with using Internet tools both inside and outside of the classroom to support class discussion, student collaboration, research, and writing. In addition, the multimedia capabilities of the WWW allow faculty to incorporate text, images, sound, and video into their lectures and instructional materials. In her Critical Reading and Writing course, English Professor Ann Woodlief is using the Web as an interface for students' access to her course syllabus and calendar of assignments. In addition, the WWW provides students access to hypertext versions of the fiction, poems, and plays studied in the course; an online glossary of literary terms and definitions; posting of student writings; and interactive discussion and chat areas for student collaboration activities.<br>Robert Godwin-Jones, chairman of the Department of Foreign Languages at VCU, has been experimenting with use of the WWW in instruction for more than a year. Currently he is developing an intermediate German course that will interface WWW materials with instructional modules developed using Authorware. His WWW pages combine multimedia learning materials (German stories complete with graphics, sound, and animation); customized chat sessions; and capabilities for online submission of assignments and tracking of completed student work. The Authorware instructional modules provide drill and practice exercises incorporating graphics, sound, and video. These exercises include score reporting capabilities, and are designed as hyperlinks within his WWW pages. This fall students will be able to select a WWW page link and launch an Authorware drill and practice or testing module. <br><p>For more information, contact: Steven Saltzberg, Virginia Commonwealth University; (804) 828-1855 or access the following WWW locations:Health Administration:<A HREF="http://http://www.vcu.edu/mdcweb/haeweb/class97/class97.html">http://www.vcu.edu/mdcweb/haeweb/class97/class97.html</A> (login as guest, password visitor)Critical Reading and Writing:<A HREF="http://www.vcu.edu/mdcweb/engweb/main.html">http://www.vcu.edu/mdcweb/engweb/main.html</A> (login as guest, password visitor)Intermediate German: <A HREF="http://www.fln.vcu.edu/gj/201/201.html">http://www.fln.vcu.edu/gj/201/201.html</A><p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Washington State University</FONT><p>Interactive Video Conferencing Servers<br><p>At Washington State University (WSU), video conferencing technology is helping provide education to people in different parts of the state. In order to serve "placebound" people, the university has developed a branch campus system with locations in Vancouver, Richland, and Spokane. <p>In 1985, WSU began to offer classes via video conference to its branch campuses through a program entitled the Washington Higher Education Telecommunications System (WHETS). WHETS allows students at any WSU location to take classes held at any other location with real-time interactive video. Video conferencing equipment at all locations is connected by VideoServer's Multimedia Conference Servers (MCS) so that every person-students and professors-can be seen and heard by each of the others. When the program began 10 years ago, WSU offered six courses through the program and had 10 students. Last semester, the program offered 77 classes via WHETS to more than 2,300 students around the state. <p>In addition to offering a variety of classes at branch campuses, WSU uses its video conferencing capabilities for programs at the Spokane Intercollegiate Research & Technical Institute, the Intercollegiate Center for Nursing Education, a Masters in Engineering program for employees at Boeing, a hotel and restaurant administrative program at Seattle Central Community College, and nursing programs at Wenatchee Valley Community College. <p>WSU's LAN-based microwave network connects the electronic classrooms, each of which is equipped with up to four cameras and video conferencing hardware. Two VideoServer MCSs residing at the main campus are at the heart of the system; they allow the video conferences to operate between multiple sites at one time. <p>"We chose VideoServer's MCS for its multipoint capabilities and because it is standards-based, says engineer Don Peters. Our plans for video conferencing include offering a WSU class to University of Maryland students. This technology is able to expand to meet our needs as we expand and update our video network."<p>WHETS program director Janise Hall says, "Video Conferencing has become the backbone of our branch campus system. It has allowed our branches to grow much more quickly than they would otherwise, since we are able to offer a fuller selection of courses to both professors and students." In fact, video conferencing has become key to all kinds of communication between different locations. "We make any excess video conferencing time available for faculty and administrative meetings. It brings the university together. In 1994, we had over 10,000 people taking part in video conferencing of some kind. We expect that number to continue to grow as it has, by 25 percent annually," says Hall. <br><p>For more information, contact: Janise Hall, Director of WHETS, (509) 335-6511 or access <A HREF="http://www.wsu.edu">http://www.wsu.edu</A><p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Wayne State University College of Engineering</FONT><p>Distance Learning<br><p><IMG SRC="images/wayne1.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Wayne State University is currently incorporating Interactive Distance Learning to reach students who are full-time workers in search of increasing their education. Using "Viewer Response System" (VRS), technology provided from One Touch Systems, upper-level engineering courses have been broadcast via the College Cable network to engineers at Ford Motor Company, and throughout Southeast Michigan. The VRS provides students in the graduate studies program the ability to directly interact with their instructor from any location. Currently, the core courses of the Electronic Computer Control Systems Masters Degree are delivered to students by broadcasting courses via the College Cable network. <br> The VRS can be used for other purposes as well, according to Dennis Kerr, operations manager, "Interactivity is incorporated every 10 to 15 minutes, enabling professors to gauge their students understanding in real-time," says Kerr, "The remote students can press a button that shows the professor a percentage of how many students are not understanding the lecture," he says. With the click of a button students can alert the professor to slow down or provide a clearer explanation on a particular topic. The professor can also use this function creatively. For instance, the professor can poll the students on a variety of subjects such as "How many of you own your own computer?" In addition, students and the professor can call on each other to answer and ask questions. All of the data taken via the VRS during each individual course session is stored in a database in the VRS host computer, which can be analyzed by the instructor. This data provides information such as the students' progress with the course material being presented, as well as the professors' strengths and weaknesses in presenting the material. The use of the VRS to bring interactivity to remote broadcast locations has proven to be a learning experience for both students and professors.<br>Studies at Wayne State University have shown that since it began using the VRS for Interactive Distance Learning in the engineering field, enrollment has gone up more than 100 percent. "In our ECE562 course, which is a course in microprocessor design, the maximum number of students that the professor could teach efficiently in a conventional classroom environment was 50 students. With the use of Interactive Distance Learning, we now have 200 students in the same course." The engineering courses are transmitted to various locations such as students' homes, and also to various corporate sites and work-stations at Ford Motor Company. <br>According to Dr. Frank Westervelt of the Electrical and Computer Engineering Department who pioneered the program in 1991, Interactive Distance Learning at Wayne State University has exhibited an increase of 600 percent more students being taught by the program over previous traditional methods. In addition, studies done at the university showed that nearly 90 percent more content is provided, and student performance has shown an increase of 20 to 25 percent as measured on proctored exams. <br> The Interactive Distance Learning Program at Wayne State University has provided a way for students who are full-time workers to continue their education without having to come to campus. With Interactive Distance Learning, they can simply watch and interact with the transmitted course from their office. Most notably, the time saved by students is enormous. Many of the students are full-time employees with other obligations who are going back to school for a higher degree. Other benefits noted from Kerr include increased productivity due to a decrease in lost time at the workplace, less traffic, less money spent on gas and baby sitters, and more time that can be focused on learning the actual material. <br> Over the summer, the VRS was used in a 500 level student masters degree course called Computers and Engineering, and during the fall semester, two more engineering courses began incorporating the VRS in instruction. Other departments at Wayne State University are also interested in using the VRS for distance learning, including the College of Nursing, the College of Medicine, and the College of Education. <br><p>For more information contact: Dennis Kerr, operations manager, Wayne State University, (313) 577-2967 or access <A HREF="http://www.wayne.edu"> http://www.wayne.edu</a><p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Wellesley College</FONT><p>Dorm Network Enables Technology Projects<br><p><IMG SRC="images/welsley.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>At Wellesley College, a liberal arts college for women in Wellesley, Mass., the presence of the campus-wide network has spurred many Macintosh-based instructional technology projects. Wellesley's campus is fully networked, including all academic and administrative buildings. High-speed network access to individual dorm rooms is also provided. The "port for every pillow" DormNet project provides universal connectivity for all on-campus students who own or lease computers. The college's Computer Purchase Program offers "DormNet-ready" Macintosh computers with built-in ethernet and ethernet cards pre-installed. Wellesley students serve as DormNet consultants, providing advice to other students in the use of computers and networked resources. Students can access the library catalog, shared laser printers, campus and Internet e-mail and bulletin boards, as well as Wellesley's Campus Wide Information System and other World Wide Web resources.Professor of biological sciences Mary Coyne started one of the first projects to take advantage of DormNet. Moving away from slides and overhead transparencies, Coyne digitized her images, transferred them to a networked AppleShare file server, and now projects them from a networked Macintosh in the lecture hall. Students can review Coyne's digitized presentations from any Macintosh on the campus-wide network. "This is so much easier than going to the library and waiting to use a carousel of slides," explains Eleanor D. Lonske, Director of Information Technology Services.<p>Among the other departments that have made digitized images available on the network are philosophy, sociology, physics, and classical civilization. The art history department has digitized hundreds of locally produced slides onto Photo CD for both introductory and upper level courses and made them available over the network. Students no longer need to plan special trips to the arts center to view reproductions mounted on the walls, but instead can simultaneously review lectures and study for exams from any Macintosh on the campus-wide network, at any hour of the day or night. Many access the collection from their dorm rooms.<p>A growing library of instructional software, such as THINK Pascal, Mathematica, and StatView, is also available to faculty and students on Wellesley's network. A program called KeyServer, from Sassafras Software, ensures that the number of concurrent users of these applications does not exceed the number of licensed copies owned by the college.<br>The number of Wellesley faculty with adequate desktop computing power to explore and adapt instructional technology increased significantly this past summer. A team of Wellesley students and staff joined by Apple employees installed and networked 275 Power Macintosh 6100 computers on a single day in July. Approximately one third of these leased Macintosh computers went to academic departments; the remainder went to administrative departments such as admissions and the career center. This triumph of logistics, fondly nicknamed the "Normandy invasion," replaced hundreds of obsolete computers, and is a central component of Wellesley's plan to maintain a network of state-of-the-art equipment within budgetary constraints. <p><br>For more information, contact Kenny Freundlich, Manager, Advanced Technology Applications, (617) 283-2801 or access <A HREF="http://www.wellesley.edu">http://www.wellesley.edu</a><p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><FONT SIZE=5>Wellesley College</FONT><p>Online Writing Program<br><p>Wellesley College, a liberal arts college for women, offers a writing class in which students collaborate on a network of Macintosh computers. Wellesley's writing program uses networked classrooms to hold discussions in which everyone is "speaking" at once, all the time-except that the conversations are being held in writing on computers linked by the Daedalus Integrated Writing Environment. Written conversations in these classes unfold at an unusually rapid rate (as much as 40 pages of text per class). Transcripts can be printed out and assigned as readings for the class, or students are asked to locate ideas in the discussion that can be developed into fuller theses for their papers. The Daedalus system was adopted three years ago at Wellesley. Some instructors have transformed their teaching styles to accommodate this mode of instruction. "In an oral class discussion," notes writing program director Wini Wood, "students only write down what their instructor says; in a Daedalus discussion, they come to value the comments of their classmates-and their own comments, as well."<p>For more information contact, Wini Wood, Writing Program Director, (617) 283-1000 or access <A HREF="http://www.wellesley.edu">http://www.wellesley.edu</a><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><ol><FONT SIZE=5>Back to SyllabusWeb <A HREF="index.html">Home Page</A></FONT></ol><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P></BODY></HTML>
