<HEAD>

<TITLE>Miami Workshop '97</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Monday, February 10, 1997  11:32 PM -->

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#B9B9DB">
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

| <A HREF="miami97_cvr.htm">Workshop Agenda</A> | <A HREF="miami97_fri.htm">Friday</A> | <A HREF="miami97_sat.htm">Saturday</A> | <A HREF="miami97_sun.htm">Sunday</A> |<br>
| <A HREF="miami97_lodg.htm">Fees, Lodging and Transportation</A> | <A HREF="miami97_reg.htm">Registration Form</A> | 

<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT color=red SIZE=5>Saturday, March 8</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<a name="sa1"></a>
<LI> <B>MM1-Presentations and Multimedia in the Classroom (BEG)</B><BR>
Workshop leader: <B>Louis Molina</B>, Miami-Dade Community College
Creating and delivering presentations for classroom use. This course explores the features of presentation software and the basics of image processing and focuses on building classroom presentations with presentation software such as PowerPoint. It offers step-by-step instruction on how to develop a presentation using PowerPoint that can incorporate text, clip art, charts, and brief video and audio clips. Participants learn how to export a presentation to the Internet, and well as scanning and photo retouching, adapting existing instructional materials, and instructional design issues. The workshop presupposes basic Macintosh or Windows skills. Participants are encouraged to bring ideas and possibly some pertinent materials related to their presentation needs. 
<P>
<a name="sa2"></a>
<LI> <B>MM2-Introduction to Multimedia Tools/Macintosh</B><BR>
Workshop leader: <B>Diana Bajzek</B>, Carnegie Mellon University
A hands-on workshop for those who have little or no familiarity with multimedia technology. Basic Macintosh proficiency is required. The workshop provides participants with the skills needed to design and develop interactive multimedia materials for both in-class and Internet applications. Topics covered include scanning and manipulating artwork and images, creating animation, digitizing sounds and video, and formatting animation for the World Wide Web. Participants work toward completion of a hands-on project in class. Applications used include: Macromedia Director, Adobe Photoshop, Adobe Premiere, and Soundedit. 
<P>
<a name="sa3"></a>
<LI> <B>MM2-Introduction to Multimedia Tools/Windows</B><BR>
Workshop leader: <B>Tom Hall</B>, Pitt Community College
This workshop provides a look at several of the currently available tools used to develop Windows multimedia presentation and applications, including PaintShop Pro, Digital Video Producer, and 3D/FX. Participants also learn how to scan photos, obtain images using a digital camera, and capture full-motion video. The course includes a brief introduction to Multimedia ToolBook.
<P>
<a name="sa4"></a>
<LI> <B>WEB1-The World Wide Web in Education (BEG)</B><BR>
Workshop leader: <B>Arlene Rinaldi</B>, Broward Community College
The basics of using the World Wide Web and how to apply it to your own educational environment. Participants learn the fundamentals of the Web by actively exploring and discussing noteworthy sites, both academic and commercial. Capabilities of helper apps, add-ins, and Java are demonstrated by visiting sites that use these well. Bookmarks, search engines, and basic search techniques are covered, along with how to save content from the Web-file downloads, and saving pages as text or as source.
<P>
<a name="sa5"></a>
<LI> <B>WEB2-Developing Courses for the World Wide Web</B>
Workshop leader: <B>Robert Cavalier</B>, Carnegie Mellon University
Creating course materials using HTML and developing a Web site for your class. This intensive one-day session explores the basics of the World Wide Web's Hypertext Markup Language (HTML). Participants are urged to bring some course materials with them. By the end of this workshop, each participant will have the beginning of his or her own WWW course site. Participants will create well-designed, class-based pages with relevant links, tables, graphics, and frames. After completing several linked pages, the participants will learn how to establish a Web site, organize their files in a directory, and access/update their site. 
<P>
<a name="sa6"></a>
<LI> <B>WEB2-Developing Courses for the World Wide Web</B>
Workshop leader: <B>Richard Knee</B>, Florida Atlantic University<br>
(Please see description above.)
<P>
<a name="sa7"></a>
<LI> <B>WEB3-Managing Courses on the World Wide Web</B>
Workshop leader: <B>Alistair Fraser</B>, Penn State University
This hands-on workshop explores the use of FORMS and aplets for course management and helps teaching faculty understand the issues of course delivery and maintenance on the World Wide Web. Attendees learn how to take advantage of the World Wide Web's interactive and data gathering capabilities. They are guided step-by-step through the processes of creating forms; setting up a "virtual office;" and selecting aplets, scripts, and plug-ins. The course illustrates how faculty can take advantage of the immediacy of Web publishing to offer students access to dynamically updated course materials. Attendees gain hands-on practice with the latest software for creating Web pages and maintaining a Web site. 
<P>
<a name="sa8"></a>
<LI> <B>S1-Seminar: Issues in Distance Learning</B><BR>
Presenter: <B>Judith Boettcher</B>, Florida State University
How interactive technologies are used to support learning and instruction over a distance. This course covers teaching strategies, development of course materials, faculty training and development, and the unique challenges of online course delivery. 
<P>
<a name="sa9"></a>
<LI> <B>S2-Seminar: Institutional Support for Technology Programs</B> <BR>
Infrastructure support, administrative resolve, and technical skills are among the key issues surrounding technology programs on campus. Among the areas covered in this seminar are technology classroom design and maintenance, faculty development, and a vision for the future. Participants will explore a broad range of issues, ranging from administrative policy to the nuts and bolts of classroom design. Funding strategies will also be discussed as well as changes in "campus culture" that accompany the entrance of technology into the mainstream of faculty needs.
<P>
<a name="sa10"></a>
<LI> <B>S3-Seminar: Evaluating Effectiveness in Instructional Technology Programs</B> <BR>
Presenters: <B>Carl Berger</B> and <B>Tricia Jones</B>, University of Michigan
This one-day seminar explores many issues relating to the evaluation of educational technology. Included in the session are overviews of formative and summative evaluation strategies and techniques. The seminar provides surveys, critical reviews, protocols, and guidelines relating to the field of assessment. Case studies will be utilized to demonstrate various options and outcomes involving the evaluation process.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
