<HEAD>

<TITLE>January 1997</TITLE>
<!-- Date: 5/1/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Highlights from Syllabus Magazine</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>January 1997</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Volume 10, No. 5</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Video and Presentation Technologies</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
The following are summaries from the latest issue of Syllabus magazine, which will be published in early January.
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
If you are not a subscriber <a name="syllsub" href="syllsub.html">Click here</a> to receive a free subscription to Syllabus magazine, the definitive magazine for high schools, colleges, and universities.
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<p>
<IMG ALT="graphic" SRC="images/jan97cvr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>
New video and presentation technologies have opened the doors to new possibilities in the delivery of educational content. Students can receive an education anywhere and at anytime; class time can be optimized without hours spent rewriting notes from a professor's blackboard; and a world of educational opportunities are provided to people with disabilities-all due to video and presentation technology. Throughout the issue we focus on this technology throughout the curriculum.
<P>
On page 10, Dr. Reza Azarmsa discusses the presentation process in education in an article entitled, "Technology-Mediated Presentations in the Classroom." 
<P>
Video products will continue to get better as the years pass, but even today we are seeing tremendous strides in the technology. Our Buyer's Guide, which begins on page 12, presents some of these new products on the market. We cover a range of products from LCD Projectors to Digital Whiteboards. 
<P>
The January issue also features a special computer science section covering the hottest topic today: JavaScript. Java is making its mark on computer science curriculums throughout the country. First, it has streamlined applications running on existing systems and second it has entered many workforce areas. Markets from healthcare to retail are planning to use the open networking approach of Java. And with all this interest being generated by Java, it is pouring into the computer science curriculums and reenergizing the learning process. We include a feature article that covers not only the technical aspects of JavaScript, but how it is used in a curriculum at the University of North Flordia. 
<P>
A new Fax Back feature focuses on the topic of universal access. We include a listing of questions and hope to receive a variety of interesting responses and gain insight to share with you, the reader. 
<P>
We also include a revamped reader service section which features new categories to receive the latest product information in specific categories. 
<P>
This issue also presents the full conference agenda for Syllabus '97 and information on Syllabus workshops.
<P>
Some highlights are short excerpts from Syllabus follow:
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>"Technology-Mediated Presentations in the Classroom."</B> <BR>
by Dr. Reza Azarmsa
<P>
Reza Azarmsa, of Humboldt State University, discusses the dynamics of a visual presentation and explores some of the basic elements of a good presentation.
<P>
<MENU>
In the last few years, computer technology has begun to work its magic on the presentation process in education. In teaching institutions, instructors and administrators rely heavily on oral presentation accompanied with visual aids. Over the past decade, powerful new presentation programs and sophisticated display devices have joined forces with the personal computer to enhance the way such classroom presentations are produced and delivered. Most recently, audio, still imaging, animation, and full-motion video have been added to the formula to offer entirely new ways to communicate abstract or complex concepts to students.
</MENU>
<P>
<B>Presentation Domains</B>
<MENU>
The use of media to communicate information and skills frees educators to concentrate on the more exciting aspect of teaching: communicating effectively with learners. Today's teachers should know how to organize a presentation environment that includes a wide variety of media. The right technology-mediated materials can communicate information, teach skills, and provide general cultural experiences. In using media, a presenter/instructor must take into account the basic tenets of creating and delivering effective presentations:
</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>Video and Presentation Buyer's Guide</B>
<P>
<B>Synergy Multimedia Projector</B><BR>
Synergy Multimedia Projector is a multi-function projector that incorporates data, video and OHP/opaque presentation capabilities. It has a built-in half-inch CCD camera, and it can project images from any type of presentation medium. Synergy features 1.3 inch polysilicon TFT panels, 16.7 million colors, over 320 ANSI lumens, and a 150 watt metal halide lamp. Contact: Apollo Inc., Ronkonkoma, NY; (516) 467-8033.
<P>
<B>Elmo DT-50</B><BR>
The Elmo DT-50 is a desk-top video presenter featuring a detachable  hi-resolution camera head. It features a one-third inch 410,000 pixels CCD chip delivering over 450 (H) lines of resolution. It also offers Y/C and S composite video output, it has a built-in microphone for video conferencing, backlight compensation for low light conditions, automatic iris and white balance with manual override and a electronic shutter to 1/100 seconds. Contact: Contact: Elmo Visual Presenters, New Hyde Park, NY; (800) 947-ELMO. 
<P>
<B>Proxima Projection Bundle</B><BR>
Proxima recently announced a new video presentation bundle that will help enhance classroom instruction. The offer includes a Proxima multimedia projector (Lightbook LB10 notebook projector or Desktop Projectors models DP4100Z, DP4200Z, DP5500); the Tegrity Digital  Flipchart system including image capture and meeting management software, a video camera, and capture card; and an optional "visualizer" camera to project and capture paper documents. Contact: Proxima Corp., San Diego, CA; (800) 447-7692. 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>A JavaScript Primer</B><BR>
by Kenneth E. Martin
<P>
Kenneth E. Martin, of the University of North Florida, introduces JavaScript and provides an example of teaching JavaScript as part of the college curriculum.
<P>
<MENU>
Little more than a year ago-December 4, 1995-Netscape Communications Corp. and Sun Microsystems Inc. announced JavaScript, a new object-based, cross-platform scripting language that would enhance and extend HTML (Hypertext Markup Language). The announcement itself was accompanied by an endorsement of JavaScript from 28 companies, ranging from America Online Inc. to Vermeer Technologies. JavaScript is envisioned as a tool for HTML authors to script the behavior of objects running on their Web pages. This important tool will shift the focus of desktop computing to network-centric applications, enhance the quality and usefulness of Web pages, and provide a tight integration with HTML.
</MENU>
<P>
<MENU>
JavaScript is designed to complement and link to Java applets-small, standalone applications written by programmers and displayed on Web pages. The result is a full range of tools now available for easy selection by the computing and user community. JavaScript is a cross-platform tool that will encourage network-based applications, for example, scriptable access to databases provided across a variety of computing platforms.
</MENU>
<MENU>
<LI><A HREF="jan97_cspg.htm">Click here</A> for a complete Computer Science Product Guide.
</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>Case Studies:</B><BR>
Columbia University, Dartmouth College, and Iowa State University
<P>
<B>Columbia University</B><BR>
Simulated Trading Room Gives Students Real-Time Experience
<P>
Columbia University Graduate School of Business is giving students hands-on experience about market trading inside the newly developed simulated trading room. Graduate students will be able to mock market behavior similar to trading rooms such as Wall Street. <BR>
<P>
"This is a valuable experience for them and a real valuable tool to have around," says John Ellrodt, Assistant Director for Instruction Technology at Columbia.<BR>
<P>
Students are responsible for their actions made, even though the simulated trading room represents a working, learning environment where they analyze "real-time" market data and  examine market movements.
<P>
<B>Dartmouth College </B><BR>
Mentors and Students Communicate in E-Mentoring Program
<P>
Dartmouth College recently developed a two-year pilot program entitled the Women In Science Project (WISP). Part of the project involves the E-Mentoring program, which matches women undergraduate and graduate students with mentor professionals in the science and the technical industry.<BR>

Male or female mentors might serve more than one student, each at different stages in their academic careers. The mentor provides the student with useful information about career opportunities, access to professional networks, and offers guidance in a personal and professional level. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/iowa.gif"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Iowa State University </B><BR>
Researchers Experience the Virtual Reality World Using C2
<P>
Researchers and students can step into another world using the new C2 virtual reality room at Iowa State University. Located at the Iowa Center for Emerging Manufacturing Technology(ICEMT), C2 helps researchers in engineering and the science fields explore, alter, and manipulate computer generated images in virtual reality.<BR>

There are 55 graduate and Ph.D. students as well as 10-12 undergraduate students in science, computer science, and electrical engineering who use C2 for research. "We let them experiment with their own ideas. If they have some creative idea they want to try out, they are free to do it," says Carolina Cruz-Neira, associate scientist at ICEMT.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
