<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>November / December 1996</TITLE>
<!-- Date: 5/1/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Highlights from Syllabus Magazine</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>November / December 1996</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Volume 10, No. 4</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>The Internet, Telecommunications, and Education</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
The following are summaries from the latest issue of Syllabus magazine, which will be published in early November.
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
If you are not a subscriber <a name="syllsub" href="syllsub.html">Click here</a> to receive a free subscription to Syllabus magazine, the definitive magazine for high schools, colleges, and universities.
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<p>
<IMG SRC="images/novdec96cvr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>
The November/December issue of Syllabus focuses on how the Internet and telecommunications technologies are providing educators with new tools for delivery of instruction. In a keynote presentation at Syllabus '96, Adobe CEO John Warnock considered how digital tools are creating fundamental changes in the way information is authored and disseminated. "Education's Digital Toolkit for the 21st Century," a feature article is based on this presentation in which Warnock suggests that new ways of managing information will ultimately cause education to be redefined. <BR>
Faculty can now offer their entire course materials on the Web, including visualizations and animations that students can download anytime they need and review as often as they like. In a feature article, "The Web, a classroom sans Walls," Alistair B. Fraser examines these Web-based courses and how they may influence the roles of instructors and educational institutions. <BR>
A Buyer's Guide covers selected products that institutions can use to connect to global Internet information networks. Seven case studies profile interesting uses of technology in schools from high school to graduate level. <br>
In our Distance Learning column, Jerald Schutte shows how a Web page template and a strategy for collecting information on the Web are helping to build a virtual community of sociologists at the California State University.
<P>
Some highlights are short excerpts from Syllabus follow:
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
Page 14<BR>
<B>"Exploring Education's Digital Toolkit for the 21st Century"</B><BR>
New digital tools are changing the ways we create, manage, and communicate information. Based on a keynote presentation by John Warnock at Syllabus '96, this article proposes that education will be redefined as these fundamental changes in information exchange take hold in our institutions. 
<P>
<MENU>
<B>From Gutenberg to the Desktop</B>
The publishing infrastructure is, as it has always been, at the core of revolutionary change. Just look back about 500 years to Gutenberg in 1445, when he published the Bible and invented movable type, dramatically changing the economics of producing a book. Prior to that, books were handwritten and very scarce. Societies in Europe had generally been oral; people remembered things and passed critical information by word of mouth. Town criers communicated and broadcast information literally by yelling. Books were extremely rare and held only by a privileged few.
<P>
While Gutenberg's contributions changed all that, two other key events changed publishing technology even more. One of these began in 1460, when Mainz was sacked and knowledge of the printing process was spread throughout Europe. Aldus Minutius extended the effects of the new availability of printing expertise in the late 1400s with a very critical invention for the communication of information. He invented the small book. Prior to that books were big: they were chained to libraries and were not available to the general public. This was the first time you could write down information and have it be communicated easily throughout the society. An explosive intellectual expansion followed in the 16th and 17th centuries with growth in the fields of literature, physics, biology, and medicine.
</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>

Page 18<BR>
<B>"The Web, a Classroom sans Walls"</B><BR>
Now students can access course materials, including visualizations and animations, in classrooms, labs, or dormitories. Here, Alistair B. Fraser examines how the opportunities for sharing courses over the Web will contribute to the evolution of education.
<P>
<MENU>
In the middle ages and colonial North America, the classroom technology of choice was the scholar's board, a paddle-shaped piece of wood upon which a student inscribed a lesson being dictated. Like the modern computer, the scholar's board was interactive and would display text and images. Like the World Wide Web, its material could be transported from place to place. But it was slow-infinitely slow by modern standards. Having a much better match with the human perception and processing system, the computer opens up many pedagogical advantages over not only the scholar's board, but over its descendant, the blackboard, especially when the computer is used in conjunction with the Web.
<P>
If the computer offers advantages over the pedagogical technology of previous generations, what are they? That there might be any at all is not entirely obvious to most participants in classes or seminars for which the presenter has-as he might unfortunately put it-computerized his lecture. 
</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>

Page 22<BR>
<B>Telecommunications and the Internet: A Buyer's Guide</B><BR>
A guide to the products connecting college and university campuses to the vast resources of global information networks.
<P>
<B>LearningSpace</B><BR>
The Lotus Notes-based LearningSpace is a collaborative distance learning solution that gives academic institutions a flexible, cost-effective way to educate students online and provide personal feedback from instructors. The heart of the program consists of five interactive databases that enable users to collaborate on problem-solving activities, debates, discussions, and exercises. Contact: Lotus Development Corp., Cambridge, MA; (800) 346-6409. Reader Service #52 

<BR CLEAR = ALL>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/smartbord.gif"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>SMART Board </B><BR>
This interactive, electronic whiteboard, which measures 4' x 3,' can be used to deliver lectures and give multimedia presentations in classrooms. By adding an LCD projector to the SMART Board, an instructor can press on the Board to control any software application or draw in electronic ink on top of projected computer images. Included with the SMART Board are software and a collection of pen tools. SMART Board is compatible with Windows and Macintosh. Contact: SMART Technologies Inc., Calgary, Alberta, Canada; (403) 245-0333. Reader Service #55 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/xxx"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Teaching Pro 5000</B><BR>
The Teaching Pro 5000 system is a portable, fully integrated distance learning system developed to assist teaching professionals in effective delivery of lesson plans to students locally and in remote locations. The user is able to conduct class with a two-way, interactive voice, with video and data communications simulating same-room lesson plan delivery through the use of onboard multimedia tools and peripherals. This system  features an instructor- controlled camera, 33mm slide-to-video converter, fax copier/printer, and touch- screen control of all system functions. Contact: NEC America, Inc., Irving, TX; (800) TEAM-NEC. Reader Service #75
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>

Page 30<BR>
<B>Technology Across the Campus:</B><BR>
At Ball State University, technology filters into all areas of the campus; at Penn State the Video Flex is used to understand difficult biological concepts; a Georgian College Communications course goes online; the University of Notre Dame develops an Executive MBA program; New Technology High School emphasizes a technology curriculum; students learn teaching skills in Cyberspace at the University of Dayton; and the New School for Social Research offers more than 100 bachelor's degrees.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
Page 38<BR>
Distance Learning<BR>
<B>"Creating the Virtual Community"</B><BR>
Distance education is more than course offerings to remote students; it includes sharing resources among faculty. In this article, Jerald Schutte reviews a system-wide project at California State University that provides sociology faculty with a World Wide Web page builder, designed for the purposes of sharing teaching and research information throughout the sociology community. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/cyberscio.gif"ALT="graphic"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
Faculty Behind the Technology Curve
Locally, on the California State University, Northridge campus, over 50 percent of all students own home computers, 70 percent of those having modems. Some 6,000 students currently use the Internet. Sixty-five percent of all students disagree that the university is spending too much on computer technology. In fact, 45 percent of students agree they would support a fee increase to provide computer access to every student. An even 50 percent of all students think the university should automatically assign them e-mail account numbers upon registration. And 40 percent of the students agree that instructors should integrate Internet assignments into their course content.
<P>
With such universal acceptance and involvement in computer and Internet technology on the part of students, it is remarkable to discover that the same homogeneity of experience does not exist among faculty. Less than 50 percent of faculty own their own computer, and of those, the majority are more likely to use them only for stand-alone word or data processing.


<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
