<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>September 1996</TITLE><!-- Date: 5/1/96 --></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Highlights from Syllabus Magazine</FONT></CENTER><P><br><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>October 1996</FONT><BR></CENTER><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Volume 10, No. 3</FONT><BR></CENTER><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Multimedia</FONT><BR></CENTER><P>The following are summaries from the latest issue of Syllabus magazine, which will be published in early October.<p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>If you are not a subscriber <a name="syllsub" href="syllsub.html">Click here</a> to receive a free subscription to Syllabus magazine, the definitive magazine for high schools, colleges, and universities.<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><IMG SRC="images/oct96cvr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>The October issue of Syllabus focuses on the use of multimedia on campus. Throughout the issue we illustrate ways to implement this technology into higher education. The first feature article, entitled "Resources for Multimedia Production: A Guide for Educators," Judith Stern suggests ways to locate helpful resources for multimedia production. In the second feature, "Multimedia in Cyberspace: Teaching with Virtual Reality," the focus is on two professors who teach a course at the University of Texas at Austin. The October issue also includes a Multimedia Buyer's Guide, a variety of case studies that illustrate technology use on campus, and three columns covering the topics of the Internet, Quantitative Tools, and Publishing. In addition, this issue provides a special Windows On Campus section, which includes an in-depth article on the versatile multimedia authoring software, Asymetrix ToolBook II. In addition, a Product Guide features some of the latest products for the Windows platform. <P>Some highlights are short excerpts from Syllabus follow:<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P>Page 12<BR><B>"Resources for Multimedia Production: A Guide for Educators"</B><BR>Judith Stern considers campus resources, user groups, Internet sites, and commercial products discounted for educators. <P><MENU>Do you want to get into multimedia, but don't know where to start or how to do it? Intimidated by the expense? Or you don't think you have the time? It's true that multimedia can be complex, costly, and time-consuming, but if you know where to find human and financial resources, you can create multimedia instructional materials with far less of a drain on you and your (probably) limited budget.  Below, you'll find suggestions to help you locate some of the resources that you may find useful.</MENU><P><MENU>Resources on Campus<BR>Look no further than your campus gates and you'll find lots of resources. Primary among these is people.<BR>Recall that multimedia is multi-disciplinary field, and is a convergence of different types of media. You'll likely find various departments, some academic and some service, specializing in different aspects of multimedia. People in these departments are often willing to share their expertise, if not their equipment. Or they may already be in the business of providing multimedia-related services to campus faculty at a price far more reasonable than that of commercial multimedia service providers. </MENU><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P>Page 16<BR><B>"Multimedia in Cyberspace: Teaching with Virtual Reality"</B><BR>by John M. Slatin and Yacov Sharir<P>Multimedia, virtual reality, and the World Wide Web merger to transform the nature of teaching in a course offered by John M. Slatin and Yacov Sharir.<P><MENU>The computer transforms relationships between teachers and students; it alters our relation to knowledge and, indeed, reshapes our notion of knowledge itself, so that knowledge becomes not an artifact, not a message to be transmitted, but a process of understanding. This incarnation of what we call knowledge, and what we try to convey as teachers, is an emerging and perhaps temporary pattern of organization: what Robert Frost called a momentary stay against confusion. Multimedia, virtual reality, the World Wide Web-all are aspects of computer technology that together contribute to this transformation in teaching. </MENU><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P>Page 24<BR><B>Multimedia Products: A Buyer's Guide</B><BR>A guide to tools for creating outstanding multimedia for the classroom.<P><IMG SRC="images/javascpt.gif"ALT="graphic"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right><B>JavaScript CD Cookbook</B><br>JavaScript CD Cookbook is a multi-platform CD-ROM application that includes more than 100 "recipes" and templates that can be incorporated into a WWW page. It provides programming code, a complete JavaScript reference, and tutorials for constructing applets. It also includes a section on JavaScript Data Structures with information on the object model, creating and using arrays, pointers, and trees. $39.95. Contact: Charles River Media Inc., Rockland, MD; (617) 871-4184. Reader Service #55 <BR CLEAR = ALL><P><IMG SRC="images/newtek.gif"ALT="graphic"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT><B>LightWave 3D</B><BR>LightWave 3D incorporates an interface based on a sound stage metaphor and includes support for VRML, allowing users to create 3D worlds on the Internet. It offers skeletal systems, inverse kinematics, object morphing, displacement mapping, front projection mapping, and many other cinematic features. It has multiple levels of undo and redo; a Metaform tool, which allows the creation of organic objects based on simple shapes; Boolean drilling functions; and a built-in translation of metric and English measurements. Contact: NewTek Inc., Topeka, KS; (800) 531-3227. Reader Service #71<BR CLEAR = ALL><P><IMG SRC="images/strata.gif"ALT="graphic"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right><B>Strata 3d XT </B><BR>Strata's 3d XT is a new XTension to QuarkXPress. It offers a new approach to graphic design with added visual benefits and other support including fully editable surfaces, customizable and ready-made backgrounds, unlimited light sources and gels, full rotation of 3D objects, and additional 3D clip libraries. Contact: Strata Inc., St. George, UT; (801) 628-5218. Reader Service #73<BR CLEAR = ALL><P><B>VALIS infoShip</B><BR>This tool gives desktop publishers the capability to add multimedia elements to portable documents created with QuarkXPress, Adobe PageMaker, and other desktop publishing applications. Users can drag-and-drop audio, video, graphics, animation, and develop "virtual books" with page turns that are visible and audible. Interactivity can also include unlimited hyperlinks and animated buttons as well as embedded programs that can be launched to demonstrate a software application or perform an instructional quiz. $589. Contact: The VALIS Group, Tiberon, CA; (415) 435-5404. Reader Service #66<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P>Page 36<BR><B>Technology Across the Campus:</B><BR><P>Students at Bard College collect archaeological data for multimedia repository of information; a state-wide video conferencing network connects learning environments across New Mexico; formerly reluctant teachers in training discover the ease of multimedia implementation; instructors at Palm Beach Community College enhance instruction through multimedia and video; students at Cal State-Sacramento use Visible Analyst Workbench to gain real-world experience; and Lotus Notes connects students around the world at Henley Management College.<P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P>Page 46<BR><B>A.D.A.M. Software: A Strategy for Custom Publishing</B><P><IMG SRC="images/adam3.gif"ALT="graphic"  vspace=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>A major revision of A.D.A.M. Comprehensive, available this fall, will offer new possibilities for educators and publishers to create their own, customized multimedia materials that draw from A.D.A.M.'s extensive database of anatomy and physiology images.<BR CLEAR=right><IMG SRC="images/adam4.gif"ALT="graphic"  vspace=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>Since 1990, Atlanta-based A.D.A.M. Software Inc. has been offering multimedia content products on human anatomy and physiology. Numerous products are available from the company, addressing a wide range of markets and applications-from K-12 education, to college-level anatomy classes, to advanced medical school courses (including gross anatomy, histology, embryology, and neuro-anatomy), to professional offices and medical clinics, to the home consumer market. The company is one of the largest providers of multimedia medical illustrations and has amassed an impressive database of electronic anatomy and physiology images.<BR CLEAR = ALL><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P>Page 48<BR><B>On the Internet</B><BR>Online Writing Clinics on the World Wide Web<P>An increasing number of universities have made use of the World Wide Web to provide online writing labs (OWLs) to assist students with basic writing skills and to provide an opportunity to receive tutorial assistance on their writing from faculty and student experts. In this article, Gary Zucca examines the characteristics of online writing labs and provides the URLs for several outstanding OWLs.<P><IMG SRC="images/intowl.gif"ALT="graphic"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>Improving students' writing and research skills has always been a primary goal of educational institutions. Traditionally, this goal has been met through standardized writing placement tests and required courses in grammar and composition. More recently, these institutions have taken a broader approach to the problem and have developed writing requirements across the curriculum. Writing centers now assist students in improving their writing and research skills.<BR>In the past few years the technology of the World Wide Web has evolved to the point where students and faculty can access information and services with a minimum of technology skills. This development has hastened the establishment and proliferation of online writing labs (OWLs).<BR CLEAR = ALL><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P>Page 52<BR><B>Quantitative Tools</B><P>Project CALC: Calculus as a Laboratory Course<BR>Lawrence Moore<P>Technology is changing the way instructors teach mathematics. In this article, Lawrence Moore outlines Project CALC, a calculus course developed at Duke University that allows students to learn by investigating real-world problems cooperatively.<P><MENU>For the last ten years, mathematics education has been swept up by a wave of change. In particular-driven by a major National Science Foundation program-there has been intense discussion, experimentation, and change in the high school and collegiate calculus curriculum. This effort, known as "calculus reform," had its beginnings in a discussion of what mathematics should become the focal point of the undergraduate curriculum in these technologically sophisticated times. The answer was "calculus," but often a radically different course from the one in place for the previous thirty years.</MENU><P><MENU>Fueling Calculus Reform<BR>Not only did technology trigger the calculus reform movement, but also it provided continuing impetus along the way. Changes in technology could not be ignored. Students were appearing in classrooms with sophisticated graphing calculators. Powerful symbolic computer programs could perform most of the detailed calculations that had constituted the major part of the conventional calculus course.</MENU><P>Special Section: Windows on Campus<BR>Windows Multimedia Authoring for Educators: ToolBook II<BR>Tom L. Hall<BR><P>Interactive multimedia is becoming a widely used phrase in higher education. It refers to any application that gets input from the user by means of the keyboard, mouse, or other pointing device and performs some action in response. Several of today's authoring programs facilitate feedback, keeping score, course management, and Internet distribution of multimedia applications. In this article, Tom Hall examines ToolBook II, the latest release of ToolBook.<P><IMG SRC="images/woctool.gif"ALT="graphic"  ALIGN=right>Asymetrix ToolBook is one of the hottest multimedia authoring tools on the market today for the Windows environment. A range of features can accommodate faculty developers with varied technical skills and different authoring needs and interests. ToolBook allows you to design applications that provide complete control of text, graphics, video, audio, animation, and Visual Basic controls. Developers can quickly position and size visual media such as bit maps, video, and animation. An Auto-Scripting scripting function and Widget Catalog allow you to create applications with a minimum of programming.<BR CLEAR = ALL><br><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><B>Windows Product Guide</B><P><IMG SRC="images/autocad2.gif"ALT="graphic"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>AutoCAD R13 for Windows 95 <BR>This release fully utilizes the benefits of a 32-bit operating system with features such as OLE, drag-and-drop functionality, and support for long file names. It can run multiple sessions of AutoCAD 13, which was not possible in Windows 3.1 or MS-DOS environments. Contact: Autodesk Inc., San Rafael, CA; (415) 507-5000. Reader Service #78 <BR CLEAR = ALL><P><IMG SRC="images/statview2.gif"ALT="graphic"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>StatView for Windows <BR>StatView is statistical analysis software that is now available as a 32-bit Windows application. The application allows researchers to work through every phase of a project by combining data management, statistical analysis, and graphing and presentation tools. Within the View window, users can combine tables and graphs with drawn objects and text to create an entire presentation. Any View can be saved and reused as a template. $595. Contact: Abacus Concepts Inc., Berkeley, CA; (510) 540-1949. Reader Service #83 <BR CLEAR = ALL><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><ol><FONT SIZE=5>Back to SyllabusWeb <A HREF="index.html">Home Page</A></FONT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Free <A HREF="RS_list.html">Product Information</A></FONT></ol><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><address>Copyright &copy; 1996 by Syllabus Press, Inc. All rights reserved.</address></BODY></HTML>
