<HEAD>

<TITLE>September 1996</TITLE>
<!-- Date: 5/1/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Highlights from Syllabus Magazine</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>September 1996</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Volume 10, No. 2</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Curriculum Software</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
The following are summaries from the latest issue of Syllabus magazine, which will be published in early September.
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
If you are not a subscriber <a name="syllsub" href="syllsub.html">Click here</a> to receive a free subscription to Syllabus magazine, the definitive magazine for high schools, colleges, and universities.
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<p>
<IMG SRC="images/sept96cvr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>
This issue of Syllabus covers software for the curriculum. Today, CD-ROMs and text/software bundles are available for every discipline from art history to zoology. In addition, the World Wide Web is growing in terms of presenting course material and making available different types of applications for use in the classroom. Our Special Feature article, by IAT's Kathryn Conway relates the history of the IAT and its current objectives. Another feature article "A Practical Guide to Teaching with the World Wide Web," Susan Polyson, Steven Saltzberg, and Robert Godwin-Jones explore the planning issues that are involved with developing a learning environment on the Web. Our second feature, "Technology-Enabled Curriculum Enhancements" illustrates outstanding examples of technology in the curriculum, including image databases, multimedia case studies, and simulation models. In addition, we include a Courseware Buyer's Guide arranged by discipline, Case Studies, and columns on multimedia and the Internet.  
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>
<BR>
Some highlights and short excerpts from Syllabus follow:
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
Page 12<br>
<B>"A Practical Guide to Teaching with the World Wide Web"</B><br>
by Susan Polyson, Steven Saltzberg, and Robert Godwin-Jones
<p>
<IMG SRC="images/wwwone.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
The authors of this article relay important information intended to help prepare instructors who are interested in implementing the WWW into instruction. Topics covered include Internet access, equipment and software, technical support, creating course materials, pedagogical issues, online course components, new assessment models, and more. 
<p>

The World Wide Web and the Internet have enticed faculty with promises of access, interactivity, ease of use, and a potential universal presence in the lives of students and teachers. For many faculty, the question now is not "Should I use the Web in my class?" but "How do I get started?" and "What does a good Web course contain?"<br>
Planning a Teaching and Learning Environment on the Web
As you begin to consider the Web as a teaching and learning environment, but before you begin creating your Internet presence, operational issues should be considered.<br>
<IMG SRC="images/wwwtwo.gif"  HSPACE=10 vspace=10 ALIGN=left>
<B>Internet Access</B><br>
When considering putting course materials online, take a realistic look at your computing environment. Students will be accessing your course materials by dialing in from home, by using equipment in on-campus computer classrooms or labs, or through campus network connections in dorms or other facilities. Knowing how your students will be accessing your course materials is important for two reasons: connection speed and availability of access.
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<p>
Page 20<br>
<B>"Technology-Enabled Curriculum Enhancements"</B><br>
by Robert Cavalier<r>
<p>
It has often been mentioned that while the use of information technology initially involves the porting of current materials to new environments (e.g., photographic slides to presentation software), the real impact will begin when it alters the curriculum itself. This article explores three such transitions which serve as good examples of the impact of technology on the curriculum.
<p>
<IMG SRC="images/cavart.gif"  VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Image Databases and the Teaching of Aesthetics and Art History</B><BR>

In the late 1980s I was involved in an interactive videodisc project entitled Art or Forgery? The Strange Case of Han van Meegeren. The genesis for our work revolved around an interest in utilizing data rich environments for exploring issues in aesthetics. How would our students think about issues in art if they had more access to the images of the art works that they were talking about? In order to get them interested in these issues in the first place, we came upon the role of forgery in prompting people to consider real differences in attribution, aesthetic judgment, and the ultimate question of what difference an artist's signature actually makes.<br>
<IMG SRC="images/cavtwo.gif"  VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>
The pedagogical ploy of the program revolved around a famous case of alleged Vermeer forgeries. Han van Meegeren, an artist whose credentials had declined in the eyes of art critics, had been accused of collaborating with the Nazis in the acquisition of a heretofore undiscovered Vermeer masterpiece: Christ and the Adulteress. At his trial shortly after the Allied victory, van Meegeren claimed to have painted the work himself. Was he telling the truth or was he risking the charge of forgery rather than face the more serious charge of collaboration?<br>
The critics had praised the work as an authentic Vermeer. How much weight should their views hold? And is a work praised by the art world no longer valuable if the experts change their minds-reducing a former Vermeer to a mere forgery of a Vermeer? It is in this context that the topic of forgery touches key issues in the philosophy of art.

<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<p>

Page 26<br>
<B>"Putting Technology in its Place: Evolution of the IAT"</B><br>
by Kathryn Conway<br>
<p>
Kathryn Conway gives an overview of the Institute of Academic Technology from its early days when computing technology had not gotten much further than word processing and spreadsheets for most faculty to its current focus on what new possibilities can be achieved and what new futures can be invented in the academic setting.
<p>
<MENU>
In 1989, the Institute for Academic Technology was founded as a partnership between the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and IBM. At that point, "state of the art" computing technology had not gotten much further than word processing and spread sheets for most faculty. James Noblitt, one of the IAT's first academic fellows, commented that "There is considerable lag between technological innovation and its acceptance as a legitimate tool for learning and research. New instructional technology is embraced only if it is perceived as supporting institutionally recognized educational objectives."<br>
Most innovations in instructional technology in the late 1980s were inspired by individual faculty efforts, not through institutional initiatives. But by the early 1990s, the decrease in public funding in proportion to higher education's traditional budgetary sources, coupled with a higher number of graduating high school seniors and adults needing higher education, caused institutions to take a greater interest in technology applications. 
</MENU>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>


Page 30<BR>
<B>Curriculum Products: A Buyer's Guide</B><BR>
A guide to the latest CD-ROM applications and curriculum software. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/actiphsc.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>ActivPhysics </B><BR>
ActivPhysics explores the major concepts in an introductory college physics course. It incorporates visualization, simulation, and multiple representation. The program also features an ActivPad that allows students to take notes and create custom links to URLs on the CD-ROM or the World Wide Web. Contact: Addison-Wesley Interactive, Reading, MA; (617) 944-3700. 
<BR CLEAR = ALL>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/adam2.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B>A.D.A.M. Practice Practical</B><BR>
This new CD-ROM application from A.D.A.M. Software Inc. provides students with a simulated anatomy lab. Students can review thousands of pinned structures in more than 500 different images; compare up to four images simultaneously including illustrations, radiographs, and cadaver photographs. In addition, instructors can use the application to create exams from a choice of more than 14,000 possible identification and objective type questions. Pricing is $69.95. Contact: A.D.A.M. Software Inc., Atlanta, GA; (800) 955-9920. 
<BR CLEAR = ALL>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/metazoa.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Metazoa 3.0</B><BR>
Metazoa is a college-level Macintosh and Windows CD-ROM multimedia exploration of invertebrate zoology. It includes more than 1,600 images, animations, and ray-traced 3D models of animals. The application is  for use in general zoology and includes invertebrates, protists, and vertebrates. Contact: Dr. Kerry Clark, Biological Sciences, Florida Tech, Melbourne, FL; (407) 725-5130. 
<BR CLEAR = ALL>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>

Page 42<BR>
<B>Technology Across the Curriculum</B><BR>
<P>
<B>Clayton State College</B>
<P>
<B>Resumes with Pizazz on Multimedia CD-ROMs</B><BR>
The Computer Information Systems students at Clayton State College have created their own unique multimedia resum&eacute;s on CD-ROM for distribution to prospective employers. As a lab component of a CIS policy course, the students are required to design their own resum&eacute; using text, images, sound, and video of various aspects of their educational, professional, or personal experiences. For each student these objects are combined into a multimedia resum&eacute; ported onto a CD-ROM.  
<P>

<B>University of Massachusetts, Lowell</B><BR>
<P>
<B>Innovative Course Combines Multimedia with Helping the Homeless</B><BR>
At the University of Massachusetts- Lowell, faculty run several sections of Values and Creative Thinking, an innovative course designed for special admissions among  minority and ESL students. A large component of this course is to provide help to nearby homeless shelters and charity organizations. At the end of the course is the creation of a multimedia project that highlights a charitable organization. The students use Gold Disk's Astound and Adobe's Premiere and Photoshop to create the multimedia project. A panel of professors from a variety of disciplines evaluate the projects for persuasiveness, originality of thought, and effectiveness of expression. 
<P>
<B>The University of Florida College of Medicine</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/adamtwo.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Students Get a Solid Foundation in Anatomy Education with A.D.A.M. Practice Practical</B><BR>
Professor Pawlina, instructor of anatomy and histology at the University of Florida College of Medicine, has authored several A.D.A.M. software products including the latest release entitled A.D.A.M. Practice Practical. This new product provides students with a simulated lab environment complete with "pinned" structures and time limits. "The software provides a perfect complement to a student's anatomy education especially in terms of attaining a thorough knowledge of the basics and having a strong base from which to continue with on through the years of their medical education," says Prof. Pawlina. The application soon will be implemented into the Gross Anatomy Lab at the University of Florida, where students already have access to other products co-authored by Prof. Pawlina. <BR>
 "Students these days are very inquisitive and want to know information right away as well as assure themselves that they thoroughly understand the material," says Prof. Pawlina. "They want to be able to mimic pins placed in the image similar to a practice exam before the big one."  
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
Page 50<BR>
<B>Multimedia Column:</B><BR>
<B>"PACE: The Four Critical Elements"</B><BR>
by Jerry Dawson, Pierian Software<BR>
<P>
This article focuses on the four critical elements of good multimedia software for the educational environment. To be effective, multimedia must have four key attributes: Presentability, Accountability, Customizability, and Extensibility-or collectively, PACE.
<P>
<MENU>
The key to educational technology is software-and what the students and teachers are doing with it. Judging the appropriateness, effectiveness, and capability of technology in the classroom is difficult, but new classroom tools mean expanded opportunities for teaching and learning. Simple-to-use multimedia authoring applications, digital media collections, Internet access, and new curriculum-based software are all making the technology-centered classroom a reality.
</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
Page 52<BR>
<B>On the Internet Column:</B><BR>
"Teaching Online Search Techniques Your Students Can Use" <BR>
by Lillian Biermann Wehmeyer<BR>
<P>
In this article the author considers useful information search techniques that can be taught to students. 
<P>
Do you remember the days when you flipped through the card catalog to find books? And when, to locate journal articles, you took one paperbound issue of one index, pored through the pages, perhaps turned to another page to find an abstract, wrote down or photocopied the references, then took the next paperbound issue, and eventually worked your way back to-and through-the hardbound annual cumulations? Whenever I think that a computer is slow in responding to a search command, I call to mind the image of a hand search, and I am supremely grateful.<P>
Now I teach the skills of online searching to university students. Some aspects of searching have not changed with the computer; others are vastly different.
<P>

<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
