<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>August 1996</TITLE><!-- Date: 5/1/96 --></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Highlights from Syllabus Magazine</FONT></CENTER><P><br><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>August 1996</FONT><BR></CENTER><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Volume 10, No. 1</FONT><BR></CENTER><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Video and Presentation Technologies</FONT><BR></CENTER><P>The following are summaries from the latest issue of Syllabus magazine, which will be published in early August.<p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>If you are not a subscriber <a name="syllsub" href="syllsub.html">Click here</a> to receive a free subscription to Syllabus magazine, the definitive magazine for high schools, colleges, and universities.<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><IMG SRC="images/august96cvr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>In this issue of Syllabus, we cover video and presentation technologies within the educational environment. Educators today are involved in creating effective video presentations, and they are concerned with planning dedicated video projection classrooms that enhance instruction. Throughout the issue, we focus on video technology as a viable mode for instruction. A Video and Presentation Buyer's Guide features the latest cameras, projectors, LCD panels, and presentation peripherals and software. Case studies focus on six higher education institutions and their varied uses of technology. Our feature article focuses on video for multimedia instruction. The issue's Internet Column covers Internet resources and course development. In addition, Syllabus Press is proud to announce new Syllabus workshops that will take place in the fall '96 and throughout '97. <BR><BR CLEAR = ALL><BR>Some highlights and short excerpts from Syllabus follow:<p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P>Page 10<br><B>"Video for Classroom Multimedia Instruction"</B><br>by Barrik Van Winkle<br><p>In this article, the author looks at what practical hurdles need to be overcome to realize the potential of video technology in the classroom. Considerations of infrastructure, equipment, personnel, and pedagogy need to be taken into account early in the planning stages of any single or coordinated multimedia teaching effort.<p><MENU><B>Infrastructure for Delivery of Multimedia Instruction</B><br>Consider the physical infrastructure of classrooms. While many institutions presently have existing "media" teaching rooms, these are often set up for slide and 16mm film presentation, with sloped floors, rows of fixed seating, a pit or stage at one end from which a faculty member lectures, and a screen behind the lectern. But LCD projectors, the equipment you will most likely use for presentation of your multimedia course, are hard to use in this environment: they usually must be within 20 or 30 feet of the screen and need to be at 90 degrees with respect to its surface to minimize distortion. They may pixilate their image if specified operating conditions are not met, so it is important to have a classroom in which they can be set up properly. In a theater or classroom with row seating, the line of sight of students sitting to the rear can be blocked, so seating arrangement is an issue.</MENU><p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p>Page 12<br><B>Video for the Classroom: Buyer's Guide</B><br><p><B>PROVISION Power Cannon</B><br>PROVISION Power Cannon is a new LCD projector which provides image accuracy from both video and computer sources. It comes standard with a 575 watt metal halide lamp that is capable of producing consistent image accuracy, along with built-in line-doubler, TV tuner, and digital stereo sound. Features include 550 ANSI lumens, variable focus lens, 9.5 degree Keystone adjustment, front, rear, ceiling, or floor projection, and audio system. Contact: Spectrel International, Burlingame, CA; (415) 343-5987. <p><B>CD-i Pro Desktop</B><br>This Compact Disc-Interactive player can be set up using still images or digital video sequences to attract and inform viewers, letting them follow on-screen instructions to suit their interests. Four serial input/output ports and a centronics parallel port allow users simultaneous operation of up to five devices, such as modems, printers, keyboards, and touch screens. It will accommodate regular and enhanced audio CDs, photo- or video-CD formats, and MPEG full-motion video standards. Contact: Philips Professional Products, Knoxville, TN; (615) 541-5800. <p><B>DataLift</B><br>Display Devices Inc. offers a full line of video projector DataLifts for lightweight LCD projectors up to heavyweight systems. Standard features include a cable management system, low-voltage trigger, adjustable show position, projection outlet, and choice of remotes. Contact: Display Devices Inc., Denver, CO; (303) 297-1754.<p>(The complete August Buyer's Guide can be found at <A HREF="www.syllabus.com/august96_BG.html">http://www.syllabus.com/august96_BG.html</A>)<p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><B>Technology Across the Campus</B><br>Technology Across the Campus, which is a regular Syllabus feature, covers innovative uses of technology in a variety disciplines and departments. This issue covers such disciplines as Russian and opera as well as an instructional technology department, and the use of fiber optics and video technology. <p><B>San Jose State University</B><br><p>Continuing Education Students Learn the Power of Electronic PresentationsToday's presentation software and LCD projection products are rapidly making slide carrousels and transparencies obsolete and are making remarkable progress in the impact of business and educational presentations. Selected wisely, located prudently, and combined with traditional presentation techniques and skills, the new electronic equipment offers tremendous assistance in preparing and delivering the perfect presentation. Nowhere do they seem to be taking to this technology faster than at the San Jose State University Instructional Department where approximately 150 continuing education students are learning to use electronic presentation equipment to enhance their careers as instructional design and presentation professionals in numerous Silicon Valley corporations. <p><B>South Dakota State University</B><br><p>Russian Instruction Via Video Technology <br>South Dakota State University, located in Brookings, S.D., offers a Russian language course via distance learning. Spearheaded by instructor Janet Johnson, the course has taken top honors two years in a row in the annual U.S. Distance Learning competition.<br>Johnson holds the class in the University's Rural Development Telecommunications Network (RDTN) studio and it is transmitted to a remote site in Pierre, S.D. The program incorporates two-way video and two-way audio.<br>Johnson relishes using visual techniques in teaching Russian. Chroma key technology, for example, allows her to place herself in pictures displayed on the monitor as if she were really at the remote location. One of the classes took the students to Red Square via distance learning. With chroma key technology, Johnson was able to place herself in the picture of Red Square and move around as though she were actually on location in Russia.<p><B>Stanford University</B><br><p>Fiberoptic Transmission Equipment Helps Enhance University Television Network<br>Engineers at Stanford University recently discovered that expanding the capabilities of a multi-faceted university television broadcast and distance learning network can be a daunting task, particularly when working within the framework of an already stretched budget. <p><IMG SRC="images/rigoleto.gif"  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right> <B>Rhodes College</B><br><p>World Wide Web Project Increases Student Interest in Opera<br>Rhodes College, located in Memphis, Tennessee, has a enrollment of 1,500 students. Classes covering the topic of music, such as Professor Patricia Gray's "History of Opera" class, usually contain fewer than 20 students. To increase student interest, Gray began incorporating the World Wide Web and the Internet into instruction by requiring her students to participate in discussion groups and navigating the Internet. Noting increased student interest and participation via this mode of instruction, she thought the creation of a class home page seemed like the obvious next step for the class to take.<p><B>University of the South</B><br><p>New "Electronic Classroom" Unveiled<br>Earlier this year, the University of the South unveiled its new, fully-equipped, 20x40' "electronic classroom."  The room allows students to learn traditional subjects such as computer science, physics, astronomy, mathematics, English, economics, and others through a very untraditional means of technology. On either side of the room is a ceiling-mounted Proxima 5100 directed at one of two 10 x 10 projection screens. Additionally, the room houses an Elmo Visual Presenter, VCRs, and laser discs. <p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p>Page 26<br><B>On the Internet</B><br>"Internet Resources for Course Development"<br>by Lillian Biermann Wehmeyer<br><p>Lillian Biermann Wehmeyer discusses the resources faculty can find on the Internet. Faculty now can develop courses with print, audio, and visual materials easily accessible from the Internet. <p><MENU>Perhaps you are developing a new course...or updating one you have taught before. In either case, can the Internet help?<br>Yes, indeed! Internet resources have limits, especially when it comes to full text. But they include indexes; print, audio, and visual materials transferred to electronic format; and most important, many treasures unavailable elsewhere. Internet search tools including archie, Veronica, and Web searchers (see "On the Internet" in the February and June issues of Syllabus) locate these resources.</MENU><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><ol><FONT SIZE=5>Back to SyllabusWeb <A HREF="index.html">Home Page</A></FONT><P><FONT SIZE=5>Free <A HREF="RS_list.html">Product Information</A></FONT></ol><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><address>Copyright &copy; 1996 by Syllabus Press, Inc. All rights reserved.</address></BODY></HTML>
