<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>June 1996</TITLE>

<!-- Date: 5/1/96 -->

</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Highlights from Syllabus Magazine</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>June 1996</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>


<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Volume 9, No. 9</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>


<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Telecommunications and Networking in Education</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
The following are summaries from the latest issue of Syllabus magazine, which will be published in early June.
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
If you are not a subscriber <a name="syllsub" href="syllsub.html">Click here</a> to receive a free subscription to Syllabus magazine, the definitive magazine for high schools, colleges, and universities.
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<p>
<IMG SRC="images/june96cvr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>
In this issue of Syllabus, we cover communications and networking in the education environment. Recently, there has been an explosion of activity in distance learning. Telecommunications technologies are changing how and when students interact with their professors. Colleges and universities are redefining themselves and expanding the idea of "the campus." Throughout the issue, we focus on how telecommunications and distance learning are extending the classroom beyond the traditional lecture. We include a feature article that looks at what new options are available for instructional delivery and what changes may result on an institutional level. Another feature article focuses on networks and professional organizations. We include a buyer's guide that covers the latest products in video conferencing and networking, eight case studies covering technology on campus, and our regular columns entitled On the Internet and Quantitative Tools.
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>
<BR>
Some highlights and short excerpts from Syllabus follow:
<p>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
Page 10<BR>
<B>"Telecommunications and the Changing Nature of Instructional Delivery"</B><BR>
by Norman Wagner<BR>
<P>
In this article, the author describes the new options for instructional delivery made possible by media fusion and advanced telecommunications technologies, and he explores the possibilities for resulting institutional change. 
<P>
<MENU>
It has been widely documented in the popular press that in the near future the ability to originate and receive telecommunications, including computing, will be available to almost everyone in schools, homes, and in the workplace, as telephones are now. Media fusion, that is the blending of telephone, computer, and television capabilities in one appliance, will allow people to interact in combinations of voice, text, and video in real time or delayed.
</MENU> 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
Page 14<BR>
<B>"In Partnership with Education: The Network Professional Association"</B><BR>
by Gerry Dye<BR>
<P>

As networks become commonplace in our institutions  and in society in general, academia can help define standards for network professionals. In this article, the author outlines how the association forms partnerships with educational institutions and with industry in order to establish programs for training network professionals and to offer new opportunities for students. 
<P>
<MENU>
When French historian and sociologist Alexis de Tocqueville traveled and studied in the United States in the nineteenth century, he was struck by the roles and prominence taken by associations in this country. In his monumental work, Democracy in America, he noted that in Europe traditional guilds had evolved into trade unions that negotiated with business and government on behalf of their members, generally from an adversarial position. However, in the U.S. the guilds had evolved into associations (with unions springing up under different circumstances) that supported their members in the development of skills and resources that tended to raise the standards of their industry and their membership's place in it.
</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>

Page 20<BR>
<B>Buyer's Guide</B><BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/bgeclipse.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=left>
<P>
<B>eclipse gold</B><BR>
<P>
This video conferencing system includes 384Kbps bandwidth operating at 30 frames per second and a T.120 multimedia gateway for collaborative document conferencing. It includes a pan, tilt, zoom camera, microphone, and remote control unit. Contact: CLI Inc., San Jose, CA; (408) 922-5429. (Note: CLI will have a booth and sponsor other activities at Syllabus 96.)
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>


<BR>

<IMG SRC="images/bglearnlnc.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=left>
<P>
<B>LearnLinc</B><BR>
<P>
LearnLinc is a desktop PC software system with interactive multimedia tools for distance learning applications. It incorporates interactivity with video/audio, hand raising, annotation, and an electronic whiteboard with multimedia authoring capabilities. Contact: Interactive Learning International Corp., Troy, NY; (518) 283-8799.
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/bgcolbrtr.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=left>
<B>Personal Collaborator</B><BR>
<P>
With Personal Collaborator, users can view and talk to each other in real time while sharing the same computer applications and files at two sites simultaneously. It consists of a single ISA or PCI card with an ISDN BRI interface, plus VTEL's new AppView, a graphical conference control interface, and a camera with microphone and speaker. Contact: VTEL Corp., Austin, TX; (512) 314-2700.
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>

<B>Case Studies</B><BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/cstufts.gif"  HSPACE=10 ALIGN=right>
<P>
<B>Tufts University </B><BR>
<P>




A new application entitled "Crime and Punishment" allows altering of the race, gender, and mannerisms of the defendant. By tracking the sentencing decisions of users, who play the role of the judge, the software helps determine whether cases that are identical can result in different sentences.
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<BR>
<B>Ithaca College and the University of Georgia</B><BR>
<P>
<MENU>
A moderated electronic National Issues Forum, entitled "How Do We Want to Govern America?" is planned for the 1996 campaign season in the fall term at Ithaca College and the University of Georgia.
</MENU>
<P>
<B>Princeton University</B><BR>
<P>
<menu>A collaborative project taking place at Princeton University entitled Mappamundi is providing students with an interactive multimedia environment for studying the Middle Ages. </menu>
<P>
<b>University of Delaware</b><br>
<P>
<MENU>
At this University, several projects have grown out of the FOCUS distance learning program.
</MENU>
<P>
<B>Indiana University</B><BR>
<P>
<MENU>
The Bloomington campus of Indiana University was confronted with a problem common to today's computer-rich campuses: its University Computing Services department needed to grow its computer network to better serve the school's faculty, staff, and students.
</MENU>
<P>
<B>North Carolina School of Science and Mathematics</B><BR>
<P>
<MENU>
Last fall, the mathematics department began offering calculus to advanced high school students at two remote sites. 
</MENU>
<P>
<B>Old Dominion University</B><BR>
<P>
<MENU>
At Old Dominion University in Norfolk, VA, students can take part in one of the largest distance learning programs in the U.S.
</MENU>
<P>

<B>Case Western Reserve University</B><BR>
<P>
<MENU>
The implementation of CWRUnet, a strictly fiber optic cable from the main wiring system has enabled data, voice, and video transmissions.
</MENU>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
Page 34<BR>
<B>On the Internet</B><BR>
"Wide-Angle Searching on the World Wide Web"<BR>
by Lillian Biermann Wehmeyer<BR>
<P>
Just as the largest network of them all, the Internet, continues to grow at a staggering rate, the World Wide Web is expanding dramatically, spawning widely scattered and diverse collections of information. The author reviews tools for "wide-angle" searching on the World Wide Web.<BR>
<P>
In writing this piece, I find myself torn between two messages. The first of these is that the Internet, and especially the World Wide Web, offers a vast and expanding resource of current information for our own research and for teaching. The second, on the other hand, is that the Internet is still a relatively meager source of information when stacked against all the resources that could be assembled on any given subject. To put it another way, libraries still have an important place, at least for the foreseeable future. But having made that point, let me return to the burgeoning wealth in the virtual realm of cyberspace.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
Page 38<BR>
<B>Quantitative Tools</B><BR>
by Jason Osborne<BR>
<P>
In this column, the author offers readers a number of Web resources for mathematics education.
<P>
<B>The Fractal Microscope</B><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Edu/Fractal/Fractal_Home.html">http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Edu/Fractal/Fractal_Home.html</A><BR>
A brief page devoted to integrating fractal geometry into the classroom, particularly using NCSA's Fractal Microscope program, which is available for downloading.
<P>
<B>The Gallery of Interactive Geometry</B><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.geom.umn.edu/apps/gallery.html">http://www.geom.umn.edu/apps/gallery.html</A><BR>
College-level geometry students will enjoy the ability to explore advanced concepts in geometry here.
<BR>
<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
