<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Syllabus '96 Highlights</TITLE>


<!-- Date: Friday, October 11, 1996  12:00 PM -->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/syll96HL.gif"ALT="graphic" hspace=0  ALIGN=center></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Syllabus '96 Highlights</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>S</FONT> yllabus '96 was a success with all areas of the conference showing tremendous growth and expansion. Sonoma State University co-sponsored the event, which witnessed the convergence of more than 1,700 educators onto the campus, ready to participate in the annual conference.<BR>
<P>
<B>Insights into Education Technology</B><BR>
Keynotes were given by such notables as <A HREF="http://http://www.oit.itd.umich.edu/~cberger/ ">Carl Berger</A>, director of Academic Information Processes at the University of Michigan, John Warnock, CEO of Adobe Systems Inc., and <A HREF="http://http://www.iat.unc.edu/publications/graves/graves.html ">Bill Graves</A>, associate provost for Information Technology and founder of the IAT. In another keynote session, attendees participated in a live video conference with the celebrated maestro and violinist Pinchas Zukerman and observed him giving music lessons to two local violin students from a distance of more than 3,000 miles away.
<P>
<B>A Focus on Classroom Technologies</B><BR>
Monday, the first day of the conference, focused on <A HREF="syll96_speak_mon.htm">classroom technologies</A>. A variety of breakout sessions expanded on technologies explored in keynote presentations: New tools available to faculty were presented by the <A HREF="syll96_speak_mon.htm#1a">New Media</A> Centers. A panel consisting of industry leaders presented their companies' positions and directions regarding education technology. Teaching faculty discussed issues regarding technology in their courses and classrooms from a front-line perspective.
<P>
Afternoon breakout sessions included case studies the areas of music, history, mathematics, psychology, biology, and chemistry. Attendees learned how instructors in each of these areas have incorporated technology into teaching their respective disciplines.
<P>
<B>An Exploration of Web-Based Environments for Teaching and Learning</B><BR>
Tuesday's sessions examined a new and often controversial model taking hold in higher education: <A HREF="syll96_speak_tues.htm">Web-based learning environments</A>. Presenters led panels and discussed their experiences with the Web, how it has enhanced their teaching, and what steps others need to take to have the smoothest transition to this medium. An industry panel offered varied outlooks on the topic of the Internet and technology. Industry representatives also gave sneak previews of where Web-based technologies are headed.
<P>
Additional break-out sessions consisted of case study presentations by instructors in a variety of disciplines on incorporating the Web in teaching. Topics covered such diverse areas as using the Web to facilitate instruction in an opera history course, hypertext/hypermedia foreign language software, dance and the arts in cyberspace, creating a virtual community for sociology, Web-based meteorology courses, and online writing clinics. These sessions featured enlightening experiences shared by presenters as they related their personal stories and offered demonstrations on how they teach with technology.
<P>
<B>Issues of Infrastructure and Implementation</B><BR>
The last day of the conference focused on <A HREF="syll96_speak_wed.htm">implementing technology in educational institutions</A>. Attendees heard faculty panels discussing the foundations for technology implementation on campus, infrastructure issues, creative ideas on how to acquire funding, and what steps smaller colleges can take to begin the implementation process. Attendees also learned about strategies for planning and financing large-scale technology programs.
<P>
<B>Experiencing Technology: Exhibits, Hands-On Labs, and Workshops</B><BR>
The conference enjoyed the largest exhibitor list in its history with more than 60 <A HREF="sconf96_exhibits.html">companies</A> displaying their latest offerings. Special technology seminars allowed hands-on participation in state-of-the-art computer labs for experiencing the latest innovations first-hand, and free access to open labs offered participants plenty of practice time to develop their skills in using different media. In addition, attendees could take part in both pre-conference and post-conference workshops to learn everything from animation on the Web to developing outstanding classroom presentations.
<P>
<B>Audio Tapes and Proceedings Available</B><BR>
Syllabus Press is making audio tapes available of the main sessions of the Syllabus '96 conference and is also offering a printed copy of the conference proceedings. 
<P>
<B>Future Syllabus Conferences and Workshops</B><BR>
Syllabus Press is proud to announce a fourth annual Syllabus conference, to be held once again next summer at Sonoma State University on July 26-30, 1997. A <A HREF="papercall97.html">Call for Papers and Presentations</A> contains guidelines for submission. 
<P>
The <A HREF="pitt96_cover.htm">Syllabus Workshops '96-'97</A> series of intensive workshops covering critical academic technologies is also continuing and expanding. The first workshops took place last spring in Miami, Fla. The next stop will be in Philadelphia, Pa. at Duquesne University on Nov. 8-10, 1996. Plans are currently being mapped out for workshops to be held throughout the country and internationally.
<P>
 SyllabusWeb will keep you up-to-date with announcements on workshop locations, or call 1-800-773-0670.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
