<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>PreConference Workshops</TITLE><!-- Date: Friday, December 15, 1995  2:25 PM --></HEAD><BODY BACKGROUND="images/sconf_bkground.gif"> <BODY LINK="#161BFF"><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><B>Pre-Conference</B><P>| <A HREF="sconf96_cvr.html">Syllabus '96 Cover</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_agenda.html">Syllabus '96 Agenda</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_mon.html">Monday</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_tues.html">Tuesday</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_wed.html">Wednesday</A> |<BR>| <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html">Faculty and Presenters</A> |<A HREF="sconf96_exhibits.html">Exhibits and Technology Demonstrations</A> | <BR>| <A HREF="sconf96_travel.html">Housing and Transportation</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_reg.html">Registration</A> |<P><A HREF="receive_credit_sconf96.htm">Receive Academic Credits for Attending Syllabus</A><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><p><B><CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>The Pre-Conference Workshops:</FONT></CENTER></B> <B><CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>July 20 - 21</FONT></CENTER></B><P><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><BR><FONT SIZE=5>Pre-Conference Workshops-at-a-Glance</FONT><P><TABLE WIDTH=100% BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=5 CELLSPACING=1><TR>    <TD></TD>    <TD></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><B>Saturday, July 20 - 9 AM-4 PM</B></TD>    <TD><B>Sunday, July 21 - 9 AM-4 PM</B></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD>Beginning Workshops:</TD>    <TD>Beginning Workshops:</TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa1">Multimedia Content Development-Macintosh</A></TD>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa3">Developing Outstanding Classroom Presentations-Macintosh</A></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa2">Multimedia Basics-Windows</A></TD>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa3">Developing Outstanding Classroom Presentations-Windows</A></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa3">Developing Outstanding Classroom Presentations-Macintosh</A></TD>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#su1">Multimedia Authoring-Macintosh</A></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa3">Developing Outstanding Classroom Presentations-Windows</A></TD>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa4">The World Wide Web in Education</A></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa4">The World Wide Web in Education</A></TD>    <TD> <B>Advanced Workshops:</B></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><B>Advanced Workshops:</B></TD>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#su2">Advanced Multimedia-Windows</A></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa5">Developing Courses for the World Wide Web</A></TD>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa5">Developing Courses for the World Wide Web</A></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa6">Multimedia on the World Wide Web</A></TD>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa6">Multimedia on the World Wide Web</A></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa7">Multimedia Design and Interfaces</A></TD>    <TD><A HREF="sconf96_preconf.html#sa7">Multimedia Design and Interfaces</A></TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD></TD>    <TD></TD>  </TR></TABLE><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><TABLE WIDTH=50% BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=2 CELLSPACING=1>  <TR>    <TD><B>(BEG)</B></TD>    <TD>Beginning. Indicates entry level course; no  previous experience with technology required.</TD>  </TR>  <TR>    <TD><B>(ADV)</B></TD>    <TD>Advanced. Requires some skills as prerequisites.</TD>  </TR></TABLE<P><BR><A NAME="saturday"></A><B><FONT SIZE=5>Saturday, July 20</FONT></B><BR><B><FONT SIZE=4>Full-day workshops (9:00AM-4:00PM with breaks, additional fees required)</FONT></B><br><p><br><A NAME="sa1"></A><LI><B><FONT SIZE=4>Multimedia Content Development-Macintosh (BEG)</FONT></B><BR><B>Workshop leaders: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Judith Stern">Judith Stern</A> and <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Robert Lettieri">Robert Lettieri</A>, University of California at Berkeley</B><br>In this hands-on workshop, participants will be introduced to the tools and concepts used for creating interactive multimedia. We will cover the steps involved in multimedia development and participants will use tools for editing graphics, sound, digital video, as well as tools for animation. These tools will be used to create and edit content for a multimedia project. (Prerequisite: basic Macintosh skills.)<P><A NAME="sa2"></A><LI><B><FONT SIZE=4>Multimedia Basics-Windows (BEG)</FONT></B><BR><B>Workshop leader: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Willem J. A. Pet">Bill Pet</A>, Institute for Academic Technology, University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill</B><BR>A hands-on workshop for those who have little or no familiarity with multimedia technology in the Windows environment. Incorporate graphics, digital audio, digital video, and animation into a presentation. Other topics covered include design techniques, video and audio capture, and basic editing techniques. Applications used: Asymetrix Multimedia ToolBook, Asymetrix Digital Video Producer, VidCap.<P><A NAME="sa3"></A><LI> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Developing Outstanding Classroom Presentations-Macintosh or Windows (BEG)</FONT></B><BR><B>Workshop leaders: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Tom L. Hall">Tom Hall</A>, Pitt Community College, Greenville, NC; <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#William H. Riffee">William H. Riffee</A>, University of Texas at Austin</B> <BR>Intended for those who have little or no familiarity with multimedia technology in Windows or Macintosh, two separate workshops will focus on building classroom presentations using presentation software such as PowerPoint, Compel, or Astound. Topics covered will include designing, building, and editing the presentation along with the addition of graphics. The use of a color scanner and digital camera for graphics will be demonstrated.  Included also will be how other multimedia components such as audio and video can be used in your presentation. You will also be shown how to use a program such as PaintShop Pro to work with digital images.<P><A NAME="sa4"></A><LI> <B><FONT SIZE=4>The World Wide Web in Education (BEG)</FONT></B><BR><B>Workshop leader: Tom Goodrich, Stanford University</B><BR>A hands-on introduction to the use of the Internet and World Wide Web for gathering and distributing educational resources. This workshop is intended for those who have used the Internet mainly for e-mail, or not at all. You will learn the basics of using the World Wide Web and how to apply it to your own education environment. Included is an introduction to the development of home pages using hypertext markup language (HTML). Numerous examples of web use in education will be highlighted throughout this workshop.<P><A NAME="sa5"></A><LI> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Developing Courses for the World Wide Web  (ADV)</FONT></B><br><B>Workshop leader: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Robert Cavalier">Robert Cavalier</A>, Carnegie Mellon University</B><BR>This intensive one-day session assumes proficiency in using the Web and a cursory understanding of HTML. Participants are expected to bring their course materials with them. By the end of this workshop, each participant will have their own WWW home page. Topics covered include an overview of HTML and the use of HTML editors. Emphasis will be on converting course syllabi and lecture outlines into Web-based course materials. Participants will create well-designed class-based pages with relevant links, tables, and graphics. The development of FORMS and communication capabilities will also be explored. The session will also provide a preview of advanced Web environments (such as Java).<P><A NAME="sa6"></A><LI> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Multimedia on the World Wide Web (ADV)</FONT></B><BR><B>Workshop leader: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Charles Kerns">Charles Kerns</A>, Stanford University; <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Rachel S. Wilson">Rachel S. Wilson</A>, Stanford University<BR> </B>This workshop teaches you how to create graphics, digitize images, and compress video for display on the Web. It assumes that you have learned to create a basic text Web page and want to add multimedia elements to your site. In the first half of the workshop, you learn how to create graphic banners that show where you are, where you can go, and how your site is organized. You will see how to create graphics that load quickly and are visually effective. Later, you will learn to digitize, crop, compress, and color correct images. Then you will convert your image files to formats that will display on the Web. Finally, you will digitize short video clips and prepare them for Web display. At the end of the class you will have Web pages, complete with video, images, and graphics, ready to take home and start your own site. The class will be taught using Macintosh computers, but the pages you create will play on most Web browsers, regardless of the computing platform. <P><A NAME="sa7"></A><LI> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Multimedia Design and Interfaces: Principles You Can "Virtually" Bank On (ADV)</FONT></B><BR><B>Workshop leader: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Douglas Chute">Doug Chute</A>, Drexel University</B> <BR>This workshop is intended for software, Web page, and multimedia developers who know they are supposed to work in high-powered, managed teams with programmers, instructional designers, artists, content experts, marketing, and video and audio professionals. Because such teams are not "reality" for most academic products, this workshop provides basic principles of design and interface-especially relevant if you are in the category of "doing-it-mostly-yourself-by-necessity." The workshop will emphasize skill development in creating publishable projects for the academic market. Basic multimedia and Web skills are a pre-requisite for this workshop. Topics to be covered include: interface design, selecting authoring tools, graphics, content development, and finding a publisher. <P><A NAME="sunday"></A><FONT SIZE=5><B>Sunday, July 21</B></FONT><br><B><FONT SIZE=4>Full-day workshops (9:00AM-4:00PM with breaks, additional fees required)</FONT></B> <P><br><A NAME="su1"></A><LI> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Multimedia Authoring-Macintosh (BEG)</FONT></B><br><B>Workshop leaders: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Judith Stern">Judith Stern</A> and <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Robert Lettieri">Robert Lettieri</A>, University of California at Berkeley</B> <BR>During this session, we will introduce multimedia authoring tools. Participants will author simple interactive projects which will incorporate graphics, audio, and video created during the previous day's session or sample files. (Intended as a follow up to Multimedia Basics on Saturday. Prerequisite: basic Macintosh skills.)<P><A NAME="su2"></A><LI> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Advanced Multimedia-Windows</FONT></B><br><B>Workshop leader: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Willem J. A. Pet">Bill Pet</A>, Institute for Academic Technology, University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill. </B> <br>A hands-on workshop for those who have some familiarity with Windows multimedia technology (builds from Saturday's session on multimedia basics). Participants will use a variety of hardware and software tools including digital video editing and effects tools (either Asymetrix Digital Video Producer or Adobe Premier), image manipulation software (Paint Shop Pro), graphic design tools (Asymetrix 3-D FX), audio editing tools, and multimedia authoring systems (Asymetrix ToolBook) in order incorporate multimedia in a simple interactive application. Other topics covered include design consideration and video and audio capture and compression.<p><br><I><B><FONT SIZE=4>Workshops repeated from Saturday</FONT></B></I><P><br><li> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Developing Outstanding Classroom Presentations-Macintosh or Windows (BEG)</FONT></B><br><B>Workshop leaders: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Tom L. Hall">Tom Hall</A>, Pitt Community College, Greenville, NC;<A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#William H. Riffee">William H. Riffee</A>, University of Texas at Austin</B><p><li><B><FONT SIZE=4>The World Wide Web in Education (BEG)</FONT></B><br><B>Workshop leader: Tom Goodrich, Stanford University</B><p><li><B><FONT SIZE=4>Developing Courses for the World Wide Web  (ADV)</FONT></B><br><B>Workshop leader:<A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Robert Cavalier">Robert Cavalier</A>, Carnegie Mellon University</B><br>(Recommended as a follow-up course for those who took the World Wide Web in Education)<p><br><LI> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Multimedia on the World Wide Web (ADV)</FONT></B> <BR><B>Workshop leader: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Charles Kerns">Charles Kerns</A>, Stanford University; <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Rachel S. Wilson">Rachel S. Wilson</A>, Stanford University<BR></b>(Recommended as a follow-up course for those who took the World Wide Web in Education)<p><li> <B><FONT SIZE=4>Multimedia Design and Interfaces (ADV)</FONT></B><br><B>Workshop leader: <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html#Douglas Chute">Doug Chute</A>, Drexel University</B><br>(Recommended as a follow-up course to Multimedia Basics)<p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT><P><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>July 21 5:00-7:30 pm</FONT></CENTER><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Opening Reception and</FONT></CENTER><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Wine Tasting</FONT></CENTER><p><CENTER>Please join us for a relaxing evening of fine wine and food</FONT></CENTER><p><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=LEFT>| <A HREF="sconf96_cvr.html">Syllabus '96 Cover</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_agenda.html">Syllabus '96 Agenda</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_mon.html">Monday</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_tues.html">Tuesday</A> | <A HREF="sconf96_wed.html">Wednesday</A> |<BR>| <A HREF="sconf96_faculty.html">Faculty and Presenters</A> |<A HREF="sconf96_exhibits.html">Exhibits and Technology Demonstrations</A> | <BR>| <A HREF="sconf96_travel.html">Housing and Transportation</A> |