<html><header><title>Syllabus Press Release</title></header><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><p><h1><center>Syllabus '96 Press Announcement</center></h1><p><hr size="4"><p>CONTACTS:<br><p>John Noon, Publisher,<br> 				Syllabus Press Inc.<br>(408) 746-2000<br>jnoon@syllabus.com<p>Mark Resmer, Associate Vice President,<br> Information Technologies<br>Sonoma State University<br>(707) 664-2889<br>resmer@sonoma.edu<br><p><br><center>New Conference on Educational Technology<br><font size="10">Grows Significantly</font></center><h1><center>Syllabus '96 returns to Sonoma State University in 1996 (July 20-24)</center></h1><p><br>SUNNYVALE, Calif.- Over 1,000 educators from around the world attended the <a href="syllconf.html#syll95">Syllabus '95</a> Conference held in late July at Sonoma State University, about a one-hour drive north of San Francisco. This is a significant increase from the 150 attendees at the Syllabus '94 conference held at UC-Santa Cruz in July 1994. Also, more than 40 major technology companies <a href="scon959.html">exhibited</a> or <a href="scon959.html">sponsored</a> tutorial sessions, including <a href="scon959.html#Adobe Systems Inc">Adobe Systems Inc.</a>, <a href="scon959.html#Eastman Kodak">Eastman Kodak,</a> <a href="scon959.html#Lotus">Lotus Development,</a> and <a href="scon959.html#Macromedia">Macromedia,</a> to name a few.<p>The conference featured demonstrations of how technologies such as the <a href="syll95tues.html">Internet</a> and <a href="syll95mon.html">multimedia</a> can be used to improve education. Several professors conducted live Internet sessions, accessing World Wide Web sites while delivering lectures on subjects as diverse as philosophy, geography, and anthropology. The weekend before the conference featured hands-on workshops that covered multimedia authoring and publishing, using educational resources on the Internet, and developing educational home pages for the World Wide Web. <P><center><strong>Page 2</strong></center><p>Syllabus '95 attendees hailed from the across the U.S., as well as Canada, Mexico, Europe, and Asia, comprising the critical stake holders in educational technologies:  66% of the attendees were faculty and 34% administrators.<p>"What a pleasure it was to have the Syllabus Conference at Sonoma State University,"  said Ruben Arminana, President, Sonoma State University. "Educating students of the '90s requires a strong focus on technology. The 1995 Syllabus Conference at Sonoma State University gave faculty numerous innovative methods for integrating that technology into their coursework." <p>Syllabus '96, to be held July 20-24, 1996, will return to Sonoma State university. The 1996 conference program will include expanded plenary sessions, more case study presentations, and a larger selection of pre-conference workshops. Also, the number of exhibits and vendor sessions will double.<p>The Syllabus conference is produced and co-sponsored by Syllabus Press, publishers of Syllabus  magazine, which covers how technology is used in teaching and learning at the secondary and post-secondary levels. Syllabus magazine reaches more than 200,000 educators world-wide. The co-sponsor of the conference is Sonoma State University, part of the large California State University system. Sonoma State recently provided multimedia-capable personal computers for all of their permanent faculty.<p>For further information or to receive a complete conference registration package, contact Syllabus Press at (800) 773-0670 or e-mail: <a href="info_conf96.html">syll96@syllabus.com</a>.  Postal address: 1307 S. Mary Avenue, Suite 211, Sunnyvale, CA 94087. Fax: 408-746-2711. Submissions for presentations will be accepted by e-mail: jnoon@syllabus.com, or by fax at 408-746-2711. The latest Syllabus '96 information can also be found on the World Wide Web at http://www.syllabus.com.<p>Syllabus Press is a registered trademark of Syllabus Press Inc. Syllabus, the Syllabus Press logo, Syllabus '96, and the Syllabus conferences are trademarks of Syllabus Press Inc. All other trademarks belong to their respective owners.<p><center>#####</center><p><hr size=4><A HREF="syllconf.html"><H3>Back to Syllabus Conference Page</H3></a><hr size=4><address>Copyright &copy; 1995 by Syllabus Press, Inc. All rights reserved.</address></body></html>
