<HEADER>
<TITLE>Desktop Computer Buyer's Guide</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<body>
<h2><strong>Desktop Computer Buyer's Guide</strong></h2>
<hr>
Desktop vendors continue to provide users with a variety of desktop computers that offer a range of technologies. The latest generation of desktop computers features a choice of the richest features and most powerful microprocessors yet. Personal computers based on new Intel 486DX4, Pentium, and Motorola/IBM microprocessors are capable of presenting full-motion video and running the newest software at high speeds. Workstations using fast RISC microprocessors continue to deliver high-speed computing for scientific and engineering applications. Other features, including the Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) bus, built-in CD-ROMs, and high-capacity hard drives, are giving users access to large amounts of multimedia and other data types. The newest computers also give users more value, integrating a host of video, audio, telephony, and networking functions for a low price. What follows is a survey of 13 vendors' latest desktop technologies. 
<p>
<strong>Apple Computer Inc.</strong><br>
Last spring, Apple Computer Inc. introduced the first PowerPC-based Macintosh computers: the Power Macintosh 6100/60, Power Macintosh 7100/66, and Power Macintosh 8100/80. When running optimized software, the RISC-based PowerPC processor can run through tasks two-to-six times faster than a Macintosh with a 68040 processor. All of the Power Macintosh models feature DRAM display support, built-in Ethernet, stereo sound input and output ports, and built-in support for most Apple and third-party displays including NTSC, PAL, VGA, and SVGA.
<p>
The 6100/60, the least expensive of the three models, is based on the 60MHz PowerPC 601 microprocessor and includes an integrated math coprocessor and a 32K on-chip cache. The 6100/60 is expandable to 72MB, has disk storage of 250MB to 350MB, and, like the 7100/66, includes built-in support for up to 32,768 colors. 
<p>
The high end of the Power Macintosh line is the 8100/80, which features a high storage capacity, nine built-in ports and three NuBus slots for expansion slots. Features include up to 1GB storage capacity, a 32K on-chip cache,  256K secondary cache, and up to 264MB DRAM. The 8100/80 is also available in an AV model that has 11 built-in ports and a 110MHz configuration. 
<p>
The fastest computer offered by Apple is the Power Macintosh 8100/110, which is powered by a 110MHz RISC-based PowerPC 601 chip. Priced at $6,379, its configuration includes 16MB RAM, a 2GB hard disk, double speed CD-ROM drive, and an Apple SuperDrive 1.4MB floppy disk drive.
<p>
 Apple is also offering a PowerPC upgrade card for its current line of entry-level computers, including the Performa and Quadra series. Many new products are currently being redesigned or created to utilize the PowerPC processor. Currently, over 330 native applications are shipping. Contact: Apple Computer Inc., Cupertino, CA; (408) 996-1010. 
<br clear=both>
<br>
<img hspace=10 align=left src="images/att.gif">
<strong>AT&T</strong><br>
In December 1994, AT&T Global Information Solutions introduced the industry's first PC with phone capabilities built-in. The new PC, called the Globalyst 360TPC, includes a speakerphone capable of transmitting voice simultaneously in two directions. The full-duplex speakerphone technology is new to the industry which previously offered only half-duplex or single direction communication capabilities. The Globalyst employs 32-bit floating point, 55MHz digital signal processing (DSP) technology, developed by AT&T Microelectronics, which provides upgradability to new functions such as name dialing and call logging. Based on the i486 DX2 66MHz processor, the ISA Mini-Tower is upgradable to Pentium. Other technical features include 8MB of memory upgradable to 64MB, 1MB standard VRAM, 420MB disk storage, six expansion slots with four open, five drive bays, 600MB dual-speed CD-ROM drive, and speakers. 
<p>
The Globalyst line of computers also includes three other new additions: the Globalyst 250, a high-end Multimedia Notebook; the Globalyst 525, a ISA/VESA Mini-Tower-i486; and the Globalyst 580 Pentium Desktop. The Globalyst 580 Pentium Desktop has a memory capacity of 8MB expandable to 128MB, PCI Local Bus video, and hard disk interface. The line comes standard with 1MB VRAM, up to 1GB of hard drive space, five expansion slots, and three drive bays. Contact: AT&T Global Information Solutions, Higher Education Program, Greenville, SC; (800) 241-1356. 
<br clear=both>
<p>
<strong>Compaq Computer Corp.</strong><br>
In December, 1994, Compaq Computer Corp. released the most powerful member of its Deskpro XL family yet, a version with a 90MHz Intel Pentium processor. The new high-end Deskpro XL 590, with a starting price of $3,999, features a PCI expansion bus and a 535MB hard drive. All Deskpro XL models come standard with 16MB RAM, a 32-bit Fast SCSI-2 controller, and 2MB VRAM. 
<p>
Compaq has also released the next generation of its 486SX2-based Presario Series of computers. The latest Presario computers include the 500, 700, and 900 Series. All of the models feature multimedia with integrated speakers, 16-bit stereo sound, and MIDI/game support. The Presario 500 Series, designed for family and home office use, includes a 14-inch monitor. The Compaq Presario Series CDS 520 and the Compaq Presario CDTV 520 feature a 486SX2/66 microprocessor, a 420MB internal hard drive, and 4MB of RAM, upgradable to 64MB. Multimedia capabilities include a double-speed CD-ROM drive, 16-bit stereo sound, built-in microphone, and 1MB VRAM, upgradable to 2MB. The CDTV 520 features a pre-installed, cable-ready television card that allows users to watch television in a scaleable "window" or listen to a broadcast while working in another application. Pricing for the 500 Series starts at $1,699.
<p>
The Compaq Presario 700 Series, which features a traditional desktop design, consists of the Presario CDS 720, which uses the 486SX/66 processor and the Presario CDS 724, which uses the 486DX2/66 processor. The 700 series comes standard with 4MB or 8MB of DRAM that can be upgraded to 100MB. Other features include a 420MB internal hard drive, 1MB VRAM upgradable to 2MB, three 16-bit ISA expansion slots and one Compaq Reserve Slot. Pricing for the 700 Series starts at $1,499.
<p>
The high-end Compaq Presario 900 Series includes the Presario CDS 920, the CDTV 920, the CDS 924, and the Presario 924, a special non-multimedia model. The CDTV 920 model has a pre-installed, cable-ready television card. Pricing starts at $1,649. The 900 Series contains the 486SX2/66 or 486DX2/66 processors, upgradable to the Pentium microprocessor. The internal hard drives range from 420MB to 525MB, and each model comes with 8MB of DRAM expandable to 100MB. The 900 Series also includes a double-speed CD-ROM drive, 16-bit stereo sound, five 16-bit ISA expansion slots, and one Compaq Reserve slot. Contact: Compaq Computer Corp., Houston, TX; (800) 345-1518. 
<br clear=both>
<br>
<img hspace=10 align=left src="images/dell.gif">
<strong>Dell Computer Corp.</strong><br>
Dell Computer Corp.  has expanded its OptiPlex, Dell OmniPlex, and Dell Dimension XPS families of desktop computers based on 75MHz and 100MHz Pentium processors. 
<p>
The Dell OptiPlex systems include the new 75MHz Pentium-based OptiPlex X575 and the 100MHz speed X5100, which have prices starting at $2,069 and $2,935, respectively. Featuring both ISA and PCI buses, the systems have integrated 64-bit PCI local bus video. 
The OmniPlex systems are based on an EISA/PCI bus architecture and provide support for the 64-bit Pentium processor, an integrated PCI/fast SCSI II subsystem, and a high-performance synchronous second-level cache for improved system performance.
The new OmniPlex 5100, priced at $4,408, features ATI's new MACH 64 video card, which is upgradable to 4MB of VRAM.
<p>
Dell has also recently released its new XPS Systems: the Dell Dimension XPS P75, based on the 75MHz Pentium processor, and Dell Dimension XPS P100, based on the 100MHz Pentium processor. Prices start at $1,869 and $2,649, respectively. The XPS line also has both ISA and PCI buses. Contact: Dell Computer Corp., Austin, TX; (512) 338-4400. 
<p>
<strong>Digital Equipment Corp.</strong><br>
Digital Equipment Corp. offers the Venturis, Celebris, and Premium lines of desktop computers. The Venturis line includes the Venturis 433SX computer, based on the 33MHz Intel 486 SX, up to the Venturis 560, which is powered by a 60MHz Pentium. Also included are full-profile configurations with five expansion slots, five device bays, and plug-and-play integration. The Celebris 466/4100/560/590 are slim-line PCs. Features include i486 and Pentium processors with an integrated PCI local bus, and 64-bit graphics acceleration. Each system comes with 8MB RAM expandable to 128MB. The high end of the computer line is the Premium line's DECpc XL 590 System, a 90MHz Pentium system that includes 8MB DRAM expandable up to 192MB. Also featured is PCI local bus architecture, a 64-bit GUI accelerator that can use up to 4MB DRAM. Contact: Digital Equipment Corp., Maynard, MA; (800) 722-9332. 
<p>
<strong>Gateway 2000</strong><br>
Gateway 2000's line of multimedia Family PCs consists of two models based on the 486 processor and three versions based on the Pentium processor. With prices starting at $1,499, the 486 Family PC comes with a double-speed CD-ROM, a fax/modem, Altec speakers, and a 14-inch SVGA color monitor. The Pentium-based systems, starting at $2,499, include the P5-60, P5-90, and the new P5-75. The Family PC Pentium line has PCI local bus graphics accelerator cards and hard drives with capacities ranging from 730 to 1GB. 
<p>
Gateway 2000's integrated systems are available in compact or mini-desktop versions, and come standard with local bus video and multiple subsystems for expansion room. The 4SX-33, priced at $1,299, is based on the Intel 486SX microprocessor, and the 4DX2-66, priced at $1,599, is based on the Intel 486DX2 microprocessor. Both systems come standard with 4MB or 8MB of RAM, a 14-inch color monitor, and an integrated PCI local bus graphics accelerator. Contact: Gateway 2000; N. Sioux City, SD; (800) 846-3606. 
<br clear=both>
<br>
<img hspace=10 align=left src="images/hpvectra.gif">
<strong>Hewlett-Packard Co.</strong><br>
Hewlett-Packard's line of PCs includes the Vectra PCs, Vectra Multimedia PCs, and the Vectra Communication PCs. Vectra Multimedia PCs combine high quality audio capabilities and the storage capacity of CD-ROMs. The multimedia PCs include a front panel volume control, microphone, headphone jacks, integrated speaker, and all-on-one-card integration. The Vectra Communication Series is for the business user and includes CD-ROM, fax/modem, and voice mail technologies. All of the components needed to send, receive, and access information are integrated on one DSP-based card. The Vectra Communication Series delivers all of the features found in the multimedia series, plus a 14.4Kbs high-speed fax/modem with data compression, FaxWorks 3.0 software, and Telephone Answering Machine software. 
<p>
The high-end HP Vectra XU PC Series includes a Pentium 90MHz processor, PCI local bus architecture, and plug-and-play functionality. The Vectra XU PCs come with an external, second-level, 256-Kbyte write-back cache. On the 5/90C model, this cache uses "burst-synchronous" technology, which yields up to 10 percent faster system performance. Users can boost the power of dual-processor-supporting operator systems by plugging a second processor into the ZIF socket. This same socket will accept the Intel OverDrive processor. The latest line of PCs are the Vectra XP Pentium processor-based series. Contact: Hewlett-Packard Co., Palo Alto, CA; (800) 637-7740. 
<p>
<strong>IBM</strong><br>
More than a year ago, IBM introduced the first PowerPC systems in the industry with the RS/6000 workstation and server line. In November, the company also introduced new IBM PC 300, 700, and Aptiva families of consumer desktops. The 700 systems are the first in the industry to offer a complete family of products using Pentium technology ranging from 75MHz to 100MHz processors.
<p>
Last October, IBM added to its RISC system/6000 line with the RS/6000 Model 40P, a low-cost PowerPC-based workstation. Based on the PowerPC processor and IBM's AIX UNIX operating system, the new RS/6000 Model 40P Entry Workstation includes two Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) interface expansion slots and three Industry Standard Architecture (ISA) bus slots. Standard features include a 66MHz PowerPC 601 microprocessor, an AIX Version 4.1.1 client operating system,16MB of memory expandable to 192MB, a 360MB hard disk expandable to 4GB, and an integrated SCSI-2 slot.
<p>
IBM's Aptiva line of multimedia PCs features systems ranging from a 33MHz 486SX to a 60MHz Pentium model. Included is a Wake Up on Ring and Scheduler, which allows users to pre-set their systems to perform certain functions, such as sending faxes. 
<p>
IBM has also redesigned its 300 and 700 systems family, reducing the number of models and lowering their cost. The 700 systems use Pentium technology and range from the new 75MHz processor for mainstream users, up to the 100MHz processor for power users. IBM PowerPC-based personal computers will be available in 1995. Contact: IBM Corp., White Plains, NY; (800) IBM-CALL. 
<p>
<strong>Micro Express</strong><br>
Micro Express, a manufacturer of notebook, laptop, portable, and desktop microcomputers, has a family of desktop PCs called the MicroFLEX-VL. The MicroFLEX-VL/P60 Pentium-based PC runs at 60MHz and includes 8MB of RAM expandable to 128MB on the motherboard. Other features include a 256K RAM cache, a 340MB hard disk drive, one 31/2" floppy disk drive, a VL local bus video card, a 15" SVGA monitor, and a standard keyboard. The MicroFLEX-VL/80G entry-level PC offers local-bus graphics and an 80MHz 486DX2 that is upgradable to DX4-100 or Pentium technology. The computer comes standard with 8MB DRAM that is expandable to 128MB. Other features include 256K cache RAM, 420MB with optional drives available to 2.4 GB. 
<p>
More offerings from Micro Express include two multimedia PCs: the MicroFLEX-VL/S/Multimedia and the MicroFLEX-VL/66/Multimedia. The VESA-standard local bus machines are available with either Cyrix CX486/40 or Intel 486DX2-66 microprocessors. Each system includes a Texel CD-ROM drive, a Media Vision Pro Audio Spectrum 16 SCSI sound card, stereo speakers, and a microphone. Configurations include a 40MHz or 66MHz CPU, a 340MB hard disk drive, and 16MB of RAM expandable to 32MB on the motherboard. The hard disk drive has a 340MB capacity with optional drives available to 2.4GB. Expansion slots consist of two 32-bit VESA Local Bus slots, five 16-bit slots and one 8-bit slot. Contact: Micro Express, Santa Ana, CA; (800) 989-9900. 
<p>
<strong>Motorola</strong><br>
Motorola has recently introduced the PowerStack family of client/server and multi-user computer systems that are based on the PowerPC 603 and PowerPC 604 microprocessors. PowerStack RISC PCs and servers include the Series E Model E603-66P, a 66MHz, a PowerPC 603 microprocessor-based, entry-level workgroup server and the E604-100P, a configuration based on a 100MHz, PowerPC 604 microprocessor. PowerStack models DT603-66 and DT604-100 are running at 66 and 100MHz, respectively. The PowerStack models use the PCI (Peripheral Component Interconnect) bus and offer a variety of memory, a SCSI device, and PCI-based expansion options. Additionally, the systems use Motorola's "snap-together" enclosure which enables users to quickly reconfigure systems to accommodate a range of performance, data storage, and interface options. The PowerStack design also enables users to configure for higher-performance systems based on future versions of the PowerPC microprocessor family. The Model E603-66P, with Windows NT 3.5, will be available in early 1995 priced starting at $5,995 for a 16MB configuration with a 1GB disk, a floppy disk, and a CD-ROM drive. Pricing for a similarly configured entry-level E604-100P starts at $7,995. Contact: Motorola Computer Group, Tempe, AZ; (800) 624-6449. 
<br clear=both>
<br>
<img hspace=10 align=left src="images/nec.gif">
<strong>NEC Technologies Inc.</strong><br>
NEC Technologies Inc.'s family of PCs includes the Image series of fast graphics PCs, Ready multimedia PCs, and the PowerMate line. 
<p>
NEC has added models to its PowerMate series of general business desktop PCs: the Model 4100M, which features the Intel 486DX4 CPU running at 100MHz; the Model 466D and the Model 466M, which are based on the 486DX2/66; and the Model 433D, which comes standard with the Intel 486SX/33 CPU. The new PowerMate D/M Series, offered in both desktop or minitower styles, features video cache RAM (VCR) technology, yielding higher resolution, more colors, and higher refresh rates for less flicker. All systems feature 1MB of VRAM, expandable to 2MB. Hard drive sizes range from 270MB to 420MB and come standard with 4MB of RAM (8MB on 4100M), expandable to 128MB. Also included are two serial ports with fast transfer rates and an enhanced high-speed parallel port that supports both ECP and EPP protocols. The PowerMate systems offer four ISA slots and one shared VL/ISA slot. To allow easy upgradability, NEC offers a ZIF (zero insertion force) socket that allows users to plug more advanced microprocessors into their existing systems. In addition, the series can accommodate up to four storage devices in desktops and five in minitower styles, enabling users to add a CD-ROM reader, tape backup, or additional disk storage to the 1.44MB drive. 
<p>
The Ready Series of multimedia PCs, designed for small offices and home users, delivers high-quality graphics performance and comes preloaded with software. The versions of the Ready Series based on the Pentium processor feature 8MB of RAM expandable to 136MB, a 420 MB hard disk drive, six device bays, and four expansion slots. The configurations based on the 486 microprocessor feature 1MB of VRAM expandable to 2MB. The low end of the line includes The Ready 433D that offers 4MB of RAM, and the high-end Ready 4100M features 8MB of RAM.
<p>
NEC has recently introduced the Image Pentium Series for the corporate user who demands high performance. The Image Pentium family combines the next generation of ImageVideo technology for graphics applications and a PCI Local Bus architecture that optimizes performance, expansion, and connectivity capabilities. The multimedia models include a 16-bit sound card, speakers, and a microphone. Starting at under $2,500, the series consists of 13 configurations ranging from the single-processor P90 models to the dual-processor P90E or P100E models. Contact: NEC Technologies Inc., Boxborough, MA; (508) 264-8000. 
<br clear=both>
<br>
<img hspace=10 align=left src="images/sgi.gif">
<strong>Silicon Graphics Inc.</strong><br>
Silicon Graphics Inc. offers a complete line of desktop workstations and graphics subsystems. The company's Indy family of desktop workstations is designed for demanding applications with built-in sound, video, and high-quality 3D graphics. The entry-level Indy workstation, priced at $4,995, includes a specially optimized 100MHz MIPS R4600 PC RISC microprocessor. All Indy systems support up to 256MB of RAM, 2GB of internal disk storage, and seven fast SCSI-2 devices. The systems come standard with the IndyCam and the Indio Magic user environment, which is a point-and-click interface that delivers the power of the IRIX multitasking operating system to users accustomed to working with Macintosh and PC systems. The Indy XL is an 8-bit and 24-bit high-resolution graphics subsystem that supports the graphics Library as well as 32-bit Z-buffering in software. The Geometry Engine graphics accelerators can manipulate 3D models with 180Mflops of computer performance. Contact: Silicon Graphics Inc., Mountain View, CA; (800) 800-7441. 
<br clear=both>
<br>
<img hspace=10 align=left src="images/sun.gif">
<strong>Sun Microsystems Computer Corp. (SMCC)</strong><br>
SMCC's desktop family ranges from low-cost color machines to high-performance computers with multiprocessing capabilities. In March, 1994, SMCC introduced the low-end SPARCstation 5, the Voyager compact desktop SPARCstation, and the SPARCstation 20 family of multiprocessing desktops. 
<p>
The SPARCstation 5 is a mid-range workstation that delivers powerful CPU performance with a 70MHz or 85MHz microSPARC II processor. The workstation also offers expandability of up to 2GB of internal storage and up to 40GB of external storage. The 70MHz SPARCstation 5 desktop, priced at $3,995, includes a 15-inch color monitor, a 535MB hard disk, and 16MB of memory. The 85MHz configuration, priced at $11,395, features a 20-inch color monitor, 32MB of memory, 1GB of storage, and the TurboGX graphics accelerator. 
<p>
The SPARCstation 20 is the new flagship of SMCC's workstation line. Available in uniprocessor and multiprocessor versions, the SPARCstation 20 is the first to use a 60MHz SuperSPARC processor in some of its models. Features include a full complement of graphics computing capabilities, such as 24-bit true color, desktop image processing performance, 3-D graphics, 2-D graphics, and accelerated video playback. Users can add up to four CPUs, increase the memory up to 512MB, increase the internal storage up to 2GB, and add up to four SBus peripheral cards. The SPARCstation 20 is available in six versions, starting at a price of $12,195. SMCC's newest addition to the SPARCstation 20-workstation family is the SPARCstation 20 Model HS11, a high-end desktop aimed at computer-intensive technical applications such as simulation, electronic design, analysis, and modeling. Model HS11 runs on the HyperSPARC processor.
<p>
Based on the microSPARC II processor, the SPARCstation Voyager features 16 to 80MB of RAM, a 340MB hard drive, TurboGX 8-bit color graphics acceleration, two PCMCIA slots, and infrared serial interface. In addition to a standard Ethernet connection, the SPARCstation Voyager supports remotely networked client-server operation via a modem and telephone line so users can connect into their network from any location. Pricing starts at $9,995 and includes an active-matrix LCD. Contact: Sun Microsystems Computer Corp., Mountain View, CA; (800) 821-4643.
