<html><Header><Title>Internet Buyer's Guide</Title></Header><body><h2><strong>Internet Buyer's Guide</strong></h2><hr>Besides the shareware and freeware tools that have evolved for mining and navigating the Internet, many commercial products have been developed for Internet users. Below, we've highlighted just a few of the latest software and hardware products, books, and starter kits currently available for purchase.<hr><strong>Connectivity and Communications Software</strong><br><br><strong>PageNOW! 1.0 Personal Edition</strong><br>PageNOW! 1.0 from Mark/Space Softworks is connectivity software for the Macintosh that allows a wireless link to the Internet. The application can forward Internet/LAN e-mail, faxes, voice mail, database files, and other system messages to alphanumeric pagers. Features include a complete e-mail forwarding to text pagers with Eudora, as well as from commercial on-line services, and LAN e-mail forwarding with Lotus cc:Mail. $79.95. Contact: Mark/Space Softworks, San Jose, CA; (408) 293-7299. <p><strong>PathWay Access 3.0</strong><br>PathWay Access 3.0 by The Wollongong Group is a TCP/IP product that combines an intuitive graphical user interface with terminal emulation and advanced graphical terminal emulation. Other features include drag-and-drop FTP, FTP scripting capability, keyboard remapping and macro keys, an e-mail client, and news reader. Contact: The Wollongong Group Inc., Palo Alto, CA; (415) 962-7100.<p><strong>SuperHighway Access</strong><br>Frontier Corp. has introduced SuperHighway Access, a Windows-based Internet communication software package. Included is Tapestry, a graphical application for accessing the Internet's Archie, Gopher, Wide Area Information Servers, and World Wide Web servers. The software includes Multipurpose Internet Mail Extension support, which lets users send and view mail messages with attached graphics, spreadsheets, sound, and video. The package supports PPP and the Serial Line IP. SuperHighway Access' SLIP provides WAN and LAN-to-WAN Internet Protocol routing support. $149. Frontier Corp., Mequon, WI; (414) 241-4555.<p><strong>TCP/Connect II 2.0</strong><br>TCP/Connect II 2.0 is communications software for the Macintosh that can provide connectivity to the Internet. The application provides multimedia support, MIME-compliant e-mail, a Gopher client for Internet access, Point-to-Point Protocol implementation, and automatic decoding of all incoming files, including FTP. TCP/Connect II 2.0 presents TCP/IP features such as FTP and Gopher through intuitive Macintosh dialogs and icons, and drag-and-drop functionality. $195. Contact: InterCon Systems Corp., Herndon, VA; (703) 709-5500. <p><strong>TCP/Connect II Remote</strong><br>InterCon Systems Corp. has released TCP/ConnectII Remote Internet access software. With TCP/ConnectII Remote, users can exchange e-mail messages, access network news, and locate and download files from the Internet as well as from their corporate networks. TCP/Connect II Remote supports telnet, FTP, Gopher clients, e-mail, and network news. $195. Contact: InterCon Systems Corp., Herndon, VA; (703) 709-5500.<br><p><img hspace=10 align=left src="images/vrsaterm.gif"><strong>VersaTerm and VersaTerm-PRO</strong><br>Synergy Software's VersaTerm and VersaTerm-PRO are terminal emulation and communications applications for Macintosh computers. Users can create macros, use multitasking capabilities, and work with all commonly used Internet clients in a single integrated face. Additional features include a built-in spellchecker, scratchpad text editor, and automatic compression/decompression via Aladdin's StuffIt. VersaTerm is $195 and VersaTerm-PRO is $295. Contact: Synergy Software, Reading, PA; (215) 779-0522.<br clear=both><hr><strong>E-Mail Interfaces</strong><br><br clear=both><br><img hspace=10 align=left src="images/eudora.gif"><strong>Eudora 2.1</strong><br>QUALCOMM Inc. is offering Eudora 2.1, the latest commercial version of the popular Macintosh e-mail application for the Internet. Eudora 2.1 adds performance enhancements as well as a new graphical user interface and network security functions. The speed of sending files with attachments has been increased to 150 percent. Interface enhancements include color coding of messages, a new sorting feature, and the capability to drag and drop messages from one mailbox to another. Security features include support for Kerberos authentication, which eliminates the need to transfer text passwords through the network. $65. Contact: QUALCOMM Inc., San Diego, CA; (800) 2-EUDORA.<p><strong>Mail*Link Internet for PowerTalk 1.5</strong><br>StarNine Technologies Inc. has introduced Mail*Link Internet for PowerTalk 1.5, a gateway application that links the universal mailbox in Apple's System 7.5 with Internet mail services. Mail*Link provides users with dial-up modem connections to the Internet via either SLIP (Serial Line IP) or PPP (Point-to-Point Protocol). Version 1.5 adds support for AppleScript, allowing the gateway to communicate with other applications, including StarNine's Mail*Link Monitor and NotifyMail, a system extension that notifies users when new mail arrives. The updated version of the gateway can connect either automatically or manually via SLIP or PPP. $49. Contact: StarNine Technologies Inc., Berkeley, CA; (510) 649-4949.<hr><strong>File Transfer and Document Sharing Software</strong><br><br><strong>A+ Texture Access 1.1</strong><br>Amdahl recently released A+ Texture Access 1.1, an application for SPARC-based servers and workstations that allows corporate users to access Internet information as easily as documents on their own network. A+ Texture Access is a World Wide Web browser that supports multiple Mosaic sessions running on a single server. A WAIS index server and customized extensions allow multiple search requests from the end-user interface. The product also supports WAIS and will soon support multiple WAIS sessions. It comes bundled with FTP and HyperText Markup Language (HTML), along with audio and video viewers for common Web formats. $250 single user. Contact: Amdahl, Sunnyvale, CA; (408) 746-6000. <p><strong>Adobe Acrobat 2.0</strong><br>Adobe Acrobat 2.0 is software that allows users to access, manage, and use electronic documents across diverse computing platforms. Version 2.0 provides direct access to electronic information, document security features, and comes with more than 500 Application Programming Interfaces (APIs). Adobe Acrobat 2.0 includes Acrobat Search, which lets users retrieve PDF files by conducting full-text searches of indexed PDF files and Acrobat Reader, a tool for viewing, navigating, and printing electronic documents. $595. Contact: Adobe Systems Inc., Mountain View, CA; (800) 833-6687. <p><strong>Snatcher</strong><br>Software Ventures Corp. is offering Snatcher, a file transfer program for the Macintosh that uses Apple's System 7.5 to put a familiar graphical user interface on the Internet. Snatcher enables users to open Finder-like windows to Internet computers and displays the files and folders as icons. Users can view the contents of any Internet file directory by icon, small icon, name, date, kind, or size. To transfer files, users can drag-and-drop icons between windows. $50. Contact: SoftwareVentures Corp., Berkeley, CA; (510) 644-3232. <p><strong>Interfaces and Navigation Tools Air Series 3.0</strong><br>The Air Series is a line of client software for the Internet that features support for Mosaic. Version 3.0 supports PPP for dial-up connections and dial-on demand, which is software that allows applications to initiate an Internet connection automatically when they are launched. New e-mail features allow users to save messages in separate folders. The software includes image viewers for GIF, JPEG, bitmap, and Targa files, with links to Mosaic. The software comes in several configurations, ranging from the $199 Air Navigator, which includes Mosaic, Gopher, mail, and netnews, to the $499 Air NFS, which includes telnet, FTP, Mosaic, mail, news, Gopher, 3270 terminal emulation, and NFS. Contact: Spry Inc., Seattle, WA; (206) 447-0300. <p><strong>Enhanced NCSA Mosaic 1.0</strong><br>Spyglass' Enhanced NCSA Mosaic1.0, the commercial version of NCSA Mosaic, is a graphical Internet browser for Windows, Macintosh, and UNIX. Version 1.0 includes faster performance, user interface improvements, and reduced memory requirements. Other features include forms support, which allows two-way communication between users and Web servers; and proxy gateway support for security in networked environments. Contact: Spyglass Inc., Savoy, IL; (217) 355-6000. <p><strong>Mosaic NetScape</strong><br>Mosaic NetScape by Mosaic Communications Corp. is a network navigator that offers a user-friendly interface for serving and accessing multimedia over the Internet. The application includes security features such as encryption and server authentication. Other features include native support for the JPEG image format and continuous document streaming, which enables users to interact with documents while waiting for them to be downloaded, allowing several documents to be downloaded simultaneously. Contact: Mosaic Communications Corp., Mountain View, CA; (800) NETSITE.<p><strong>WinGopher</strong><br>WinGopher is a graphical interface for navigating the Internet. The software consists of a Microsoft Windows-based client that interacts with Gopher servers as well as with Archie, Veronica, telnet, and TN3270 protocols. WinGopher provides pull-down menus and point-and-click functionality. A Collections feature allows users to save locations so that they can return to them without having to follow the same long pathway. Other features are support for sound, text, and various types of image files. $69.95. Contact: Notis Systems Inc., Evanston, IL; (800) 55-NOTIS.<p><strong>WinPAC</strong><br>WinPAC by NOTIS Systems Inc. is a Windows-based graphical interface to Z39.50 and Gopher databases on the Internet. Capabilities include searches by authors, titles, and subjects. Other searching capabilities include browsing, hypertext links for search expansion, retained search histories, and use of the boolean operators "and," "or," and "not." WinPAC includes all the functionality of WinGopher, plus Archie, Veronica, WAIS, and telnet. $99. NOTIS Systems Inc. also is offering WinPAC Complete, which contains WinPAC, Winsock-compliant TCP/IP software, and information about Internet SLIP/PPP access services. $169. Contact: NOTIS Systems Inc., Evanston, IL; (800) 55-NOTIS. <hr><strong>Internet Server Product</strong><br><br><strong>Mosaic NetSite</strong><br>The Mosaic NetSite server line, which runs UNIX-based platforms, is comprised of two main products: the Mosaic NetSite Communications Server and the Mosaic NetSite Commerce Server. The Communications Server is designed for organizations that want to deliver non-secure multimedia content, e.g., on-line marketing materials for existing or potential customers, customer support information, or free software updates. The Commerce Server includes the features of the Communications Server, as well as having additional security functions for delivering secure content across global networks. A promotional price of $1,495 is being offered for the Communications Server; the Commerce Server is $25,000. Contact: Mosaic Communications Corp., Mountain View, CA; (800) NETSITE. <hr><strong>Books on the Internet</strong><br><br><strong>!%@:: A Directory of Electronic Mail Addressing & Networks</strong><br>An up-to-date directory that charts the networks making up the Internet. Included are more than 190 networks, an index to networks indexed by name, country or area, and country code. Also included is an index to second- and third-level domains and many sites within each network. $9.95. Contact: O'Reilly & Assoc., Inc. Sebastopol, CA; (800) 998-9938. <p><strong>Connecting to the Internet</strong><br>Connecting to the Internet: An O'Reilly Buyer's Guide shows users how to determine which Internet service best fits their needs. The guide also describes how to find a local access provider and evaluate the services it offers. Connecting to the Internet also includes appendices listing public access service providers. $15.95. Contact: O'Reilly & Assoc., Inc. Sebastopol, CA; (800) 998-9938. <p> <strong>Hands-On Internet</strong><br>Published by Prentice Hall, Hands-On Internet is a guide for beginners who wish to navigate the Internet. Included are exercises that show users how to connect and find information on the Internet. The book covers such topics as logging onto your account, Usenet News, mailing lists, FTP, Archie, Gopher, WAIS, and WWW. The final section contains a reference, review, and useful appendices. $29.95. Contact: Prentice Hall, Englewood Cliffs, NJ; (800) 223-1360. <br clear=both><br><img hspace=10 align=left src="images/tracy.gif"><strong>The Internet Companion, Second Edition</strong><br>Addison-Wesley has released the second edition of Tracy LaQuey's bestseller The Internet Companion, A Beginner's Guide to Global Networking. The guide, written in non-technical language, covers the latest developments of the Internet, explores its growing commercialization, and examines the advantages of using the Internet for business. The book also reveals ways to tap into university databases, on-line archives, and where to gather the most up-to-date information available on the Internet. $12.95. Contact: Addison-Wesley Publishing Co., Reading, MA.<br clear=both><br><strong>The Internet for Everyone: A Guide for Users and Providers</strong><br>In this comprehensive guide to the Internet, Richard Wiggins instructs both new and experienced users on the basics of the Internet, including FTP, telnet, Gopher, WAIS, World Wide Web, Mosaic, and more. In more than 600 pages, Wiggins gives a history of the Internet, explains the protocols and tools, gives examples on conducting information searches on the net, describes methods of becoming an Internet service provider, and gives scores of references to information resources. $29.95. Contact: McGraw-Hill Inc., New York, NY; (212) 337-5951. <p><strong>The Mosaic Handbook</strong><br>O'Reilly and Associates Inc. is bundling platform-specific manuals on the use of Mosiac with Spyglass' Enhanced NCSA Mosaic Internet interface. The book/software packages, which come in versions for Windows, Macintosh, and X-Windows platforms, show how to use Mosaic to find information on the World Wide Web (WWW). The book also describes how to add external viewers to Mosaic and how to customize the elements of the interface, such as screen elements, colors, and fonts. The handbooks cover HTML (HyperText Markup Language), the format for documents distributed on the WWW, and they explain how to create a home page, complete with links to other servers. $29.95. Contact: O'Reilly and Assoc., Inc., Sebastopol, CA; (800) 998-9938. <p><strong>The Mosaic Quick Tour</strong><br>Published by Ventana Press, The Mosaic Quick Tour gives users a fundamental understanding of Mosaic and the World Wide Web. The book includes hands-on instructions for locating, downloading, installing, and using software to explore the Web, FTP sites, and newsgroups. Also included is information on how to create a customized Web site called a "Home Page," which allows users to store audio and video information in a digital form for other Web users to access. $12. Contact: Ventana Press, Chapel Hill, NC; (800) 743-5369. <p><strong>Point and Click Internet</strong><br>Point and Click Internet is a book/disk/tool to help Macintosh users access the Internet via America Online (AOL) within minutes. Included are detailed instructions and illustrations guiding users on installating the AOL software and connecting to AOL. The package contains a trial membership to AOL, including 10 free hours. $12.95. Contact: Peachpit Press, Berkeley, CA; (800) 283-9444. <p><strong>WAIS and Gopher Servers</strong><br>Published by Mecklermedia, WAIS and Gopher Servers is a tutorial for Internet end-users on WAIS and Gopher. The book covers WAIS and Gopher protocols and how to use these clients for DOS, Macintosh, and Unix computers. Also included are descriptions of various Gopher server tools such as external texts, scripts, and files used to provide enhanced library service. $30. Contact: Mecklermedia, Westport, CT; (203) 226-6967. <p><strong>The Whole Internet User's Guide & Catalog</strong><br>The latest edition of The Whole Internet User's Guide & Catalog by Ed Krol features new tools and resources for Internet users. The book presents the history and ethics of the Internet, how to talk to other users, and an in-depth exploration of the tools for finding people, software, and information on remote computers. The last section of the book, "The Whole Internet Catalog," illustrates the breadth of information available on the Internet and where to find resources. Some of the new features include an in-depth look at Mosaic, MIME, and an introduction to Xarchie, an X-Windows-based Archie client with an FTP client built-in. $24.95. Contact: O'Reilly & Assoc., Inc. Sebastopol, CA; (800) 998-9938. <hr><strong>Starter Kits</strong><br><br><strong>Internet in a Box</strong><br>Internet in a Box, produced by Spry Inc. and O'Reilly and Associates Inc., provides PC users with instant connectivity to the Internet. The package contains a multimedia interface, a full suite of applications, and an on-line Internet guide. The user is given access to two ways to connect to the Internet, plus a subscription the Global Network Navigator (GNN), software to access Mosaic, electronic mail, a Usenet news reader, drag-and-drop file transfer, gopher, and telnet. Also included are three books by O'Reilly and Associates Inc.: The Whole Internet User's Guide & Catalog, a Getting Started Guide, and an Install Guide. $149. Contact: O'Reilly and Assoc. Inc., Sebastopol, CA; (800) 998-9938. <p><strong>Internet Membership Kit</strong><br>The Internet Membership Kit from Ventana Media provides users with Internet access tools. The Kit consists of graphical software, step-by-step instructions, a tour of the Internet, listings of resources, and free access time. To use the kit, users need a PC running Windows or a Macintosh running System 7 or later; 4MB of hard disk space; a 9600 BAUD or faster modem; a phone line; and a mouse. The software works with a SLIP or PPP connection from any service provider. The Macintosh version contains MacTCP, Eudora, Fetch, Stuffit Expander, and TurboGopher. The Windows version contains the Chameleon Sampler, which provides users with e-mail, file transfer, and telnet. Users are also provided with two bestsellers: Internet Tour Guides and The Internet Yellow Pages. $69.95. Contact: Ventana Media, Chapel Hill, NC; (919) 942-0220. <p><strong>Internet Starter Kit for the Macintosh</strong><br>Internet Starter Kit for the Macintosh, published by Hayden Books, contains step-by-step instructions for connecting to the Internet. Included with the book is a disk with the applications MacTCP, MacPPP & InterSLIP, Anarchie, Eudora, MacWAIS, MacWEB, and TurboGopher. The Starter Kit provides an automatic installer for getting connected to the Internet and coverage of PPP connections and troubleshooting. The book also includes a section on freeware and shareware over the Internet for academic areas. $29.95. Contact: Hayden Books, Indianapolis, IN; (800) 428-5331. <hr><a href="syllmart.html"><h3>Back to SyllabusMart Page</h3></a><hr><address>Copyright &copy; 1995 by Syllabus Press, Inc. All rights reserved.</address></body></html>
